biography |year= 1993 |publisher= [[William Morrow & Company]] |location= New York |isbn= 978-0-688-09759-2 |url= https://archive.org/details/tonycurtisautobi00curt }}\n* {{Cite book |last= Curtis |first= Tony |authorlink=  |author2= [[Peter Golenbock]] |title= Tony Curtis: American Prince: My Autobiography |year= 2008 |publisher= [[Harmony Books]] |location= New York |isbn= 978-0-307-40849-5 |url= https://archive.org/details/americanprinceme00curt }}\n* {{Cite book |last= Curtis |first= Tony |authorlink=  |title= Some Like it Hot: My Memories of Marilyn Monroe and the Making of the Classic Movie |year= 2009 |publisher= [[John Wiley & Sons]] |location= New York |page= [https://archive.org/details/makingofsomelike00curt/page/240 240] |isbn= 978-0-470-53721-3 |url= https://archive.org/details/makingofsomelike00curt/page/240 }}\n* Wise, James. ''Stars in Blue: Movie Actors in America's Sea Services''. Annapolis, MD: Naval Institute Press, 1997.  {{ISBN|1557509379}} {{OCLC|36824724}}\n\n==External links==\n{{external links|section|date=August 2013}}\n{{Commons}}\n* [http://www.tonycurtis.com Tonycurtis.com]\n* {{IMDb name|0000348}}\n* Remembering Tony Curtis [http://www.bronx.com/Local/obituaries/2550.html] Bronx News, 2012\n* {{YouTube|zcf5zUEw764|Tony Curtis, 1925-2010}}\n* {{Tcmdb name}}\n* [http://www.oralhistoryproject.com/TonyCurtis1.html Biography] and [http://www.oralhistoryproject.com/tcurtis_navy.html naval service] from the California Center for Military History website\n* [http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/visual_arts/article3779814.ece Alison Jackson, ''Some tormented Hollywood souls still like their gossip hot, Profile: Tony Curtis,'' ''Sunday Times'', 20 April 2008]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110920220616/http://www.frenchcx.com/en_films/tonyc-en.html Documentary film, ''The Jill & Tony Curtis Story'']\n* [http://film.virtual-history.com/person.php?personid=4784 Photographs and literature]\n* [http://www.life.com/image/first/in-gallery/49761/tony-curtis-life-and-times Tony Curtis: Life and Times] \u2013 slideshow by ''[[Life magazine]]''\n* [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/culture-obituaries/film-obituaries/8034695/Tony-Curtis.html ''The Telegraph'' obituary]\n* [https://www.gq.com/entertainment/celebrities/201006/tony-curtis-last-of-the-playboys Interview by Michael Hainey for ''GQ Magazine'']\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Curtis, Tony}}\n[[Category:1925 births]]\n[[Category:2010 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:American activists]]\n[[Category:American male comedy actors]]\n[[Category:American male film actors]]\n[[Category:American male painters]]\n[[Category:American male television actors]]\n[[Category:American naval personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:American people of Slovak-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Hungarian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:Analysands of Ralph Greenson]]\n[[Category:California Democrats]]\n[[Category:City College of New York alumni]]\n[[Category:David di Donatello Career Award winners]]\n[[Category:Deaths from cardiac arrest]]\n[[Category:Deaths from emphysema]]\n[[Category:Entertainers from the Bronx]]\n[[Category:Jewish activists]]\n[[Category:Jewish American male actors]]\n[[Category:Jewish American writers]]\n[[Category:Jewish American military personnel]]\n[[Category:Male actors from California]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Nevada]]\n[[Category:Male actors from New York City]]\n[[Category:Military personnel from New York City]]\n[[Category:Nevada Democrats]]\n[[Category:New York (state) Democrats]]\n[[Category:The New School alumni]]\n[[Category:United States Navy sailors]]\n[[Category:Writers from California]]\n[[Category:Writers from Nevada]]\n[[Category:Writers from New York City]]\n[[Category:Seward Park High School alumni]]\n", "name_user": "JHunterJ", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up,typo(s) fixed: 1992-93 \u2192 1992\u201393", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tony_Curtis"}
{"title_page": "Climate change in China", "text_new": "{{short description|Effects of global warming on the east Asian country and adaptation to it}}\n{{About|the effects of global warming on the east Asian country and adaptation to it|gases which contribute to global warming, and their mitigation|Greenhouse gas emissions by China}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2018}}\n\n'''Climate change in China''' is having major effects on the economy, society and the environment.<ref name=NC3>{{Cite web|url=https://unfccc.int/documents/197660|title=China National communication 3: Part III Impacts of Climate Change and Adaptation|website=unfccc.int|access-date=2019-09-26}}</ref> The energy structure and human activity caused [[global warming]] and climate change, and [[China]] suffered from negative [[effects of global warming]] in agriculture, forestry and water resources.\n\n==Current situation==\nChina observed a ground average temperature increase of 0.24\u2103/decade from 1951 to 2017, exceeding the global rate. The average precipitation of China was 641.3&nbsp;mm in 2017, 1.8% more than average precipitation of previous years. The [[sea level rise]] was 3.3mm/year from 1980 to 2017. There was an annual increase in concentrations of [[carbon dioxide]] from 1990 to 2016. The annual mean concentration of [[atmospheric carbon dioxide]],  [[methane]] and [[nitrous oxide]] at Wanliguan Station were 404.4 ppm, 1907 ppb and 329.7 ppb separately in 2016, slightly higher than the global mean concentration in 2016.<ref name=\":14\">{{Cite web|url=http://env.people.com.cn/n1/2018/0403/c1010-29905684.html|title=\u300a\u4e2d\u56fd\u6c14\u5019\u53d8\u5316\u84dd\u76ae\u4e66\u300b\uff1a\u5e74\u5e73\u5747\u6c14\u6e29\u663e\u8457\u4e0a\u5347--\u4eba\u6c11\u7f51\u73af\u4fdd\u9891\u9053--\u4eba\u6c11\u7f51|last=2170|website=env.people.com.cn|access-date=2018-04-10}}</ref>\n\n=== Public opinion  ===\nAccording to the Chinese citizen climate change recognition and understanding report<ref name=\":0\" /> conducted by the China Climate Change Communication program, 94% of interviewees supported fulfilling the [[Paris agreement]], 96.8% of interviewees supported international cooperation on global climate change, and more than 70% of interviewees were willing to purchase [[environmentally friendly]] products. 98.7% of interviewees supported implementing climate change education at schools. Respondents were most concerned about the [[air pollution]] caused by climate change. The investigation included 4025 samples.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=November 2017|title=\u4e2d\u56fd\u516c\u4f17\u6c14\u5019\u53d8\u5316\u4e0e\u6c14\u5019\u4f20\u64ad\u8ba4\u77e5\u60c5\u51b5\u8c03\u7814\u62a5\u544a|url=http://www.efchina.org/Attachments/Report/report-comms-20171108/%E4%B8%AD%E5%9B%BD%E5%85%AC%E4%BC%97%E6%B0%94%E5%80%99%E8%AE%A4%E7%9F%A5%E8%B0%83%E7%A0%942017.pdf|journal=\u4e2d\u56fd\u516c\u4f17\u6c14\u5019\u53d8\u5316\u4e0e\u6c14\u5019\u4f20\u64ad\u8ba4\u77e5\u60c5\u51b5\u8c03\u7814\u62a5\u544a|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref>\n\nThe investigation showed that Chinese citizens agreed that they were experiencing climate change, and that it was caused by human activities.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sohu.com/a/201860164_100011535|title=2017\u5e74\u4e2d\u56fd\u516c\u4f17\u6c14\u5019\u53d8\u5316\u4e0e\u6c14\u5019\u4f20\u64ad\u8ba4\u77e5\u72b6\u51b5\u8c03\u7814\u62a5\u544a\u53d1\u5e03|date=2017-11-02|website=www.sohu.com|access-date=2018-04-10}}</ref>\n\nFurthermore, most Chinese citizens believe [[individual action on climate change]] can help, although the government is still seen as the entity most responsible for dealing with climate change. If the government does take action, fiscal and taxation policies are seen as potentially effective.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Yu|first=Hao|last2=Wang|first2=Bing|last3=Zhang|first3=Yue-Jun|last4=Wang|first4=Shouyang|last5=Wei|first5=Yi-Ming|date=2013-05-22|title=Public perception of climate change in China: results from the questionnaire survey|journal=Natural Hazards|volume=69|issue=1|pages=459\u2013472|doi=10.1007/s11069-013-0711-1|issn=0921-030X}}</ref>\n\n=== Government stance ===\nClimate change has not been a priority to China until recently, when this issue was brought to a higher platform. China as a unitary state is not a federal system, as presented by its typical hierarchy. For example, the central government makes decisions and the local governments fulfill them. As a result, the local governments receive constraints and are measured by their performance from the central governments. Solving environmental issues such as climate change requires long-term investments in money, resources, and time. It is believed that these efforts will be detrimental to economic growth, which is of particular importance to the promotion of local government executives. This is why local governments have no engagement in addressing this issue<ref>  Qi, Y., Ma, L., Zhang, H., & Li, H. (2008). Translating a Global Issue Into Local Priority: China\u2019s Local Government Response to Climate Change. The Journal of Environment & Development, 17(4), 379\u2013400. https://doi.org/10.1177/1070496508326123\n</ref>.\n\nAttitudes of the Chinese government on climate change, specifically regarding the role of China in climate change action, have shifted notably in recent years. Historically, climate change was largely seen as a problem that has been created by and should be solved by industrialized countries; in 2015, China said it supports the \"common but differentiated responsibilities\" principle,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/world/XiattendsParisclimateconference/2015-12/01/content_22597769.htm|title=China reaffirms the key principle of 'common but differentiated responsibility'|access-date=2015-12-01}}</ref> which holds that since China is still developing, its abilities and capacities to reduce emissions are comparatively lower than developed countries'.\n\nRecently, the government has urged countries to continue to support the Paris agreement, even in the wake of the United States' withdrawal in 2017.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/07/19/world/asia/china-climate-change-report.html|title=China Is a Climate Leader but Still Isn't Doing Enough on Emissions, Report Says|access-date=2018-11-20}}</ref>\n\n==Effects of climate change ==\n{{update section|date=September 2019}}\nChina has and will suffer some of the [[effects of global warming]], including [[sea level rise]], [[Retreat of glaciers since 1850|glacier retreat]] and air pollution.\n\nThe implications of climate change impose serious setbacks on global health and will hinder the economic development of various regions worldwide impacting countries on more than just the basic environmental scale.  As in the case of China, we will see the effects on a social and economic level.\n\nChina's first National Assessment of Global Climate Change, released in the 2000s by the [[Ministry of Science and Technology of the People's Republic of China|Ministry of Science and Technology (MOST)]], states that China already suffers from the environmental impacts of climate change: increase of surface and ocean temperature, rise of sea level.<ref>http://www.die-gdi.de/CMS-Homepage/openwebcms3_e.nsf/(ynDK_contentByKey)/ENTR-7BDE2T?OpenDocument&nav=expand:Research%20and%20Consulting\\Projects;active:Research%20and%20Consulting\\Projects\\ENTR-7BDE2T{{dead link|date=November 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>{{better source needed|date=September 2019}} Qin Dahe, former head of China's Meteorological Administration, has said that temperatures in the Tibetan Plateau of China are rising four times faster than anywhere else.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.strategicforesight.com/publication_pdf/10345110617.pdf|title=The Indus Equation Report, Strategic Foresight Group}}</ref> Rising sea level is an alarming trend because China has a very long and densely populated coastline, with some of the most economically developed cities such as Shanghai, Tianjin, and Guangzhou situated there. Chinese research has estimated that a one-meter rise in sea level would inundate 92,000 square kilometers of China's coast, thereby displacing 67 million people.<ref name=\"stonybrook.digication.com2\">{{cite web|url=http://stonybrook.digication.com/egimenez/Case_Study_Impact_of_Climate_Change_on_China|title=Digication e-Portfolio :: Eda Charmaine Gimenez :: Welcome|website=stonybrook.digication.com}}</ref>{{better source needed|date=September 2019}}\n\nThere has also been an increased occurrence of climate-related disasters such as drought and flood, and the amplitude is growing. These events have grave consequences for productivity when they occur, and also create serious repercussions for natural environment and infrastructure. This threatens the lives of billions and aggravates poverty.\n\nFurthermore, climate change will worsen the uneven distribution of [[water resources in China]]. Outstanding rises in temperature would exacerbate evapo-transpiration, intensifying the risk of water shortage for agricultural production in the North. Although China's southern region has an abundance of rainfall, most of its water is lost due to flooding. As the Chinese government faces challenges managing its expanding population, an increased demand for water to support the nation's economic activity and people will burden the government. In essence, a water shortage is indeed a large concern for the country.<ref name=\"stonybrook.digication.com2\" />{{better source needed|date=September 2019}}\n\nLastly, [[Effects of climate change on human health|climate change could endanger human health]] by increasing outbreaks of disease and their transmission. After floods, for example, infectious diseases such as diarrhea and cholera are all far more prevalent. These effects would exacerbate the degradation of the ecologically fragile areas in which poor communities are concentrated pushing thousands back into poverty.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oxfam.org.hk/en/climatepoverty.aspx|title=Climate Change Aggravates Poverty|website=Oxfam Hong Kong|access-date=26 April 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120315071624/http://www.oxfam.org.hk/en/climatepoverty.aspx|archive-date=15 March 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>{{better source needed|date=September 2019}}\n\n=== Agriculture ===\nThe negative effects on China's agriculture caused by climate change have appeared. There was an increase in agricultural production instability, severe damages caused by high temperature and drought, and lower production and quality in prairie. In the near future, climate change may cause negative influences, causing a reduction of output in wheat, rice and corn, and change agricultural distribution of production.<ref name=\":132\">{{Cite web|url=http://waterschool.cn/projects/climate-change/approach/|title=Climate Change in China {{!}} Shangri-la Institute|website=waterschool.cn|access-date=2018-04-15}}</ref>{{better source needed|date=September 2019}} China is also dealing with agricultural issues due global demands of products such as soy beans. This global demand is causing coupled effects that stretch across oceans which in turn is effecting other countries. [[Environmental factor#Socioeconomic Drivers]]\n\n=== Forest and other natural ecosystems ===\nClimate change increases forest belt limits and frequencies of pests and diseases, decreases frozen earth areas, and threatens to decrease glacial areas in the northwest China. The vulnerability of ecosystems may increase due to future climate change.<ref name=\":132\" />{{better source needed|date=September 2019}}\n\n===  Water resource and coastal zone ===\nClimate change decreased total water resources in north China while increasing total water resources in south China. There were more floods, drought and extreme weather events. There may be a big impact in the spatial and temporal distribution in China's water resources, increasing extreme weather events and natural disasters. Climate change caused an increase in sea level, threatening to impair the functions of harbors.<ref name=\":132\" />{{better source needed|date=September 2019}}\n\n=== Diseases ===\nSome regions in China will be exposed to a 50 percent higher malaria transmission probability rate (B\u00e9guin et al., 2011).<ref name=\"WB2012\">[http://climatechange.worldbank.org/sites/default/files/Turn_Down_the_heat_Why_a_4_degree_centrigrade_warmer_world_must_be_avoided.pdf Why a 4 degree centrigrade warmer world must be avoided] November 2012 World Bank</ref>{{better source needed|date=September 2019}}\n\n=== Conclusion of [https://www.ipcc.ch/ IPCC]===\n{{update section|date=September 2019}}\nAccording to [[IPCC]] (2007), from 1900 to 2005, precipitation has declined in parts of southern Asia. By the 2050s, freshwater availability, including large river basins, is projected to decrease in Asian regions. Coastal areas, especially the delta areas in Asia, are projected to have increased flooding risk. Floods and droughts are expected to increase health concerns: diseases and mortality.<ref name=IPCC2007>{{cite web|url=http://www.mnp.nl/ipcc/pages_media/FAR4docs/final%20pdfs%20of%20chapters%20WGIII/IPCC%20WGIII_SPM_final.pdf|title=IPCC Working group III fourth assessment report, Summary for Policymakers 2007|publisher=}}{{dead link|date=October 2019|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n\n==Adaptation and Solution==\n{{expand section|date=September 2019}}\nIn China's first NDC submission, key areas were identified for climate change adaptation, including agriculture, water resources, and vulnerable areas. It also mentioned that an adaptation strategy should be implemented through regional strategies. <ref>China's First NDC Submission<nowiki/>https://www4.unfccc.int/sites/ndcstaging/PublishedDocuments/China%20First/China%27s%20First%20NDC%20Submission.pdf</ref> Flooding in cities is being tackled by collecting and recycling rainwater.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/china/politics/article/3017761/china-taps-global-expertise-climate-change-battle-against|title=China taps into global expertise in climate change battle against increasing floods and drought|date=2019-07-09|website=South China Morning Post|language=en|access-date=2019-09-26}}</ref>\nIn 2013, China issued its National Strategy for Climate Change Adaptation and set goals of reducing vulnerability, strengthening monitoring, and raising public awareness. Efforts on implementation have been put in adapting forestry, meteorological management, infrastructure, and risk planning. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://energypolicy.columbia.edu/sites/default/files/pictures/Guide%20to%20Chinese%20Climate%20Policy%207-27-18.pdf|title=GUIDE TO CHINESE CLIMATE POLICY 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe development of technology and economy in China share more responsibility in tackling climate change. After facing the 2011 smog issue, China's government launched an extensive strategy, which is to improve air quality by reducing the growth of coal consumption. Nevertheless, the trade war that involved China as one of the leading participants has resulted in the loss control of polluting industries, especially in the steel and cement during 2018. Fortunately, nearly 70 multinational and local brands implemented the monitoring data by The Institute of Public & Environmental Affairs (IPE) in China, stimulating nearly 8,000 suppliers approaching regulatory violations<ref>How China Can Truly Lead the Fight Against Climate Change https://time.com/5669061/china-climate-change/</ref>.\n\nInternally in the provinces of China, there are various projects held aiming to solve emissions reduction and energy-saving, which is a big step in tackling climate change. Beijing is developing in replacing traditional bulbs with energy-saving light bulbs. Provinces such as Rizhao and Dezhou are promoting solar energy in the building heating system. Besides, Tsinghua University launched a lead on low-carbon city development. The city is currently working with Tsinghua University to improve the urban environment by introducing renewable energy into industries and households.<ref>Translating a Global Issue Into Local Priority: China\u2019s Local Government Response to Climate Change   Qi, Y., Ma, L., Zhang, H., & Li, H. (2008). Translating a Global Issue Into Local Priority: China\u2019s Local Government Response to Climate Change. The Journal of Environment & Development, 17(4), 379\u2013400. https://doi.org/10.1177/1070496508326123</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Global warming|China}}\n{{Overly detailed|section|date=September 2019}}\n*[[Chinese national carbon trading scheme]]\n*[[China Carbon Forum]]\n*[[China Beijing Environmental Exchange]]\n*[[Coal power in China]]\n*[[Deforestation and climate change]]\n*[[Environment of China]]\n*[[Politics of global warming]]\n*[[Renewable energy in China]]\n*[[Renewable energy commercialization]]\n*[[Solar power in China]]\n*[[Scientific Development Concept]]\n*[[Tianjin Climate Exchange]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20180708222411/http://www.ccchina.gov.cn/ China Climate Change Information Network]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090813162812/http://www.greenpeace.org/china/en/campaigns/stop-climate-change Greenpeace China's China climate change resources]\n*[http://chinauseealliance.org/news.php China-US Energy Efficiency Alliance: China Climate Change News & Resources]\n\n{{Energy in the People's Republic of China}}\n{{Asia topic|Climate change in}}\n\n[[Category:Climate change in China| ]]\n[[Category:Environmental issues in China]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Effects of global warming on the east Asian country and adaptation to it}}\n{{About|the effects of global warming on the east Asian country and adaptation to it|gases which contribute to global warming, and their mitigation|Greenhouse gas emissions by China}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2018}}\n\n'''Climate change in China''' is having major effects on the economy, society and the environment.<ref name=NC3>{{Cite web|url=https://unfccc.int/documents/197660|title=China National communication 3: Part III Impacts of Climate Change and Adaptation|website=unfccc.int|access-date=2019-09-26}}</ref> The energy structure and human activity caused [[global warming]] and climate change, and [[China]] suffered from negative [[effects of global warming]] in agriculture, forestry and water resources.\n\n==Current situation==\nChina observed a ground average temperature increase of 0.24\u2103/decade from 1951 to 2017, exceeding the global rate. The average precipitation of China was 641.3&nbsp;mm in 2017, 1.8% more than average precipitation of previous years. The [[sea level rise]] was 3.3mm/year from 1980 to 2017. There was an annual increase in concentrations of [[carbon dioxide]] from 1990 to 2016. The annual mean concentration of [[atmospheric carbon dioxide]],  [[methane]] and [[nitrous oxide]] at Wanliguan Station were 404.4 ppm, 1907 ppb and 329.7 ppb separately in 2016, slightly higher than the global mean concentration in 2016.<ref name=\":14\">{{Cite web|url=http://env.people.com.cn/n1/2018/0403/c1010-29905684.html|title=\u300a\u4e2d\u56fd\u6c14\u5019\u53d8\u5316\u84dd\u76ae\u4e66\u300b\uff1a\u5e74\u5e73\u5747\u6c14\u6e29\u663e\u8457\u4e0a\u5347--\u4eba\u6c11\u7f51\u73af\u4fdd\u9891\u9053--\u4eba\u6c11\u7f51|last=2170|website=env.people.com.cn|access-date=2018-04-10}}</ref>\n\n=== Public opinion  ===\nAccording to the Chinese citizen climate change recognition and understanding report<ref name=\":0\" /> conducted by the China Climate Change Communication program, 94% of interviewees supported fulfilling the [[Paris agreement]], 96.8% of interviewees supported international cooperation on global climate change, and more than 70% of interviewees were willing to purchase [[environmentally friendly]] products. 98.7% of interviewees supported implementing climate change education at schools. Respondents were most concerned about the [[air pollution]] caused by climate change. The investigation included 4025 samples.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=November 2017|title=\u4e2d\u56fd\u516c\u4f17\u6c14\u5019\u53d8\u5316\u4e0e\u6c14\u5019\u4f20\u64ad\u8ba4\u77e5\u60c5\u51b5\u8c03\u7814\u62a5\u544a|url=http://www.efchina.org/Attachments/Report/report-comms-20171108/%E4%B8%AD%E5%9B%BD%E5%85%AC%E4%BC%97%E6%B0%94%E5%80%99%E8%AE%A4%E7%9F%A5%E8%B0%83%E7%A0%942017.pdf|journal=\u4e2d\u56fd\u516c\u4f17\u6c14\u5019\u53d8\u5316\u4e0e\u6c14\u5019\u4f20\u64ad\u8ba4\u77e5\u60c5\u51b5\u8c03\u7814\u62a5\u544a|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref>\n\nThe investigation showed that Chinese citizens agreed that they were experiencing climate change, and that it was caused by human activities.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sohu.com/a/201860164_100011535|title=2017\u5e74\u4e2d\u56fd\u516c\u4f17\u6c14\u5019\u53d8\u5316\u4e0e\u6c14\u5019\u4f20\u64ad\u8ba4\u77e5\u72b6\u51b5\u8c03\u7814\u62a5\u544a\u53d1\u5e03|date=2017-11-02|website=www.sohu.com|access-date=2018-04-10}}</ref>\n\nFurthermore, most Chinese citizens believe [[individual action on climate change]] can help, although the government is still seen as the entity most responsible for dealing with climate change. If the government does take action, fiscal and taxation policies are seen as potentially effective.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Yu|first=Hao|last2=Wang|first2=Bing|last3=Zhang|first3=Yue-Jun|last4=Wang|first4=Shouyang|last5=Wei|first5=Yi-Ming|date=2013-05-22|title=Public perception of climate change in China: results from the questionnaire survey|journal=Natural Hazards|volume=69|issue=1|pages=459\u2013472|doi=10.1007/s11069-013-0711-1|issn=0921-030X}}</ref>\n\n=== Government stance ===\nClimate change has not been a priority to China until recently, when this issue was brought to a higher platform. China as a unitary state is not a federal system, as presented by its typical hierarchy. For example, the central government makes decisions and the local governments fulfill them. As a result, the local governments receive constraints and are measured by their performance from the central governments. Solving environmental issues such as climate change requires long-term investments in money, resources, and time. It is believed that these efforts will be detrimental to economic growth, which is of particular importance to the promotion of local government executives. This is why local governments have no engagement in addressing this issue<ref>  Qi, Y., Ma, L., Zhang, H., & Li, H. (2008). Translating a Global Issue Into Local Priority: China\u2019s Local Government Response to Climate Change. The Journal of Environment & Development, 17(4), 379\u2013400. https://doi.org/10.1177/1070496508326123\n</ref>.\n\nAttitudes of the Chinese government on climate change, specifically regarding the role of China in climate change action, have shifted notably in recent years. Historically, climate change was largely seen as a problem that has been created by and should be solved by industrialized countries; in 2015, China said it supports the \"common but differentiated responsibilities\" principle,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/world/XiattendsParisclimateconference/2015-12/01/content_22597769.htm|title=China reaffirms the key principle of 'common but differentiated responsibility'|access-date=2015-12-01}}</ref> which holds that since China is still developing, its abilities and capacities to reduce emissions are comparatively lower than developed countries'.\n\nRecently, the government has urged countries to continue to support the Paris agreement, even in the wake of the United States' withdrawal in 2017.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/07/19/world/asia/china-climate-change-report.html|title=China Is a Climate Leader but Still Isn't Doing Enough on Emissions, Report Says|access-date=2018-11-20}}</ref>\n\n==Effects of climate change ==\n{{update section|date=September 2019}}\nChina has and will suffer some of the [[effects of global warming]], including [[sea level rise]], [[Retreat of glaciers since 1850|glacier retreat]] and air pollution.\n\nThe implications of climate change impose serious setbacks on global health and will hinder the economic development of various regions worldwide impacting countries on more than just the basic environmental scale.  As in the case of China, we will see the effects on a social and economic level.\n\nChina's first National Assessment of Global Climate Change, released in the 2000s by the [[Ministry of Science and Technology of the People's Republic of China|Ministry of Science and Technology (MOST)]], states that China already suffers from the environmental impacts of climate change: increase of surface and ocean temperature, rise of sea level.<ref>http://www.die-gdi.de/CMS-Homepage/openwebcms3_e.nsf/(ynDK_contentByKey)/ENTR-7BDE2T?OpenDocument&nav=expand:Research%20and%20Consulting\\Projects;active:Research%20and%20Consulting\\Projects\\ENTR-7BDE2T{{dead link|date=November 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>{{better source needed|date=September 2019}} Qin Dahe, former head of China's Meteorological Administration, has said that temperatures in the Tibetan Plateau of China are rising four times faster than anywhere else.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.strategicforesight.com/publication_pdf/10345110617.pdf|title=The Indus Equation Report, Strategic Foresight Group}}</ref> Rising sea level is an alarming trend because China has a very long and densely populated coastline, with some of the most economically developed cities such as Shanghai, Tianjin, and Guangzhou situated there. Chinese research has estimated that a one-meter rise in sea level would inundate 92,000 square kilometers of China's coast, thereby displacing 67 million people.<ref name=\"stonybrook.digication.com2\">{{cite web|url=http://stonybrook.digication.com/egimenez/Case_Study_Impact_of_Climate_Change_on_China|title=Digication e-Portfolio :: Eda Charmaine Gimenez :: Welcome|website=stonybrook.digication.com}}</ref>{{better source needed|date=September 2019}}\n\nThere has also been an increased occurrence of climate-related disasters such as drought and flood, and the amplitude is growing. These events have grave consequences for productivity when they occur, and also create serious repercussions for natural environment and infrastructure. This threatens the lives of billions and aggravates poverty.\n\nFurthermore, climate change will worsen the uneven distribution of [[water resources in China]]. Outstanding rises in temperature would exacerbate evapo-transpiration, intensifying the risk of water shortage for agricultural production in the North. Although China's southern region has an abundance of rainfall, most of its water is lost due to flooding. As the Chinese government faces challenges managing its expanding population, an increased demand for water to support the nation's economic activity and people will burden the government. In essence, a water shortage is indeed a large concern for the country.<ref name=\"stonybrook.digication.com2\" />{{better source needed|date=September 2019}}\n\nLastly, [[Effects of climate change on human health|climate change could endanger human health]] by increasing outbreaks of disease and their transmission. After floods, for example, infectious diseases such as diarrhea and cholera are all far more prevalent. These effects would exacerbate the degradation of the ecologically fragile areas in which poor communities are concentrated pushing thousands back into poverty.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oxfam.org.hk/en/climatepoverty.aspx|title=Climate Change Aggravates Poverty|website=Oxfam Hong Kong|access-date=26 April 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120315071624/http://www.oxfam.org.hk/en/climatepoverty.aspx|archive-date=15 March 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>{{better source needed|date=September 2019}}\n\n=== Agriculture ===\nThe negative effects on China's agriculture caused by climate change have appeared. There was an increase in agricultural production instability, severe damages caused by high temperature and drought, and lower production and quality in prairie. In the near future, climate change may cause negative influences, causing a reduction of output in wheat, rice and corn, and change agricultural distribution of production.<ref name=\":132\">{{Cite web|url=http://waterschool.cn/projects/climate-change/approach/|title=Climate Change in China {{!}} Shangri-la Institute|website=waterschool.cn|access-date=2018-04-15}}</ref>{{better source needed|date=September 2019}}\n\n=== Forest and other natural ecosystems ===\nClimate change increases forest belt limits and frequencies of pests and diseases, decreases frozen earth areas, and threatens to decrease glacial areas in the northwest China. The vulnerability of ecosystems may increase due to future climate change.<ref name=\":132\" />{{better source needed|date=September 2019}}\n\n===  Water resource and coastal zone ===\nClimate change decreased total water resources in north China while increasing total water resources in south China. There were more floods, drought and extreme weather events. There may be a big impact in the spatial and temporal distribution in China's water resources, increasing extreme weather events and natural disasters. Climate change caused an increase in sea level, threatening to impair the functions of harbors.<ref name=\":132\" />{{better source needed|date=September 2019}}\n\n=== Diseases ===\nSome regions in China will be exposed to a 50 percent higher malaria transmission probability rate (B\u00e9guin et al., 2011).<ref name=\"WB2012\">[http://climatechange.worldbank.org/sites/default/files/Turn_Down_the_heat_Why_a_4_degree_centrigrade_warmer_world_must_be_avoided.pdf Why a 4 degree centrigrade warmer world must be avoided] November 2012 World Bank</ref>{{better source needed|date=September 2019}}\n\n=== Conclusion of [https://www.ipcc.ch/ IPCC]===\n{{update section|date=September 2019}}\nAccording to [[IPCC]] (2007), from 1900 to 2005, precipitation has declined in parts of southern Asia. By the 2050s, freshwater availability, including large river basins, is projected to decrease in Asian regions. Coastal areas, especially the delta areas in Asia, are projected to have increased flooding risk. Floods and droughts are expected to increase health concerns: diseases and mortality.<ref name=IPCC2007>{{cite web|url=http://www.mnp.nl/ipcc/pages_media/FAR4docs/final%20pdfs%20of%20chapters%20WGIII/IPCC%20WGIII_SPM_final.pdf|title=IPCC Working group III fourth assessment report, Summary for Policymakers 2007|publisher=}}{{dead link|date=October 2019|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n\n==Adaptation and Solution==\n{{expand section|date=September 2019}}\nIn China's first NDC submission, key areas were identified for climate change adaptation, including agriculture, water resources, and vulnerable areas. It also mentioned that an adaptation strategy should be implemented through regional strategies. <ref>China's First NDC Submission<nowiki/>https://www4.unfccc.int/sites/ndcstaging/PublishedDocuments/China%20First/China%27s%20First%20NDC%20Submission.pdf</ref> Flooding in cities is being tackled by collecting and recycling rainwater.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/china/politics/article/3017761/china-taps-global-expertise-climate-change-battle-against|title=China taps into global expertise in climate change battle against increasing floods and drought|date=2019-07-09|website=South China Morning Post|language=en|access-date=2019-09-26}}</ref>\nIn 2013, China issued its National Strategy for Climate Change Adaptation and set goals of reducing vulnerability, strengthening monitoring, and raising public awareness. Efforts on implementation have been put in adapting forestry, meteorological management, infrastructure, and risk planning. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://energypolicy.columbia.edu/sites/default/files/pictures/Guide%20to%20Chinese%20Climate%20Policy%207-27-18.pdf|title=GUIDE TO CHINESE CLIMATE POLICY 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe development of technology and economy in China share more responsibility in tackling climate change. After facing the 2011 smog issue, China's government launched an extensive strategy, which is to improve air quality by reducing the growth of coal consumption. Nevertheless, the trade war that involved China as one of the leading participants has resulted in the loss control of polluting industries, especially in the steel and cement during 2018. Fortunately, nearly 70 multinational and local brands implemented the monitoring data by The Institute of Public & Environmental Affairs (IPE) in China, stimulating nearly 8,000 suppliers approaching regulatory violations<ref>How China Can Truly Lead the Fight Against Climate Change https://time.com/5669061/china-climate-change/</ref>.\n\nInternally in the provinces of China, there are various projects held aiming to solve emissions reduction and energy-saving, which is a big step in tackling climate change. Beijing is developing in replacing traditional bulbs with energy-saving light bulbs. Provinces such as Rizhao and Dezhou are promoting solar energy in the building heating system. Besides, Tsinghua University launched a lead on low-carbon city development. The city is currently working with Tsinghua University to improve the urban environment by introducing renewable energy into industries and households.<ref>Translating a Global Issue Into Local Priority: China\u2019s Local Government Response to Climate Change   Qi, Y., Ma, L., Zhang, H., & Li, H. (2008). Translating a Global Issue Into Local Priority: China\u2019s Local Government Response to Climate Change. The Journal of Environment & Development, 17(4), 379\u2013400. https://doi.org/10.1177/1070496508326123</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Global warming|China}}\n{{Overly detailed|section|date=September 2019}}\n*[[Chinese national carbon trading scheme]]\n*[[China Carbon Forum]]\n*[[China Beijing Environmental Exchange]]\n*[[Coal power in China]]\n*[[Deforestation and climate change]]\n*[[Environment of China]]\n*[[Politics of global warming]]\n*[[Renewable energy in China]]\n*[[Renewable energy commercialization]]\n*[[Solar power in China]]\n*[[Scientific Development Concept]]\n*[[Tianjin Climate Exchange]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20180708222411/http://www.ccchina.gov.cn/ China Climate Change Information Network]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090813162812/http://www.greenpeace.org/china/en/campaigns/stop-climate-change Greenpeace China's China climate change resources]\n*[http://chinauseealliance.org/news.php China-US Energy Efficiency Alliance: China Climate Change News & Resources]\n\n{{Energy in the People's Republic of China}}\n{{Asia topic|Climate change in}}\n\n[[Category:Climate change in China| ]]\n[[Category:Environmental issues in China]]\n", "name_user": "Lfabina", "label": "safe", "comment": "added link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Climate_change_in_China"}
{"title_page": "List of films considered the worst", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikimedia list article}}\n{{for|the 2011 American action comedy|The Worst Movie Ever!}}\n{{pp-protected|reason=Persistent [[WP:Disruptive editing|disruptive editing]]|small=yes}}\n</noinclude>[[File:Reefer Madness (1936).jpg|220px|thumb|''[[Reefer Madness]]'', one of the earliest films to garner particularly negative contemporary reviews<ref name=\"psmag\">{{cite news|last1=Lincoln|first1=Kevin|title=The Benefits of Being the Worst Movie Ever Made|url=https://psmag.com/economics/benefits-worst-movie-ever-made-84813|accessdate=October 23, 2017|work=[[Pacific Standard]]|date=July 2, 2014|language=en}}</ref>]]\nThe [[film]]s listed below have been cited by a variety of notable critics in varying media sources as being among the '''worst films ever made'''. Examples of such sources include [[Metacritic]], [[Roger Ebert]]'s list of most-hated films, ''[[The Golden Turkey Awards]]'', ''[[Leonard Maltin's Movie Guide]]'', [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the [[Stinkers Bad Movie Awards]], the cult TV series ''[[Mystery Science Theater 3000]]'', and the [[Golden Raspberry Awards]] (aka the \"Razzies\"). Films on these lists are generally [[feature film|feature-length films]] that are [[commerce|commercial]]/[[art film|artistic]] in nature (intended to turn a profit and/or to express personal statements), professionally or independently produced (as opposed to [[amateur]] productions), and released in theaters, then on television, or more recently through on-demand [[streaming media|streaming services]].\n\n== 1930s ==\n\n=== ''Maniac'' (1934) ===\n''[[Maniac (1934 film)|Maniac]]'', also known as ''Sex Maniac'', is an [[exploitation film|exploitation]]/[[horror film]] directed by [[Dwain Esper]]. The story is a loose adaptation of the [[Edgar Allan Poe]] story \"[[The Black Cat (short story)|The Black Cat]]\" and follows a [[vaudeville]] impersonator who becomes an assistant to a [[mad scientist]]. [[Danny Peary]] believes that ''Maniac'' is the worst film ever made, Charlie Jane Anders of [[Gawker Media]]{{'}}s [[io9]] described it as \"possibly the worst movie in history\" and ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'' critic Michael Wilmington wrote that it may be the worst film he had ever seen, writing: \"There are some voyages into ineptitude, like Dwain Esper's anti-classic ''Maniac,'' that defy all reason.\"<ref>{{Cite book|last1=Peary|first1=Danny|authorlink=Danny Peary|title=Cult Midnight Movies: Discover the 37 Best Weird, Sleazy, Sexy, and Crazy Good Cinema Classics|publisher=[[Workman Publishing Company]]|url=https://books.google.com/?id=TTsPBAAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=Maniac+(1934)#v=snippet&q=Maniac%20(1934)%20Dwain%20Esper&f=false|year=2014|isbn=9780761181699}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://io9.gizmodo.com/did-the-worst-movie-of-all-time-come-out-75-years-ago-5161275 |title=Did The Worst Movie Of All Time Come Out 75 Years Ago? |publisher=[[io9]] |last=Anders|first=Charlie Jane |date=February 26, 2009|accessdate=February 18, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-2005-08-12-0508120290-story.html| work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|title='Chaos' a loathsome exercise in horror\n|last =Wilmington|first=Michael|date=August 12, 2005|accessdate=February 18, 2019}}</ref> [[Rotten Tomatoes]] placed ''Maniac'' on their list of movies \"So Bad They're Unmissable\",<ref name=\"sobad\"/> the Italian ''[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]'' included the film on its list of the 20 worst movies ever, and it is featured in ''[[The Official Razzie Movie Guide]]''.<ref name=italianvanity>{{cite news|url=https://www.vanityfair.it/show/cinema/2018/02/25/20-film-piu-brutti-di-sempre| work=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]|title=I 20 film pi\u00f9 brutti di sempre|last =Pellegrini|first=Francesca|language=Italian|date=25 February 2018|accessdate=February 18, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Reefer Madness'' (1936) ===\n[[File:ReeferMadness 12.JPG|thumb|upright|Originally titled ''Tell Your Children'', ''[[Reefer Madness]]'' was called \"the grand-daddy of all 'Worst' movies\" by [[Leonard Maltin]]]]\n''[[Reefer Madness]]'' (originally released as ''Tell Your Children'' and sometimes titled or subtitled as ''The Burning Question'', ''Dope Addict'', ''Doped Youth'', and ''Love Madness'') is a 1936 American [[exploitation film]] and [[propaganda|propaganda work]] revolving around the melodramatic events that ensue when high school students are lured by pushers to try [[cannabis (drug)|marijuana]]\u2014from a [[Hit and run (vehicular)|hit and run accident]], to [[manslaughter]], suicide, attempted rape, and descent into madness. ''[[Pacific Standard]]'' wrote that ''Reefer Madness'' was \"one of the first films ever to be considered transcendentally bad\"<ref name=\"psmag\"/> and [[Leonard Maltin]] has called it \"the grand-daddy of all 'Worst' movies\".<ref name=\"Maltin01211\">{{cite book |last=Maltin |first=Leonard |authorlink=Leonard Maltin |title=Leonard Maltin's Movie and Video Guide 2004 |publisher=Signet |year=2003 |isbn=0-451-20940-0 |url=https://archive.org/details/leonardmaltinsmo00leon }}</ref> ''[[Las Vegas CityLife]]'' named it the \"worst ever\" runner-up to ''[[Plan 9 from Outer Space]]'',<ref>{{cite news |url=http://archives.lasvegascitylife.com/articles/2009/09/24/ae/stage/iq_31362594.txt |date=September 24, 2009 |last=McKee |first=David |work=Las Vegas CityLife |accessdate=November 17, 2013 |title=What's the Worst Movie Ever? |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130903051856/http://archives.lasvegascitylife.com/articles/2009/09/24/ae/stage/iq_31362594.txt |archivedate=September 3, 2013 }}</ref> and [[AMC (TV channel)|AMC]] described it as \"one of the worst movies ever made\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://movies.amctv.com/movie/1936/Reefer+Madness|work=[[AMC (TV channel)]] |accessdate=November 17, 2013 |title= Reefer Madness (1936)}}</ref> [[News.com.au]] considered it a \"disastrous flop turned cult classic\" due to its \"terrible acting and exaggerated drug-addicted stereotypes\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.news.com.au/national/nsw-act/when-hollywoods-worst-films-become-cult-classics/news-story/792f3f09aba66809245d65328c73921c|title=When Hollywood's worst films become cult classics|work=[[News.com.au]]|first=Troy|last=Lennon|date=December 7, 2017|accessdate=January 20, 2019}}</ref> The film has inspired a number of parodies, including an [[off-Broadway]] [[Reefer Madness (musical)|musical satire]] and a [[Reefer Madness (2005 film)|2005 film]] based on the musical.<ref>[http://www.tcm.com/tcmdb/title/546510/Reefer-Madness/ Reefer Madness (2005)-Overview-TCM.com]</ref>\n\n=== ''The Terror of Tiny Town'' (1938)===\n''[[The Terror of Tiny Town]]'', directed by [[Sam Newfield]] and produced by [[Jed Buell]], remains the only [[musical film|musical]] [[Western (genre)|Western]] with an all-[[Dwarfism|dwarf]] cast. The film was pulled from obscurity as a [[camp (style)|camp classic]] after appearing in college and [[midnight film|midnight screenings]] in the early 1970s.<ref>[http://www.tcm.com/tcmdb/title/92598/The-Terror-of-Tiny-Town/articles.html The Terror of Tiny Town (1938) - Articles - TCM.com]</ref> In 1978, it was included in ''[[The Fifty Worst Films of All Time]]''<ref name=\"tinyterror\">{{cite web|url=https://filmthreat.com/uncategorized/the-terror-of-tiny-town-dvd/|title=The Terror of Tiny Town (DVD)|work=Film Threat|date=June 17, 2005|accessdate=March 23, 2020}}</ref> and has since been listed as one of the worst films ever made by ''[[Flavorwire]]'',<ref name=\"Flavorwire\"/> Rotten Tomatoes,<ref name=\"sobad\"/>  and ''[[The Golden Turkey Awards]]''.<ref name=\"tinyterror\"/> [[Melvin Defleur]] referred to it as \"Perhaps the worst film of all time\",<ref>{{Cite book|last1=Defluer|first1=Melvin|authorlink=Melvin Defleur|title=Understanding Mass Communication: A Liberal Arts Perspective|publisher=[[Houghton Mifflin Harcourt]]|edition=6|year=1998|page=160}}</ref> and critic Gabriel Ricard listed it as the worst film ever made; stating,\"not only is it pretty terrible, but ''Tiny Town'' is also pretty endearing.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://culturedvultures.com/best-worst-movies/|title=20 Best Worst Movies Of All Time|work=Cultured Vultures|last=Richard|first=Gabriel|date=June 5, 2019|accessdate=March 23, 2020}}</ref> In 1986, ''The Terror of Tiny Town'' was the first film featured on ''[[Canned Film Festival]]'', a [[late night television]] show featuring the worst movies ever made.<ref name=\"cannedfilm\">{{cite web|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-1986-06-20-8602140300-story.html|title=A 'Terror' Kicks Off World's Worst Film Festival|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|last=Terry|first=Clifford|date=June 20, 1989|accessdate=March 23, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== 1940s ==\n\n=== ''No Orchids for Miss Blandish'' (1948) ===\n\n''[[No Orchids for Miss Blandish (film)|No Orchids for Miss Blandish]]'', a British gangster film adapted from the 1939 [[No Orchids for Miss Blandish (novel)|novel]] by [[James Hadley Chase]], received a very hostile reception from the press. This was mainly due to the film's high (for the time) level of sexual and violent content, but also because its attempt to portray Americans using a largely British cast (including an early role for [[Sid James]])<ref name=\"goodwin\">{{cite book |first=Cliff |last=Goodwin |title=Sid James: A Biography |publisher=Random House |year=2011 |isbn=978-0-7535-4682-6 |pages=67\u201368 }}</ref> was seen as unconvincing.<ref name=\"bmc\">{{cite book |last=McFarlane |first=Brian |year=1999 |chapter=Outrage: No Orchids for Miss Blandish |title=British Crime Cinema |editor-first1=Steve |editor-last1=Chibnall |editor-first2=Robert |editor-last2=Murphy |publisher=Routledge |isbn=0-415-16870-8 |pages=37\u201350 }}</ref> The British film journal ''[[Monthly Film Bulletin]]'' called it \"the most sickening exhibition of brutality, perversion, sex and sadism ever to be shown on a cinema screen\".<ref name=\"bmc\" /> The ''[[Sunday Express]]'' film reviewer called ''No Orchids for Miss Blandish'' \"the worst film I have ever seen\".<ref name=\"hfg\">{{cite book |title=Halliwell's Film Guide |publisher=HarperPerennial |year=1994 |isbn=978-0-06-273318-4 |page=781 }}</ref> The Australian newspaper ''[[The Age]]'' also gave a harsh review: \"''No Orchids for Miss Blandish'' is not only a disgrace to the studio that made it, but it also reflects on the British industry as a whole ... the entire production is unpardonable.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=The Chiel's Film Review |newspaper=The Age |date=November 27, 1948 |page=5 }}</ref> Cliff Goodwin, discussing ''No Orchids For Miss Blandish's'' initial reception, notes it was \"unanimously dubbed 'the worst film ever made{{'\"}}.<ref name=\"goodwin\" /> Later reviews of the film were equally antipathetic. ''No Orchids for Miss Blandish'' was described by British film reviewer [[Leslie Halliwell]] as a \"hilariously awful gangster film ... one of the worst films ever made\".<ref name=\"hfg\" /> ''Leonard Maltin's Classic Movie Guide'' states that ''No Orchids for Miss Blandish'' \"aspires to be a Hollywood film noir and misses by a mile.\"<ref>{{cite book |last=Maltin |first=Leonard |year=2011 |title=Leonard Maltin's Classic Movie Guide: From The Silent Era Through 1965 |edition=Second |publisher=Penguin |isbn=978-0-452-29577-3 |page=474 }}</ref>\n\n=== ''The Babe Ruth Story'' (1948) ===\n\n''[[The Babe Ruth Story]]'' is a 1948 baseball film biography of [[Babe Ruth]], starring [[William Bendix]], [[Claire Trevor]] and [[Sam Levene]].<ref>{{Citation|last=Del Ruth|first=Roy|title=The Babe Ruth story|date=2010|publisher=Warner Home Video|language=English|oclc=694103117|last2=Considine|first2=Bob|last3=Callahan|first3=George|last4=Bendix|first4=William|last5=Trevor|first5=Claire|last6=Bickford|first6=Charles|last7=Frawley|first7=William|last8=Levene|first8=Sam|last9=Allied Artists Productions}}</ref> ''[[The New York Times]]'' describes it as \"the ''[[Plan 9 from Outer Space]]'' of baseball biopics\".<ref>{{cite news |title=The Babe Ruth Story (1948)|newspaper=The New York Times |url=https://www.nytimes.com/movies/movie/3535/The-Babe-Ruth-Story/overview |accessdate=30 November 2013}}</ref> It was rushed into release while Ruth was still alive. In the final scene, Ruth delivers on a promise he made to a young cancer patient that he would hit a [[home run]]. Not only does Ruth succeed in fulfilling the promise, but also the child is subsequently cured of his cancer. [[Dan Shaughnessy]] of ''[[The Boston Globe]]'' claimed the film was the worst he had ever seen,<ref>{{cite news |title=Duke as Williams? A Prince of an Idea |author=Dan Shaughnessy |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=XscSAAAAIBAJ&sjid=vvkDAAAAIBAJ&pg=7230,788739&dq=babe+ruth+story+worst+film |newspaper=Spokane Chronicle |date=Apr 3, 1986 |accessdate=30 November 2013}}</ref> while ''[[The Washington Times]]'' stated that it \"stands as possibly the worst movie ever made\".<ref>{{cite news |last=Heller |first=Dick |title=Clinic and reception in the works to honor NBA pioneer Lloyd |newspaper=The Washington Times |date=July 23, 2000 |url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=WT&p_theme=wt&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EB08BFA289BE4FB&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D |accessdate=30 November 2013}}{{subscription required}}</ref> The film has been called one of the worst sports films ever by ''[[Newsday]]'' and ''[[The A.V. Club]]'',<ref>{{cite news |last=Isaacs |first=Stan |title=Out ofLeft Field \u2013 The 10 Worst Sports Movies Of All Time |newspaper=Newsday |date=Feb 26, 1989 |url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/newsday/doc/278087041.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Feb%2026,%201989&author=Stan%20Isaacs&pub=Newsday%20%28Combined%20editions%29&edition=&startpage=&desc=OUT%20OF%20LEFT%20FIELD%20The%2010%20Worst%20Sports%20Movies%20Of%20All%20Time |accessdate=30 November 2013}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://film.avclub.com/the-home-run-that-cured-cancer-16-amazing-movie-sports-1798214998|title=The home run that cured cancer: 16 Amazing Movie Sports Feats|last=Mincher|first=Chris|last2=Bahn|first2=Christopher|date=October 6, 2008|website=[[The A.V. Club]]|language=en-US|access-date=April 16, 2019|last3=Modell|first3=Josh|last4=Gillette|first4=Amelie|last5=Tobias|first5=Scott|last6=Murray|first6=Noel|last7=Pierce|first7=Leonard}}</ref> and called one of the worst biopics by [[Moviefone]] and [[Spike (TV network)|Spike]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.moviefone.com/2009/11/05/worst-movie-biopics/|title=Worst Movie Biopics: Real-Life Catastrophes|date=November 5, 2009|accessdate=30 November 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203031806/http://news.moviefone.com/2009/11/05/worst-movie-biopics/|archive-date=3 December 2013|url-status=dead|publisher=[[Moviefone]]|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.spike.com/articles/td0rkp/all-access-weekly-blockbuster-hollywood-bios-the-good-the-bad-and-the-jobs|title=Blockbuster Hollywood Bios: The Good, the Bad, and the \"Jobs\"|last=Marshall|first=Kevin|date=August 16, 2013|website=[[Spike (TV network)|Spike]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203195640/http://www.spike.com/articles/td0rkp/all-access-weekly-blockbuster-hollywood-bios-the-good-the-bad-and-the-jobs|archive-date=December 3, 2013|url-status=dead|access-date=April 16, 2019}}</ref> Michael Sauter included it in his book ''The Worst Movies of All Time'' and Leonard Maltin called it \"perfectly dreadful\".<ref name=\"Maltin01211\"/>\n\n== 1950s ==\n\n=== ''Glen or Glenda'' (1953) ===\n[[File:Ed wood glen or glenda.jpg|thumb|[[Ed Wood]] appears in a scene from ''[[Glen or Glenda]]''. He directed ''Glen or Glenda'' and  ''[[Plan 9 from Outer Space]]'' and was named the Worst Director of All Time in ''[[The Golden Turkey Awards]]''.]]\nA semi-[[Autobiography|autobiographical]] quasi-[[Documentary film|documentary]] about [[transvestism]], ''[[Glen or Glenda]]'' starred and was directed by [[Ed Wood]]. After a nightmarish [[dream sequence]], Glen undergoes psychotherapy to help cure his affliction. [[Bela Lugosi]] appears in this film, as he did in several other Wood films toward the end of his career. Leonard Maltin insists this was far worse than Wood's later ''[[Plan 9 from Outer Space]]'' and considers it \"possibly the worst movie ever made\".<ref name=\"Maltin01211\"/> Richard Barrios describes ''Glen or Glenda'' as \"one of the funniest and worst movies ever made\".<ref>Richard Barrios, ''Screened Out: Playing Gay in Hollywood from Edison to Stonewall'', Psychology Press, 2003, {{ISBN|0-415-92328-X}}, Page 235.</ref> In his book ''Cult Movies 3'', [[Danny Peary]] suggests this is actually a radical, if ineptly made, film that presents a far more personal story than is contained in films by more well-respected [[auteur theory|auteurs]], and it was taken seriously and seen as a significant work by Steve Jenkins, writing for ''[[The Monthly Film Bulletin]]'' when the film was finally released in the UK in 1981.<ref>{{cite book |last=Peary |first=Danny |authorlink=Danny Peary |title=Cult Movies 3: 50 More of the Classics, the Sleepers, the Weird and the Wonderful |publisher=Simon & Schuster |year=1988 |isbn=978-0-671-64810-7}}</ref> In 1994, [[Tim Burton]] directed ''[[Ed Wood (film)|Ed Wood]]'', which includes some material about the trials and tribulations of making ''Glen or Glenda''.\n\n=== ''Robot Monster'' (1953) ===\n\n''[[Robot Monster]]'', a [[science-fiction film]] originally shot and exhibited in [[3-D film|3D]], features an actor dressed in a gorilla suit and what looks almost like a [[diving helmet]]. The film, produced and directed by [[Phil Tucker]], is listed in Michael Sauter's book ''The Worst Movies of All Time'' among \"The Baddest of the Bs\". It is also featured in ''[[The Book of Lists]]''' 10 worst movies list, and in ''[[The Fifty Worst Films of All Time]]''. ''[[The Golden Turkey Awards]]'' confers on its main character the title of \"Most Ridiculous Monster in Screen History\" and, listing director Tucker among the runners-up to \"Worst Director of All Time\" (the winner being Ed Wood), states, \"What made ''Robot Monster'' ineffably worse than any other low-budget sci-fi epic was its bizarre artistic pretension\". It was featured in an episode of the movie-mocking television show ''[[Mystery Science Theater 3000]]'',<ref>{{cite web |title=Mystery Science Theater 3000 \u2013 Robot Monster |work=TV.com |url=http://www.tv.com/mystery-science-theater-3000/robot-monster/episode/46805/summary.html?tag=ep_list;title;6/ |accessdate=2011-03-07}}</ref> and was fondly remembered by author [[Stephen King]], who quotes, and agrees with, a review in ''[[Castle of Frankenstein]]'' magazine (\"certainly among the finest terrible movies ever made\", \"one of the most laughable [[Poverty Row|poverty row]] quickies\").<ref>{{cite book |first=Stephen |last=King |title=Danse Macabre |year=1981 |publisher=Everest House |location=New York |isbn=978-0-89696-076-3|title-link=Danse Macabre (book) }}</ref>\n\n=== ''The Conqueror'' (1956) ===\n\n[[Howard Hughes]] funded ''[[The Conqueror (1956 film)|The Conqueror]]'', an [[epic film]] featuring [[John Wayne]] as [[Mongolia]]n chieftain [[Genghis Khan]] and the redheaded [[Susan Hayward]] as a [[Tatars|Tatar]] princess. The movie was filmed near [[St. George, Utah]], downwind from a [[nuclear testing]] range in [[Nevada]], and is often blamed for the [[cancer]] deaths of many of the cast and crew, including Hayward, Wayne, [[Agnes Moorehead]], [[Pedro Armend\u00e1riz]], and director [[Dick Powell]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Adams |first=Cecil |title=Did John Wayne die of cancer caused by a radioactive movie set? |publisher=The Straight Dope |date=October 26, 1984 |url=http://www.straightdope.com/classics/a2_016.html |accessdate=2011-03-07}}</ref> In addition to filming near the testing range, truckloads of the red sands were transported back to the studios for interior scenes. The film made the ten-worst list in ''[[The Book of Lists]]'', appears in Michael Sauter's book ''The Worst Movies of All Time'', and was among those listed in [[Michael Medved]]'s book ''[[The Fifty Worst Films of All Time]]''. Originally written for [[Marlon Brando]], ''[[The Guardian]]'' called the choice of Wayne for Khan \"one of the worst casting decisions of all time\".<ref name=geng/> ''[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]'' listed ''The Conqueror'' as the worst biopic ever made.<ref>{{cite web |last=Barone |first=Matt |title=The 10 Worst Biopic Movies Of All Time |work=Complex |date=November 12, 2012 |url=http://www.complex.com/pop-culture/2012/11/10-worst-biopic-movies-of-all-time/ |accessdate=July 7, 2017}}</ref>\n\nHughes, one of the world's wealthiest people at the time, had previously produced the successful dramatic films ''[[Hell's Angels (film)|Hell's Angels]]'', ''[[Scarface (1932 film)|Scarface]]'', and ''[[The Outlaw]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/april/5/newsid_4739000/4739940.stm |title=BBC On THis Day &#124; 5 &#124; 1976: Billionaire Howard Hughes dies |work=BBC News |date=1976-04-07 |accessdate=2013-11-18}}</ref> After seeing ''The Conqueror'' himself, Hughes bought every existing print for $12 million and refused to let the film be seen on television until 1974, reportedly out of guilt over the decision to shoot at such a hazardous location.<ref>{{cite book |title=My Year of Flops |last=Rubin |first=Nathan |year=2010 |publisher=[[Charles Scribner's Sons|Scribner]] |location= |isbn=978-1-4391-5312-3 |page= |pages= |url=https://archive.org/details/myyearofflopsavc0000rabi |accessdate= }}</ref> By 1980, 91 of the 220 cast and crew members had been diagnosed with cancer, over 41%.<ref name=geng>{{cite news|last=von Tunzelmann|first=Alex|title=The Conqueror: Hollywood gives Genghis Khan a kicking he won't forget|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/filmblog/2013/may/03/the-conqueror-hollywood-genghis-khan|newspaper=The Guardian|date=3 May 2013|location=London}}</ref> This was the last film Hughes produced.\n\n=== ''Fire Maidens from Outer Space'' (1956) ===\n\n''[[Fire Maidens from Outer Space]]'', a low-budget British [[space opera]] film (known in the US as ''Fire Maidens of Outer Space''), is about a group of astronauts visiting an all-female society on a moon of [[Jupiter]]. This film developed a negative reputation for its poor special effects (including a scene on the alien planet in which an automobile is visible driving past).<ref name=\"dt\">[https://www.dvdtalk.com/reviews/61441/fire-maidens-of-outer-space/ Fire Maidens Of Outer Space]. ''DVD Talk'', August 13, 2013. Retrieved January 21, 2014.</ref> Leslie Halliwell described ''Fire Maidens from Outer Space'' as \"a strong contender for the title of the worst movie ever made, with diaphanously clad English gals striking embarrassed poses against cardboard sets\".<ref>John Walker (ed.) ''Halliwell's Film and Video Guide 2000'', London and New York; HarperCollins, 1999, {{ISBN|0-06-273645-0}} (p.287).</ref> British film historian I.Q. Hunter included it in his list of candidates for \"the worst British film ever made\".<ref name=\"iqh\">I. Q Hunter, \"From Window Cleaner to Potato Man\" in ''British Comedy Cinema'', edited by I.Q. Hunter and Laraine Porter. Routledge, 2012. {{ISBN|0-415-66667-8}}. (p.154)</ref> The [[Internet Brands|DVD Talk]] website's review claimed it \"may be among the worst-ever professionally produced science fiction films\".<ref name=\"dt\" /> In November 1992, the film was featured in an episode of ''Mystery Science Theater 3000''.\n\n=== ''Plan 9 from Outer Space'' (1959) ===\n[[File:Plan 9 Alternative poster.jpg|thumb|''[[Plan 9 from Outer Space]]'' has been named the worst movie ever made by ''[[The Golden Turkey Awards]]'' and other sources]]\n[[Ed Wood]]'s ''[[Plan 9 from Outer Space]]'' was labeled the \"Worst Film Ever\" by ''[[The Golden Turkey Awards]]''. This movie marked the final film appearance of [[Bela Lugosi]]. Wood shot only a small amount of test footage featuring his idol Lugosi before the actor's death. Afterwards, the character was played by [[Tom Mason]], the [[chiropractic|chiropractor]] of Wood's wife (Kathy O'Hara) at the time, who played his scenes holding the character's cape in front of his face.\n\nWood was apparently undeterred by the numerous physical differences that distinguished Mason from Lugosi {{spaced ndash}} such as height and build, and the fact that Mason was nearly bald while Lugosi retained a full head of hair until he died.  Worst of all, Mason may have been the only man in the world who couldn't do an impression of Lugosi's accent. Years later, video distributors such as Avenue One DVD began to make light of this, adding such blurbs as \"Almost Starring Bela Lugosi\" to the cover art. Numerous critics also pointed out the cheap, hardly believable special effects and [[wikt:kitschy|kitschy]] dialogue.\n\nShot in 1956, the film was not released until 1959 because of difficulty in finding a distributor. It has played at the New Orleans Worst Film Festival. In 1994, [[Tim Burton]] directed ''[[Ed Wood (film)|Ed Wood]]'', which includes some material about the trials and tribulations of making ''Plan 9''. Phil Hall of ''Film Threat'' calls it \"far too entertaining to be considered as the very worst film ever made\".<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/plan-9-from-outer-space/reviews/|title=Plan 9 from Outer Space - Movie Reviews|last=|first=|date=|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|access-date=April 16, 2019}}</ref> Likewise, John Wirt of ''The Advocate'' goes as far as to call it \"the ultimate cult flick\",<ref name=\":2\" /> and ''Videohound's Complete Guide to Cult Flicks and Trash Pics'' states, \"In fact, the film has become so famous for its own badness that it's now beyond criticism.\"<ref>{{cite book |last=Schwartz |first=Carol |title=Videohound's Complete Guide to Cult Flicks and Trash Pics |publisher=Visible Ink Press |year=1995 |isbn=978-0-7876-0616-9}}</ref> Ian Berriman of ''[[SFX (magazine)|SFX]]'' commented about the unintentional comedy, \"Some things are best watched at 3 am, wrapped in the warm glow of drunkenness ... ''Plan 9 From Outer Space'' is one of them.\" ''The [[Radio Times]] Guide to Films'' described ''Plan 9'' as \"the worst film ever made\" and \"tediously depressing\".<ref>''Radio Times Guide to Films 2014''. Radio Times, London, 2013. {{ISBN|0-9567523-6-5}} (p.947).</ref>\n\n== 1960s ==\n\n=== ''The Beast of Yucca Flats'' (1961) ===\n\n''[[The Beast of Yucca Flats]]'' by [[Coleman Francis]], shot silently with added narration, concerns a scientist ([[Tor Johnson]]) who is exposed to radiation from an atomic blast, which turns him into a monster. The film opens with a scene of implied [[necrophilia]] that has nothing to do with the remainder of the movie and does not fit anywhere into the film's chronology. ''Leonard Maltin's TV and Movie Guide'' calls it \"one of the worst films ever made\".<ref>{{cite book| first=Leonard |last=Maltin |edition=2007 |title=Leonard Maltin's Movie and Video Guide |publisher=Plume |location=New York |isbn=978-0-452-28893-5 |page=94|year=2007 }}</ref> [[Bill Warren (film historian and critic)|Bill Warren]] said, \"It may very well be the worst non-[[pornographic film|porno]] science fiction movie ever made.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.monstershack.net/sp/index.php/the-beast-of-yucca-flats-1961/ |title=Full Movie Walk-throughs |publisher=Monster Shack |date=2009-02-10 |accessdate=2011-01-17}}</ref> It was featured on ''Mystery Science Theater 3000'', where members of the cast state it is one of the worst films they have seen up to that point.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.castleforrester.com/media/guide/0621.htm |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080907155815/http://www.castleforrester.com/media/guide/0621.htm |url-status=dead |archive-date=2008-09-07 |title=Experiment Guide |publisher=Castle Forrester |accessdate=2011-01-17}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Eegah'' (1962) ===\n\nThe low-budget shocker ''[[Eegah]]'' features [[Richard Kiel]] as a prehistoric caveman emerging in early 1960s California who clumsily finds love with a teenage girl. [[Arch Hall Jr.]] performs musical numbers, with lyrics widely considered terrible. The film's notoriety was enhanced as a result of being featured on episodes of ''[[Canned Film Festival]]'' and ''Mystery Science Theater 3000'',<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.castleforrester.com/media/guide/0506.htm |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080829141244/http://www.castleforrester.com/media/guide/0506.htm |url-status=dead |archive-date=2008-08-29 |title=Experiment Guide |publisher=Castle Forrester |accessdate=2011-01-17}}</ref> where the cast of the show stated in ''The Mystery Science Theater 3000 Amazing Colossal Episode Guide'' ({{ISBN|0-553-37783-3}}), that they consider the shaving scene (where Eegah lolls his tongue around and laps up shaving cream) one of the most disgusting things they have seen. It was also one of the films listed in Michael Medved's book ''The Fifty Worst Films of All Time''.<ref>{{cite book|last=Medved|first=Michael|title=The Fifty Worst Films Of All Time|year=1980|publisher=Random House|isbn=0-449-04139-5}}</ref>\n\n=== ''The Creeping Terror'' (1964) ===\n\nThe science-fiction/horror film ''[[The Creeping Terror]]'' was directed, produced, and edited by Vic Savage (under the pseudonym A.J. Nelson, but he keeps his name when credited as an actor). The movie is about a large slug-like alien that lands on Earth and terrorizes an American town.<ref>Medved, Harry and Michael (1986). ''Son of Golden Turkey Awards''. New York: Random House/Villard Books. {{ISBN|0-394-74341-5}}. p. 197.</ref> The film is memorable for its use of some bargain-basement effects: stock footage of a rocket launch played in reverse to depict the landing of an alien spacecraft, and the \"monster\" appears to be composed of a length of shag carpet draped over several actors. Notably, the creature's victims inexplicably stand perfectly still as the slow-moving monster approaches them. Scott Weinberg of efilmcritic.com simply summarizes the movie with \"You've seen clips of this one in those 'awful, awful movies' documentaries.\" The movie was featured in the sixth season of ''Mystery Science Theater 3000''.<ref>{{cite web |title=\"Mystery Science Theater 3000\" The Creeping Terror |work=imdb.com |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0770613/ |accessdate=2013-05-24}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://rottentomatoes.com/m/the-creeping-terror-dangerous-charter-the-crawling-monster/ |title=The Creeping Terror (Dangerous Charter) (The Crawling Monster) |website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |accessdate=2013-11-18}}</ref>\n\n=== ''The Horror of Party Beach'' (1964) ===\n\n''Mystery Science Theater 3000'' featured ''[[The Horror of Party Beach]]'' in 1997, and the film was listed in ''[[The Fifty Worst Films of All Time]]''. [[Del Tenney]] directed it, and the plot mainly consists of sea monsters attacking young women at slumber parties on a beach, who keep returning even after a few murders. ''[[The New York Times]]'' film review stated, \"The most to be said for him is that he has not stinted on the gore.\"<ref>[https://movies.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9A06E1D61138E13ABC4850DFB266838F679EDE New York Times Movie Review] April 30, 1964</ref> Thomas Lisanti in ''Hollywood Surf and Beach Movies: The First Wave, 1959\u20131969'' called it \"by far the worst of the sixties beach films\", and [[Stephen King]] called it \"an abysmal little wet fart of a film\".<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=eBvMFuHle2kC&pg=RA1-PA1925&dq=%22the+horror+of+party+beach%22+worst#v=onepage&q=%22the%20horror%20of%20party%20beach%22%20worst Hollywood Surf and Beach Movies: The First Wave, 1959\u20131969] By Thomas Lisanti, number 8</ref> Joe Meyers in the [[Hearst Publishing|Hearst]] newspaper blog for the ''[[Stamford Advocate]]'' said on Del Tenney's passing: \"Connecticut had its own Ed Wood, an actor, director and entrepreneur named Del Tenney who made a series of truly awful pictures in the Stamford area during the 1960s, the most notorious of which is ''Horror of Party Beach'', a 1964 drive-in quickie about an atomic mutation that terrorizes [[Stamford, Connecticut|Stamford]] ('Party Beach' was actually [[Shippan Point]]).\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.ctnews.com/meyers/2013/03/01/the-passing-of-the-b-movie-king-of-connecticut-%E2%80%94-del-tenney/|title=The passing of the B-movie king of Connecticut \u2014 Del Tenney|date=1 March 2013|website=ctnews.com}}</ref> It is also listed in Michael Sauter's book ''The Worst Movies of All Time''.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=H2FZAAAAMAAJ&q=sauter+%22horror+of+party+beach%22&dq=sauter+%22horror+of+party+beach%22 The worst movies of all time, or, What were they thinking?] Michael Sauter; Carol Pub. Group, 1999 358 pages, page 306</ref>\n\n=== ''The Incredibly Strange Creatures Who Stopped Living and Became Mixed-Up Zombies'' (1964) ===\n\n''[[The Incredibly Strange Creatures Who Stopped Living and Became Mixed-Up Zombies]]'' (sometimes billed as ''The Incredibly Strange Creatures'') is a 1964 American monster movie written and directed by [[Ray Dennis Steckler]]. Steckler also starred in the film, billed under the pseudonym \"Cash Flagg\". In the film, three friends visit a carnival and stumble into a group of occultists and disfigured monsters. Produced on a $38,000 budget, much of it takes place at The Pike amusement park in [[Long Beach, California]], which resembles [[Brooklyn]]'s [[Coney Island]]. The film was billed as the first \"monster musical\", beating out ''The Horror of Party Beach'' by a mere month in release date. The 2004 DVD ''The 50 Worst Movies Ever Made'' listed this film as the worst film of all time.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0449786/movieconnections|title=The 50 Worst Movies Ever Made (Video 2004)|publisher=|via=www.imdb.com}}</ref> The [[Music journalism|rock critic]] [[Lester Bangs]] wrote an appreciative 1973 [[essay]] about ''Incredibly Strange Creatures'' in which he tries to explain and justify the movie's value: \"This flick doesn't just rebel against, or even disregard, standards of taste and art. In the universe inhabited by ''The Incredibly Strange Creatures Who Stopped Living and Became Mixed-Up Zombies'', such things as standards and responsibility have never been heard of. It is this lunar purity which largely imparts to the film its classic stature. Like ''[[Beyond the Valley of the Dolls]]'' and a very few others, it will remain as an artifact in years to come to which scholars and searchers for truth can turn and say, '''This'' was trash!{{'\"}}<ref name=\"Bangs\">{{cite book\n | author =Lester Bangs\n | authorlink = Lester Bangs\n | editor = Greil Marcus\n | title = Psychotic Reactions and Carburetor Dung\n | year = 1987\n | publisher = Random House\n | location = New York\n | isbn = 0-394-53896-X\n | chapter = The Incredibly Strange Creatures Who Stopped Living and Became Mixed-Up Zombies, or, The Day The Airwaves Erupted\n | page = 122\n}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Santa Claus Conquers the Martians'' (1964) ===\n\nThe sci-fi movie ''[[Santa Claus Conquers the Martians]]'' was the creation of [[Nicholas Webster]]. Because [[Martian]] children only get to see Santa Claus on TV signals beamed from Earth, their parents decide to abduct Santa to make them happy. The film was initially criticized for its oddity and poor special effects. It is also known for starring a very young [[Pia Zadora]].<ref name=\"ft1111\">{{cite web|url=https://filmthreat.com/features/1295/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121130200629/https://filmthreat.com/features/1295/|url-status=dead|archive-date=30 November 2012|title=Film Threat \u2013 The Bootleg Files: \"Santa Claus Conquers The Martians\"|work=Filmthreat.com|accessdate=4 May 2012}}</ref> [[BBC]] critic Nick Cramp described it as \"possibly the worst film ever made\".<ref>{{cite web |title=Santa Claus Conquers the Martians (1964) |publisher=[[BBC]] |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/films/2000/12/11/santa_claus_conquers_the_martians_1964_review.shtml |last=Cramp|first=Nick|date= December 11, 2020 |accessdate=March 25, 2020}}</ref> The film is cited on a 10-worst list in ''The Book of Lists'' and in ''The Fifty Worst Films of All Time''. Like many others in this category, it has been featured in ''Mystery Science Theater 3000'',<ref>{{cite web |title=Mystery Science Theater 3000 \u2013 Santa Claus Conquers the Martians |work=TV.com |url=http://www.tv.com/mystery-science-theater-3000/santa-claus-conquers-the-martians/episode/46920/summary.html?tag=ep_list;title;47/ |accessdate=2011-03-07}}</ref> and ''[[Cinematic Titanic]]'' (a spin-off of ''MST3K'') revisited the film in 2008.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://cinematictitanic.twinvision.com/products/ |title=Cinematic Titanic &#124; The Store |work=Cinematictitanic.twinvision.com |date=2012-10-11 |accessdate=2013-11-18 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131015034626/https://cinematictitanic.twinvision.com/products/ |archivedate=2013-10-15 }}</ref> \n\nA remake was rumoured with [[David Zucker (filmmaker)|David Zucker]] as producer, and [[Jim Carrey]] attached to play Dropo. An estimated release date was announced as 2002, though it was then believed to have been in [[development hell]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Santa Claus Conquers the Martians |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0058548/ |publisher=imdb.com |accessdate=May 16, 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050206013433/http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0158916/ |archivedate=February 6, 2005 |date=February 6, 2005 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n=== ''Monster a Go-Go!'' (1965) ===\n\n''[[Monster a Go-Go|Monster a Go-Go!]]'' began as ''Terror at Halfday'' by [[Bill Rebane]]. The production ran out of money and the film was abandoned. [[Herschell Gordon Lewis]], who reportedly needed a second feature to comprise a double bill, purchased and completed it for a minimal amount of money. Several of the film's actors were unable to return, so Lewis simply replaced their parts with new characters who mysteriously appear and fill the roles of the missing characters. One of the actors Lewis managed to rehire had gained weight, gone bald, and grown a goatee, so Lewis recast him as the brother of the original character.<ref name=\"agony\">{{cite web |date=June 16, 2003 |url=http://www.agonybooth.com/monster_a_go_go/default.asp?Page=5 |title=Recap: Monster A-Go Go (1965)|work=The Agony Booth |accessdate=2007-01-21}}</ref> The picture consists mostly of lengthy dialogue sequences concerning the apparent mutation of an astronaut into a monster portrayed by the giant [[Henry Hite]]. Poor audio quality makes much of the dialogue unintelligible, and when the film is overexposed, several characters' faces appear as bright white, glowing circles. At one point, when a phone supposedly rings, the sound effect is obviously a person making a noise with their mouth.<ref>{{youtube|5dKiaRUKgmA|MST3K \u2013 421 \u2013 Human Phone Ring}}</ref> During the climax of the movie, as soldiers prepare to confront the mutated astronaut, he abruptly vanishes and the narrator informs the audience, \"there was no monster\", and that the astronaut has, in fact, been in the [[Atlantic Ocean]] the entire time. [[Allmovie|All Movie Guide]] calls the film a \"surreal anti-masterpiece\".<ref>{{cite web |last=Beldin |first=Fred |title=Monster A Go-Go! |work=Allmovie.com |url=https://allmovie.com/movie/monster-a-go-go%21-v33169/review |accessdate=2012-09-12}}</ref> It was also featured on ''Mystery Science Theater 3000'', where writer [[Paul Chaplin]] called the dialogue \"garbled beyond recognition\".<ref>{{cite web |title=Mystery Science Theater 3000 \u2013 Monster A Go-Go |publisher=Castle Forrester |url=http://www.castleforrester.com/media/guide/0421.htm |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081120215055/http://www.castleforrester.com/media/guide/0421.htm |url-status=dead |archive-date=2008-11-20 |accessdate=2011-03-07}}</ref> The entire cast of the show later stated it was officially the worst movie they have ever seen.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.angelfire.com/ga/hikeeba/mst3kguide.html |title=Hi-keeba!'s MST3K Episode Guide |work=Angelfire.com |date=2001-03-01 |accessdate=2011-01-17}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Manos: The Hands of Fate'' (1966) ===\n[[File:Manosposter.jpg|thumb|''[[Manos: The Hands of Fate]]'' was featured in ''[[Mystery Science Theater 3000]]'''s most popular episode]]\nThe low-budget horror film ''[[Manos: The Hands of Fate]]'', made by [[El Paso, Texas|El Paso]] insurance and fertilizer salesman Hal P. Warren, concerns a vacationing family kidnapped by a [[polygamy|polygamous]] cult of [[paganism|pagans]]. The film was conceived after Warren bet Academy Award-winning screenwriter [[Stirling Silliphant]] that anyone could make a horror movie.<ref name=\"EW2\">{{cite news |url=https://ew.com/article/2005/06/06/worst-movie-ever-made/|title=The Worst Movie Ever Made |page=2 |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |date=June 6, 2005 |accessdate=December 3, 2019|first=Dalton |last=Ross}}</ref> Warren was convinced by the film's cinematographer and stunt coordinator that most of its glaring mistakes could be fixed in a [[Dallas]] post-production studio, when in reality the two wanted to quickly wrap the production because they were not being paid.<ref name=\"EW2\"/> Several technical gaffes made it into the film, including scenes filmed out of focus, a marking slate being seen in one shot, the scarf on the female lead's head disappearing and reappearing, and an insect bumping the camera lens.<ref name=\"EW2\"/><ref name=\"ma\">{{cite book |first=Michael |last=Adams |title=Showgirls, Teen Wolves, and Astro Zombies: a film critic's year-long quest to find the worst movie ever made |location=New York |publisher=Itbooks |year=2010 |isbn=978-0-06-180629-2 |pages=91\u20132 }}</ref> The film was shot with a camera that could not record sound and had a 32-second maximum shot length. All dialogue was later dubbed by Warren and four others, including a grown woman who dubbed the voice for a seven-year-old girl.<ref name=\"ma\"/><ref name=\"NBC\">{{cite web |url=http://entertainment.nbcnews.com/_news/2012/08/13/12645253-torgo-lives-mystery-science-alums-revisit-worst-movie-ever-manos-the-hands-of-fate |title=Torgo lives! 'Mystery Science' alums revisit worst movie ever, 'Manos: The Hands of Fate' |last1=Fashingbauer Cooper |first1=Gael |date=August 13, 2012 |work=[[NBC News]] |accessdate=March 4, 2013}}</ref> It opens with a nine-minute driving scene that the filmmakers intended to use for cast and crew credits, but failed to do so.<ref name=\"NBC\"/> The movie includes dialogue spoken while all characters are facing away from the camera, a character complaining about it getting dark while the sun is brightly shining, and the character Torgo, a [[satyr]] with overly large thighs, that three women attempt to massage to death.<ref name=\"EW2\"/><ref name=\"NBC\"/><ref name=\"ElPaso\">{{cite news |title=Hero Massaged to Death in 'Manos-- The Hands of Fate' |author=Betty Pierce |url=http://www.mst3ktemple.com/images/manos_review-post-x.jpg |newspaper=[[El Paso Herald-Post]] |date= November 11, 1966|accessdate=March 1, 2013}}</ref> The film gained notoriety and cult popularity by being featured on ''Mystery Science Theater 3000'',<ref>{{cite web |title=Mystery Science Theater 3000 \u2013 Manos: The Hands of Fate |work=TV.com |url=http://www.tv.com/mystery-science-theater-3000/manos-the-hands-of-fate/episode/46947/summary.html?tag=ep_list;title;74/ |accessdate=2011-03-07}}</ref> and was the show's most popular episode.<ref name=\"EW2\"/> The film has a 7% on [[Rotten Tomatoes]],<ref>{{rotten-tomatoes|id=manos_the_hands_of_fate|title=Manos \u2013 the Hands of Fate |accessdate=July 2, 2018}}</ref> and ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' says the movie is \"widely regarded as, quite simply, the worst movie ever made\".<ref name=\"EW2\"/> Even Warren himself would later admit his film was one of the worst ever, suggesting it might make a passable comedy if redubbed.<ref>{{cite news |first=Richard |last=Brandt |url=http://www.jophan.org/mimosa/m18/brandt.htm |title=The Hand That Time Forgot |work=Mimosa |date=May 1996 |accessdate=2006-08-17 |pages=35\u201338}}</ref> The film was later restored <ref>[https://www.npr.org/2011/12/12/143573040/manos-the-hands-of-fate-carefully-restoring-the-opposite-of-a-masterpiece 'Manos: The Hands of Fate': Carefully Restoring The Opposite Of A Masterpiece : NPR]</ref> and released on Blu-ray in 2015.<ref>[https://news.avclub.com/read-this-the-battle-over-the-infamous-cult-classic-ma-1798284742 Read this: The battle over the infamous cult classic Manos: The Hands of Fate|AV Club]</ref><ref>[https://synapse-films.com/synapse-films/manos-the-hands-of-fate-special-edition-blu-ray/ Synapse Films]</ref>\n\n=== ''A Place for Lovers'' (1968) ===\n\n''[[A Place for Lovers]]'' is a French-Italian [[romantic film]] directed by [[Vittorio De Sica]], starring [[Faye Dunaway]] as a terminally ill American fashion designer in [[Venice, Italy]], and [[Marcello Mastroianni]] as a race car driver who has a whirlwind affair with her. [[Roger Ebert]] of the ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'' called it the \"most godawful piece of pseudo-romantic slop I've ever seen!\"<ref>{{cite news |last=Ebert |first=Roger |title=A Place for Lovers |newspaper=[[Chicago Sun-Times]] |date=December 16, 1969 |url=https://rogerebert.com/reviews/a-place-for-lovers-1969 |accessdate=2013-10-19}}</ref> and [[Charles Champlin]] of the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' referred to it as \"the worst movie I have seen all year and possibly since 1926\".<ref>{{cite news |title=A Place For Lovers Film 'Worst' One Critic's Seen |author=Charles Champlin|author-link=Charles Champlin |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=FmlkAAAAIBAJ&sjid=5HwNAAAAIBAJ&pg=1127,904508&dq=a+place+for+lovers+dunaway+worst |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=18 December 1969|accessdate=19 August 2013}}</ref> Leonard Maltin noted Ebert's comments in his review and offered that the film was \"low points for all concerned\".<ref name=\"Maltin01211\"/> ''A Place for Lovers'' was included as one of the choices in ''The Fifty Worst Films of All Time'' and the Italian ''[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]'' listed it as one of the 20 worst movies ever made.<ref name=italianvanity/>\n\n=== ''They Saved Hitler's Brain'' (1968) ===\n''[[They Saved Hitler's Brain]]'' is a [[science fiction film]] directed by [[David Bradley (director)|David Bradley]].\n<ref>[http://www.tcm.com/tcmdb/title/92846/They-Saved-Hitler-s-Brain/ They Saved Hitler's Brain (1964) - TCM.com]</ref> It was [[made-for-TV movie|adapted for television]] from a shorter 1963 theatrical [[feature film]], ''Madmen of Mandoras'',<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0057273/ The Madmen of Mandoras (1963) - IMDb]</ref> and was lengthened by about 20 minutes with additional footage shot by [[University of California, Los Angeles|UCLA]] students at the request of the distributor. In the film, [[Adolf Hitler]]'s head was severed from his body at the end of [[World War II]] and the head plans to rule over a new [[Third Reich]] from [[South America]]. It has a [[List of films with a 0% rating on Rotten Tomatoes|rare rating of 0%]] on Rotten Tomatoes, based on 5 reviews from critics, with an average rating of 1.3/10.<ref name=\"hitlersbrain\">{{cite web | url = http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/they_saved_hitlers_brain/ | title = They Saved Hitler's Brain | work = [[Rotten Tomatoes]]  | accessdate = March 26, 2020 }}</ref> ''[[TV Guide]]'' called it \"One of the all-time worst\",<ref name=\"hitlersbrain\"/> while Danny Peary said it was \"A legitimate candidate for Worst Film Ever Made title.\"<ref>{{Cite book|last1=Peary|first1=Danny|authorlink=Danny Peary|title=Guide for the Film Fanatic|publisher=[[Simon & Schuster]]|page=430|year=1986|isbn=0671610813}}</ref> In 1979, it won the World's Worst Film Festival in [[Ottawa, Canada]], which reportedly delighted Bradley.<ref name=\"aslide\">{{Cite book|last1=Slide|first1=Anthony|authorlink=Anthony Slide|title=Magnificent Obsession: The Outrageous History of Film Buffs, Collectors, Scholars, and Fanatics|publisher=[[University Press of Mississippi]]|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ep9GDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT105&dq=they+saved+hitler%27s+brain+worst&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiqudvQ_7joAhVCn-AKHZy9BSUQ6AEwAHoECAEQAg#v=onepage&q=they%20saved%20hitler's%20brain%20&f=false|year=2018|isbn=1496810538}}</ref> It has been featured in ''The Golden Turkey Awards'', ''Canned Film Festival'',<ref name=\"cannedfilm\"/> and has been spoofed on ''[[The Simpsons]]'' multiple times.<ref name=\"aslide\"/>\n\n== 1970s ==\n\n=== ''Myra Breckinridge'' (1970) ===\n\nThe comedy ''[[Myra Breckinridge (film)|Myra Breckinridge]]'', based on the [[Myra Breckinridge|book of the same name]] by [[Gore Vidal]], directed by [[Mike Sarne|Michael Sarne]] and starring [[Raquel Welch]], [[Rex Reed]], [[Mae West]], [[John Huston]] and [[Farrah Fawcett]], provoked controversy due to a scene in which Welch [[rape|forcibly]] [[Pegging (sexual practice)|sodomizes]] a bound man while clips from various classic films play onscreen. The film was initially [[X-rated|rated X]] before edits and an appeal to the [[Motion Picture Association of America|MPAA]] brought it down to an R. It also used the technique of inserting clips from [[Classical Hollywood cinema|Golden Age]] movies in such a way that the dialogue took on sexual undertones. Several stars whose films were featured objected to the gimmick, and some (such as [[Loretta Young]]) sued to remove the footage. The film was a critical failure, with ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine saying \"''Myra Breckinridge'' is about as funny as a child molester\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Cinema:Some Sort of Nadir |work=time.com |date=July 6, 1970 |url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,878382,00.html |accessdate=2011-03-07}}</ref> Leonard Maltin gave it a BOMB (the lowest score possible) and stated that it was \"as bad as any movie ever made\".<ref name=\"Maltin01211\"/> The ''[[Miami News]]'' critic Herb Kelly nominated ''Myra Breckinridge'' as the worst film ever made.<ref>{{cite news |title='Breckinridge' Worst Ever |author=Herb Kelly |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=4QxgAAAAIBAJ&sjid=E-oFAAAAIBAJ&pg=2413,4500090&dq=myra+breckinridge+worst+ever |newspaper=The Miami News |date=29 August 1970 |accessdate=17 August 2013}}</ref> The film is also cited in ''The Fifty Worst Films of All Time''. It also was included in ''The Book of Lists''{{'}} worst movies of all time, claiming there was something in the movie to offend absolutely everyone. Gore Vidal disowned it, calling it \"an awful joke\",<ref>{{cite book |last1=Hoberman |first1=J. |authorlink1=J. Hoberman |last2=Rosenbaum |first2=Jonathan |authorlink2=Jonathan Rosenbaum |title=Midnight Movies |publisher=Da Capo Press |year=1991 |isbn=0-306-80433-6 |page=268}}</ref> and blamed the movie for a decade-long drought in the sale of the original book.<ref>{{cite book |last=Conner |first=Floyd |title=Hollywood's Most Wanted: The Top 10 Book of Lucky Breaks, Prima Donnas, Box Office Bombs, and Other Oddities |publisher=Brassey's |year=2002 |isbn=1-57488-480-8 |page=[https://archive.org/details/hollywoodsmostwa0000conn/page/65 65] |url=https://archive.org/details/hollywoodsmostwa0000conn/page/65 }}</ref>\n\n=== ''Zaat'' (1971) ===\n\nDirected by Don Barton, ''[[Zaat]]'' was also known under various titles including ''Hydra'', ''Attack of the Swamp Creatures'', ''Legend of the Zaat Monster'', and ''The Blood Waters of Dr. Z'' (the name under which it was lampooned on ''Mystery Science Theater 3000''). The film follows a Nazi [[mad scientist]] who injects himself with a formula that turns him into a mutated catfish. ''[[Florida Times-Union]]'' critic Matt Soergel quipped that ''Zaat'' \"could very well be the best film ever made about a mutated catfish\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://jacksonville.com/tu-online/stories/061201/enm_zaat.html|title=Locally made sci-fi thriller is all 'Zaat' and then some|date=2001-06-12|accessdate=2013-09-30}}</ref> Critic Jeffrey Kauffman said, \"this is the sort of film Ed Wood, Jr. might have made\u2014on a bad day\" and added, \"Lovers of fantastically bad films rate ''Zaat'' one of the worst\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blu-ray.com/movies/Zaat-Blu-ray/35923/#Review|title=Zaat Blu Ray|date=2012-02-21|last=Kauffman|first=Jeffrey |accessdate=2013-09-30}}</ref> Patrick Naugle of [[DVD Verdict]] stated, \"The acting in ''Zaat'' is below subpar. Actors seem to be whispering their lines and trying hard not to fully comprehend that they're in one of the worst films ever made\", while Michael Rubino of DVD Verdict also claimed, \"''Zaat'' may be one of the worst films ever created\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://dvdverdict.com/printer/zaatbluray.php|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131002180849/https://dvdverdict.com/printer/zaatbluray.php|url-status=dead|archive-date=2013-10-02|title=DVD Verdict Review \u2013 Zaat (Blu Ray)|date=2012-02-12|last=Naugle|first=Patrick|work=[[DVD Verdict]]|accessdate=2013-09-30}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://dvdverdict.com/reviews/mst3kxvii.php |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100225160816/https://dvdverdict.com/reviews/mst3kxvii.php |url-status=dead |archive-date=2010-02-25 |title=DVD Verdict Review \u2013 Mystery Science Theater 3000 |date=2010-02-22 |last=Rubino |first=Michael |work=[[DVD Verdict]] |accessdate=2013-09-30 }}</ref> [[NPR]] called it a \"sci-fi fiasco\" when it became \"the winner \u2014 er, loser \u2014\" on IMDb's Bottom 100.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=101056819|title=10 Reasons Why We Love Making Lists|date=2009-02-24|last=Weeks|first=Linton|work=[[NPR]]|accessdate=2013-09-30}}</ref> ''Zaat'' appeared on ''Mystery Science Theater 3000'', which gave it significant exposure,<ref>{{cite web|author=Sampo, on May 20th, 2010 |url=http://www.mst3kinfo.com/?p=5866 |title=Season 10 Episode Guide! |publisher=MST3Kinfo |date=2010-05-20 |accessdate=2013-12-19}}</ref> and was also featured on [[RedLetterMedia]] show ''Half in the Bag'' where they called it one of their favorite \"[[so bad it's good]]\" films.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://redlettermedia.com/half-in-the-bag-zaat/|title=Half in the Bag:Zaat!|date=2012-04-30|work=[[RedLetterMedia]]|accessdate=2013-09-30}}</ref> ''[[Total Film]]'' included it in their list of the 66 worst films of all time.<ref name=TotalFilm/>\n\n=== ''An American Hippie in Israel'' (1972) ===\n\nThe Israeli ''[[An American Hippie in Israel]]'' is about an American hippie traveling to [[Israel]] after being involved with the [[Vietnam War]], befriending Israeli flower children, and encountering \"menacing\" [[Mime artist|mimes]] along the way. The film was presumed [[Lost film|lost]], but after resurfacing 38 years after its production, it became a \"midnight sensation\" in [[Tel Aviv]] and developed a cult following akin to ''[[The Rocky Horror Picture Show]]''. It was then released internationally on home video by [[Grindhouse Releasing]]. Gil Shefler of ''[[The Jewish Daily Forward]]'' described it as \"perfectly awful\", offering that it \"probably is the worst Israeli movie ever made, and a serious candidate for the worst movie of all time\".<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=[[The Jewish Daily Forward]] |url=http://forward.com/articles/134946/finding-new-life-as-a-cult-classic/ |date=January 26, 2011 |last=Shefler |first=Gil |accessdate=August 14, 2013 |title=Finding New Life As a Cult Classic}}</ref> Ben Hartman of ''[[The Jerusalem Post]]'' stated the film was \"surely one of the worst films ever made in Israel, or beyond\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.jpost.com/Arts-and-Culture/Entertainment/Horrendous-Israeli-70s-film-becomes-a-cult-favorite |date=January 9, 2011 |last=Harman|first=Ben|work=[[The Jerusalem Post]] |accessdate=August 29, 2013 |title= 'Horrendous' Israeli '70s film becomes a cult favorite}}</ref> ''[[Nana 10]]'' said it claims the title of \"worst Israeli film and most amusing\".<ref>{{in lang|he}} [http://news.nana10.co.il/Article/?ArticleID=766710 News article from Nana 10] (Last accessed August 26, 2013).</ref>\n\n=== ''Bat Pussy'' (unknown, possibly 1973) ===\n\nA loose spoof of the 1966 ''[[Batman (TV series)|Batman]]'' television series cited as one of the earliest examples of a [[pornographic parody film]], the presumably-1970s [[pornographic film]] ''[[Bat Pussy]]'' has been \"widely described\" as the worst pornographic film ever made, on account of \"some incredibly unarousing sex and a general attitude of awfulness\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/men/the-filter/11395280/The-rise-of-parody-porn-the-Chaucer-of-our-times.html |title=The rise of parody porn, 'the Chaucer of our times' |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |author=Merz, Theo |date=February 23, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"BP73io9\">{{cite web |url=http://io9.gizmodo.com/5914178/the-bizarre-history-of-superhero-porn-nsfw |title=The Bizarre History of Superhero Porn [NSFW] |author=Anders, Charlie Jane |date=May 30, 2012 |publisher=[[io9]]}}</ref> Possessing no credits or copyright information, there is no known record of ''Bat Pussy''{{'}}s existence prior to the mid-1990s, when it was discovered in the storeroom of an adult movie theater in [[Memphis, Tennessee]], and subsequently released on home video by [[exploitation film]] distributor [[Something Weird Video]]. [[Gawker Media]]{{'}}s [[io9]] proclaimed the film to be \"the absolute nadir of pornography, period. Not just Batman-themed pornography. ALL pornography\", deriding its \"obese redneck\" cast as rendering the film \"[[masturbation|wank]]-proof\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://io9.gizmodo.com/5545416/a-brief-history-of-batman-themed-pornography-nsfw |title=A brief history of Batman-themed pornography (NSFW) |publisher=[[io9]] |author=Lamar, Cyriaque |date=May 22, 2010}}</ref> ''PornParody.com'', a website dedicated to pornographic parody films, acknowledged its status as \"the worst adult movie of all time\", describing ''Bat Pussy'' as \"renowned for its technical ineptness and anti-eroticism\" due to its \"physically unappealing\" actors.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://pornparody.com/2014/10/bat-pussy-the-first-superhero-porn-parody/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141008174205/http://pornparody.com/2014/10/bat-pussy-the-first-superhero-porn-parody/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=October 8, 2014 |title=Bat Pussy \u2013 the first superhero porn parody? |date=October 6, 2014 |publisher=PornParody.com}}</ref> ''AV Maniacs'' contested ''Bat Pussy''{{'}}s categorization as pornography on the grounds of the lead actor's visible [[erectile dysfunction|impotence]] and instead labeled the film \"anti-porn\", asking \"How else do you categorize an adult film that completely and utterly fails to elicit even the minutest amount of arousal in its viewers?\"<ref name=\"BPAVClub\">{{cite web |url=http://avmaniacs.com/features/bat_pussy.html |title=Deep Inside Bat Pussy |author=Allison, Matthew |publisher=AV Maniacs}}</ref> The book ''The Many More Lives of Batman'' by [[William Uricchio]] and [[Will Brooker]] also labeled ''Bat Pussy'' \"the worst porn film ever made\", criticizing its poor adaptation of the source material,<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0hZ5CgAAQBAJ&pg=PA115&dq=%22Bat+Pussy%22#v=onepage&q=%22Bat%20Pussy%22 |title=The Many More Lives of Batman |author1=Pearson, Rebecca |author2=Brooker, Will |author3=Uriccho, William |date=2015 |isbn=978-1844577644 |publisher=[[British Film Institute]]}}</ref> while Tim Lewis, the general manager of Something Weird Video, selected ''Bat Pussy'' as the one film \"so nuts it has to be seen to be believed\" out of the company's entire catalog, saying it was \"only for the truly jaded adult film viewer\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://atomiclegdropzine.wordpress.com/2014/03/04/something-weird-video/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140727143331/https://atomiclegdropzine.wordpress.com/2014/03/04/something-weird-video/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=July 27, 2014 |title=Something Weird Video |date=March 4, 2014 |publisher=The Atomic Leg Drop Zine!}}</ref>\n\n=== ''At Long Last Love'' (theatrical version, 1975) ===\n\n''[[At Long Last Love]]'' was renowned director [[Peter Bogdanovich]]'s musical homage to great 1930s Hollywood musicals. It features songs by [[Cole Porter]] and stars [[Cybill Shepherd]] and [[Burt Reynolds]]. Upon release, it received very negative reviews. [[CNN]] noted it was once considered \"the worst musical extravaganza in Hollywood history\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2013/07/10/showbiz/movies/big-bombs-revisited|title=Picking up the pieces on Hollywood's biggest bombs|date=2013-07-11|accessdate=2013-08-23|work=CNN}}</ref> ''[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]]'' film critic [[John Simon (critic)|John Simon]] said, \"it may be the worst movie musical of this \u2013 or any \u2013 decade\".<ref name=PictureShows>{{cite book | last =Yule | first =Andrew | title =Picture shows: the life and films of Peter Bogdanovich | publisher =[[Hal Leonard Corporation]] | year =1992 | location = | page =[https://archive.org/details/pictureshowslife00yule/page/90 90] | isbn =0-87910-153-9 | url =https://archive.org/details/pictureshowslife00yule/page/90 }}</ref> ''[[Buffalo News]]'' film critic Jeff Simon wrote, \"About 45 minutes in, it became apparent to one and all that this was one of the worst and most embarrassing major-talent turkeys of all time.\"<ref name=\"BufNews\">{{cite news |title=Wisecrack Addicts Laughing at the Not-So-Bad |url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=BN&p_theme=bn&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EAF994638769706&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D |newspaper= [[The Buffalo News]] |date= May 24, 1996| author =Simon, Jeff }}</ref> Film critic [[Jay Cocks]] has said the film was \"regarded as the great [[white elephant]] catastrophe of its time\".<ref name=SinginANewTune>{{cite book | last =Muir | first =John Kenneth | title =Singing a new tune:the rebirth of the modern film musical, from Evita to De-lovely and beyond | publisher =[[Hal Leonard Corporation]] | year =2005 | location = | page =[https://archive.org/details/singingnewtunere0000muir/page/58 58] | isbn =1-55783-610-8 | url =https://archive.org/details/singingnewtunere0000muir/page/58 }}</ref> [[Hollis Alpert]] stated, \"This failure is so dismal that it goes beyond failure.\"<ref>{{cite book | last =Tookey | first =Christopher | title =Named and Shamed: The World's Worst and Wittiest Movie Reviews from Affleck to Zeta-Jones | publisher =Troubador Publishing | year =2010 | location = | page =34 | isbn =978-1-84876-560-3}}</ref> It was included in the book ''The Fifty Worst Films of All Time'' and Michael Sauter's book ''The Worst Films of All Time''.<ref name=50worst>{{cite book | last =Medved | first =Harry | title =The fifty worst films of all time: (and how they got that way) | publisher =[[Popular Library]] | year =1978 | location = | page =37 | isbn =0-445-04139-0}}</ref> It is also included in the ''Golden Turkey Awards Nominees and Winners, the Worst Achievements in Hollywood History''.<ref name=Goldenturkeys>{{cite book | last =Medved | first =Michael | title =The Golden Turkey Awards | publisher =[[G. P. Putnam's Sons]] | year =1980 | location = | page =209 | isbn =0-399-50463-X| title-link =The Golden Turkey Awards }}</ref> Bogdanovich, who was also the screenwriter, sent press releases to newspapers across the country apologizing for this film.<ref name=SinginANewTune/>\n\nOne defender of the film was Roger Ebert, who stated, \"The movie's no masterpiece, but I can't account for the viciousness of some of the critical attacks against it.\" He continued, \"It's a light, silly, impeccably stylish entertainment ... if [Bogdanovich] doesn't go spectacularly right, at least he provides small pleasures and great music.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Sobczynski |first=Peter |url=https://rogerebert.com/reviews/at-long-last-love-1975 |title=At Long Last Love Movie Review (1975) |publisher=Roger Ebert |date=1975-01-01 |accessdate=2014-03-05}}</ref> In a recent documentary on his career, Bogdanovich lamented being influenced by studio previews to cut the film before its theatrical release. He subsequently recut it again before it debuted on [[cable TV]] the next year. A fan of the film, a studio editor who preferred the director's first cut, secretly saved that original version and quietly put it in place of the others. When news of this version streaming on [[Netflix]] reached Bogdanovich, he contacted Fox and made a few finishing touches, resulting in a critically acclaimed director's cut that debuted on [[home video]] in 2013.<ref>{{cite web|last=McWeeny |first=Drew |url=http://www.hitfix.com/blogs/motion-captured/posts/peter-bogdanovich-screens-new-cut-of-at-long-last-love-and-tells-story-behind-it |title=Peter Bogdanovich screens new cut of At Long Last Love and tells story behind it |work=Hitfix.com |date=2012-01-09 |accessdate=2014-03-05}}</ref>\n\n=== ''HaMal'ach Haya Satan'' (''The Angel Was a Devil'') (1976) ===\n\n''The Angel Was a Devil'' (filmed in 1971, released in 1976) is an Israeli [[horror film]] about a young woman fleeing a murderer<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mubi.com/films/the-angel-was-a-devil|website=MUBI|title=The Angel Was a Devil|access-date=4 May 2019}}</ref> that has been described by Meir Schnitzer, a leading authority on [[Israel]]i [[Film|cinema]] and by others, as \"the worst film ever made in Israel.\"<ref name=haaretz>{{cite newspaper|first=Nirit|last=Anderman|url=http://www.haaretz.co.il/gallery/television/1.1522771 |title=\u05d1\u05de\u05d0\u05d9 \"\u05d4\u05e1\u05e8\u05d8 \u05d4\u05d9\u05e9\u05e8\u05d0\u05dc\u05d9 \u05d4\u05d2\u05e8\u05d5\u05e2 \u05d1\u05d9\u05d5\u05ea\u05e8\" \u05d3\u05d5\u05e8\u05e9 \u05db\u05d1\u05d5\u05d3|trans-title=Director of the \"worst Israeli film\" demands respect|newspaper=[[Haaretz]]|date=14 October 2011|access-date=4 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|journal=Moznayim|volume=70|page=62|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=g0k_AQAAIAAJ|via=[[Google Books]]|quote=\u05e1\u05d9\u05e4\u05d5\u05e8 \u05e2\u05dd \u05de\u05d5\u05e1\u05e8 \u05d4\u05e9\u05db\u05dc: \u05d0\u05dc \u05e0\u05d7\u05e6\u05f3\u05d4 \u05e9\u05de\u05e8, \u05de\u05d6\u05db\u05d9\u05e8 \u05e7\u05d9\u05d1\u05d5\u05e5 \u05f3\u05e2\u05d9\u05df \u05e0\u05d9\u05e6\u05e0\u05d9\u05dd\u05f3 \u05e9\u05d1\u05e0\u05d2\u05d1, \u05d4\u05d2\u05d9\u05e2 \u05d1\u05d0\u05d5\u05e4\u05df \u05de\u05d7\u05ea\u05e8\u05ea\u05d9 \u05d4\u05de\u05d9\u05d3\u05e2 \u05e2\u05dc \u05d4\u05d4\u05db\u05ea\u05e8\u05d4 \u05d4\u05e4\u05d5\u05de\u05d1\u05d9\u05ea \u05e9\u05dc \u05d4\u05e1\u05e8\u05d8 \u05d4\u05d9\u05e9\u05e8\u05d0\u05dc\u05d9 \u05d4\u05d2\u05e8\u05d5\u05e2 \u05d1\u05d9\u05d5\u05ea\u05e8 \u05d1\u05db\u05dc \u05d4\u05d6\u05de\u05e0\u05d9\u05dd, \u05f4\u05d4\u05de\u05dc\u05d0\u05da \u05d4\u05d9\u05d4 \u05e9\u05d8\u05df\u05f4 \u05e9\u05dc \u05de\u05e9\u05d4 \u05d2\u05d6, \u05d5\u05e2\u05dc \u05d4\u05d4\u05e7\u05e8\u05e0\u05d4 \u05d4\u05d7\u05d2\u05d9\u05d2\u05d9\u05ea \u05d4\u05d7\u05d3\u05be\u05e4\u05e2\u05de\u05d9\u05ea \u05e9\u05ea\u05d9\u05e2\u05e8\u05da \u05dc\u05d5 \u05d1\u05e1\u05d9\u05e0\u05de\u05d8\u05d9\u05e7 \u05ea\u05dc \u05d0\u05d1\u05d9\u05d1.|access-date=4 May 2019|year=1995|script-title=he:\u05d4\u05e1\u05e8\u05d8 \u05d4\u05d9\u05e9\u05e8\u05d0\u05dc\u05d9 \u05d4\u05d2\u05e8\u05d5\u05e2 \u05d1\u05d9\u05d5\u05d7\u05e8 \u05d1\u05db\u05dc \u05d4\u05d6\u05de\u05d2\u05d9\u05dd|trans-title=The worst Israeli film of all times|language=he}}</ref> Moshe Guez was the [[film director]], [[scriptwriter]], [[movie star|star]], [[cinematographer]], recorder, [[film editor|editor]] and the [[composer]] of some of its [[film score|original music]].<ref name=haaretz/><ref>[https://mubi.com/cast/moshe-guez Moshe Guez-MUBI]</ref> Due to the high concentration of crew positions, the production missed out on the subsidy for full-length Israeli movies that is almost automatically given to local productions. The production and distribution were plagued by many additional problems, including impacts of the [[Yom Kippur War]], script and actor changes, and the instant bankruptcy of its final distributor.<ref name=haaretz/> In 2011, Avida Livny released the documentary ''[[Looking for Moshe Guez]]'', describing the film and a search after its director in Israel and the US.<ref name=haaretz/> The creator released a slightly improved digital version of his movie in 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5pJEcXlmTts|website=[[YouTube]]|title=The Angel was a Devil Trailer 277 MP4|accessdate=4 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite newspaper|url=https://www.ynet.co.il/articles/0,7340,L-4781180,00.html|title=\u05e1\u05d9\u05e4\u05d5\u05e8\u05d5 \u05e9\u05dc \u05d4\u05e1\u05e8\u05d8 \u05d4\u05d9\u05e9\u05e8\u05d0\u05dc\u05d9 \u05d4\u05d2\u05e8\u05d5\u05e2 \u05d1\u05d9\u05d5\u05ea\u05e8|trans-title=The story of the worst Israeli film|quote=\"\u05d4\u05de\u05dc\u05d0\u05da \u05d4\u05d9\u05d4 \u05e9\u05d8\u05df\", \u05de\u05d5\u05ea\u05d7\u05df \u05d0\u05d9\u05de\u05d4 \u05d9\u05e9\u05e8\u05d0\u05dc\u05d9 \u05e9\u05e0\u05d5\u05e6\u05e8 \u05dc\u05e4\u05e0\u05d9 40 \u05e9\u05e0\u05d4, \u05d9\u05e8\u05d3 \u05de\u05d4\u05de\u05e1\u05db\u05d9\u05dd \u05d1\u05de\u05d4\u05d9\u05e8\u05d5\u05ea \u05e9\u05d9\u05d0 \u05d5\u05d4\u05d5\u05d2\u05d3\u05e8 \u05db\"\u05e1\u05e8\u05d8 \u05d4\u05d9\u05e9\u05e8\u05d0\u05dc\u05d9 \u05d4\u05d2\u05e8\u05d5\u05e2 \u05d1\u05d9\u05d5\u05ea\u05e8 \u05d1\u05db\u05dc \u05d4\u05d6\u05de\u05e0\u05d9\u05dd\". \u05d0\u05d9\u05da \u05d6\u05db\u05d4 \u05dc\u05ea\u05d5\u05d0\u05e8 \u05d4\u05de\u05e9\u05de\u05d9\u05e5 \u05d5\u05de\u05d4 \u05d2\u05e8\u05dd \u05dc\u05d1\u05de\u05d0\u05d9 \u05de\u05e9\u05d4 \u05d2\u05d6 \u05dc\u05d9\u05e6\u05d5\u05e8 \u05d2\u05e8\u05e1\u05d4 \u05d7\u05d3\u05e9\u05d4 \u05e9\u05ea\u05d5\u05e7\u05e8\u05df \u05d1\u05e7\u05e8\u05d5\u05d1?|newspaper=[[Yediot Ahronot]]|first=Idan|last=Rozen}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timeout.co.il/%d7%97%d7%90%d7%a4%d7%a8%d7%95%d7%95%d7%93-%d7%a1%d7%99%d7%a4%d7%95%d7%a8%d7%9d-%d7%a9%d7%9c-%d7%94%d7%a1%d7%a8%d7%98%d7%99%d7%9d-%d7%94%d7%9b%d7%99-%d7%97%d7%90%d7%a4%d7%a8%d7%99%d7%9d-%d7%91%d7%aa/|title=\u05d7\u05d0\u05e4\u05e8\u05d5\u05d5\u05d3: \u05e1\u05d9\u05e4\u05d5\u05e8\u05dd \u05e9\u05dc \u05d4\u05e1\u05e8\u05d8\u05d9\u05dd \u05d4\u05db\u05d9 \u05d7\u05d0\u05e4\u05e8\u05d9\u05dd \u05d1\u05ea\u05d5\u05dc\u05d3\u05d5\u05ea \u05d4\u05e7\u05d5\u05dc\u05e0\u05d5\u05e2 \u05d4\u05d9\u05e9\u05e8\u05d0\u05dc\u05d9|last=\u05e8\u05d9\u05e0\u05d2\u05dc|first=\u05de\u05d0\u05ea \u05e9\u05d9|date=2016-03-24|website=\u05d8\u05d9\u05d9\u05dd \u05d0\u05d0\u05d5\u05d8|language=he-IL|access-date=2020-02-22}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Exorcist II: The Heretic'' (1977) ===\n\n''[[Exorcist II: The Heretic]]'' is the sequel to [[William Friedkin]]'s [[Academy Award]]-winning [[The Exorcist (film)|1973 film]], directed by [[John Boorman]]. While British film critic [[Mark Kermode]] called the original film his favourite film of all time, he believes the sequel to be the worst film ever made.<ref name=\"guardianworst\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2004/jul/02/1 |title= 'If I'd made that, I'd change my name' |accessdate=2013-12-01 |newspaper=The Guardian}}</ref> The ''Golden Turkey Awards'' named it the second-worst film ever made, after ''Plan 9 from Outer Space''. Critic Bill Chambers stated it was \"Possibly the worst film ever made and surely the worst sequel ever made.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/exorcist_ii_the_heretic/reviews/|title=Exorcist II \u2013 The Heretic Reviews|last=|first=|date=|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango]]|accessdate=April 16, 2019}}</ref> It also appeared in ''[[The Official Razzie Movie Guide: Enjoying the Best of Hollywood's Worst]]'' book. Friedkin believes the sequel diminished the value of the original film and called it \"the worst piece of shit I've ever seen\" and \"a fucking disgrace.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cinemablend.com/news/2464836/original-exorcist-director-says-the-sequel-was-the-worst-movie-hes-ever-seen|title=Original Exorcist Director Says The Sequel Was The Worst Movie He's Ever Seen |publisher=CinemaBlend|date=January 9, 2019|accessdate=January 20, 2019|last=Libbey|first=Dirk}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.blastr.com/2013-4-15/exorcist-director-says-sequel-one-worst-films-ive-ever-seen |title= Exorcist director says sequel is 'one of the worst films I've ever seen' |accessdate=December 1, 2013|date=April 15, 2013 |author=Don Kaye |publisher=[[Blastr]]}}</ref> Eventually, the film garnered so much hate that Boorman disowned it. In an interview with Bob McCabe for the book ''The Exorcist: Out of the Shadows'', he confessed, \"The sin I committed was not giving the audience what it wanted in terms of horror.\"<ref>John Boorman, cited in Bob McCabe, ''The Exorcist: Out of the Shadows'' (Omnibus Press, 1999), p.164</ref>\n\n=== ''The Swarm'' (1978) ===\n\n''[[The Swarm (film)|The Swarm]]'' is a horror film about a [[Africanized bee|killer bee]] invasion of [[Texas]], directed and produced by [[Irwin Allen]]. Despite its all-star cast (including [[Michael Caine]], [[Henry Fonda]], [[Richard Widmark]] and [[Olivia de Havilland]]), it was a box-office failure and was excoriated by reviewers.<ref name=\"ts\">''Halliwell's film and video guide 2002'' edited by John Walker. London. HarperCollins Entertainment, 2001. {{ISBN|0-00-712265-9}} (p. 804).</ref> On its UK release, ''[[The Sunday Times]]'' described ''The Swarm'' as \"simply the worst film ever made\".<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2001/apr/26/artsfeatures2 The worst movie ever?] ''The Guardian'', 26 April 2001. Retrieved 29 March 2014.</ref> [[Leslie Halliwell]] described it as a \"very obvious disaster movie with risible dialogue\".<ref name=\"ts\" /> ''[[The Guardian]]'' article on ''The Swarm'' stated, \"You could pass it all off as a sick joke, except it cost twelve million dollars, twenty-two million bees, and several years of someone's life.\"<ref name=\"ts\" /> [[Barry Took]], reviewing it for ''[[Punch (magazine)|Punch]]'', stated, \"the story is of a banality matched only by the woodenness of the acting\".<ref name=\"ts\" /> ''[[Time Out (magazine)|Time Out]]'' magazine called ''The Swarm'' a \"risibly inadequate disaster movie\".<ref>[https://www.timeout.com/london/film/the-swarm \"The Swarm\"] Retrieved 29 March 2014.</ref> ''The Swarm'' is included in several \"worst movie\" books, including the Medved brothers' ''The Golden Turkey Awards'',<ref>Mikel J. Koven, ''Film, Folklore and Urban Legends''. Scarecrow Press, 2008 {{ISBN|0-8108-6025-2}} (p. 91)</ref> and John Wilson's book ''The Official Razzie Movie Guide'', as one of the 100 Most Enjoyably Bad Movies Ever Made.<ref name=\"Wilson 2005\">{{cite book|last=Wilson|first=John|title=The Official Razzie Movie Guide: Enjoying the Best of Hollywood's Worst |year=2005|publisher=Grand Central Publishing|isbn=0-446-69334-0}}</ref> It soon gained a cult status (enough so that [[Warner Archive]] released the extended version on [[Blu-ray]]).<ref>[https://bloody-disgusting.com/home-video/3517106/warner-archive-releasing-extended-version-1978s-swarm-blu-ray/ Warner Archive Releasing Extended Version of 1978\u2019s \u2018The Swarm\u2019 on Blu-ray-Bloody Disgusting]</ref><ref>[https://addictedtohorrormovies.com/2017/07/14/on-this-day-in-horror-history-the-mind-boggling-the-swarm-hit-theaters/ On This Day in Horror History: The Mind Boggling \u2018The Swarm\u2019 Hit Theaters-Addicted to Horror]</ref>\n\n=== ''I Spit on Your Grave'' (1978) ===\n\n''[[I Spit on Your Grave]]'' became controversial for its graphic violence and lengthy depictions of gang rape. It was initially unable to find a distributor until 1980, when it received a wider release. Luke Y. Thompson of the ''[[New Times LA|New Times]]'' stated, \"Defenders of the film have argued that it's actually pro-woman, due to the fact that the female lead wins in the end, which is sort of like saying that cockfights are pro-rooster because there's always one left standing\".<ref name=\"Spiton\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/i_spit_on_your_grave|title=I Spit on Your Grave (Day of the Woman)|last=|first=|date=|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango]]|accessdate=April 16, 2019}}</ref> Critic David Keyes named it the worst film of the 1980s.<ref name=\"Spiton\"/> Scott Tobias of ''The A.V. Club'' called it \"one of the era's most abhorrent pieces of exploitation trash\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://avclub.com/article/emi-spit-on-your-graveem-2010-53367 |title=I Spit On Your Grave (2010) |author=Scott Tobias |date=March 21, 2011 |newspaper=[[The A.V. Club]]}}</ref> and Patrick Naugle of DVD Verdict stated, \"It's one of the most soulless, vile, and morally reprehensible things I've ever had to sit through.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://dvdverdict.com/reviews/dontmesssister.php |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040426083712/https://dvdverdict.com/reviews/dontmesssister.php |url-status=dead |archive-date=April 26, 2004 |title=Don't Mess With My Sister |author=Patrick Naugle |date=February 15, 2002 |publisher=[[DVD Verdict]] }}</ref> Roger Ebert gave the film no stars, referring to it as \"a vile bag of garbage ... without a shred of artistic distinction,\" adding, \"Attending it was one of the most depressing experiences of my life.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/19800716/REVIEWS/7160301/1023 |title=Review of ''I Spit on Your Grave'' |accessdate=2007-03-20 |author=Roger Ebert|author-link=Roger Ebert |date=July 16, 1980 |newspaper=[[Chicago Sun-Times]] }}</ref> Ebert also included it on his \"most hated\" list<ref name=\"eberthated\"/> and considered it the worst movie ever made.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://beaconnews.suntimes.com/news/2247859-418/ebert-movie-chaz-roger-writer.html |title=Movie, journalism fans queue up to see Ebert |accessdate=2007-03-20 |author=Steve Lord |date=November 7, 2010 |newspaper=[[Chicago Sun-Times]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101111153312/http://beaconnews.suntimes.com/news/2247859-418/ebert-movie-chaz-roger-writer.html |archivedate=November 11, 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Video Q&A |author=Roger Ebert|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=0U9IAAAAIBAJ&sjid=NP0DAAAAIBAJ&pg=2655,5621128&dq=roger+ebert+i+spit+on+your+grave+worst+ever |newspaper=[[The Ledger]] |date=28 May 1998 |accessdate=3 November 2013}}</ref> [[Gene Siskel]] also considered it one of the worst films ever made.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/chicagotribune/doc/175977821.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:AI&type=historic&date=Aug%2017,%201983&author=&pub=Chicago%20Tribune&edition=&startpage=&desc=Tempo |title= 'Man Who Wasn't There' would best be left unseen |accessdate=2013-10-02 |author=Gene Siskel|author-link=Gene Siskel |date=1983-08-17|newspaper=Chicago Tribune }}{{subscription required}}</ref> Author James Livingston wrote in ''The World Turned Inside Out'' that ''I Spit on Your Grave'' was the second worst movie ever made,<ref>James Livingston, ''The World Turned Inside Out: American Thought and Culture at the End of the 20th Century'', Rowman & Littlefield Publishers, 2011, {{ISBN|978-0742535428}}, Page 189.</ref> ''Film Racket'' featured it as their first entry in to their \"Worst Movie Ever?\" series,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://filmracket.com/worst-movie-ever-i-spit-on-your-grave/ |title=Worst Movie Ever? I Spit On Your Grave |author=Pete Croatto |date= May 1, 2013 |publisher=Film Racket}}</ref> and ''Flavorwire'' named it the eleventh worst movie ever made.<ref name=\"Flavorwire\">{{cite web|url=http://flavorwire.com/477608/the-50-worst-movies-ever-made/view-all |title=The 50 Worst Movies Ever Made|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190330132846/https://www.flavorwire.com/477608/the-50-worst-movies-ever-made/view-all|author=Jason Bailey |date= September 17, 2014 |archivedate=March 30, 2019 |work=[[Flavorwire]]}}</ref> Despite the intense negative reception from some critics, the film has a 55% rating on [[Rotten Tomatoes]], with critics arguing that \"It shows us the raw, shocking reality of rape, in all its bloody viciousness.\"<ref name=\"Spiton\"/>\n\n=== ''Caligula'' (1979) ===\n[[File:Caligula8.jpg|thumb|[[Teresa Ann Savoy]] and [[Malcolm McDowell]] appear in ''[[Caligula (film)|Caligula]]'', which was panned for its explicit sex scenes]]\nThe erotic/historical drama ''[[Caligula (film)|Caligula]]'', directed by [[Tinto Brass]], about the infamous [[Caligula|Roman Emperor]] was in part financed by ''[[Penthouse magazine|Penthouse]]'' founder [[Bob Guccione]]. The film, featuring a prestigious cast ([[Malcolm McDowell]], [[Helen Mirren]], [[Peter O'Toole]], and [[John Gielgud]]) is notable for its explicit scenes of sex and violence, including six minutes of hardcore porn footage filmed by Guccione and another editor. ''Caligula'' earned some prerelease controversy after [[Gore Vidal]], who had written the script, distanced himself from the film. When ''Caligula'' was released, it received strongly hostile reviews, reviewers criticizing its extreme scenes of sex and violence and lack of narrative coherence.<ref name=\"ebert19800922\">{{cite news |url=http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/19800922/REVIEWS/9220301/1023 |title=Caligula |newspaper=[[Chicago Sun-Times]] |author=Roger Ebert|author-link=Roger Ebert |date=22 September 1980 |accessdate=7 January 2014}}</ref> [[Rex Reed]] of ''[[New York (magazine)|New York]]'' magazine called the film \"a trough of rotten swill\".<ref>Thomas Vinciguerra, \"[https://nymag.com/nymetro/movies/features/1407/ Porn Again: \"Caligula\" is remastered in all its gross glory]\".</ref> Roger Ebert gave ''Caligula'' a zero stars rating, dubbing it \"sickening, utterly worthless, shameful trash\", accusing it of being artistically vulgar in its depiction of sex and violence, and of having technically incompetent direction and structure.<ref name=\"ebert19800922\"/> ''Caligula'' was one of the few films Ebert ever walked out on (two hours into its 170-minute running time), after describing himself as feeling \"disgusted and unspeakably depressed\",<ref>{{cite news|url=http://blogs.suntimes.com/ebert/2008/10/dont_read_me_first.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081018181430/http://blogs.suntimes.com/ebert/2008/10/dont_read_me_first.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=18 October 2008 |title=Don't read me first! |author=Roger Ebert |date=16 October 2008 |work=blog.suntimes.com |accessdate=9 June 2012 }}</ref> and he also placed it on his \"Most Hated\" list.<ref name=\"eberthated\"/> [[Jay Scott]], reviewing ''Caligula'' for ''[[The Globe and Mail]]'', stated, \"''Caligula'' doesn't really work on any level\" and the film and its production \"constitute a boondoggle of landmark proportions\".<ref>Jay Scott, ''The Globe and Mail'', February 7th, 1980.</ref> So negative was its initial reception, Australian newspaper ''[[The Age]]'' stated that ''Caligula'' was being \"billed by critics everywhere as one of the worst films ever made\".<ref>''News Diary'', ''The Age'' June 8, 1981 (p.2).</ref> Leslie Halliwell dubbed it \"a vile curiosity of interest chiefly to sadomasochists\".<ref>''Photoplay Magazine'', Volume 38, 1987 (p.38)</ref> ''[[The Hamilton Spectator]]'' later referred to ''Caligula'' as \"possibly the worst movie ever made\".<ref>\"Lowest:100 Really Bad Moments in 20th Century Entertainment\". ''The Hamilton Spectator'', July 24, 1999 (p. W17).</ref> Joe Holleman, in an article in the ''[[St. Louis Post-Dispatch]]'' discussing historical films set in Ancient Rome, argued, \"two of the worst movies made in the 20th century were ancient Rome pieces ... ''[[Cleopatra (1963 film)|Cleopatra]]'' and ''Caligula''\".<ref>Joe Holleman, \"Roman Warriors roam the big screen again\". ''St. Louis Post-Dispatch'' May 5th, 2000 (p. E1).</ref> Christopher Armstead, reviewing ''Caligula'' for the website Film Critics United, stated, \"Dollar for dollar, this could very well be the worst movie ever made.\"<ref>[http://filmcriticsunited.com/caligula.html \"Caligula\" by Christopher Armstead] Film Critics United. Retrieved 10 January 2014.</ref>\n\n== 1980s ==\n\n=== ''Heaven's Gate'' (theatrical version, 1980) ===\n\nThe [[Western (genre)|Western]] epic ''[[Heaven's Gate (film)|Heaven's Gate]]'', loosely based on the [[Johnson County War]] in 1890s [[Wyoming]], was plagued by massive cost and time overruns, largely due to director [[Michael Cimino]]'s extreme attention to detail. He demanded 50 takes of at least one scene, and refused to start shooting for another until a cloud he liked rolled across the sky. It cost over $44 million, but brought in only $3.5 million at the box office.<ref>[https://www.cnbc.com/id/38815985?slide=9 \"The 15 Biggest Box Office Bombs -> ''Heaven's Gate'' #8\"]. CNBC. Retrieved 2011-09-07.</ref> The original version ran at nearly four hours, but was yanked from release after only one week due to scathing reviews. It later resurfaced in a 149-minute version, but by then the damage was done. [[Vincent Canby]] called it \"an unqualified disaster\", among other things. Roger Ebert called it \"the most scandalous cinematic waste I've ever seen\".<ref>[[Roger Ebert|Ebert, Roger]] (1981). [http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/19810101/REVIEWS/101010302/1023 \"''Heaven's Gate''\"]. ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]''. Retrieved 2011-09-07.</ref>\n\nAfter word of his grandiose spending and defiant nature toward studio [[United Artists]] got out (detailed in ''Final Cut'' by [[Steven Bach]], a studio executive involved with the film from the beginning).<ref>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/finalcutartmoney00bach|url-access=registration|page=[https://archive.org/details/finalcutartmoney00bach/page/6 6]|quote=heaven's gate april 16 1979.|isbn=9781557043740|title=Final Cut: Art, Money, and Ego in the Making of Heaven's Gate, the Film that Sank United Artists|year=1999|publisher=Newmarket Press|last=Bach|first=Steven}}</ref> Cimino was awarded the 1980 [[Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Director]], and the film was nominated for four more Razzies, including Worst Picture.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://razzies.com/asp/content/XcNewsPlus.asp?cmd=view&articleid=21 |title=Summary of 1981 Razzies |work=Razzies.com |accessdate=2013-12-19 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140116032635/http://razzies.com/asp/content/XcNewsPlus.asp?cmd=view&articleid=21 |archivedate=2014-01-16 }}</ref> In 1999, ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' placed the film on a list of the 100 worst ideas of the 20th century.<ref name=\"worstideas\"/> In February 2010, the readers of ''[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]'' voted it the sixth-worst film of all time.<ref name=\"The 50 Worst Movies Ever\"/> That same year, [[Joe Queenan (author)|Joe Queenan]] of ''[[The Guardian]]'' also called it the worst film ever made, saying that it \"defies belief\".<ref name=\"queenan\"/> Cimino was initially considered a director on the rise after directing ''[[The Deer Hunter]]'' (which won five Oscars, including Best Picture and Best Director), but his reputation never recovered after ''Heaven's Gate''. The production is also notorious for the cruelty to animals that occurred both on screen and on site, including deliberately killing a horse with explosives.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0080855/trivia|title=Heaven's Gate (1980)|work=IMDb|accessdate=1 October 2014}}</ref> The film effectively ended not only the existence of [[United Artists]] as an independent Hollywood studio (its parent firm sold the company to [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer]], where it still operates), but also, largely, Cimino's career \u2014 he would not direct again until 1985's ''[[Year of the Dragon (film)|Year of the Dragon]]''.\n\nDespite the vicious reviews, the film's reputation improved over time.<ref>[https://www.newyorker.com/culture/richard-brody/movie-of-the-week-heavens-gate Movie of the Week: \"Heaven's Gate|The New Yorker]</ref> In fall 2012, the [[New York Film Festival]], the venue for its infamous opening, premiered the restored director's cut. In stark contrast, ''The Times'' (London) called the restored version \"a modern masterpiece\" and its 1980 cut \"one of the greatest injustices of cinematic history\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/arts/film/article3554129.ece |title=Heaven's Gate: box office turkey that sank a studio is a modern masterpiece |newspaper=The Times |date=2012-10-01 |accessdate=2013-11-18}}</ref> The film has also been released on Blu-ray and DVD by the [[Criterion Collection]].<ref>[https://www.criterion.com/films/28036-heaven-s-gate Heaven's Gate (1980)-The Criterion Collection]</ref> Manohla Dargis of ''[[The New York Times]]'' said that the film \"has been called a disaster and a disgrace, yet also anointed a masterpiece.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/03/17/movies/michael-ciminos-heavens-gate-returns-to-film-forum.html|title=The Second Coming of 'Heaven's Gate'|last=Dargis|first=Manohla|date=March 15, 2013|accessdate=June 13, 2013|work=The New York Times}}</ref>\n\n=== ''The Apple'' (1980) ===\n\n''[[The Apple (1980 film)|The Apple]]'' (also called ''Star Rock'') is a 1980 [[Science fiction film|science fiction]] [[Musical film|musical]] [[comedy film]] written and directed by [[Menahem Golan]]. It stars [[Catherine Mary Stewart]] as a young singer named Bibi, who, in a futuristic 1994, signs to an evil label named Boogalow International Music. It deals with themes of conformity versus rebellion, and makes use of [[Bible#Christian Bibles|Biblical allegory]]<ref name = \"Flavorwire2\">Bailey, Jason (10 July 2017). [http://flavorwire.com/607226/bad-movie-night-the-distinctive-disco-cheese-of-the-apple \"Bad Movie Night: The Distinctive Disco Cheese of \u2018The Apple\u2019\"]. ''[[Flavorwire]]''. Retrieved 9 December 2017.</ref> including the tale of [[Adam and Eve]].\n\nOn Rotten Tomatoes, the film has a 20% score based on 10 reviews, with an average rating of 3.99/10.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/1001131-apple/ | title=The Apple (1980) | work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] | publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango Media]] | accessdate=July 7, 2019}}</ref> Common criticism from both reviews that appeared in trade publications and major news outlets and the audience were a lack of originality,<ref name=\"afi\" /> a weak script,<ref name=\"afi\">{{cite web|url=http://www.afi.com/members/catalog/DetailView.aspx?s=&Movie=56362|publisher=[[American Film Institute]]|title=The Apple|accessdate=January 31, 2016}}</ref> uninspired music,<ref name=\"afi\" /> poor execution,<ref name=\"afi\" /> and Golan's inexperienced take on the 1960s hippie movement.<ref name = \"SlashFilm2\"/> At the 1980 [[Montreal World Film Festival]], some watchers threw [[vinyl records]] of music from the film at the screen.<ref name = \"SlashFilm2\">Harris p. [http://www.slashfilm.com/the-apple-oral-history/2/ 2]</ref> ''The Apple'' was nominated for Worst Picture at the [[1980 Stinkers Bad Movie Awards]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://theenvelope.latimes.com/extras/lostmind/year/1980/1980st.htm|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070815004414/http://theenvelope.latimes.com/extras/lostmind/year/1980/1980st.htm|url-status=dead|archive-date=August 15, 2007|title=Past Winners Database|date=August 15, 2007}}</ref> The ballot was revised and re-released in 2006, where the Worst Picture results remained the same. In addition, the film received six more nominations, two of which were wins: Worst Director (Golan) and Least \u201cSpecial\u201d Special Effects.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://theenvelope.latimes.com/extras/lostmind/year/1980/1980st.htm|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070815004414/http://theenvelope.latimes.com/extras/lostmind/year/1980/1980st.htm|url-status=dead|archive-date=August 15, 2007|title=Past Winners Database|date=August 15, 2007}}</ref> Sean Burns in the ''[[Philadelphia Weekly]]'' gave the film a scathing review: \"''The Apple'' isn't just the worst disco musical ever made; it could very well be the worst movie ever made, period.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Summer Camp |first=Sean |last=Burns |newspaper=Philadelphia Weekly |date=July 12, 2006 }}</ref> In 2004, after a poor transfer on VHS that lead years of fans rediscovering it ala midnight screenings at sci-fi conventions while also becoming a staple at film festivals and art houses, the cult film was finally released on DVD.<ref>[http://www.mtv.com/news/1579735/american-idol-executive-producers-secret-flop-the-apple/ 'American Idol' Executive Producer's Secret Flop: 'The Apple' - MTV]</ref>\n\n=== ''Inchon'' (1981) === <!-- This qualifies as a 1981 film, for it made its world premiere a year prior to its general release, a few months before \"Mommie Dearest\". -->\n\nThe [[war film]] ''[[Inchon (film)|Inchon]]'', directed by [[Terence Young (director)|Terence Young]] and starring [[Laurence Olivier]] as General [[Douglas MacArthur]],<ref>[http://www.tcm.com/tcmdb/title/3139/Inchon/ Inchon (1982)-TCM.com]</ref> was meant to depict the [[Battle of Inchon]] during the [[Korean War]]. Producer Mitsuharu Ishii was a senior member of the Japanese branch of the [[Unification Church]], whose leader, [[Sun Myung Moon]],<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wiWctDyWhDI Slate's Bad Movies: Oscar Slumming - Slate on YouTube]</ref> claimed he had the film made to show MacArthur's spirituality and connection to God and the Japanese people.<ref>[[s:U.S. v. Sun Myung Moon 532 F.Supp. 1360 (1982)]]</ref> Its eventual production cost of $46 million resulted in a $5 million box office gross, and ''[[The New York Times]]'' review written by [[Vincent Canby]] calls the movie \"the most expensive B-movie ever\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Inchon (1981) \u2013 'Inchon,' At Last |author=Vincent Canby |url=https://movies.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9A03E0D8123BF934A2575AC0A964948260 |work=The New York Times |date=1982-09-17}}</ref> ''[[The Washington Post]]'' described ''Inchon'' as \"one of the biggest commercial disasters in film history\".<ref>{{cite news | last =The Washington Post staff | title =Terence Young dies \u2013 Directed Bond movies | work =[[The Washington Post]] | page =B6 | publisher =[[The Washington Post Company]] | date =September 9, 1994}}</ref> Every conceivable kind of problem plagued production, including labor issues, the U.S. military withdrawing support due to the film's Unification Church connection, weather and natural disasters, customs difficulties, expensive directorial blunders, and the original director ([[Andrew McLaglen]]) quitting before the start of production. Olivier's performance was criticised, and he was awarded the [[3rd Golden Raspberry Awards|1982 Golden Raspberry award]] for Worst Actor.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.razzies.com/forum/forum_posts.asp?TID=332&PN=3 |title=1982 Razzie Nominees & \"Winners\" \u2013 The Official Razzie Forum |work=Razzies.com |accessdate=2011-01-17 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160820075540/http://www.razzies.com/forum/forum_posts.asp?TID=332&PN=3 |archive-date=2016-08-20 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The film itself took the 1982 Razzies for Worst Picture and Worst Screenplay, and Young's direction earned him a tie for Worst Director of 1982. A number of reviewers at various media outlets described ''Inchon'' as the worst film ever made, including ''The Washington Post'',<ref>{{cite news | last =Mayo | first =Mike | title =Hollywood's untapped resources \u2013 worthwhile movies don't always make it to video | work =[[The Washington Post]] | publisher =[[The Washington Post Company]] | date =April 13, 1997 |page=G7}}</ref> ''Newsweek'',<ref>{{cite news | last =Boedeker | first =Hal | title =The Magic of Olivier his film legacy sets standard for all actors | work =[[The Miami Herald]] | page =36G | date =July 21, 1989 |quote=The worst of his choices was probably taking on the role of Gen. Douglas MacArthur in 1982's Inchon. ''Newsweek'' called Inchon 'the worst movie ever made, a turkey the size of Godzilla.'}}</ref> ''TV Guide'',<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://movies.tvguide.com/inchon/review/102041 |title=Inchon Review |magazine=[[TV Guide]] |date=2012-11-28 |accessdate=2013-11-18}}</ref> and the [[The Canadian Press|Canadian Press]].<ref>{{cite news | last =McKay | first =John ([[Canadian Press]]) | title =Welch fleshes out worst in film | work =The Record (Kitchener, Ontario, Canada) | page =E4 | date =March 23, 2004}}</ref> ''Inchon'' was later profiled in multiple books on worst in film, including ''[[The Hollywood Hall of Shame]]'' by Harry and Michael Medved,<ref>{{cite book |last=Medved |first=Harry |author2=Michael Medved |author2-link=Michael Medved |title=The Hollywood Hall of Shame: The Most Expensive Flops in Movie History |publisher=Perigee Books |location=[[New York City|New York]], [[New York (state)|NY]] |year=1984 |pages=[https://archive.org/details/hollywoodhallofs00medv/page/189 189\u2013197] |isbn=0-399-51060-5 |title-link=The Hollywood Hall of Shame }}</ref> and ''The Worst Movies of All Time'' by Michael Sauter.<ref name=\"sauter\">{{cite book |last=Sauter |first=Michael |title=The Worst Movies of All Time: Or, What Were They Thinking? |publisher=[[Citadel Press]] |year=1999 |page=197 |isbn=0-8065-2078-7}}</ref> To date, ''Inchon'' has never been released on home video in the United States.\n\n=== ''Tarzan, the Ape Man'' (1981) ===\n\nThe [[adventure film]] ''[[Tarzan, the Ape Man (1981 film)|Tarzan, the Ape Man]]'', loosely based on the novel ''[[Tarzan of the Apes]]'' by [[Edgar Rice Burroughs]], stars [[Miles O'Keefe]] in the [[Tarzan|title role]] and [[Bo Derek]] as his partner [[Jane Porter (Tarzan)|Jane Parker]], and is told from Jane's point of view. Despite being a box office success, it was poorly received by critics upon its release, due to its poor screenplay, bad acting, and unintentional humor. [[Leonard Maltin]], writing for his ''[[Movie Guide]]'', stated that the film \"lacks action, humor and charm\", and considered it so bad that it \"nearly forced editors of this book to devise a rating lower than BOMB\".<ref name=\"Maltin01211\"/> [[Leslie Halliwell]] was equally harsh; he described ''Tarzan, the Ape Man'' as \"certainly the worst of the Tarzan movies and possibly the most banal film so far made; even the animals give poor performances\".<ref>Leslie Halliwell, John Walker, ''Halliwell's Film Guide''. HarperPerennial, 1996 (p. 1119).</ref> Writer Thomas S. Hischak described it thus: \"Produced and directed without a shred of talent by [[John Derek]], ''Tarzan, the Ape Man'' often ranks high in the lists of the worst movies ever made.\"<ref>Thomas S. Hischak, ''American Literature on Stage and Screen: 525 Works and Their Adaptations'' McFarland, 2012. {{ISBN|0-7864-9279-1}} (p. 237)</ref> Film critic John Nesbit considered it \"my pick for worst film ever\",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://oldschoolreviews.com/rev_80/tarzan.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140304212347/http://oldschoolreviews.com/rev_80/tarzan.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=2014-03-04 |title=John Derek, Tarzan the Ape Man |publisher=Old School Reviews |accessdate=2014-03-05}}</ref> while Matt Brunson of ''[[Creative Loafing]]'' wrote, \"this cinematic atrocity truly is one of the all-time worsts\".<ref>{{cite web|last=Brunson |first=Matt |url=http://clclt.com/charlotte/view-from-the-couch/Content?oid=2354590 |title=View From The Couch &#124; View from the Couch &#124; Creative Loafing Charlotte |work=Clclt.com |date=2004-06-16 |accessdate=2014-03-05}}</ref> ''Tarzan, the Ape Man'' was nominated for six awards at the [[2nd Golden Raspberry Awards]], winning one for Worst Actress (Bo Derek). It holds an 11% rating on [[Rotten Tomatoes]] based on 19 reviews.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://rottentomatoes.com/m/1020897-tarzan_the_ape_man/|title=Tarzan, the Ape Man|last=|first=|date=|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango]]|accessdate=April 16, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Mommie Dearest'' (1981) ===\n\n''[[Mommie Dearest (film)|Mommie Dearest]]'' was based on the [[Mommie Dearest|memoir of the same name]] by [[Christina Crawford]] about her upbringing by [[Joan Crawford]].<ref>[https://mubi.com/de/films/mommie-dearest MUBI]</ref> It was the first film to sweep the Golden Raspberry Awards nominations, winning a total of five Razzies out of the nine nominations, including \"Worst Picture\" and Worst Actress ([[Faye Dunaway]], shared with Bo Derek).<ref name=SGTW>{{cite book | last =Adams | first =Michael | title =Showgirls, Teen Wolves, and Astro Zombies:A Film Critic's Year-Long Quest to Find the Worst Movie Ever Made | publisher =[[HarperCollins]] | year =2010 | location = | page =188 | isbn =978-0-06-180629-2}}</ref> The same organization also named it \"Worst Picture of the Decade\" in 1989/90, and was nominated for \"Worst Drama of Our First 25 Years\" in 2004/05.<ref name=\"GR1\">{{cite news| url=http://www.razzies.com/asp/content/XcNewsPlus.asp?cmd=view&articleid=12| title=Decade's Worst -The 80's| author=Wilson, John| publisher=[[Golden Raspberry Awards]]| date=March 15, 1990| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130511065558/http://www.razzies.com/asp/content/XcNewsPlus.asp?cmd=view&articleid=12| archivedate=May 11, 2013}}</ref> The film is part of the \"100 most awful\" in the book ''[[The Official Razzie Movie Guide: Enjoying the Best of Hollywood's Worst]]''.<ref name=\"OFMG\">{{cite news | url=https://www.usatoday.com/life/movies/movieawards/2005-02-24-razzies_x.htm| title=Razzies still knocking Hollywood down a peg after 25 years | publisher=[[Associated Press]] / [[USA Today]]| date=February 24, 2005}}</ref><ref name=ORG>{{cite book | last =Wilson | first =John | title =The official Razzie movie guide: enjoying the best of Hollywood's worst | publisher =[[Hachette (publisher)|Hachette]] | year =2005 | location = | pages = | isbn =0-446-69334-0}}</ref> Entertainment writer Michael Sauter included the film in his book ''The Worst Movies of All Time''.<ref name=WMOAT>{{cite book | last =Sauter | first =Michael. | title =The worst movies of all time, or, What were they thinking? | publisher =Carol Publishing | year =1999 | location = | pages = | isbn =0-8065-2078-7}}</ref> It earned, as film critic and television host [[Richard Crouse]] put it, \"some of the nastiest reviews ever\".<ref name=RW>{{cite book | last =Crouse | first =Richard | title =Reel Winners: Movie Award Trivia | publisher =[[Dundurn Group]] | year =2005 | location = | page =[https://archive.org/details/reelwinnersmovie0000crou/page/123 123] | isbn =1-55002-574-0 | url =https://archive.org/details/reelwinnersmovie0000crou/page/123 }}</ref> Eric Henderson of ''[[CBS Minneapolis]]'' named it at the top of his \"Best 'Worst Movies Ever{{'\"}} list.<ref name=\"WCCO\">{{cite news | url=http://minnesota.cbslocal.com/2010/07/21/movie-blog-best-worst-movies-ever/| title=Movie Blog: Best 'Worst Movies Ever' | author=Henderson, Eric | publisher=[[CBS Minneapolis]]| date=June 21, 2010}}</ref> Roger Ebert wrote of this film, \"I can't imagine who would want to subject themselves to this movie. ''Mommie Dearest'' is a painful experience that drones on endlessly, as Joan Crawford's relationship with her daughter, Christina, disintegrates from cruelty through jealousy into pathos.\"<ref>[http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/19810101/REVIEWS/101010346/1023 Mommie Dearest] Roger Ebert, Chicago Sun Times, January 1, 1981</ref> Of the performance of Faye Dunaway, ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' said \"Dunaway does not chew scenery. Dunaway starts neatly at each corner of the set in every scene and swallows it whole, co-stars and all.\"<ref>[https://variety.com/review/VE1117793196.html?categoryid=31&cs=1&p=0] Variety, Jan. 1, 1981</ref>\n\nDespite the reviews at the time,<ref>[https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2017/06/05/joan-crawfords-explosive-offscreen-life Joan Crawford's Explosive Offscreen Life-The New Yorker]</ref> the film was a box office success, grossing $39 million worldwide on a $5 million budget. It has a 50% rating on [[Rotten Tomatoes]]. The site's consensus reads, \"''Mommie Dearest'' certainly doesn't lack for conviction, and neither does Faye Dunaway's legendary performance as a wire-wielding monster; unfortunately, the movie is too campy and undisciplined to transcend guilty pleasure\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/mommie_dearest/|title=Mommie Dearest (1981)|last=|first=|date=|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango]]|access-date=June 26, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== ''D\u00fcnyay\u0131 Kurtaran Adam'' (''The Man Who Saved the World'') (1982) ===\n\nThe Turkish science-fiction adventure ''[[D\u00fcnyay\u0131 Kurtaran Adam]]'' (also commonly known as ''Turkish Star Wars'') was directed by [[\u00c7etin \u0130nan\u00e7]] and starred [[C\u00fcneyt Ark\u0131n]]. It is notorious for illegally using footage from well known science fiction films and shows, most notably ''[[Star Wars]]'', along with stealing the music score from films such as ''[[Moonraker (film)|Moonraker]]'' and ''[[Raiders of the Lost Ark]]''. The film is also criticized for its nonsensical plot, badly written dialogue, and crude special effects.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.austinchronicle.com/gyrobase/Issue/story?oid=oid%3A197912 |title=There Is No Try...: Foleyvision does the Turkish 'Star Wars' Austin Screens |publisher=AustinChronicle.com |date=2004-02-20 |accessdate=2011-01-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://filmthreat.com/reviews/2341/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100312030851/https://filmthreat.com/reviews/2341/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=2010-03-12 |title=The Turkish Star Wars |publisher=Film Threat |date=2005-05-18 |accessdate=2011-01-17 }}</ref> Jos Kirps of [[ArticlesBase]] called it \"The Worst Movie Ever\", and stated, \"There are many bad sci-fi movies, and for many years movie addicts even considered Ed Wood's ''Plan 9 From Outer Space'' the worst movie of all times. But ''Plan 9'' is still a pretty good movie when compared to ''D\u00fcnyayi Kurtaran Adam''.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.contour2002.org/article/the-worst-movie-ever-a-turkish-star-wars-clone|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140810150129/http://www.contour2002.org/article/the-worst-movie-ever-a-turkish-star-wars-clone|url-status=dead|archive-date=10 August 2014|title=Contour2002.org|accessdate=1 October 2014}}</ref> ''[[Sabah (newspaper)|Sabah]]'' called it the \"world's worst film\".<ref>{{in lang|tr}} [http://www.sabah.com.tr/Gunaydin/Magazin/2012/04/15/turkun-uzayla-imtihani-nereye-kadar-surecek News article from Sabah newspaper] (Last accessed August 29, 2013).</ref> ''[[H\u00fcrriyet]]'' described the film as \"sitting on the throne of the king\" when compared to other [[So bad it's good|\"so bad it's good\" cult films]].<ref>{{in lang|tr}} [http://www.hurriyet.com.tr/yazarlar/20291864.asp News article from H\u00fcrriyet] (Last accessed August 29, 2013).</ref> ''[[Toronto Standard]]'' called it a \"dollar-store Star Wars\" and compared it to the works of Ed Wood.<ref>{{cite news|title=Dollar-store Star Wars |publisher= [[Toronto Standard]]|date=2012-05-04|url= http://torontostandard.com/culture/dollar-store-star-wars|accessdate=2013-08-24}}</ref> After a strong worldwide cult developed around the film, a sequel, ''The Son of the Man Who Saved the World'' ([[Turks in Space|''D\u00fcnyay\u0131 Kurtaran Adam'\u0131n O\u011flu'']]), was shot in 2006 and featured many returning members of the original cast and crew.<ref>{{in lang|tr}} [http://www.sabah.com.tr/2006/04/13/gny/gny119-20060413-200.html News article from Sabah newspaper] (Last accessed July 29, 2006).</ref>\n\n=== ''The Lonely Lady'' (1983) ===\nA [[Drama (film and television)|drama film]] directed by [[Peter Sasdy]], adapted from the 1976 novel written by [[Harold Robbins]], ''[[The Lonely Lady]],'' starring [[Pia Zadora]], became a critical and commercial failure and until today is the last adaptation of a Harold Robbins story. [[Roger Ebert]] opened his review saying that \"If ''The Lonely Lady'' had even a shred of style and humor, it could qualify as the worst movie of the year. Unfortunately, it's not that good.\"''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/the-lonely-lady-1983|title=The Lonely Lady Movie Review & Film Summary (1983) {{!}} Roger Ebert|last=Ebert|first=Roger|website=www.rogerebert.com|language=en|access-date=2019-07-18}}</ref>'' [[John J.B. Wilson]] included it in ''[[The Official Razzie Movie Guide]]'' as one of the most enjoyable bad movies ever, saying: \"In rough cut, ''The Lonely Lady'' was one of the funniest bad movies ever made.\"<ref name=\"Wilson 2005\" /> Dennis Schwartz called it \"A true candidate for one of the worst films ever.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://homepages.sover.net/~ozus/lonelylady.html|title=lonelylady|website=homepages.sover.net|access-date=2019-07-18}}</ref> Zadora herself said that ''The Lonely Lady'' was \"a real turkey, done very badly\", that she \"knew it was bad all along\" and that despite being taken seriously by its director it became a \"[[Camp (style)|camp]] classic, one of those movies that's so bad it's funny.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1985-11-19-ca-7761-story.html|title=ZADORA LOOKING FOR CREDIBILITY|date=1985-11-19|website=Los Angeles Times|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-18}}</ref> The film was nominated for eleven [[Golden Raspberry Awards]] (a record at that time until being surpassed by ''[[Showgirls]]'' with 13 nominations) and won six: Worst Actress, Worst Director, Worst Musical Score, Worst Original Song (\"The Way You Do It\"), Worst Picture, and Worst Screenplay. It was the first movie to win more than five Razzies.<ref name=\"Wilson 2005\" /> It was also nominated for a [[Stinkers Bad Movie Awards]] for Worst Picture as well as for a Razzie for Worst Picture of the Decade, but lost to ''[[Mommie Dearest (film)|Mommie Dearest]]'', and for Worst Drama of the Razzies' First 25 Years, but lost to ''[[Battlefield Earth (film)|Battlefield Earth]].'' Zadora's performance in this film and ''[[Butterfly (1982 film)|Butterfly]]'' also led to her being nominated for three special Razzies: Two in 1990, for \"Worst New Star of the Decade\", which she won, and \"Worst Actress of the Decade\", where she lost against [[Bo Derek]], and \"Worst Actress of the Century\" in 2000, where she lost against [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]]. The film has a [[List of films with a 0% rating on Rotten Tomatoes|0% rating at Rotten Tomatoes]], based on 11 reviews.<ref>{{Citation|title=The Lonely Lady (1983)|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/lonely_lady|language=en|access-date=2019-07-18}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Bolero'' (1984) ===\nA 1984 American [[Romance film|romantic]] [[Drama (film and television)|drama film]], ''[[Bolero (1984 film)|Bolero]],'' starring [[Bo Derek]], written and directed by her husband [[John Derek]], became a box-office bomb and a critical failure''. [[TV Guide]]'' says: \"''BOLERO'' must rank as one of the worst major movies ever made. Many awful movies are at least funny in a [[Camp (style)|campy]] sort of way. Bo and John Derek, however, make films so sincerely bad that they offer nothing in the way of relief.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tvguide.com/movies/bolero/117489|title=Bolero {{!}} TV Guide|website=TVGuide.com|language=en|access-date=2019-11-20}}</ref> [[Alan Jones (film critic)|Alan Jones]] of ''[[Radio Times]]'' named it \"One of the funniest bad movies ever made\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.radiotimes.com/film/cjwjx/bolero/|title=Bolero \u2013 review {{!}} cast and crew, movie star rating and where to watch film on TV and online|website=Radio Times|language=en|access-date=2019-11-20}}</ref> Matt Brunson of ''[[Creative Loafing]]'' said: \"I daresay even waterboarding is less punishing than watching this.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://clclt.com/charlotte/ghosts-cant-do-it-everest-the-martian-among-new-home-entertainment-titles/Content?oid=3718575|title=Ghosts Can't Do It, Everest, The Martian among new home entertainment titles|last=Brunson|first=Matt|website=Creative Loafing Charlotte|language=en|access-date=2019-11-20}}</ref> ''[[Fade In (magazine)|Fade In]]'' included it on its list of the \"30 worst vanity projects of all time\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fadeinonline.com/the-30-worst-vanity-projects-of-all-time.html|title=The 30 worst vanity projects of all time|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=}}</ref> It was nominated for nine [[Golden Raspberry Awards]] and won six, including Worst Picture, Worst Actress, Worst Director and Worst Screenplay. It was also nominated for a [[Stinkers Bad Movie Awards]] for Worst Picture, and in 1990, the film was nominated for an additional Razzie award for \"Worst Picture of the Decade.\", but lost to ''Mommy Dearest''. It has a [[List of films with a 0% rating on Rotten Tomatoes|0% rating]] on [[Rotten Tomatoes]], based on 17 reviews.<ref>{{Citation|title=Bolero - Movie Reviews|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/bolero_1984/reviews|language=en|access-date=2019-11-20}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Howard the Duck'' (1986) ===\n\nProduced by [[George Lucas]] and based on the [[Marvel Comics]] [[Howard the Duck|character of the same name]], ''[[Howard the Duck (film)|Howard the Duck]]'' received overwhelmingly negative reviews from film critics. ''[[Orange Coast Magazine]]'' writer Marc Weinberg and Leonard Maltin criticized the decision to shoot the film in live action.<ref>{{cite journal | last = Weinberg | first = Marc | date = 1986 | title = Out-Foxed | journal = [[Orange Coast Magazine]] | volume = 12 | issue = 9 | pages = 143\u2013144 }}</ref><ref name = \"Maltin\">{{cite book | last = Maltin | first = Leonard | title = Leonard Maltin's 2009 Movie Guide | year = 2008 | publisher = Penguin Group | isbn = 978-0-452-28978-9 | page = [https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780452289789/page/641 641] | chapter = H | url = https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780452289789/page/641 }}</ref> Maltin described it as a \"hopeless mess ... a gargantuan production which produces a gargantuan headache\".<ref name = \"Maltin\" /> The appearance of Howard was criticized as being unconvincing due to his poorly functioning mouth, drunkenness, perverted tendencies, and expressionless face. Reviewers also criticized the acting and humor and found the film boring.<ref name = \"Stanley\">{{cite book | last = Stanley | first = John | title = Creature Features: The Science Fiction, Fantasy, and Horror Movie Guide | year = 2000 | publisher = Berkley Boulevard Books | page = 253 | isbn = 0-425-17517-0 | quote = For one, the duck costume and makeup are phony&nbsp;\u2014 Howard looks like a midget in a Halloween costume. }}</ref><ref name = \"Hunter\">{{cite book | last = Hunter | first = Lew | title = Lew Hunter's Screenwriting 434: The Industry's Premier Teacher Reveals the Secrets of the Successful Screenplay | year = 2004 | publisher = Perigee | isbn = 0-399-52986-1 | page = 21 | chapter = Nothing in the Mind, Please | quote = Because we all know what a duck looks like, Lucas could not get an audience to suspend their belief that Howard was a little person in a duck suit. }}</ref> Jay Carr of ''[[The Boston Globe]]'' claimed that \"They Don't Get Much Worse Than ''Howard''{{-\"}},<ref>{{cite news|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/boston/doc/294411402.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Aug%201,%201986&author=Jay%20Carr,%20Globe%20Staff&pub=Boston%20Globe%20%28pre-1997%20Fulltext%29&edition=&startpage=&desc=THEY%20DON%27T%20GET%20MUCH%20WORSE%20THAN%20%27HOWARD%27|title=They Don't Get Much Worse Than 'Howard'|work=[[The Boston Globe]]|accessdate=2013-09-30|first=Jay|last=Carr|date=1986-08-01}}{{subscription required}}</ref> Glenn Heath Jr. of ''[[Slant Magazine]]'' wrote that it \"has a rightful place in the canon of worst films ever\",<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.slantmagazine.com/house/2011/07/summer-of-86-tarred-and-feathered-howard-the-duck/|title= Summer of '86: Tarred and Feathered: Howard the Duck |work=[[Slant Magazine]]|date=2011-07-28|accessdate=2014-03-14}}</ref> and ''[[TV Guide]]'' states it is \"one of the worst big-budget movies ever made\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://movies.tvguide.com/howard-the-duck/review/101469|title= Howard the Duck |work=[[TV Guide]]|accessdate=2014-03-14}}</ref> Film website [[Rotten Tomatoes]] gives the film a score of 15% based on 48 reviews, making it the lowest-rated [[Lucasfilm]] production of those reviewed on the site. The site's consensus states: \"While it has its moments, ''Howard the Duck'' suffers from an uneven tone and mediocre performances.\"<ref name = \"Tomatoes\">{{cite web | url = https://rottentomatoes.com/m/howard_the_duck/ | title = ''Howard the Duck'' (1986) | website = [[Rotten Tomatoes]] | accessdate = March 22, 2019 }}</ref> It received seven [[Golden Raspberry Award]] nominations in 1987 including [[Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Supporting Actor|Worst Supporting Actor]] ([[Tim Robbins]]), [[Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Director|Worst Director]] ([[Willard Huyck]]) and [[Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Original Song|Worst Original Song]] (\"Howard the Duck\"). It won four trophies for [[Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Screenplay|Worst Screenplay]], [[Golden Raspberry Award for Worst New Star|Worst New Star]] (\"the six guys and gals in the duck suit\"), Worst Visual Effects, and [[Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Picture|Worst Picture]], tied with ''[[Under the Cherry Moon]]''.<ref name=\"Razzies\">{{cite web | last = Wilson | first = John | title = 1986 Archive | url = http://www.razzies.com/asp/content/XcNewsPlus.asp?cmd=view&articleid=25 | publisher = [[Golden Raspberry Award]] | accessdate = October 11, 2009 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20130602153152/http://www.razzies.com/asp/content/XcNewsPlus.asp?cmd=view&articleid=25 | archivedate = June 2, 2013 }}</ref> The movie won also a [[Stinkers Bad Movie Awards]] for Worst Picture.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://theenvelope.latimes.com/extras/lostmind/year/1986/1986st.htm|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061017172107/http://theenvelope.latimes.com/extras/lostmind/year/1986/1986st.htm|archivedate=2006-10-17|title=1986 9th Hastings Bad Cinema Society Stinkers Awards|accessdate=April 2, 2013|work=[[Stinkers Bad Movie Awards]]|publisher=[[Los Angeles Times]]}}</ref> ''Howard the Duck'' was also featured in ''[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]''{{'}}s poll of the 50 worst films ever made.<ref name=\"The 50 Worst Movies Ever\"/> The negative reaction to the film took its toll on the cast, who found themselves unable to work on other projects as a result.<ref name=\"Release-2\">{{cite video |people=Thompson, Lea; Jones, Jeffry; Gale, Ed |date=2009 |title=Releasing the Duck |medium=DVD |publisher=Universal Home Video |id=UPC 025195052306}}</ref> Since then, it had become a cult film<ref>[https://www.cinemablend.com/news/2434140/lea-thompson-is-pitching-a-howard-the-duck-movie-to-marvel Lea Thompson Is Pitching A Howard The Duck Movie To Marvel-Cinema Blend]</ref> to the point of a cameo in ''[[Guardians of the Galaxy (film)|Guardians of the Galaxy]]'' played by [[Seth Green]] in that first film.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cinemablend.com/new/Guardians-Galaxy-End-Credits-Sequence-Explained-66562.html|title=Guardians Of The Galaxy End Credits Sequence Explained|last=Eisenberg|first=Eric|date=August 1, 2014|website=CinemaBlend|access-date=April 16, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Ishtar'' (1987) ===\n\n''[[Ishtar (film)|Ishtar]]'' was written and directed by [[Elaine May]] and starred [[Academy Award]]-winning duo [[Warren Beatty]] and [[Dustin Hoffman]] as Rogers and Clarke, two untalented lounge singers who travel to [[Morocco]] in hopes of finding a gig.<ref name=\"brody\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.newyorker.com/culture/richard-brody/movie-of-the-week-ishtar|title=Movie of the Week: \"Ishtar\"|last=Brody|first=Richard|authorlink=Richard Brody|work=[[The New Yorker]]|access-date=February 11, 2019|date=August 6, 2015}}</ref> Due to unanticipated problems with filming in the desert\u2014which resulted in numerous reshoots\u2014the film ran over budget by $30 million. While its final budget cost was $55 million, ''Ishtar'' earned only $14,375,181 at the North American box office leading ''Ishtar'' to become synonymous with \"[[Box office bomb|box office flop]]\". It was also subject to harsh reviews from critics. The film was nominated for Worst Picture and Worst Screenplay in the [[8th Golden Raspberry Awards]], winning one for Worst Director. ''[[San Jose Mercury News]]'' claimed that \"Time has not improved this film's reputation as being one of the worst ever made.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mercurynews.com/movies-dvd/ci_17017300 |title=Review: 'Dinner for Schmucks' a savory comedy |newspaper=[[San Jose Mercury News]]|date=1 May 2011}}</ref> ''[[Time Out (magazine)|Time Out]]'' suggested it was \"so bad it could have been deliberate\", and called it \"one of the worst films ever made\",<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.timeout.com/london/film/ishtar |title=Ishtar |magazine=[[Time Out (magazine)|Time Out]]}}</ref> while ''[[Hot Air (news site)|Hot Air]]'' referred to it as \"The ''[[Citizen Kane]]'' of big-budget, A-list vehicular homicides.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hotair.com/archives/2009/02/22/what-were-the-worst-movies-of-all-time/ |title=What were the worst movies of all time? |first= Ed |last=Morrissey |authorlink= Ed Morrissey|date=February 22, 2009 |publisher=[[Hot Air (news site)|Hot Air]]}}</ref> It was included in Michael Sauter's ''The Worst Movies of All Time'' book<ref name=\"sauter\"/> and [[Richard Roeper]] included it on his list of the 40 worst films he had seen.<ref name=\"RichardRoeper\">Richard Roeper, 10 Sure Signs a Movie Character is Doomed and Other Surprising Movie Lists, New York: Hyperion Books, 2003, pp. 66\u201367</ref> In 1999, ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' placed the film on a list of the 100 worst ideas of the 20th century.<ref name=\"worstideas\">{{cite news|url=http://content.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,991230,00.html |title=The 100 Worst Ideas Of The Century |date=June 14, 1999 |accessdate=April 8, 2018|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |first1=Melissa |last1=August |first2=Harriet |last2=Barovick |first3=Michelle |last3=Derrow |first4=Tam |last4=Gray |first5=Daniel S. |last5=Levy |first6=Lina |last6=Lofaro |first7=David |last7=Spitz |first8=Joel |last8=Stein |first9=Chris |last9=Taylor}}{{subscription required}}</ref>\n\nHowever, the film has since become a cult classic,<ref>[https://www.filminquiry.com/10-movies-low-ratings-actually-good/ 10 Movies With Low Ratings That Are Actually Good-Film Inquiry]</ref><ref>[http://streamline.filmstruck.com/2011/05/24/hearts-and-minds/ Streamline-The Official Filmstruck Blog-An Evening with Elaine May (and ISHTAR)]</ref> and it has also seen a recent minor critical re-evaluation, with some critics, including [[Richard Brody]],<ref name=\"brody\"/> praising the film, and directors [[Quentin Tarantino]], [[Edgar Wright]] and [[Martin Scorsese]] liking it.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://whatculture.com/film/6-guilty-pleasure-films-you-wont-believe-these-famous-directors-enjoy?page=7|title=6 Guilty Pleasure Films You Won't Believe These Famous Directors Enjoy|last=Paciuszko|first=Owain|date=2012-10-19|website=WhatCulture.com|language=en|access-date=2019-01-14}}</ref> [[Joe Queenan (author)|Joe Queenan]] compared the film to another comedy film considered the worst, ''[[Gigli]]'', and wrote that although it was considered one of the worst films ever made at the time of its release, it \"has several comic moments\" and does not get worse on subsequent viewings, unlike ''Gigli''.<ref name=\"queenan\"/>\n\n=== ''Nukie'' (1987) ===\n\n''[[Nukie]]'' is a 1987 South African film directed by Sias Odendaal (credited as Sias Odendal) and Michael Pakleppa, and starring [[Steve Railsback]], Ronald France, and [[Glynis Johns]]. The plot concerns an alien, Nukie, who crash lands on earth and seeks help from two children to reunite with his brother, Miko, who has been captured by the [[United States|U.S.]] government. The film was heavily inspired by [[Steven Spielberg]]'s 1982 film ''[[E.T. the Extra-Terrestrial]]''. Simon Abrams of [[Politico]] wrote that ''Nukie'' was worse than 1988 ''E.T.'' knock-off, ''[[Mac and Me]]'', writing that it is \"probably the most incompetent ''E.T.'' ripoff of any time period ... While ''Mac and Me'' was just rotten and ill-conceived, ''Nukie'' is uniquely perplexing\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.politico.com/states/new-york/albany/story/2011/10/in-the-year-of-spielberg-a-reminder-of-his-most-shameless-imitators-067306|title=In the year of Spielberg, a reminder of his most shameless imitators|last=Abrams|first=Simon|publisher=[[Politico]]|date=October 1, 2011|accessdate=July 8, 2017}}</ref> Critic [[The Cinema Snob|Brad Jones]] has said that ''Nukie'' is the worst film he has ever reviewed.<ref>{{cite web|last = Jones|first = Brad|title = E.T. Week: Nukie|url = http://www.thecinemasnob.com/the-cinema-snob/et-week-nukie|website = TheCinemaSnob|accessdate = July 8, 2017 |date = 2011-02-11}}</ref> ''[[Total Film]]'' named ''Nukie'' the worst kids movie ever made.<ref name=\"kidsmovie\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gamesradar.com/50-worst-kids-movies/|title=50 Worst Kids Movies|last=Winning|first=Joshua|work=[[Total Film]]|publisher=[[GamesRadar]]|date=November 8, 2011|accessdate=July 8, 2017 }}</ref> They also named it one of the worst science-fiction films ever made.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamesradar.com/25-worst-science-fiction-films/|title=25 Worst Science-Fiction Films|last=Winning|first=Joshua|work=[[Total Film]]|publisher=[[GamesRadar]]|date=June 30, 2014|accessdate=July 8, 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Superman IV: The Quest for Peace'' (1987) ===\n\n''[[Superman IV: The Quest for Peace]]'' was the last film in the [[Christopher Reeve]] series of [[Superman in film|Superman]] films, and co-starred [[Mark Pillow]] as the villain Nuclear Man. Despised by fans and critics alike, it is the lowest-grossing film in the series, only taking in $15,681,020 at the North American box office. Many critics pointed out the film's poor screenplay, acting, and special effects (such as a scene in which Superman repairs the [[Great Wall of China]] with his super-vision), while some have criticized it for its lack of attention to the comic book source material. Such special effects led Rita Kempley of ''[[The Washington Post]]'' to call it \"one of the cheesiest movies ever made\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/style/longterm/movies/videos/supermanivthequestforpeacepgkempley_a0ca6d.htm |title='Superman IV: The Quest for Peace' (PG) |work=Washingtonpost.com |date=1987-07-25 |accessdate=2014-03-05}}</ref> Film critic Jeffrey Lyles voiced similar hatred, claiming that the film \"isn't just one of the worst comic book films, it's one of the worst films ever made\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://lylesmoviefiles.com/2013/06/11/review-superman-iv-the-quest-for-peace/ |title=Review: Superman IV \u2013 The Quest for Peace &#124; Jeffrey K. Lyles' Movie Files |work=Lylesmoviefiles.com |date=2013-06-11 |accessdate=2014-03-05}}</ref> ''Superman IV'' holds a 11% rating on [[Rotten Tomatoes]] based on 44 reviews.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://rottentomatoes.com/m/superman_iv_the_quest_for_peace/ |title=Superman IV: The Quest for Peace |website=Rotten Tomatoes |accessdate=2019-07-17}}</ref> It appears on ''[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]'''s list of the 50 worst movies of all time,<ref name=\"The 50 Worst Movies Ever\"/> as well as the MRQE's 50 Worst Movies list.<ref name=\"MRQE50\"/> The film was nominated for two Razzies at the [[8th Golden Raspberry Awards]]: Worst Supporting Actress ([[Mariel Hemingway]]) and Worst Visual Effects.\n\n=== ''The Garbage Pail Kids Movie'' (1987) ===\n\n''[[The Garbage Pail Kids Movie]]'' is a [[live-action]] adaptation of the then-popular [[Garbage Pail Kids|trading card series of the same name]], itself a gross-out parody of the [[Cabbage Patch Kids]] dolls. The title characters are depicted by dwarf actors in low-budget costumes, with poorly functioning mouths and expressionless faces. The film is often criticized for its [[gross-out humor]], nonsensical plot, poor explanations, bad acting, and the unsettling appearance of the Garbage Pail Kids. It has a [[List of films with a 0% rating on Rotten Tomatoes|0% rating]] on [[Rotten Tomatoes]].<ref>{{rotten-tomatoes|id=garbage_pail_kids_movie|title=The Garbage Pail Kids Movie}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film holds a score of 1, making it tied for the lowest scoring film on the site.<ref name=\"Metacritic\"/> Caryn James of ''[[The New York Times]]'' said the movie is \"too repulsive for children or adults of any age\"<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-e8f3vgi-iQ Top 10 Movies So Bad They Were Pulled From Theatres-WatchMojo on YouTube]</ref> and is \"enough to make you believe in strict and faraway boarding schools\".<ref>{{cite news |first=Caryn |last=James |url=https://movies.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9B0DE1D81030F931A1575BC0A961948260 |title=Movie Review \u2013 The Garbage Pail Kids Movie |newspaper=[[New York Times]] |accessdate=6 Jun 2010 |date=1987-08-28}}</ref> Carlos Coto of the ''[[Sun-Sentinel]]'' called it \"one of the worst ever made\".<ref>{{cite news |url =http://articles.sun-sentinel.com/1987-09-05/features/8703110946_1_garbage-pail-kids-cabbage-patch-kids-kids-show |title=Trashy 'Garbage Pail Kids' Has No Value |newspaper=[[Sun-Sentinel]] |accessdate=29 Sep 2010 |date=1987-09-05}}</ref> Much of its content is said to be inappropriate for children, its intended audience. Throughout the movie, the Garbage Pail Kids steal, get in fights, bite toes off people, flatulate in people's faces, threaten others with [[switchblade]]s, urinate upon themselves, and run over cars. In addition to scatological behavior, the movie has several scenes that feature sexual images, violence, and drinking. Offended parents launched a nationwide protest of the movie that successfully resulted in the movie being withdrawn from circulation.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://allmovie.com/work/the-garbage-pail-kids-movie-19217 |title=The Garbage Pail Kids Movie > Overview |publisher=[[AllMovie]] |accessdate=6 Jun 2010}}</ref> The shortened release contributed to the movie's poor gross of only $1,576,615.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=garbagepailkids.htm |title=The Garbage Pail Kids Movie (1987) \u2013 Box Office Mojo |work=Boxofficemojo.com |accessdate=7 March 2011}}</ref> It was nominated for three Razzies at the [[8th Golden Raspberry Awards]]: Worst Visual Effects, Worst New Star for the Garbage Pail Kids collectively, and Worst Original Song.<!-- Doug Walker (\"The Nostalgia Critic\") is a comedian, not a movie critic. Please do NOT use his views. -->\n\n=== ''Leonard Part 6'' (1987) ===\n[[File:Bill cosby 1969.JPG|thumb|upright|[[Bill Cosby]] became the first person to [[List of people who have accepted Golden Raspberry Awards|accept a Golden Raspberry Award]] for ''[[Leonard Part 6]]'', which he said was the worst movie ever made]]\n''[[Leonard Part 6]]'', starring (as well as written and produced by) [[Bill Cosby]], was intended as a parody of spy movies. Leonard Parker, a former [[Central Intelligence Agency|CIA]] spy, is brought out of retirement to save the world from an evil vegetarian who brainwashes animals to kill people. Rita Kempley at ''[[The Washington Post]]'' noted the large number of Coca-Cola product placements and said \"The only good thing about Bill Cosby's ''Leonard Part 6'' is that we didn't have to see Parts 1 through 5.\"<ref name=\"wprk\">{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/style/longterm/movies/videos/leonardpart6pgkempley_a0ca2f.htm|title=Leonard Part 6 (PG)|last=Kempley|first=Rita|date=December 19, 1987|work=Washington Post|accessdate=27 June 2012}}</ref> Scott Weinberg at DVD Talk noted the film as \"truly one of the worst movies you'll ever see ... movies this bad should be handled with Teflon gloves and a pair of tongs\".<ref name=\"weinberglp6\">{{cite web|url=https://www.dvdtalk.com/reviews/15632/leonard-part-6/|title=Leonard Part 6|last=Weinberg|first=Scott|date=April 26, 2005|work=DVD Talk|accessdate=27 June 2012}}</ref> By 1990, Dennis King of ''[[Tulsa World]]'' wrote that the film had \"become synonymous with 'bomb.'\"<ref>{{cite news|last=King|first=Dennis|title=Ghost Dad|date=July 6, 1990|newspaper=[[Tulsa World]]|url=http://www.tulsaworld.com/archives/ghost-dad/article_5b0372e5-e91b-5570-b2c7-c9edabbfae0a.html|accessdate=January 27, 2019}}</ref> ''Total Film'' included ''Leonard Part 6'' on their list of the \"66 Worst Films of all Time\".<ref name=TotalFilm/> Cosby himself disowned the film, and when it was released to theaters he publicly advised people not to see it. It earned [[Golden Raspberry]]s for Worst Actor (Cosby), Worst Picture, and Worst Screenplay. It was also nominated for two more Razzie Awards, for Worst Supporting Actress and Worst Director.<ref name=LATimes>{{cite news|title= Leonard RIP?|newspaper= [[The Los Angeles Times]]|date=1987-12-20|url= https://articles.latimes.com/1987-12-20/entertainment/ca-29856_1_leonard-part|accessdate=2010-12-26|first=Pat H.|last=Broeske}}</ref> Cosby became the first person to [[List of people who have accepted Golden Raspberry Awards|accept a Golden Raspberry Award]],<ref name=\"feran\">{{Cite news | last = Feran | first = Tim | title = Section: Features - Accent & Arts - Intermission | newspaper = [[Columbus Dispatch]] | location = [[Columbus, Ohio]] | page = 01F | publisher = The Dispatch Printing Co. | date = April 26, 1992}}</ref> and said \"It was the worst movie I ever made - the worst movie anyone ever made\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Stars take critics with a grain of salt |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=waFEAAAAIBAJ&sjid=6bUMAAAAIBAJ&pg=1013,2816922&dq=leonard+part+6+worst+ever&hl=en |newspaper=[[The Daily Union]] |date=May 12, 1991 |accessdate=April 1, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Hobgoblins'' (1988) ===\n\n''[[Hobgoblins (film)|Hobgoblins]]'', by [[Rick Sloane]], is widely considered a low-budget [[Mockbuster|knock-off]] that capitalizes on the popularity of the 1984 film ''[[Gremlins]].''<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://brokehorrorfan.com/post/152859915403/blu-ray-review-hobgoblins|title=Blu-ray Review: Hobgoblins|last=DiVincenzo|first=Alex|date=|website=Broke Horror Fan|language=en|access-date=April 16, 2019}}</ref> It gained popularity in 1998 after being featured on an episode of ''[[Mystery Science Theater 3000]]''. ''MST3K'' writer [[Paul Chaplin]] later commented on ''Hobgoblins'', saying, \"Oh, man. You have no idea the torture it was to watch this movie several times in the space of a week. It shoots right to the top of the list of the worst movies we've ever done.\" Specific points of the film that were lampooned was the extreme misogyny and atrocious treatment of women, the film's technical incompetence and repetitive scenes, its moronic, very poorly conceived plot, its dreadful acting, its ugly look and its preference towards rather needless vulgarity, particularly in regards to its characters and subject matter.<ref>[http://www.castleforrester.com/media/guide/0907.htm] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081013042500/http://www.castleforrester.com/media/guide/0907.htm |date=October 13, 2008 }}</ref> Greg Muskewitz at Efilmcritic.com called it \"[[Jim Henson]]'s worst nightmare\",<ref>{{cite web |url=http://efilmcritic.com/review.php?movie=4694&reviewer=172&highlight=hobgoblins |title=Movie Review \u2013 Hobgoblins |publisher=eFilmCritic |date=1987-06-02 |accessdate=2011-01-17}}</ref> while David Cornelius of DVD Talk stated, \"There's not one aspect of this movie that isn't the Worst Thing Ever.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dvdtalk.com/reviews/38236/mad-monster-rally/ |title=Mad Monster Rally : DVD Talk Review of the DVD Video |work=Dvdtalk.com |accessdate=2014-03-05}}</ref> After seeing the ''MST3K'' episode himself, Sloane was inspired to direct [[Hobgoblins 2|a sequel]], which was released in 2009.\n\n=== ''Mac and Me'' (1988) ===\n\n''[[Mac and Me]]'' is about a young boy in a wheelchair who meets and befriends an alien who has crash-landed on Earth. A box office failure,<ref>{{cite news|title=Advertising is so much a part of life that it's understandable to find familiar products in films. But sometimes it goes too far.|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=August 29, 1999|url=https://articles.latimes.com/1999/aug/29/entertainment/ca-4591/3|access-date=May 17, 2012}}</ref> the film grossed $6,424,112 in the United States<ref>{{mojo title|macandme|Mac and Me}}</ref> on a $13 million budget.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://catalog.afi.com/Catalog/MovieDetails/58827|title=Mac and Me|website=[[AFI Catalog of Feature Films]]|access-date=April 27, 2018}}</ref> It has a [[List of films with a 0% rating on Rotten Tomatoes|0% rating]] on [[Rotten Tomatoes]], whose critical consensus notes that it is \"duly infamous\" as both an imitation of ''[[E.T. the Extra-Terrestrial]]'' (1982), and a marketing vehicle for [[McDonald's]] and [[Coca-Cola]]<ref name=\"rottentomatoes1\">{{rotten-tomatoes|id=mac_and_me|title=Mac and Me}}</ref> (the filmmakers had admitted a profit-sharing arrangement with the former).<ref>{{cite news|title= Movie Review Mac and Me Takes a Big McBite Out of E.T.|newspaper=[[The Los Angeles Times]]|url= https://articles.latimes.com/1988-08-15/entertainment/ca-300_1_big-mac|accessdate=2010-12-05}}</ref> One scene features a large, impromptu dance-off with the alien (dressed in a teddy bear costume), a football team, [[Ronald McDonald]], and various other people inside and outside of a McDonald's restaurant. [[Leonard Maltin]] described the film as being \"more like a TV commercial than a movie\",<ref name=\"Maltin01211\"/> and Marjorie Baumgarten of the ''[[Austin Chronicle]]'' called it a \"shameless ''E.T.'' knockoff\".<ref name=\"rottentomatoes1\"/> ''Mac and Me'' is widely regarded as one of the worst films ever made,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://screenrant.com/movies-with-bizarre-weird-source-material/|title=15 Movies With Bizarre Source Material|last=McGranaghan|first=Mike|date=March 21, 2017|website=[[Screen Rant]]|access-date=June 23, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://movieweb.com/mac-and-me-movie-alternate-ending-video/|title=Alternate Mac and Me Ending Unearthed and It's Insane|last=Millican|first=Josh|date=August 8, 2018|work=[[MovieWeb]]|access-date=December 15, 2018}}</ref> with ''[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]'' reporting that it is \"frequently pulled out in 'worst film of all time' arguments\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/films/2016/07/18/top-aliens-in-the-movies/mac-and-me/|title=Top 20 aliens in the movies|date=December 19, 2017|website=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]|access-date=April 27, 2018}}</ref> Filmmaker [[Morgan Spurlock]] (responsible for the 2004 Oscar-nominated ''[[Super Size Me]]'') declared it the \"worst thing you'll ever see in your entire life\", as well as the most egregious example of [[product placement]] in cinema history.<ref name=\"crow\">{{cite news|url=https://movies.yahoo.com/blogs/movie-talk/morgan-spurlock-dubs-mac-worst-movie-ever-sold-060910653.html|date=April 22, 2011|last=Crow|first=Jonathan|work=[[Yahoo! Movies]]|accessdate=August 29, 2013|title=Morgan Spurlock Dubs 'Mac and Me' the Worst Film Ever Sold|url-status=bot: unknown|archiveurl=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20130829025758/https://movies.yahoo.com/blogs/movie-talk/morgan-spurlock-dubs-mac-worst-movie-ever-sold-060910653.html|archivedate=August 29, 2013}}</ref> The film was also named the worst ever in the ''[[San Francisco Chronicle]]'',<ref>{{cite journal|date=January 22, 2017|title=Mac and Me|journal=[[San Francisco Chronicle]]|publisher=[[Hearst Communications]]|quote=McDonald's created an 'E.T.' rip-off called 'Mac and Me' in 1988... It's the worst movie ever made.}}</ref> as well as by broadcaster [[Simon Mayo]]<ref name=\"mayo\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p03slrls|title=Paul Rudd and Chris Evans interviewed by Simon Mayo|date=April 29, 2016|publisher=[[BBC Radio 5 Live]]|access-date=April 27, 2018|time=10 minutes|quote=''Mac and Me''... we're talking about the worst film ever made.}}</ref> and writer/producer [[Damon Lindelof]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gq.com/story/damon-lindelof-paul-alien-comedy|title=Damon Lindelof's Open Letter to Paul the Alien|last=Lindelof|first=Damon|authorlink=Damon Lindelof|date=March 14, 2011|website=[[GQ]]|access-date=April 27, 2018}}</ref> Michael Hayden of ''[[GQ (Indian edition)|GQ India]]'' referred to it as \"hands down the worst family movie in Hollywood history\".<ref name=\"gqindia\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gqindia.com/content/6-best-bad-films/#s-cust0|title=The 6 best bad films|last=Hayden|first=Michael|date=November 10, 2011|website=[[GQ (Indian edition)|GQ India]]|access-date=May 11, 2018}}</ref> The film was nominated for four Razzie Awards including Worst Picture and Worst Screenplay, and won two trophies: Worst Director for [[Stewart Raffill]] (tied with [[Blake Edwards]] for ''[[Sunset (1988 film)|Sunset]]'') and Worst New Star for Ronald McDonald in a cameo. ''Mac and Me'' has however [[Mac and Me#Legacy|gained a cult following]] and was featured on the second season of the ''[[Mystery Science Theater 3000]]'' revival (the only Razzie-winning film ever to be riffed in the history of the show).<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thrillist.com/entertainment/nation/mcdonalds-mac-and-me-paul-rudd-movie-et-spinoff|title=How McDonald's Bizarre 'E.T.' Knockoff Got Made|last=Patches|first=Matt|date=2017-04-03|publisher=[[Thrillist]]|access-date=2017-12-11}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://nerdist.com/mac-and-me-bottleneck-gallery-figure-pins/|title=Mac and Me Finally (?) Gets Figure and Pin Collection|last=McNally|first=Victoria|date=April 24, 2017|publisher=[[Nerdist Industries|Nerdist]]|access-date=May 11, 2018}}</ref><ref>[https://uproxx.com/tv/mystery-science-theater-3000-mac-and-me-season-2/ \u2018Mystery Science Theater 3000\u2019 Will Tackle \u2018Mac And Me\u2019 In Season 2 - UPROXX]</ref>\n\n=== ''Things'' (1989) ===\n\n''Things'', a Canadian [[low budget]], [[independent film|independent]], horror [[exploitation film]], was written and produced by Andrew Jordan & Barry J. Gillis. It cost approximately $35,000 in total to make<ref name=\"CANUX\">{{cite web |url=http://www.canuxploitation.com/review/things.html|title=''Things'' review |publisher=Canuxploitation|accessdate=}}</ref> and marked the [[mainstream]] film debut of [[porn star]] [[Amber Lynn]]. It was ostensibly made as [[Homage (arts)|homage]] to horror icons and films, such as [[George A. Romero]] and his ''[[Night of the Living Dead]]''.<ref name=\"CO1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.critcononline.com/films_on_the_fringe.htm|title=Films on the Fringe: Things (1989)|publisher=Critic Online|accessdate=June 7, 2009}}</ref> ''[[Cinema Sewer]]'' magazine has repeatedly proclaimed that \"this is the worst movie ever made\".<ref name=sew>[http://www.cinemasewer.com/?p=35 \"''Things'' on DVD!!\"], ''[[Cinema Sewer]]'', 12 September 2008</ref> Robin Bougie, its founder and editor, wrote \"I don't mean [\"bad\"] like the way [[Troma Entertainment|Troma]] makes bad movies. I'm talking about bad with the best of intentions, like all of the best \"bad\" movies. You like tormenting yourself with hilariously trashy, moronic, gory, ''idiotic'' bad films? ''Things'' is the fucking ''king'' of bad movies. This is the movie you put on when you have a get together of pals \u2014 and just blow them away. Trust me, you have never seen anything like this in your life. It's absolutely astonishing in how it is able to ''mentally wreck'' anyone who watches it.\"<ref name=sew/> Jeff Kirschner of [[Dread Central]] has also named it the worst movie ever made.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://dreadcentral.com/news/142337/things-worst-movie-ever-made/|title=Things: The Worst Movie Ever Made|author=Jeff Kirschner|date=December 10, 2015|publisher=[[Dread Central]]|accessdate=March 21, 2016}}</ref> ''Things'' was covered in an episode of [[RedLetterMedia]] show ''Half in the Bag''; during the discussion Jay Bauman stated that ''Things'' was \"probably one of the worst movies ever made\", to which Mike Stoklasa replied \"I would remove 'probably'.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://redlettermedia.com/half-in-the-bag-the-conjuring-only-god-forgives-blue-jasmine-and-things/|title=Half in the Bag: The Conjuring, Only God Forgives, Blue Jasmine, and THINGS|date=October 7, 2013|publisher=[[RedLetterMedia]]|accessdate=March 15, 2014}}</ref>\n\n== 1990s ==\n\n=== ''Troll 2'' (1990) ===\n\nDespite its title, ''[[Troll 2]]'' does not feature any trolls (the antagonists are actually goblins) and has no relation to the [[Troll (film)|original film]], which was also poorly reviewed.<ref>Janet Maslin, ''The New York Times'', January 17, 1986; Patricia Smith, ''The Chicago Sun-Times'', January 20, 1986; Alan Carter, ''The New York Daily News'', January 17, 1986; Rex Reed, January 17, 1986</ref> Released in relative obscurity, it was re-taken by the public in later years. [[NPR]] claims that it is \"known as the worst movie of all time\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=105420828 |title=The Beauty Of The 'Best Worst Movie' |work=NPR |accessdate=2009-06-15}}</ref> while ''[[The A.V. Club]]'' calls it \"a popular candidate for the worst film ever made\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://avclub.com/article/ibest-worst-movie-iuncovers-the-heartbreaking-psyc-95807 |title=Best Worst Movie uncovers the heartbreaking psychodrama in a memorably insane B-movie |work=The A.V. Club |accessdate=2013-03-29}}</ref> Rumsey Taylor of ''[[Not Coming to a Theater Near You]]'' opined that it was \"one of the worst films I've ever seen\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.notcoming.com/reviews/troll2/ |title= Troll 2 |work=Not Coming to a Theater Near You |date=2009-03-23}}</ref> Ken Hanke of ''[[Mountain Xpress]]'' gave it one-half star out of five, and stated in his review, \"There are movies that are bad. There are movies that are so-bad-they're-good. And then there's ''Troll 2''\u2014a movie that's so bad that it defies comprehension.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mountainx.com/movies/review/troll_2 |title=Movie Review: Troll 2 &#124; Mountain Xpress |work=mountainx.com |accessdate=2014-03-05}}</ref> In addition, ''[[TV Guide]]'' proclaimed that \"''Troll 2'' is really as bad as they come.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tvguide.com/movies/troll-2/review/129231 |title=Troll 2 Review |work=Tvguide.com |accessdate=2014-03-05}}</ref> Nearly twenty years after its release, the movie's child star, Michael Stephenson, made a documentary about its production and fanbase titled ''[[Best Worst Movie]]'', released to critical success in 2009.\n\n=== ''Highlander 2: The Quickening'' (1991) ===\n\nThe French-British film ''[[Highlander II: The Quickening|Highlander 2: The Quickening]]'' is a sequel to the cult film ''[[Highlander (film)|Highlander]],'' which transitions the [[fantasy]] of the original film into [[science fiction]], and [[retcons]] the mystical warriors of the first film into [[Extraterrestrial life|aliens]]. It was met with harsh criticism by both critics and audiences. Based on 23 reviews collected by [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film holds a [[List of films with a 0% rating on Rotten Tomatoes|0% \"Rotten\" rating]]. Common criticisms included the lack of motivation for the characters, the blatant disregard for established characters and background set forth in the first film (such as the new and seemingly incongruent origin for the Immortals), the massive number of gigantic plot holes, the film's messy, nonsensical story structure, the filmmaker's inability to balance the rather unrelated plots and subplots involved, the unexplained resurrection of Ramirez, and rampantly apparent contradictions in the film's internal logic.<ref>[https://www.ign.com/articles/2000/06/16/highlander-2-renegade-version Highlander 2: Renegade Version-IGN]</ref> Roger Ebert named it the worst film of 1991, stating: \"If there is a planet somewhere whose civilization is based on the worst movies of all time, ''Highlander 2: The Quickening'' deserves a sacred place among their most treasured artifacts.\"<ref>[http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/19911101/REVIEWS/111010305/1023 \"''Highlander II: The Quickening'' review\"], Roger Ebert, ''Chicago Sun-Times'', November 1, 1991</ref> An [[IGN]] review said: \"How bad is this movie? Well, imagine if [[Ed Wood]] were alive today, and someone gave him a multi-million dollar budget. See his imagination running rampant, bringing in aliens from outer space with immensely powerful firearms, immortals who bring each other back to life by calling out their names, epic duels on flying skateboards, and a blatant disregard for anything logical or previously established\u2014now you are starting to get closer to the vision of ''Highlander II''.\"<ref>[http://dvd.ign.com/articles/037/037360p1.html \"Highlander 2: Renegade Version Review\"], IGN, June 16, 2000</ref> \n\nIn 1995, the film's director [[Russell Mulcahy]]<ref>[https://mubi.com/films/highlander-ii-the-quickening Highlander II: The Quickening (1991)-MUBI]</ref>\nmade a [[director's cut]] version known as ''Highlander 2: Renegade Version'' and then later released another version simply known as ''Highlander 2: The Special Edition'' for its 2004 DVD release. The film was reconstructed on both occasions largely from existing material, with certain scenes removed and others added back in, and the entire sequence of events changed. The reconstructed film's reception was far better than the original's; it was elevated to a mixed reception.<ref>{{cite web| url = https://joblo.com/horror-movies/news/highlander-ii-there-can-be-only-four-cuts---part-2| title = Highlander II: There can be only four cuts!| work = JoBlo Movie Network| accessdate = 2013-03-16}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Cattive ragazze (Bad Girls)'' (1992) ===\n\nThe [[Italian language|Italian]] erotic thriller ''[[Cattive ragazze]] (Bad Girls)'' was directed by gossip columnist [[Marina Ripa di Meana]], and stars [[Eva Grimaldi]] as a recently divorced woman falling in love with a male stripper, alongside a cast of big names such as [[Anita Ekberg]] and [[Burt Young]]. The production received bad publicity, as it was made using money from the country's [[Ministry of Cultural Heritage and Activities (Italy)|Ministry of Cultural Heritage and Activities]]. Paolo Mereghetti in his film encyclopedia ''Dizionario dei Film'' described the film as a \"vapid mess that can only serve those incapable of understanding what cinema is\", and considered it able to \"compete for the title of worst film in cinema history and win!\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.mymovies.it/dizionario/recensione.asp?id=4831 | title=Cattive ragazze MYMovies \u2013 Morandini |journal=MyMovies |giorno= |year= |access-date=2014-07-29}}</ref> G. Giraud wrote in ''Il Lavoro'' that ''Cattive ragazze'' \"does not resemble anything in a real movie, or even recall anything previously seen at the cinema, even in its worst\". Film critic Marco Giusti refers to it as \"one of the pillars of Italian trash cinema\".<ref name=stracult>{{cite book|last=Marco Giusti|title=Dizionario dei film italiani stracult|year=1999|publisher=Sperling & Kupfer|isbn=8820029197}}</ref> While ''Cattive ragazze'' was Ripa Di Meana's directorial debut, she never made another film.<ref>{{cite web |title=Marina Ripa di Meana filmography |work=imdb.com |url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0224079/ |accessdate=2014-07-29}}</ref>\n\n=== ''North'' (1994) ===\nThe [[Rob Reiner]] film ''[[North (1994 film)|North]]'' is an adaptation of the novel ''North: The Tale of a 9-Year-Old Boy Who Becomes a Free Agent and Travels the World in Search of the Perfect Parents'' by [[Alan Zweibel]], who also wrote the screenplay and has a minor role in the film. ''North'', which was also [[Scarlett Johansson]]'s film debut, was a critical and commercial failure, earning only $7,138,449 worldwide despite its budget of over $40 million. It was widely criticized for its plot, its all-star cast of insensitive characters, lack of humor and portrayal of numerous ethnic stereotypes. It has a 14% approval rating at [[Rotten Tomatoes]].<ref>{{cite web |title=North Movie Reviews, Pictures \u2013 Rotten Tomatoes |work=Rottentomatoes.com |url=https://rottentomatoes.com/m/north/ |accessdate=2011-03-07}}</ref> Roger Ebert gave it zero stars and, in his review, infamously wrote \"I hated this movie. Hated, hated, hated, hated, ''hated'' this movie. Hated it. Hated every simpering stupid vacant audience-insulting moment of it. Hated the sensibility that thought anyone would like it. Hated the implied insult to the audience by its belief that anyone would be entertained by it.\" He continued saying \"''North'' is a bad film \u2013 one of the worst movies ever made\",<ref>{{cite news| url=http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/19940722/REVIEWS/407220302/1023 | work=Chicago Sun-Times | title=North | date=1994-07-22}}</ref> and it is also on his list of most hated films.<ref name=\"eberthated\"/> Both Ebert and [[Gene Siskel]] named ''North'' as the worst film of 1994.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Official Site of Gene Siskel |work=Cmgww.com |url=http://www.cmgww.com/stars/siskel/screening_room/thumbs_down.htm |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090226070236/http://www.cmgww.com/stars/siskel/screening_room/thumbs_down.htm |url-status=dead |archive-date=2009-02-26 |accessdate=2011-03-07 }}</ref> Mick LaSalle of the ''San Francisco Chronicle'' said in his review that \"''North'' is director Rob Reiner's first flat-out failure, a sincerely wrought, energetically made picture that all the same crashes on takeoff. It's strange and oddly distasteful, at its best managing to be bad in some original and unexpected ways.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/1995/01/06/dd59113.dtl |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20031113141403/http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=%2Fc%2Fa%2F1995%2F01%2F06%2Fdd59113.dtl |url-status=dead |archive-date=2003-11-13 |work=The San Francisco Chronicle |title=Rob Reiner's 'North' Is Distastefully Bad |date=2011-01-08 }}</ref> [[Richard Roeper]] named ''North'' as one of the 40 worst movies he has ever seen, saying that, \"Of all the films on this list, ''North'' may be the most difficult to watch from start to finish.\"<ref name=\"RichardRoeper\" /> The film was nominated for the following awards at the [[15th Golden Raspberry Awards]]: Worst Picture, Worst Actor ([[Bruce Willis]], also for ''[[Color of Night]]''), Worst Supporting Actress ([[Kathy Bates]]), Worst Supporting Actor ([[Dan Aykroyd]], also for ''[[Exit to Eden (film)|Exit to Eden]]''), Worst Director, and Worst Screenplay ([[Andrew Scheinman]] and [[Alan Zweibel]]).\n\n=== ''Dis \u2013 en historie om kj\u00e6rlighet'' (''A Story About Love'') (1995) ===\n\nThe Norwegian [[romantic film]] ''[[A Story About Love|Dis \u2013 en historie om kj\u00e6rlighet]]'' was directed by Aune Sand. The film follows different couples and their love stories around the world, in [[Cairo]], [[Normandy]], [[Oslo]] and [[New York City]]. ''Dis'' received universally poor reviews by critics, and has been called the most poorly reviewed Norwegian film in history.<ref>{{cite news|last=Kristoffersen|first=Marius Vartdal|title=Hva Var I Veien Med Dis?|url=http://znett.com/2011/05/hva-var-i-veien-med-dis/|date=3 May 2011|accessdate=14 July 2014|newspaper=Z Filmtidsskrift|language=Norwegian}}</ref><ref name=\"osloby.no\" /> Critic Harald Kolstad of ''[[Dagsavisen]]'' gave it a score of zero, refused to acknowledge ''Dis'' as a film, and claimed to have never seen anything worse.<ref>{{cite news|last=Pedersen |first=Brent Erik |title=Hedrer Dagsavisens kritiker |url=http://www.dagsavisen.no/kultur/hedrer-dagsavisens-kritiker/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140617125554/http://www.dagsavisen.no/kultur/hedrer-dagsavisens-kritiker/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=17 June 2014 |accessdate=14 July 2014 |newspaper=Dagsavisen |language=Norwegian }}</ref> ''[[Aftenposten]]'' referred to the film as \"the largest turkey\" and \"the most reviled film\",<ref name=\"osloby.no\">{{cite news|title=Norges st\u00f8rste kalkun flyr igjen|url=http://www.osloby.no/article199599_2.ece|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120814005215/http://www.osloby.no/article199599_2.ece|url-status=dead|archive-date=14 August 2012|date=28 June 2012|accessdate=14 July 2014|newspaper=Aftenposten|language=Norwegian}}</ref> and ''[[Total Film]]'' included it on its list of the 66 worst films ever made.<ref name=\"TotalFilm\" /> Despite being a critical disaster it became a commercial success, gaining [[cult film]] status with a following akin to ''[[The Rocky Horror Picture Show]]'', with fans embracing its \"so bad it's good\" qualities.<ref name=\"osloby.no\" /> Director Aune Sand insists that ''Dis'' is a masterpiece.<ref>{{cite news|title= Slakter norsk film|url=http://www.dagbladet.no/kultur/2005/07/20/437937.html|accessdate=14 July 2014|newspaper=Dagbladet|language=Norwegian}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Showgirls'' (1995) ===\n[[File:SHOWGIRLS.png|thumb|''[[Showgirls]]'' holds the record for number of [[Golden Raspberry Award]] nominations]]\nA large amount of hype of ''[[Showgirls]]'' was put behind promoting the sex and nudity in this [[Motion Picture Association of America film rating system#Commercial viability of the NC-17 rating|NC-17]] French-American film with a $45 million budget, but the final result was critically derided. Most of the hype revolved around the film's star, [[Elizabeth Berkley]], who only two years before had been one of the stars of the Saturday morning teen [[situation comedy|sitcom]] ''[[Saved by the Bell]]''. The film won seven [[Golden Raspberry Award|Razzie Awards]], a record at that time, and received 13 nominations, a record that still stands. It received an additional award at the [[20th Golden Raspberry Awards]], where it was awarded Worst Picture of the Decade. Kenneth Turan of the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' called it, \"a film of thunderous oafishness that gives adult subject matter the kind of bad name it does not need or deserve\",<ref>{{cite web|url=https://rottentomatoes.com/m/showgirls/reviews/#page=2&sort=source |title=Showgirls \u2013 Movie Reviews |website=Rotten Tomatoes |accessdate=2014-03-05}}</ref> while Rob Gonsalves of eFilmCritic.com stated, \"Even the grossest porn is more cheerfully sexual than this movie.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.efilmcritic.com/review.php?movie=1247&reviewer=416 |title=Movie Review \u2013 Showgirls |publisher=eFilmCritic |accessdate=2013-11-18}}</ref> Michael Dequina of TheMovieReport.com also criticized the film, claiming that it was \"the best bad filmmaking Hollywood has to offer\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://themoviereport.com/movierpt1.html#showgirls |title=The Movie Report Archive, Volume 1 |work=TheMovieReport.com |accessdate=2013-11-18}}</ref> Stephen Lynch of the ''[[Knight Ridder|Knight Ridder/Tribune]]'' named it the worst movie ever made, calling it \"so bad it may be brilliant\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Critic picks worst movies of all time |author=Stephen Lynch|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=398&dat=20011003&id=oGhOAAAAIBAJ&sjid=vj4DAAAAIBAJ&pg=6912,5443994|newspaper=Bartow Press |date=October 3, 2001 |accessdate=12 June 2014}}</ref> [[Rotten Tomatoes]] selected it as one of 25 movies that are so bad they're unmissable while ''[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]'' featured it on its poll of the worst films ever made.<ref name=\"sobad\"/><ref name=\"The 50 Worst Movies Ever\"/> ''Showgirls'' was also featured in Michael Sauter's ''The Worst Movies of All Time'' book as well as ''[[The Official Razzie Movie Guide: Enjoying the Best of Hollywood's Worst]]''. The edited R-rated version, which director [[Paul Verhoeven]] developed for video outlets that would not carry NC-17 films, deletes about three minutes of the more graphic sex scenes. [[TBS (TV network)|TBS]] has broadcast the film on television in its prime time schedule, but this version adds digitally animated solid black underwear to hide breasts and genitalia. This version has also been broadcast by [[VH1]] as part of its ''Movies That Rock'' series. It holds a 22% rating on [[Rotten Tomatoes]] based on 54 reviews.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://rottentomatoes.com/m/showgirls/ |title=Showgirls |website=Rotten Tomatoes |accessdate=2019-07-06}}</ref> Despite a negative theatrical and critical consensus, ''Showgirls'' enjoyed much bigger success on the [[home video]] market, generated more than $100 million from home video market and became one of [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer|MGM]]'s top 20 all-time bestsellers.<ref>[http://www.rollingstone.com/culture/culture-news/showgirls-paul-verhoeven-on-the-greatest-stripper-movie-ever-made-54740/\u2018Showgirls\u2019: Paul Verhoeven on the Greatest Stripper Movie Ever Made-Rolling Stone]</ref>\n\n=== ''Striptease'' (1996) ===\n\nA comedy-drama directed by [[Andrew Bergman]], based on a [[Strip Tease (novel)|novel]] by [[Carl Hiaasen]], ''[[Striptease (film)|Striptease]]'' centers on a woman ([[Demi Moore]]) who becomes a stripper in order to fund an appeal for custody of her daughter. The film was criticized as boring and humourless, and was also accused of being a vanity project for Moore.<ref name=\"bdj\">Brian D. Johnson, \"A Demi-talented actor bares all\", ''[[Maclean's]]'' 7/08/96, Vol. 109 Issue 28, page 49.</ref> Daniel P. Franklin, discussing ''Striptease'' in his book ''Politics and Film: The Political Culture of Film in the United States'' stated \"This is the worst film ever made.\"<ref>Daniel P. Franklin, ''Politics and Film: The Political Culture of Film in the United States''. Lanham, [[Rowman & Littlefield|Rowman and Littlefield]], 2006, {{ISBN|0742538095}}, (p. 203).</ref> [[Joe Queenan (author)|Joe Queenan]] cited ''Striptease'' as an example of what he considered the poor quality of contemporary Hollywood cinema: \"One thing that I admire about films like ''Striptease'' is that they serve as powerful reminders that on any given day, Hollywood has the potential to release the worst film in history.\"<ref>Joe Queenan, ''Red Lobster, White Trash, and the Blue Lagoon: Joe Queenan's America'' Hyperion Books, 1999 {{ISBN|0786884088}}, (p.50 )</ref> [[Richard Schickel]] in ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'', also criticized the film: \"Bergman ... misses Hiaasen's strength: setting mean-funny characters spinning through lowlife milieus ... the crazy, nothing-to-lose anarchy of people living below the margin and beyond the fringe is not within Bergman's fastidious reach.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Schickel|first=Richard|title=Cinema: Only the Bare Essentials \"Striptease isn't raunchy, but it isn't witty either|url=http://content.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,984828,00.html|date=July 8, 1996|work=Time Magazine|accessdate=June 9, 2014}}</ref> [[Leonard Maltin]] stated that ''Striptease'' was \"Not funny enough, or dramatic enough, or sexy enough, or bad enough, to qualify as entertainment in ''any'' category.\"<ref>Leonard Maltin, ed., ''Leonard Maltin's 2002 Movie & Video Guide''. A Signet Book, 2001, page 1323.</ref> Brian D. Johnson of ''[[Maclean's]]'' stated \"While ''[[Showgirls]]'' was honestly sleazy, ''Striptease'' is tacky, pretentious \u2013 and boring. Trying to be a comedy, a morality tale and a titillating sideshow, ''Striptease'' fails on all counts.\"<ref name=\"bdj\" /> ''Striptease'' was awarded six [[1996 Golden Raspberry Awards|Golden Raspberry]] awards, for Worst Picture, Worst Director, Worst Screenplay, Worst Actress (Moore), Worst Original Song (\"(Pussy Pussy Pussy) Whose Kitty Cat Are You?\"), and Worst Screen Couple (Moore and [[Burt Reynolds]]).<ref>\"Moore, ''Striptease'' get blasted with Razzie for Worst Picture, 5 others\". ''[[Milwaukee Journal Sentinel]]'', March 24, 1997, (p. 66).</ref>\n\n=== ''Le Jour et la Nuit'' (''Day and Night'') (1997) ===\n\nThe French [[romance film]] ''[[Day and Night (1997 film)|Le Jour et la Nuit]]'' was directed by philosopher [[Bernard-Henri L\u00e9vy]]. It follows a French author who fled to Mexico for a quiet life and an actress who is willing to seduce him to get a part in a film adapted from one of his books. Before its release, ''Le Jour et la Nuit'' was heavily promoted in many French newspapers and magazines.<ref name=\"ti\">Jade Lindgaard and Xavier De La Porte, ''The Imposter: BHL in Wonderland'' (Translated by John Howe) London; Verso, 2012. {{ISBN|978-1-84467-748-1}} (p. 48-9).</ref> When the film premiered at the [[Berlin International Film Festival]] in 1997, hundreds of journalists walked out of the screening and those that stayed audibly ridiculed it.<ref name=Plato>{{cite news |last=Dahlburg |first=John-Thor |title=The Film That Plato Didn't Make |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |date=March 28, 1997 |url=https://articles.latimes.com/1997-03-28/entertainment/ca-42798_1_european-film |accessdate=2013-10-14}}</ref> Following its release, ''Le Jour et la Nuit'' was very harshly criticized by the French media. G\u00e9rard Lefort of ''[[Lib\u00e9ration]]'' described the film as \"BHL pedalling through guacamole\", and it was also panned by ''[[Le Monde]]'' and ''[[Le Nouvel Observateur]]''.<ref name=\"ti\" /> The film also did poorly commercially, with only 73,147 seats for ''Le Jour et la Nuit'' having been sold two months after its release.<ref name=\"ti\" /> ''Le Jour et la Nuit'' was considered the worst French film since 1945 by film magazine ''[[Cahiers du cin\u00e9ma]]'', and considered as a possible \"worst film in history\" by the French version of ''[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.slate.fr/story/27925/pire-film-du-monde-bhl-concurrence |title=\"Le Jour et la Nuit\", pire film de l'histoire ... Vraiment? |publisher=Slate.fr |accessdate=2013-12-19}}</ref> ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' said the film was {{nowrap|\"[l]augh}}-out-loud awful without touching the cult realm of 'so bad it's good{{'\"}}, [[Fran\u00e7oise Giroud]] stated that {{nowrap|\"[i]t's}} a bad movie, there's no question\",<ref name=Plato/> and ''[[L'Humanit\u00e9]]'' called it an \"Absolute debacle\".<ref>{{cite news |title=The volcano a molehill |newspaper=[[L'Humanit\u00e9]] |date=February 19, 1997 |url=https://www.humanite.fr/node/154931 |accessdate=2013-10-14}}</ref> An original documentary, ''Anatomy of a Massacre'', was released with the ''Le Jour et la Nuit'' DVD, and focused on its intense negative reception and failure.<ref>{{cite news |title=BHL et la critique cin\u00e9, c'\u00e9tait le jour et la nuit |newspaper=[[20 minutes (France)]] |date=October 11, 2010 |url=http://www.20minutes.fr/medias/607145-media-bhl-critique-cine-jour-nuit |accessdate=2013-10-14}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Batman & Robin'' (1997) ===\n[[File:Btrjpg.jpg|thumb|''[[Batman & Robin (film)|Batman & Robin]]'' was named the worst movie ever made by ''[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]'']]\n''[[Batman & Robin (film)|Batman & Robin]]'' is a [[superhero film]] based on the [[DC Comics|DC]] character [[Batman]] and is the fourth and final installment of the [[Burton/Schumacher Batman film series]]. It is directed by [[Joel Schumacher]] and stars [[George Clooney]] as [[Batman]]/[[Bruce Wayne]], [[Arnold Schwarzenegger]] as [[Mr. Freeze]], [[Uma Thurman]] as [[Poison Ivy (comics)|Poison Ivy]], [[Chris O'Donnell]] as [[Robin (comics)|Robin]]/[[Dick Grayson]], [[Alicia Silverstone]] as [[Batgirl]]/[[Barbara Gordon|Barbara Wilson]] and [[Michael Gough]] as [[Alfred Pennyworth]]. This film was largely criticized for its [[toyetic]] and [[camp (style)|camp]] approach, Mr. Freeze's approach and [[one-line joke]]s, as well as its possible homosexual innuendo. {{as of|2017|June|}}, [[review aggregator]] [[Rotten Tomatoes]] reports that 11% of critics have given the film a positive review based on 89 reviews, certifying it \"Rotten\" with an average rating of 3.7/10, and the critics consensus: \"Joel Schumacher's tongue-in-cheek attitude hits an unbearable limit in ''Batman & Robin'', resulting in a frantic and mindless movie that's too jokey to care much for.\"<ref>{{cite web | url = https://rottentomatoes.com/m/1077027-batman_and_robin/ | title = Batman & Robin | website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] | accessdate = 2019-07-06}}</ref> By comparison [[Metacritic]] collected an average score of 28/100, based on 21 reviews.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://metacritic.com/movie/batman-robin | title = Batman & Robin (1997): Reviews | work=[[Metacritic]] | publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=2010-04-17}}</ref> ''[[International Business Times]]'' included it on its list of Hollywood's top five worst movies ever made.<ref name=\"IBT\"/> [[Michael J. Nelson]], of ''Mystery Science Theater 3000'' fame, wrote of the movie in his book, ''Movie Megacheese'', \"''Batman & Robin'' is not the worst movie ever. No, indeed. It's the worst thing ever. Yes, it's the single worst thing that we as human beings have ever produced in recorded history.\"<ref>{{Cite book | url = https://archive.org/details/mikenelsonsmovie00nels | url-access = registration | page = [https://archive.org/details/mikenelsonsmovie00nels/page/79 79] | title = Mike Nelson's Movie Megacheese | publisher = Harper Collins | isbn = 978-0-380-81467-1 | last1 = Nelson | first1 = Michael J | date = 2000-06-20}}</ref> ''Batman & Robin'' also came in first in an ''[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]'' poll of the 50 worst films ever.<ref name=\"The 50 Worst Movies Ever\"/> Joel Schumacher apologized to disappointed fans on the 2005 DVD release of ''Batman & Robin''.<ref>{{cite AV media | people = Joel Schmacher | title = \"Making of\" Introduction | medium = DVD | publisher = Warner Bros. | year = 2005 }}</ref>\n\n=== ''The Avengers'' (1998) ===\nAn adaptation of the popular 1960s [[The Avengers (TV series)|British series]] of the same name, ''[[The Avengers (1998 film)|The Avengers]]'' starred [[Ralph Fiennes]] as John Steed and [[Uma Thurman]] as [[Emma Peel]], with [[Sean Connery]] as their antagonist, Sir August de Wynter. It was directed by [[Jeremiah S. Chechik]]. ''The Avengers'' began to receive negative publicity after [[Warner Bros.]], the film's distributor, refused to allow any early press-screenings for movie reviewers.<ref>{{cite journal |authorlink=Godfrey Cheshire III |first=Godfrey |last=Cheshire |url=https://variety.com/review/VE1117913229.html?categoryid=31&cs=1 |title=The Avengers \u2013 Sputtering Spies: Steed and Peel Lack Appeal |journal=Variety |date=August 17, 1998 |accessdate=January 27, 2015 }}</ref> After early test screenings, ''The Avengers'' was heavily edited by the studio.<ref name=NYTreview2>{{cite news |first=Janet |last=Maslin |authorlink=Janet Maslin |url=https://www.nytimes.com/library/film/081598avengers-film-review.html |title='The Avengers': Shh! They're Trying Not to Be Noticed |newspaper=The New York Times |date=August 15, 1998 |accessdate=January 27, 2015 }}</ref> On its release, ''The Avengers'' was savaged by film critics, with the ''[[Birmingham Post]]'' stating \"''The Avengers'' is being slated by critics as the worst film ever made\" and adding that one reviewer had joked the film was such a \"turkey\" that the makers should have handed distribution to the poultry chain [[Bernard Matthews Farms|Bernard Matthews]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Film-''The Avengers'' |newspaper=The Birmingham Post |date=August 19, 1998 }}</ref> Several reviewers disparaged ''The Avengers'' for lacking the wit and excitement of its source material.<ref name=rt2>{{cite journal |url=http://www.radiotimes.com/film/cjykx/the-avengers |title=Review: The Avengers |first=Alan |last=Jones |journal=Radio Times |accessdate=27 January 2015 }}</ref><ref name=\"db\">{{cite news |url=http://www.nydailynews.com/archives/entertainment/not-so-excellent-avengers-insults-old-series-awful-film-debases-tv-inspiration-article-1.807212 |title=Not So Excellent Avengers |first=David |last=Bianculli |newspaper=[[New York Daily News]] |date=August 18, 1998 |accessdate=January 27, 2015 }}</ref> [[Janet Maslin]] strongly criticised ''The Avengers'': \"With pseudo-suave repartee that would make [[Austin Powers (character)|Austin Powers]] blush and with so many shades of ''[[Howard the Duck (film)|Howard the Duck]]'' that one scene depicts man-size pastel teddy bears sitting around a conference table, it's a film to gall fans of the old television series and perplex anyone else. I can't remember another Friday morning show where I heard actual cries of \"Ugh!\" on the way out the door\" and finished her review with, \"At a pared-down, barely rational 100 minutes, ''The Avengers'' is short but not short enough.\"<ref name=NYTreview2 /> David Bianculli said \"This ''Avengers'' film is so horrendously, painfully and thoroughly awful, it gives other cinematic clunkers like ''[[Ishtar (film)|Ishtar]]'' and ''Howard the Duck'' a good name.\"<ref name=\"db\" /> Alan Jones in ''[[The Radio Times]]'' stated \"The cult 1960s TV series gets royally shafted by Hollywood in this stunningly designed blockbuster that's stunningly awful in every other department ... Terrible special effects and zero chemistry between Fiennes and Thurman make this notorious disaster a total waste of everyone's time and energy.\"<ref name=rt2 /> ''The Avengers'' also shared a [[Razzie Award]] for \"Worst Remake or Sequel\" with the 1998 adaptations of ''[[Psycho (1998 film)|Psycho]]'' and ''[[Godzilla (1998 film)|Godzilla]]'' at the [[19th Golden Raspberry Awards]]. ''[[Total Film]]'' magazine later voted Fiennes and Thurman in ''The Avengers'' as \"The Worst Movie Double Act Of All Time\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Double disasters make it to top of the flops |newspaper=[[Western Mail (Wales)|The Western Mail]] |location=Cardiff |date=December 1, 2003 }}</ref> The film also appeared on Metacritic's list of the all-time lowest-scoring films.<ref name=\"Metacritic\"/>\n\n=== ''Cinderela Baiana'' (''Bahian Cinderella'') (1998) ===\n\nThe Brazilian film ''[[Cinderela Baiana]]'' was directed by Conrado Sanchez and stars former [[\u00c9 o Tchan!]] dancer [[Carla Perez]] in the lead role. It is a heavily fictionalized biographical account of Perez's early life and how she came into fame. Despite an all-star cast, including [[Alexandre Pires]], Perez's then-boyfriend and a very popular singer in Brazil at the time, the movie was criticized for its campy dialogue, badly written script, numerous plot holes and ludicrous acting, to the point of Perez herself disowning the film years later.<ref>[http://www.meionorte.com/noticias,--Eu-era-uma-crianca-sem-maldade----diz-dancarina-Carla-Perez-sobre-E-o-Tchan,47976.html \"'Eu era uma crian\u00e7a sem maldade', diz dan\u00e7arina Carla Perez sobre \u00c9 o Tchan!\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080516051117/http://www.meionorte.com/noticias%2C--Eu-era-uma-crianca-sem-maldade----diz-dancarina-Carla-Perez-sobre-E-o-Tchan%2C47976.html |date=2008-05-16 }} \u2013 ''Meio Norte'', May 14, 2008 {{in lang|pt}}</ref> It was a [[box office bomb]], and it was some time later banned from circulation by request of Perez herself. It was also the debut of a then-unknown [[L\u00e1zaro Ramos]], who used his salary to pay for acting classes. On March 15, 2010, Brazilian magazine ''[[Veja (magazine)|Veja]]'' made a Top 10 list of the worst Brazilian movies of all time, and ''Cinderela Baiana'' was featured in first place. The reviewer, Pollyane Lima e Silva, called the film \"a shame\".<ref>[http://veja.abril.com.br/blog/10-mais/cinema/os-10-piores-filmes-da-historia-do-cinema-brasileiro/ Os Piores 10 Filmes da Hist\u00f3ria do Cinema Brasileiro] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160428071504/http://veja.abril.com.br/blog/10-mais/cinema/os-10-piores-filmes-da-historia-do-cinema-brasileiro/ |date=2016-04-28 }}, Pollyane Lima e Silva; ''Veja'', March 15, 2010 {{in lang|pt}}</ref> Author Renzo Mora included it in his ''25 Movies That Can Ruin Your Life'' book, while Luis Nassif claimed that, \"For me this is the worst of all.\"<ref>[http://www.advivo.com.br/comentario/re-o-pior-filme-do-mundo-50 Os 25 Piores Filmes do Mundo], Luis Nassif; ''Avido.com.br'', May 20, 2011 {{in lang|pt}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Fatal Deviation'' (1998) ===\n''[[Fatal Deviation]]'' is often credited as being the first [[martial arts film]] to be filmed in Ireland. It stars martial artist James Bennett and [[Michael Graham (singer)|Michael Graham]], who is best known for being a member of the boy band [[Boyzone]]. ''[[The Irish Post]]'' and ''[[Den of Geek]]'' write that it is a mainstay of worst film lists.<ref name=\"irishpost\"/><ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.denofgeek.com/movies/fatal-deviation/looking-back-at-fatal-deviation-irelands-only-martial-arts-film|title=Meet Fatal Deviation, Ireland's only martial arts film|last=Lines|first=Craig|date=November 4, 2015|accessdate=June 7, 2019|work=[[Den of Geek]]}}</ref> Luke McKinney of [[Cracked.com]] called it the worst film ever made, writing: \"There are so many things about making a movie that Jimmy doesn't know, that you could replace film school with this movie alone--just screening it once for students and asking them to list all the things it did wrong. Anyone who doesn't write 'everything' instantly fails.\"<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.cracked.com/article_18632_irelands-only-kung-fu-movie-is-worst-film-ever-made.html|title=Ireland's Only Kung Fu Movie (Is The Worst Film Ever Made)|last=McKinney|first=Luke|date=July 3, 2010|accessdate=March 9, 2019|work=[[Cracked.com]]}}</ref> ''The Irish Post'' named it the worst Irish film of all time,<ref name=\"irishpost\">{{cite web |url= https://www.irishpost.com/entertainment/definitive-ranking-7-worst-irish-films-time-158594|title= A definitive ranking of the 7 worst Irish films of all-time|first= Aidan|last=Lonergan|date= August 16, 2018|accessdate= March 9, 2019|work= [[The Irish Post]]}}</ref> and the ''[[Irish Independent]]'' wrote that it is \"regarded as one of the worst films ever made\".<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.independent.ie/lifestyle/westlife-what-next-26785226.html|title=Westlife: what next?|date= October 22, 2011|accessdate=March 9, 2019|work=[[Irish Independent]]}}</ref> [[Entertainment.ie]] placed it on its list of \"10 So Bad They're Good Movies You Need To See Before You Die\" and it was covered in ''[[Paste (magazine)|Paste]]''{{'}}s ''Bad Movie Diaries'' column.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://entertainment.ie/cinema/movie-news/10-so-bad-theyre-good-movies-you-need-to-see-before-you-die-227463/|title=10 So Bad They're Good Movies You Need To See Before You Die|last=Lloyd|first=Bryan|accessdate=March 9, 2019|work=[[entertainment.ie]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2018/07/bad-movie-diaries-fatal-deviation-1998.html |title=Bad Movie Diaries: Fatal Deviation (1998)|last1=Vorel|first1=Jim|last2=Lowe|first2=Kenneth|accessdate=June 7, 2019|work=[[Paste (magazine)|Paste]]}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Parting Shots'' (1999) ===\n\nThe British [[black comedy]] ''[[Parting Shots]]'' was the last film directed by [[Michael Winner]]. It starred rock musician [[Chris Rea]] as a man who, told he has only six months to live, begins murdering people who have wronged him. ''Parting Shots'' was accused of being poorly acted, filmed and scripted, as well as treating [[murder]] flippantly.<ref name=\"tookey\">Christopher Tookey, \"Michael Winner's latest film is his most offensive yet.\" ''[[The Daily Mail]]'', May 11, 1999, (p.11).</ref> [[Andrew Collins (broadcaster)|Andrew Collins]] took a very negative view of the film: \"''Parting Shots'' ... is going to set the course of British film-making back 20 years. It is not only the worst British film produced in this country since ''[[Carry On Emmannuelle]]'' (quite a feat in itself), it is a thoroughbred contender for the crown of Worst Film Ever Made.\"<ref>Andrew Collins, \"How to Shoot a Real Turkey\" ''[[The Observer]]'', March 28, 1999. ''Observer Screen'', p.6.</ref> [[Christopher Tookey]] was even more harsh, stating: \"''Parting Shots'' is not only the most horrible torture for audiences that Winner has ever devised. It is also profoundly offensive, even by Winner standards\" and later called ''Parting Shots'' \"the most tasteless, abysmal comedy of all time\".<ref name=\"tookey\"/> Tookey also stated that Winner had \"established himself, over his last dozen films, as beyond doubt the worst director of all time\".<ref name=\"tookey\"/> In an interview about the film, Charlotte O'Sullivan, [[The Independent|the ''Independent'']]'s film editor, claimed ''Parting Shots'' was \"the worst film I've ever seen\". O'Sullivan also criticised it for glorifying vigilantism: \"It's Michael Winner and you know, he doesn't have any sense of irony. He seems to be saying it is okay to go and kill people.\"<ref>\"Winner's Turkey has a bad aftertaste\". ''[[The Sunday Herald]]'', May 2, 1999 (p.7)</ref> The journalist [[Miles Kington]] later claimed \"''Parting Shots'' ... was directed by Michael Winner and despite the glittering cast, was possibly the worst film ever made.\"<ref>Miles Kingston, \"One or two plots to occupy my declining years\". ''[[The Independent]]'', May 3, 2005, (p.30).</ref> I. Q. Hunter listed ''Parting Shots'' as one of the candidates for \"the Worst British film ever made\".<ref name=\"iqh\" /> ''Parting Shots'' was also featured in a poll of ''[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]'' magazine readers' \"50 Worst Movies Ever\" poll.<ref name=\"The 50 Worst Movies Ever\"/>\n\n=== ''The Underground Comedy Movie'' (1999) ===\n\nThe comedy ''[[The Underground Comedy Movie]]'' is based on a [[cable access]] show from 1988. Director and lead actor [[Vince Offer]] constructed the film out of a series of tasteless, [[low culture|lowbrow skits]] (including [[Gena Lee Nolin]] loudly using the restroom and a superhero named ''Dickman'' who dresses in a giant penis costume and defeats his enemies by squirting them with semen). In 1999, Offer filed a suit against [[20th Century Fox]] and the co-directors of ''[[There's Something About Mary]]'', Bobby and Peter Farrelly, claiming that 14 scenes in ''Mary'' were stolen from his film.<ref name=\"ewol\">{{cite magazine|url=https://ew.com/article/1999/06/11/underground-comedy-movie-2/|title=Movie Review Underground Comedy Movie |date=June 11, 1999|accessdate=December 3, 2019|magazine=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|last=Gleiberman|first=Owen}}</ref> The Farrellys released this statement: \"We've never heard of him, we've never heard of his movie, and it's all a bunch of baloney.\"<ref name=\"ewx\">{{cite magazine|url=https://ew.com/article/1998/10/16/monitor-269/|title=Monitor: Celebrity news for October 16, 1998|last=Karger|first=Dave|first2=Suna|last2=Chang|date=October 16, 1998|magazine=Entertainment Weekly|accessdate=December 3, 2019}}</ref> [[Lawrence Van Gelder]] of ''[[The New York Times]]'' referred to it as a \"wretched film\" and stated that \"'The Underground Comedy Movie' stands as a monument to ineptitude and self-delusion.\"<ref name=\"nytvangelder\">{{cite news|url=https://archive.nytimes.com/www.nytimes.com/library/film/052899comedy-film-review.html|title=Lawrence Van Gelder's review of ''The Underground Comedy Movie'' |work=New York Times|date=1999-05-28 |accessdate=2013-12-19}}</ref> [[Rod Dreher]] of the ''[[New York Post]]'' said it \"may be the least amusing comedy ever made\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Dreher|first=Rod|title='Comedy' is Really Buried by Its Trash|work=New York Post|date=May 28, 1999}}</ref> [[Nathan Rabin]] covered the film in his column detailing terrible films and stated that: \"nothing I\u2019ve covered for this column was quite as soul-crushingly, brain-meltingly terrible as ... ''The Underground Comedy Movie''.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nathanrabin.com/happy-place/2018/9/4/this-looks-terrible-the-underground-comedy-movie-1999|title=This Looks Terrible! The Underground Comedy Movie (1999)|last=Rabin|first=Nathan|authorlink=Nathan Rabin|work=www.nathanrabin.com|date=September 4, 2018|accessdate=February 23, 2019}}</ref> Thom Bennett at ''[[Film Journal International]]'', wrote \"Anyone offended by unbearably bad films, jokes that are not funny and wasting 90 minutes of their lives is, as promised, guaranteed to be offended. In fact, to even call this mess a comedy is giving it far too much credit\", and \"''The Underground Comedy Movie'' may well be the worst film I have ever seen.\"<ref name=\"fji\">{{cite web|url=http://www.filmjournal.com/filmjournal/esearch/article_display.jsp?vnu_content_id=1000697847|title=Underground Comedy Movie, The|last=Bennett|first=Thom|work=Film Journal International|accessdate=7 March 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131105184223/http://www.filmjournal.com/filmjournal/esearch/article_display.jsp?vnu_content_id=1000697847|archive-date=5 November 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> Writing in ''[[Central Western Daily]]'', Peter Young said, \" I am pretty sure that I can declare this The Worst Film I Have Ever Seen\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.centralwesterndaily.com.au/story/1386763/comedy-film-best-kept-underground/|title=Comedy film best kept underground|last=Young|first=Peter|work=[[Central Western Daily]]|date=March 26, 2013|accessdate=March 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== 2000s ==\n\n=== ''Battlefield Earth'' (2000) ===\n[[File:John Travolta Battlefield Earth signing.jpg|thumb|[[John Travolta]] during ''[[Battlefield Earth (film)|Battlefield Earth]]'''s pomotional tour]]\n''[[Battlefield Earth (film)|Battlefield Earth]]'' is based on the first half of [[L. Ron Hubbard]]'s [[Battlefield Earth (novel)|novel of the same name]], and stars [[John Travolta]], [[Barry Pepper]] and [[Forest Whitaker]]. Although a sequel covering the second half of the book was planned, the panning from critics, poor box office performance, and financial ruin of [[Franchise Pictures]] killed off such plans. It was criticized for a poor script, hammy acting, overuse of [[Dutch angle]]s, repetitive dialogue, and several inconsistencies and plot holes. The movie's producer, Franchise Pictures, was later forced out of business after it emerged that it had fraudulently overstated the film's budget by $31 million. It has a 3% rating at [[Rotten Tomatoes]],<ref>{{rotten-tomatoes|id=battlefield_earth|title=Battlefield Earth}}</ref> and it was included in their Top 100 worst-reviewed movies of the 2000s.<ref name=\"rottenworst\">{{cite web|url=https://rottentomatoes.com/guides/worst_of_the_worst/ |title=The worst of the worst pictures |website=Rotten Tomatoes |date=2009-09-21 |accessdate=2011-01-17}}</ref> [[Roger Ebert]] predicted that the film, \"for decades to come will be the punch line of jokes about bad movies\".<ref name=\"BEarth\">{{cite news |url=http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20000512/REVIEWS/5120301/1023 |work=Chicago Sun-Times |title=Battlefield Earth | date=2000-05-12}}</ref> Ebert also wrote, \"the director, [[Roger Christian (filmmaker)|Roger Christian]], has learned from better films that directors sometimes tilt their cameras, but he has not learned why\".<ref name=\"BEarth\" /> It is also on his \"most hated\" list.<ref name=\"eberthated\">{{cite news|url=http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20050811/COMMENTARY/50808002/ |title=Ebert's Most Hated |work=Rogerebert.suntimes.com |accessdate=2011-01-17}}</ref> [[Nathan Rabin]] of [[The A.V. Club]] called it \"a fiasco that occupies a distinguished place high atop the pantheon of widely reviled crap\" and said, \"A legendary disaster well before it finished completion, ''Battlefield Earth'' hit theaters with a \"Kick Me\" sign on it so massive it could be detected from outer space.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://film.avclub.com/my-year-of-flops-case-file-66-battlefield-earth-1798212540|title=My Year OF Flops Case File #66: Battlefield Earth|last=Rabin|first=Nathan|website=Film|language=en-US|access-date=2019-01-27}}</ref> It won seven [[Golden Raspberry Award]]s, including Worst Picture and Worst Screen Couple (John Travolta and \"anyone on the screen with him\").<ref>{{cite web |url=http://razzies.com/asp/content/XcNewsPlus.asp?cmd=view&articleid=44/ |title=It's official \u2013 \"Battlefield Earth\" ties with \"Showgirls\" |work=Razzies.com |date=2000-02-03 |accessdate=2011-01-17 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110715160151/http://razzies.com/asp/content/XcNewsPlus.asp?cmd=view&articleid=44%2F |archive-date=2011-07-15 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In 2005, an eighth Razzie (for Worst \"Drama\" of Our First 25 Years) was awarded to the film,<ref>{{cite web |title=Awards for Battlefield Earth |work=Internet Movie Database |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0185183/awards |accessdate=2008-06-27}}</ref> and in 2010 it won a ninth Razzie at the [[30th Golden Raspberry Awards]] for ''Worst Picture of the Decade'',<ref name=\"30thRazzies\">{{cite web |title=Razzie Noms for Worst Picture of the Decade |work=Razzies.com |url=http://www.razzies.com/history/09NomPOD.asp |accessdate=2010-02-02}}</ref> the most of any film in the history of the awards at the time,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.razzies.com/history/07release.asp |title=Golden Raspberry Award Foundation |work=Razzies.com |accessdate=2013-11-18 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130321103846/http://www.razzies.com/history/07release.asp |archivedate=2013-03-21 }}</ref> before ''[[Jack and Jill (2011 film)|Jack and Jill]]'' surpassed its record with ten wins in 2012.<ref name=RazzieWin/> The movie appeared on Metacritic's list of the all-time lowest-scoring films,<ref name=\"Metacritic\">{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/browse/movies/score/metascore/all?sort=asc|title=Movie Releases By Score|last=|first=|date=|work=[[Metacritic]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|accessdate=April 17, 2019}}</ref> and is on the MRQE's 50 Worst Movies list.<ref name=\"MRQE50\">{{cite web|url=https://www.mrqe.com/lists/50_worst_movies|title=50 Worst Movies|last=|first=|date=|work=[[Movie Review Query Engine]]|accessdate=April 17, 2019}}</ref> ''[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]'' named it the second worst movie ever made after ''[[Batman & Robin (film)|Batman & Robin]]'' and ''[[The Register]]'' listed it as the worst movie ever made.<ref name=\"The 50 Worst Movies Ever\"/><ref name=\"battlefieldregister\">{{cite web |title=Battlefield Earth ruled worst film Ever|work=[[The Register]]|last=Haines|first=Lester|url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2012/04/20/worst_movie/|accessdate=April 5, 2018|date=April 20, 2012}}</ref> ''Battlefield Earth'' screenwriter [[J. David Shapiro]] later apologized for making \"the suckiest movie ever\".<ref name=\"battlefieldregister\"/>\n\n=== ''Honest'' (2000) ===\n\n''[[Honest (film)|Honest]]'' is the directorial debut of [[Eurythmics]] member [[David A. Stewart]], and starring three members of the British/Canadian [[girl group]] [[All Saints (group)|All Saints]] ([[Melanie Blatt]], [[Nicole Appleton|Nicole]] and [[Natalie Appleton]]). It received a large amount of media criticism following its release.<ref name=\"dr\">\"Honest, it's the worst movie ever; All Saints' film debut is holy awful, say critics\". ''The Daily Record'', May 26, 2000</ref> The Scottish newspaper ''[[Daily Record (Scotland)|Daily Record]]'' described ''Honest'' thus: \"This turgid tale of Sixties London isn't just bad \u2013 it's quite probably the worst film ever.\"<ref name=\"dr\" /> [[Peter Bradshaw]] noted that ''Honest'' \"subscribes to the usual credulous fictions about the charm, glamour and wit of violent criminals, and leaves out these qualities in spades\" and added \"However silly and implausible, it would be all right if there was the slightest hint of brio or fun in the script, written by comedy giants [[Dick Clement]] and [[Ian La Frenais]]. But there isn't.\"<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/film/2000/may/26/culture.reviews \"Honest\"] Peter Bradshaw, ''The Guardian'', 26 May 2000. Retrieved 2 October 2014.</ref> [[Alexander Walker (critic)|Alexander Walker]] called ''Honest'' \"An ugly, ratty-looking load of jazzy cliches buried in flashy has-been styles, including slowmo frolicking in the Trafalgar Square fountains, strobe-lit druggy sessions and accelerated action on the mattress.\"<ref>Alexander Walker, ''The Evening Standard'', 26 May 2000.</ref> British film historian I.Q. Hunter later listed ''Honest'' as one of the candidates for the title of \"Worst British film ever made\".<ref name=\"iqh\" />\n\n=== ''Freddy Got Fingered'' (2001) ===\n\nThe comedy film ''[[Freddy Got Fingered]]'' stars [[Tom Green]], who also wrote and directed it, featuring largely [[gross-out comedy|gross-out]] and [[shock humor]] similar to that featured in ''[[The Tom Green Show]]''. In the film, Green stars as a 28-year-old slacker and cartoonist who falsely accuses his father of [[child molestation]] when he questions his son's life goals. ''Freddy Got Fingered'' received overwhelmingly negative reviews, with [[CNN]] critic [[Paul Clinton]] declaring it \"quite simply the worst movie ever released by a major studio in Hollywood history\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Clinton |first=Paul |title='Freddy Got Fingered' is a bad, bad film |publisher=CNN |date=April 19, 2011 |url=http://archives.cnn.com/2001/SHOWBIZ/Movies/04/19/Freddy.Fingered/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061230080518/http://archives.cnn.com/2001/SHOWBIZ/Movies/04/19/Freddy.Fingered/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=December 30, 2006 |accessdate=February 9, 2011 }}</ref> Warren Epstein of ''[[The Gazette (Colorado Springs)|The Gazette]]'' described ''Freddy Got Fingered'' as \"the worst movie ever made\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-5965104.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180319151405/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-5965104.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=19 March 2018 |title='Freddy Got Fingered' is but the latest in a long line of stinkers |author=Warren Epstein |newspaper=[[The Gazette (Colorado Springs)|The Gazette]] |date=26 April 2001|via=HighBeam Research}}</ref> A review in ''[[The Washington Post]]'' said: \"If ever a movie testified to the utter creative bankruptcy of the Hollywood film industry, it is the abomination known as ''Freddy Got Fingered''.\"<ref>{{cite news |last=Hughes |first=Scott |title=The worst movie ever? |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=April 26, 2001 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2001/apr/26/artsfeatures2 |accessdate=February 9, 2011 |location=London}}</ref> Robert Koehler of ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' called it, \"One of the most brutally awful comedies ever to emerge from a major studio.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Freddy Got Fingered |work=[[Metacritic]] |url=https://metacritic.com/movie/freddy-got-fingered/critic-reviews |accessdate= March 17, 2014}}</ref> Film reviewer [[Roger Ebert]] included the film on his \"most hated\" list,<ref name=\"eberthated\" /> gave it zero out of four stars, and wrote: \"This movie doesn't scrape the bottom of the barrel. This movie isn't the bottom of the barrel. This movie isn't below the bottom of the barrel. This movie doesn't deserve to be mentioned in the same sentence with barrels.\"<ref>{{cite news |last=Ebert |first=Roger |author-link=Roger Ebert |title=Freddy Got Fingered |work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]] |date=April 20, 2011 |url=http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20010420/REVIEWS/104200304/1023 |accessdate=February 9, 2011}}</ref> ''Freddy Got Fingered'' was nominated for eight awards at the [[22nd Golden Raspberry Awards|2001 Razzies]], and won for Worst Picture, Worst Actor, Worst Director, Worst Screenplay, and Worst On-Screen Couple.<ref name=\"BBC0211\">{{cite news |title=Freddy heads Razzies nominations |work=BBC News |date=February 11, 2002 |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/1814018.stm |accessdate=February 9, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"BBC0323\">{{cite news |last=Waters |first=Darren |title=Green gets fingered for Razzies |work=BBC News |date=March 23, 2002 |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/in_depth/entertainment/2002/oscars_2002/1889555.stm |accessdate=February 9, 2011}}</ref> Razzies founder [[John J. B. Wilson]] called it \"offensive, stupid and obnoxious\" and said it had \"no redeeming value\".<ref name=\"BBC0211\"/> Green accepted his awards in person, traveling to the ceremony in a white [[Cadillac]], wearing a tuxedo and rolling out his own [[red carpet]] to the presentation. The movie has an 11% rating on [[Rotten Tomatoes]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://rottentomatoes.com/m/freddy_got_fingered/ |title=Freddy Got Fingered |website=Rotten Tomatoes |accessdate=2013-11-18}}</ref> In 2010, the film was nominated at the [[30th Golden Raspberry Awards]] for ''Worst Picture of the Decade'',<ref name=\"30thRazzies\"/> though it lost to ''Battlefield Earth''.<ref>{{cite news |last=Masters |first=Tim |title=Sandra Bullock wins worst actress award at Razzies |work=BBC News |date=March 7, 2010 |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/8554035.stm |accessdate=February 9, 2011}}</ref> ''Freddy Got Fingered'' also appeared on Metacritic's list of the all-time lowest-scoring films,<ref name=\"Metacritic\"/> was featured in ''[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]'''s list of the \"50 Worst Movies Ever\" poll,<ref name=\"The 50 Worst Movies Ever\">{{cite web | url = https://www.empireonline.com/movies/features/50-worst-movies-ever-2/ |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200201223813/https://www.empireonline.com/movies/features/50-worst-movies-ever-2/ | title = The 50 Worst Movies Ever | work=[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]] | date=February 4, 2010 |archivedate=February 1, 2020 | accessdate = March 17, 2014}}</ref> and is on the MRQE's 50 Worst Movies list.<ref name=\"MRQE50\"/>\n\n=== ''Glitter'' (2001) ===\nStarring [[Mariah Carey]] in the lead role as an aspiring singer, the romantic musical drama ''[[Glitter (film)|Glitter]]'' was intended to be her breakthrough role but was a critical failure and a box office bomb. ''[[Hindustan Times]]'' claimed that ''Glitter'' \"was slammed by almost all critics for being the worst film ever\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Mariah Carey's flop movie 'Glitter' almost killed her |newspaper= Hindustan Times |date=November 4, 2009 |quote=Carey, 39, had to be hospitalised due to an emotional breakdown after Glitter was slammed by almost all critics for being the worst film ever.}}</ref> ''[[Fade In (magazine)|Fade In]]'' stated that \"''Glitter'' isn't just one of the worst music-themed films ever \u2014 it's one of the worst films ever made, period.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=The 30 worst Vanity Projects of all time|url=http://fadeinonline.com/the-30-worst-vanity-projects-of-all-time.html|website=Fadeinonline.com|publisher=[[Fade In (magazine)|Fade In]]|accessdate=August 23, 2015}}</ref> Author Bob McCann wrote in ''Encyclopedia of African American Actresses in Film and Television'' that it's \"rightfully in the running as one of the worst films ever made\".<ref>{{cite book |first=McCann |last=Bob |title=Encyclopedia of African American Actresses in Film and Television |location=New York |publisher=Performing Arts |year=2009 |isbn=9780786458042 |page=70 }}</ref> [[News.com.au]],<ref name=\":1\">{{cite news|url=https://www.news.com.au/entertainment/movies/absolute-stinkers-the-15-worst-movies-of-all-time/news-story/0023085ea96fa3f2c581778a070f1308|title=Absolute stinkers: The 15 worst movies of all time|last=Stephenson|first=Alison|date=November 13, 2013|work=|accessdate=April 17, 2019|website=[[News.com.au]]}}</ref> ''[[Hi (magazine)|Hi]]'',<ref>{{cite web|title=Worst Films Ever: Glitter|url=http://www.hihimag.com/hi/ents/film/2013/07/worst-films-ever-glitter/|website=[[Hi (magazine)|Hi]]|accessdate=August 23, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924030115/http://www.hihimag.com/hi/ents/film/2013/07/worst-films-ever-glitter/|archive-date=2015-09-24|url-status=dead}}</ref> ''[[Flavorwire]]'',<ref name=\"Flavorwire\"/> Metacritic,<ref name=\"Metacritic\"/> and ''[[Empire (magazine)|Empire]]'' are amongst those who have listed it as one of the worst films ever made.<ref name=\"The 50 Worst Movies Ever\"/> ''Glitter'' received six Razzie nominations and Carey won for Worst Actress.<ref>{{cite news|title=Tom Green, Estella Warren are Razzie ''winners'' |url=https://www.ew.com/article/2002/03/25/tom-green-estella-warren-are-razzie-winners |newspaper=Entertainment Weekly |accessdate=August 23, 2015 |first=Brian |last=Hiatt |date=2002-03-25}}</ref> It was also featured in John Wilson's ''The Official Razzie Movie Guide'', and in 2005, it was nominated for \"Worst Musical of Our First 25 Years\", but lost to ''[[From Justin to Kelly]]''. In an interview in 2010, Carey stated that she believed that the film's failure at the box office was largely due to the soundtrack being released the same day as the [[September 11 attacks]].<ref name=\"digitalspy\">{{cite web|title=Carey Blames 9/11 For 'Glitter' Flop|work=[[Digital Spy]]|publisher=[[Hachette Filipacchi M\u00e9dias]]|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/movies/news/a199302/carey-blames-911-for-glitter-flop.html|last=Reynolds|first=Simon|date=January 26, 2010|accessdate=August 23, 2015}}</ref> It has a 7% rating on [[Rotten Tomatoes]] based on 87 reviews.<ref>{{cite web|title=Glitter (2001)|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/glitter|website=Rotten Tomatoes|accessdate=3 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Swept Away'' (2002) ===\nA remake of [[Swept Away (1974 film)|a 1974 Italian film of the same name]], the [[romantic comedy]] film ''[[Swept Away (2002 film)|Swept Away]]'' was directed by [[Guy Ritchie]] and starred his then-wife [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]] and [[Adriano Giannini]]. It received mostly extremely negative reviews, with most of the criticism going towards Madonna's bad acting, the original film being considered superior and the remake being considered just a star vehicle for Madonna.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/northamerica/usa/1410000/Madonna-and-Guy-swept-away-on-tide-of-criticism.html|title=Madonna and Guy swept away on tide of criticism|last=Poole|first=Oliver|date=2002-10-11|access-date=2018-12-28|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref> [[Rotten Tomatoes]] holds a 5% rating, based on 79 reviews, with an average rating of 2.76/10. The site's consensus states: \"Muddled and lacking the political context of the original, ''Swept Away'' offers further proof that Madonna can't act.\"<ref>{{Citation|title=Swept Away|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/1116774-swept_away/|language=en|access-date=2018-12-28}}</ref> [[Metacritic]] reports an 18 out of 100 rating, based on 27 critics, indicating \"overwhelming dislike\".<ref>{{Citation|title=Swept Away|url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/swept-away|access-date=2018-12-28}}</ref> Rex Reed of ''[[The Observer]]'' said: \"If there is one thing worse than a Guy Ritchie movie, it's a Guy Ritchie movie with Madonna in it.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://observer.com/2002/10/not-swept-away-by-madonna/|title=Not Swept Away By Madonna|date=2002-10-21|website=Observer|language=en|access-date=2018-12-28}}</ref> [[Joe Queenan (author)|Joe Queenan]] of ''[[The Guardian]]'' discussed the movie in an article on what makes a movie the worst of all time and said, \"[...] ''[[Showgirls]]'' has a certain campy allure that grows a bit each time I see it. Madonna's ''Swept Away'' doesn't; it seems more amateurish on each viewing, like a morass that starts out as a quagmire, then morphs into a cesspool and finally turns into a slime pit on the road to its ultimate destination in the bowels of Hell.\"<ref name=\"queenan\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2008/mar/21/1|title=Joe Queenan on the worst movie of all time|last=Queenan|first=Joe|authorlink=Joe Queenan (author)|date=March 21, 2008|work=The Guardian|access-date=December 28, 2018|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> [[Julie Burchill]], also from ''The Guardian'', selected it as her pick for the worst film ever made.<ref name=\"guardianworst\"/> John Anderson of ''[[Newsday]]'' said, \"New ways of describing badness need to be invented to describe exactly how bad it is.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/1116774-swept_away/reviews/?page=2&sort=|title=Swept Away - Movie Reviews - Rotten Tomatoes|website=www.rottentomatoes.com|access-date=2018-12-28}}</ref> ''Swept Away'' was also a [[box office bomb]]; against a $10 million budget, it grossed $598,645 in the United States and around $437,875 from foreign territories for a worldwide total gross of $1,036,520.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=sweptaway.htm|title=Swept Away (2002) - Box Office Mojo|website=www.boxofficemojo.com|access-date=2018-12-28}}</ref> The film was awarded five awards at the [[23rd Golden Raspberry Awards|2002 Golden Raspberry Awards]], for Worst Picture, Worst Actress (Madonna), Worst Screen Couple (Madonna and Giannini), Worst Remake or Sequel and Worst Director (Ritchie), while also being nominated for Worst Actor (Giannini) and Worst Screenplay. It was the first film to win both Worst Picture and Worst Remake or Sequel. At the [[25th Golden Raspberry Awards]], it was nominated for ''Worst \"Drama\" of Our First 25 Years'', and at the [[30th Golden Raspberry Awards]], it was nominated for ''Worst Picture of the Decade'', but in both cases lost to ''[[Battlefield Earth (film)|Battlefield Earth]]''. [[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]] ranked it #20 in its list of \"The 50 Worst Movies Ever\",<ref name=\"The 50 Worst Movies Ever\" /> and [[AfterEllen.com and TheBacklot.com|After Ellen]] ranked it #7 in its list of \"The worst movies ever to grace the screen\".<ref name=\"afterellen\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.afterellen.com/movies/58522-the-worst-movies-ever-to-grace-the-screen|title=The worst movies ever to grace the screen|date=2009-09-08|website=AfterEllen|access-date=2019-01-30}}</ref>\n\n=== ''The Master of Disguise'' (2002) ===\n\nThe comedy film ''[[The Master of Disguise]]'' was produced in part by [[Adam Sandler]] and stars [[Dana Carvey]] as Pistachio Disguisey, an undercover Italian waiter who must save his father Fabbrizio ([[James Brolin]]) from the evil Devlin Bowman ([[Brent Spiner]]) by using his inherent skills in disguise. Although the film was a box office success, it received scathing reviews from critics upon its release, many of which pointed out its sophomoric plot, unfunny humor (in particular, its [[flatulence]] gags) and disguises that would clearly not be recognized by children (such as [[Tony Montana]] from ''[[Scarface (1983 film)|Scarface]]''). Many critics also pointed out the short running time, consisting of 72 minutes of the film itself and over ten minutes of end credits juxtaposed with outtakes. [[Roger Ebert]] gave it one star out of four, claiming, \"The movie is a desperate miscalculation. It gives poor Dana Carvey nothing to do that is really funny, and then expects us to laugh because he acts so goofy all the time.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Fragoso |first=Sam |url=https://rogerebert.com/reviews/the-master-of-disguise-2002 |title=The Master Of Disguise Movie Review (2002) |publisher=Roger Ebert |date=2002-08-02 |accessdate=2014-03-05}}</ref> Alan Morrisson, writing for the film magazine ''[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]'', proclaimed that ''The Master of Disguise'' was \"the worst film ever made: a film about idiots, made by idiots, for idiots\",<ref name=\"The 50 Worst Movies Ever\"/> while Matthew Turner of ''ViewLondon'' remarked, \"This is a serious contender for the title of The Worst Film Ever Made.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.viewlondon.co.uk/films/the-master-of-disguise-film-review-3673.html |title=The Master of Disguise Film Review \u2013 The Master of Disguise Film Pictures, The Master of Disguise Film Trailer |work=Viewlondon.co.uk |date=2006-10-16 |accessdate=2014-03-05}}</ref> In addition, Chris Parry of eFilmCritic.com stated, \"Quite honestly, I've never seen anything less competent. And I mean that.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.efilmcritic.com/review.php?movie=6017&reviewer=1 |title=Movie Review \u2013 Master of Disguise, The |publisher=eFilmCritic |accessdate=2014-03-05}}</ref> The film holds a 1% rating on [[Rotten Tomatoes]] based on 104 reviews,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://rottentomatoes.com/m/master_of_disguise/ |title=The Master of Disguise |website=Rotten Tomatoes |accessdate=2014-07-24}}</ref> and was featured on the site's list of the top 100 worst-reviewed films of the 2000s.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://rottentomatoes.com/guides/worst_of_the_worst/9/ |title=Worst of the Worst 2009 \u2013 Crossover |website=Rotten Tomatoes |accessdate=2014-03-05}}</ref> It also appears on Metacritic's list of the all-time lowest-scoring films,<ref name=\"Metacritic\"/> and is on the MRQE's 50 Worst Movies list.<ref name=\"MRQE50\"/> A cameo appearance by [[Bo Derek]] landed her a nomination for Worst Supporting Actress at the [[23rd Golden Raspberry Awards]], but she lost to [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]] for ''[[Die Another Day]]''.\n\n=== ''Ballistic: Ecks vs. Sever'' (2002) ===\n\nThe action film ''[[Ballistic: Ecks vs. Sever]]'' stars [[Antonio Banderas]] and [[Lucy Liu]] as opposing secret agents. Critics panned it, generally regarding it as having no redeeming features, not even the unintentional comedic value normally associated with bad films. They variously described the film as \"A picture for idiots\", \"Boring to an amazing degree\", \"A fine achievement in stupidity and dullness\", \"Dreadful\", \"[Giving] new meaning to the word incoherent\", and \"bad on just about every level\". One critic suggested an alternative title as \"''Simplistic: Bullets Vs. Humans''\".<ref>[https://hollywoodreporter.com/hr/search/article_display.jsp?vnu_content_id=1689821/ ''Ballistic: Ecks vs. Sever''] at ''The Hollywood Reporter''</ref> [[Stephen Hunter]] of ''[[The Washington Post]]'' wrote, \"You could run this film backward, soundtrack included, and it would make no less sense.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/ac2/wp-dyn/A42115-2002Sep19 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110628231426/http://www.washingtonpost.com/ac2/wp-dyn/A42115-2002Sep19 |url-status=dead |archive-date=2011-06-28 |title=''Goosey Lucy: 'Ballistic,' a Lot of Noisy Dumdum'' |work=Washingtonpost.com |date=2002-09-20 |accessdate=2011-01-17}}</ref> [[Roger Ebert]], who included the film in his \"most hated list\", called the movie \"a chaotic mess, overloaded with special effects and explosions, light on continuity, sanity and coherence\".<ref>[http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=%2F20020920%2FREVIEWS%2F209200302%2F1023&AID1=%2F20020920%2FREVIEWS%2F209200302%2F1023&AID2= Roger Ebert \u2013 Ballistic: Ecks vs. Sever]. Retrieved 2009-10-09.</ref> In addition to being lambasted by critics, it was a disaster financially, recouping just over $19.9 million of its $70 million budget. ''[[International Business Times]]'' included it on its list of Hollywood's top 5 worst movies ever made.<ref name=\"IBT\"/> In March 2007, the movie review site [[Rotten Tomatoes]] ranked it #1 among \"The Worst of the Worst\" movie list,<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20090303154232/https://rottentomatoes.com/features/special/2007/wotw/?r=1&mid=1116131 \"The Worst of the Worst\"], rottentomatoes.com (archived at Wayback Machine)</ref> with 108 \"rotten\" reviews and no \"fresh\" ones. ''[[Mental Floss]]'' also listed it as the worst movie ever made.<ref name=\"Mental Floss\"/>\n\n=== ''Ben and Arthur'' (2002) ===\nA low-budget 2002 American romantic drama film about the titular gay couple who come into conflict with Arthur's religious brother, ''[[Ben and Arthur]]'' was written, directed, produced, edited, and scored by Sam Mraovich, who also played the character Arthur. ''Ben and Arthur'' received strong criticism (especially from the LGBT community) for its low budget and poor plotting. [[BuzzFeed]] described it as the \"worst gay movie of all time\".<ref name=\"peitzman\">{{cite news|url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/louispeitzman/the-man-behind-the-worst-gay-movie-of-all-time-doesnt-care-i |title=The Man Behind The \"Worst Gay Movie Of All Time\" Doesn't Care If You Hate It |first=Louis |last=Peitzman |publisher=[[BuzzFeed]] |date=September 5, 2014 |accessdate=March 15, 2018}}</ref> The gay popular culture site [[Queerty]] described ''Ben and Arthur'' as \"unintelligible\" and ended its review by calling it the \"Worst. Movie. Ever.\"<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://www.queerty.com/ben-arthur-the-worst-gay-movie-of-all-time-20090220 |title=Ben & Arthur: The Worst Gay Movie of All Time |first=Japhy |last=Grant |journal=[[Queerty]] |date=February 20, 2009 |accessdate=January 25, 2015 }}</ref> The gay movie review site Cinemaqueer likewise stated: \"''Ben and Arthur'' is so terrible that it has awoken the dormant Bette Davis in me. It is so painfully bad that it wouldn't even make good fodder on ''[[Mystery Science Theater 3000]]''. This just might possibly be the worst movie I have ever seen ... Unless you get a kick out of mocking bad films, avoid this one at all costs.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cinemaqueer.com/review%20pages/9deadgayguysben.html |title=9 dead gay guys/ben & arthur |first=Michael D. |last=Klemm |website=Cinemaqueer |date=July 2004 |accessdate=January 25, 2015 }}</ref> Michael Adams, reviewing the film for his book ''Showgirls, Teen Wolves, and Astro Zombies'', describes it thus: \"''Ben & Arthur'' is as over-the-top insane as it is ludicrously executed ... the production values, from biscuits on plates comprising the main course of a candlelit dinner to a church literally having a cardboard cross and a cartoon Jesus on the wall, are as bad as anything I've seen.\"<ref>{{cite book |first=Michael |last=Adams |title=Showgirls, Teen Wolves, and Astro Zombies: a film critic's year-long quest to find the worst movie ever made |location=New York |publisher=Itbooks |year=2010 |isbn=978-0-06-180629-2 |page=301 }}</ref> A [[Rotten Tomatoes]] article placed ''Ben and Arthur'' on their list of \"Films So Bad They're Unmissable\", saying \"If [[Tommy Wiseau]]'s ''[[The Room (2003 film)|The Room]]'' is the over-wrought, melodramatic and self-pitying heterosexual camp classic of choice, then Sam Mraovich's ''Ben & Arthur'' is its gay equivalent.\" Rotten Tomatoes also stated \"Every scene, every line, every hissy fit is simultaneously hilariously amateur and hysterically fever-pitched.\"<ref name=\"sobad\">{{cite web |url=https://editorial.rottentomatoes.com/article/25-movies-so-bad-theyre-unmissable/|title=25 Movies So Bad They're Unmissable |website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |date=January 30, 2010 |accessdate=January 25, 2015 }}</ref> ''[[Total Film]]'' ranked ''Ben and Arthur'' at #58 in their list of the 66 worst films of all time.<ref name=TotalFilm>{{cite web|url=http://www.totalfilm.com/features/66-worst-movies-of-all-time|title=66 Worst Movies Of All Time|date=February 15, 2012 |work=[[Total Film]]|publisher=[[GamesRadar]]|accessdate=September 30, 2013 }}</ref> Mraovich finds ''Ben and Arthur''{{'}}s placement among the canon of worst films to be a blessing as the film has received more attention than he ever anticipated.<ref name=\"peitzman\"/>\n\n=== ''Pinocchio'' (US dub, 2002) ===\n''[[Pinocchio (2002 film)|Pinocchio]]'', a 2002 Italian [[Fantasy film|fantasy]] [[comedy-drama]] film based on ''[[The Adventures of Pinocchio]]'' by [[Carlo Collodi]], directed by and starring [[Roberto Benigni]], garnered largely negative reviews mostly for Benigni's poor portrayal of [[Pinocchio]]. It received an English-language dub in the United States in December 2002, released by [[Miramax]], which was universally panned and further contributed to the negative reception. Bob Grimm of ''[[News & Review]]'' called it \"quite possibly the worst movie-going experience in all of my 34 years\" and said, \" ''Pinocchio'' garners Benigni the dubious distinction of having directed one of the worst movies ever unleashed upon an unsuspecting public.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsreview.com/reno/monstrous-terrifying/content?oid=19474|title=Pinocchio - Monstrous and terrifying - Film Reviews - Film - January 2, 2003|website=Reno News & Review|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> Elvis Mitchell of ''[[The New York Times]]'' called it \"a movie so bad that it quickly enters the pantheon of wreckage that includes ''Battleship Earth'' [sic] and ''Showgirls''.<nowiki>''</nowiki><ref>{{Cite news|last=Mitchell|first=Elvis|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/12/26/movies/film-review-how-many-actors-does-it-take-to-make-a-log-talk.html|title=FILM REVIEW; How Many Actors Does It Take to Make a Log Talk?|date=2002-12-26|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-12|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Keith Phillips of ''[[The A.V. Club]]'' said that it \"could have become a ''Howard The Duck-'' or ''Battlefield Earth''-like synonym for cinematic miscalculation, were its title not already so familiar.\" <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://film.avclub.com/pinocchio-1798198162|title=Pinocchio|website=Film|language=en-us|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> ''[[News.com.au]]'' included it in its list of the 15 worst films of all time.<ref name=\":1\" /> It was the fist non-English-language-film to get nominated for the Golden Raspberry Awards, earning six nominations, for Worst Picture, Worst Director, Worst Screenplay, Worst Actor, Worst Remake or Sequel and Worst Screen Couple (Roberto Benigni and Nicoletta Braschi), with Benigni winning one for Worst Actor. The film has a [[List of films with a 0% rating on Rotten Tomatoes|0% rating]] at Rotten Tomatoes and it is on Metacritic's list of the all-time lowest-scoring films.<ref name=\"Metacritic\"/><ref>{{Citation|title=Pinocchio (2002)|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/1119026_pinocchio|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>  Despite this, Benigni starred in [[Pinocchio (2019 film)|another Pinocchio film]] in 2019, this time playing [[Mister Geppetto|Gepetto]].\n\n=== ''From Justin to Kelly'' (2003) ===\n\nThe romantic-comedy musical ''[[From Justin to Kelly]]'' stars [[Kelly Clarkson]] and [[Justin Guarini]], the winner and runner-up, respectively, of the [[American Idol (season 1)|first season]] of ''[[American Idol]]''. The film was a critical and commercial disaster, earning only $4.9 million at the North American box office and achieving a 10% rating on [[Rotten Tomatoes]] based on 63 reviews.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://rottentomatoes.com/m/from_justin_to_kelly/ |title=From Justin To Kelly |website=Rotten Tomatoes |accessdate=2014-07-24}}</ref> [[Josh Tyrangiel]] of ''[[Time Magazine]]'' described ''From Justin to Kelly'' as \"a monstrous ''Idol'' movie musical that in the most generous light is the worst film so far this century\",<ref name=\"kc\">[http://content.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,1156616,00.html \"Miss Independent\"] Josh Tyrangiel. ''Time Magazine''  February 5, 2006 (Subscription Required).</ref> while ''[[The Free Lance\u2013Star]]'' referred to it as \"the world's worst movie\".<ref>\"Dishing it!\" ''The Free Lance\u2013Star'', July 9th, 2003, (p.56).</ref> [[Nathan Rabin]] of ''[[The A.V. Club]]'', reviewing the film for his \"My Year of Flops\" series, stated, \"All films require suspension of disbelief. ''From Justin To Kelly'' requires something more like a temporary lobotomy. Nothing about the main characters or their relationships makes sense.\"<ref name=\"fjtk\">[https://avclub.com/article/contest-winning-case-file-150-ifrom-justin-to-kell-35221 Contest-Winning Case File #150: From Justin To Kelly] Nathan Rabin, ''[[The A.V. Club]]'', November 11th, 2009. Retrieved 28 January 2014.</ref> It won a special [[Razzie]]\u2014\"Governor's Award \u2013 Distinguished Under-Achievement in Choreography\"\u2014at the [[24th Golden Raspberry Awards]].<ref>\"Gigli Takes Razzie Dishonors as Year's Worst\", ''[[Reading Eagle]]'', March 1st, 2004 (p.20)</ref> It was nominated for eight additional Razzies (including a second special award, \"Worst Excuse for an Actual Movie\"), and a year later it won for [[25th Golden Raspberry Awards|Worst \"Musical\" of Our First 25 Years]]. ''[[Total Film]]'' included ''From Justin to Kelly'' on their list of \"The 66 Worst Films of All Time\",<ref name=TotalFilm/> and ''[[International Business Times]]'' included the film on its list of Hollywood's top 5 worst movies ever made.<ref name=\"IBT\"/> In a later interview, Clarkson expressed regret over ''From Justin to Kelly'', stating she only did it because she was contractually obligated to do so: \"I knew when I read the script it was going to be real, real bad, but when I won, I signed that piece of paper, and I could not get out of it.\"<ref name=\"kc\" />\n\n=== ''The Room'' (2003) ===\n[[File:Tommy-Wiseau-1.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Tommy Wiseau]] in a promotional picture for ''[[The Room (2003 film)|The Room]]'']]\nThe independently produced ''[[The Room (2003 film)|The Room]]'', about an amiable banker whose friends betray him one by one, has been called \"the ''[[Citizen Kane]]'' of bad movies\" by some critics.<ref name=\"ew1\">{{cite magazine |url=https://ew.com/article/2008/12/12/crazy-cult-room/|title=The Crazy Cult of 'The Room'|date=July 20, 2009 |magazine=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |accessdate=December 3, 2019|first=Clark |last=Collis}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/features/the-couch-surfer-it-may-be-sublimely-rubbish-but-the-room-makes-audiences-happy-1752708.html |title=The Couch Surfer: 'It may be sublimely rubbish, but The Room makes audiences happy' |date=2009-07-20 |work=Independent.co.uk |accessdate=23 November 2009 |location=London}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://ew.com/article/2008/12/30/the-room-postsc/ |title='The Room': Worst movie ever? Don't tell that to its suddenly in-demand star |last=Collis |first=Clark |date=December 30, 2008 |work=Entertainment Weekly |accessdate=December 3, 2019}}</ref> ''[[The Guardian]], [[Vox (website)|Vox]], [[The Washington Post]], [[Australian Broadcasting Corporation|ABC Australia]]'' and ''[[S\u00fcddeutsche Zeitung]]'' called it the worst film ever made.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Rose|first=Steve|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/filmblog/2009/sep/10/cinema-the-room-cult|title=Is this the worst movie ever made?|date=2009-09-09|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-03-18|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/culture/2017/12/2/16720012/the-room-tommy-wiseau-backstory-explained|title=The Room: how the worst movie ever became a Hollywood legend as bizarre as its creator|last=Romano|first=Aja|date=2017-12-02|website=Vox|language=en|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/entertainment/the-room-is-the-worst-movie-ever-made-but-ive-seen-it-a-hundred-times--without-irony/2017/11/30/6475b096-d3ae-11e7-b62d-d9345ced896d_story.html|title=Perspective {{!}} \u2018The Room\u2019 is the worst movie ever made, but I\u2019ve seen it a hundred times \u2014 without irony|last=ParkReporterEmailEmailBioBioFollowFollowReporter|first=Gene Park closeGene|website=Washington Post|language=en|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2017-12-05/the-room-tommy-wiseau-worst-film-ever-made-endures/9223516|title=The worst movie ever made, explained|last=Donoughue|first=pop culture reporter Paul|date=2017-12-05|website=ABC News|language=en-AU|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sueddeutsche.de/kultur/schlechtester-film-aller-zeiten-wie-eine-atombombe-die-jeden-moment-explodiert-1.1680571|title=\"The Room\", schlechtester Film aller Zeiten|last=Graff|first=Bernd|website=S\u00fcddeutsche.de|language=de|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref> Ignatiy Vishnevetsky of ''[[The A.V. Club|The A.V Club]]'' called it \"the greatest bad movie of our time\" and said, \"''The Room'' is nearly an anti-film\u2014an inane and unintentionally surreal soap opera, filled with non sequiturs, confused characters, and gratuitous, anatomically incorrect sex.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.avclub.com/the-disaster-artist-is-a-lousy-tribute-to-the-greatest-1820787988|title=The Disaster Artist is a lousy tribute to the greatest bad movie of our time|last=Vishnevetsky|first=Ignatiy|website=The A.V. Club|access-date=2019-01-04}}</ref> Though the film's star, writer, producer, and director [[Tommy Wiseau]] has claimed it is a [[black comedy]] and its numerous flaws are intentional, other actors involved in the production have denied this, saying that Wiseau intended it as a [[melodrama]]tic romance.<ref name=\"Times1\">{{cite news |title=Cult hit (Even M is a recycled sex scene) The Room is best worst film |url=http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/film/article6067024.ece |newspaper= The Times |first=Christopher |last=Goodwin |date=April 12, 2009 |location=London}}</ref> ''The Room'' has been noted for its bizarre and non-sequiturial dialogue, protracted sex scenes, various subplots that are inadequately resolved or simply disappear altogether (most notably, a character announces that she has been diagnosed with [[breast cancer]], but this is never mentioned again throughout the entire film), and infamous use of [[chroma key|green-screen]] for \"outdoor\" rooftop scenes. It made its broadcast premiere as an [[April Fools' Day]] special in 2009 on [[Cartoon Network]]'s [[Adult Swim]] block, edited down from its original R rating to a TV-14/DSLV rating. The day after its appearance, its DVD became the top-selling [[independent film]] on [[Amazon.com]]. In June 2010, ''The Room'' started playing at the [[American Film Institute]] [[AFI Silver|Silver Theatre]] in [[Silver Spring, Maryland]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Siblo |first=Matt |url=http://www.washingtoncitypaper.com/articles/39009/tommy-wiseau-and-the-room-at-afi-silver-theatre-friday |title=Tommy Wiseau and The Room at AFI Silver Theatre: Friday, June 11 through Sunday, June 13 |newspaper=Washington City Paper |date=2010-06-12 |accessdate=2011-01-17}}</ref> ''[[Mystery Science Theater 3000]]'' alumni [[Michael J. Nelson]], [[Kevin Murphy (actor)|Kevin Murphy]], and [[Bill Corbett]] produced an audio commentary track to accompany the movie through their site [[RiffTrax]].com. In 2013, the book ''[[The Disaster Artist]]'', written by [[Greg Sestero]] and [[Tom Bissell]], was published; the book is Sestero's memoir of his involvement in the production of the movie. The book was adapted into an Oscar-nominated film<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BNtvTr4hADk \"Call Me by Your Name\" wins Best Adapted Screenplay-Oscars on YouTube]</ref><ref>[https://www.oscars.org/oscars/ceremonies/2018 2018|Oscars.org]</ref> [[The Disaster Artist (film)|of the same name]], directed by and starring [[James Franco]] as Wiseau (winning a [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actor - Motion Picture Musical or Comedy|Best Actor Golden Globe Award]] for his performance)<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_81Peb7Atc4 James Franco Wins Best Actor, Musical or Comedy at the 2018 Golden Globes]</ref><ref>[https://www.goldenglobes.com/film/disaster-artist Disaster Artist, The|Golden Globes]</ref> and his brother [[Dave Franco]] as Sestero.\n\n=== ''Gigli'' (2003) ===\n\nThe [[Martin Brest]] movie ''[[Gigli]]'' features [[Jennifer Lopez]] and [[Ben Affleck]], with appearances by [[Al Pacino]] and [[Christopher Walken]]. ''Gigli'' was originally a [[black comedy]] with no romantic subplot. The producers demanded script rewrites throughout filming, hoping to cash in on the [[Jennifer Lopez#Ben Affleck|Lopez-Affleck romance]] that was big news in celebrity-watching publications of the time, such as ''[[Us Weekly|Us]]'' and ''[[People (magazine)|People]]''. This film cost $54 million to make but grossed only $6 million, making it one of the biggest box office bombs of all time. ''[[The Times]]'' gave the film a zero, making ''Gigli'' the lowest scored film review in the publication's history at that time.<ref name=\"IBT\">{{cite news|url=http://au.ibtimes.com/articles/271260/20111222/hollywood-s-5-worst-movies.htm#page1 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120110143252/http://au.ibtimes.com/articles/271260/20111222/hollywood-s-5-worst-movies.htm |url-status=dead |archive-date=2012-01-10 |title=Hollywood's Top 5 Worst Movies Ever Made |newspaper=International Business Times |accessdate=2013-06-19 }}</ref> ''[[International Business Times]]'', which included ''Gigli'' in its list of Hollywood's top five worst movies ever made, described reviewers calling it \"the ultimate turkey of all time\".<ref name=\"IBT\"/> ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'' stated that it was \"[t]he worst movie\u2014all right, the worst allegedly major movie\u2014of our admittedly young century\",<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2013/08/01/a-look-back-at-gigli-the-infamous-bennifer-starring-film-on-its-10th-anniversary.html |title=A Look Back at 'Gigli,' the Infamous Bennifer-Starring Film, on Its 10th Anniversary |website=The Daily Beast |date=2013-08-01 |accessdate=2013-09-20}}</ref> while [[Roger Friedman]] of [[Fox News]] claimed it was \"[t]he worst movie ever made\".<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/2003/07/30/gigli-is-up/ |title=The 'Gigli' Is Up |publisher=[[Fox News]]|date=2003-07-30 |accessdate=2013-09-20}}</ref> It was also the winner of seven [[Golden Raspberry Award|Razzies]] (including 2005's Worst \"Comedy\" of Our First 25 Years),<ref name=\"twenty-five\">{{cite web |url=http://www.razzies.com/asp/directory/25thWinners.htm |title=Halle's Feline Fiasco Catwoman and President's Fahrenheit Blunders Tie for 25th Razzie Dis-Honors |work=Razzies.com |accessdate=2011-03-07 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110315210719/http://www.razzies.com/asp/directory/25thWinners.htm |archive-date=2011-03-15 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and in 2010 the film was nominated at the [[30th Golden Raspberry Awards]] for \"Worst Picture of the Decade\".<ref name=\"30thRazzies\"/> It is in [[Rotten Tomatoes]]' Top 100 worst reviewed movies of the 2000s,<ref name=\"rottenworst\"/> where it has a 6% rating.<ref>{{rotten-tomatoes|id=gigli|title=Gigli}}</ref> It was also featured in ''[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]''{{'}}s poll of the 50 worst films ever made,<ref name=\"The 50 Worst Movies Ever\"/> and ''[[AfterEllen.com and TheBacklot.com|AfterEllen]]'' ranked it #1 in its list of the worst films of all time.<ref name=\"afterellen\" />\n\n=== ''Sex Lives of the Potato Men'' (2004) ===\n\nThe British [[sex comedy]] ''[[Sex Lives of the Potato Men]]'' is about a group of potato delivery men. The film received strongly hostile reviews from the British media. Reviews claimed ''Sex Lives of the Potato Men'' was unfunny, disgusting, and depressing.<ref name=\"slotpm1\">[https://web.archive.org/web/20131012015015/http://news.sky.com/story/248096/critics-pan-worst-film-ever Critics Pan \"Worst Film Ever\"] [[Sky News]], 23 February 2004. Retrieved 11 October 2013.</ref> Writing in the ''[[Daily Mirror]]'', film critic Kevin O'Sullivan called ''Sex Lives of the Potato Men'' \"one of the worst films ever made\".<ref>Kevin O'Sullivan, ''The Daily Mirror'', March 5th, 2004, (p.14)</ref> Novelist [[Will Self]], in his review for ''[[The Evening Standard]]'', called ''Sex Lives of the Potato Men'' \"mirthless, worthless, toothless, useless\".<ref name=\"slotpm1\" /> ''[[The Times]]'' reviewer James Christopher dubbed ''Sex Lives of the Potato Men'' \"one of the two most nauseous films ever made ... a masterclass in film-making ineptitude\".<ref name=\"slotpm1\" /> The ''[[Sunday Express]]'' film critic, Henry Fitzherbert, also strongly condemned the film: \"''Sex Lives'' is so awful it left me slack-jawed in disbelief ... it must be one of the worst British comedies.\"<ref>Henry Fitzherbert, ''The Sunday Express'', 22nd February 2004 (p.67).</ref> Catherine Shoard, in a critique in ''[[The Sunday Telegraph]]'', stated \"It's hard to know what to say to this \u2013 it's like finding the right words at a nasty accident ... ''Sex Lives of the Potato Men'' is probably the lewdest Brit-com since ''[[Confessions of a Window Cleaner]]'', and certainly the worst.\" Shoard also described the film as \"Less a film than an appetite suppressant.\"<ref>Catherine Shoard, ''The Sunday Telegraph'', 22nd February 2004.</ref> Alan Morrison in the Scottish ''[[Daily Record (Scotland)|Daily Record]]'' described it as \"puerile smut of the very worst kind ... ''Sex Lives of the Potato Men'' should never have been made\".<ref>\"Review:Sex Lives of the Potato Men''. ''Daily Record'', February 20th, 2004.</ref> ''[[The Irish Times]]'' later noted that \"''Sex Lives of the Potato Men'' attracted some of the worst reviews in living memory.\"<ref>Donald Clarke, \"Out of Office:Interview with Mackenzie Crook\". \"The Ticket\" Magazine, ''The Irish Times'', April 25th, 2008, (p.6).</ref> ''The [[Birmingham Post]]'' described ''Sex Lives of the Potato Men'' as \"quite possibly the worst film ever made\",<ref>Mike Davies, ''The Birmingham Post'', April 24, 2008 (p.&nbsp;13).</ref> while ''[[The Independent on Sunday]]'' stated that the film was \"a strong contender for the title of worst film of all time\".<ref>Matthew Bell, ''Independent on Sunday'', February 8, 2009, (p. 42).</ref> It was also featured in ''[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]''{{'}}s ''50 Worst Movies Ever'' poll.<ref name=\"The 50 Worst Movies Ever\"/> The film has a [[List of films with a 0% rating on Rotten Tomatoes|0% rating]] on [[Rotten Tomatoes]], based on 14 reviews.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://rottentomatoes.com/m/the-sex-lives-of-the-potato-men/ |title=Sex Lives Of The Potato Men on Rotten Tomatoes |publisher=Rottentomatoes.com |date= |accessdate=2015-01-12}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Catwoman'' (2004) ===\n\nNominally based on [[Catwoman|the DC Comics character]], ''[[Catwoman (film)|Catwoman]]'' stars [[Halle Berry]] as the title character. It bears little resemblance to the [[Batman]] antagonist: the cinematic Catwoman has [[superpower (ability)|superpowers]], unlike in the comics, and leaps from rooftop to rooftop in stiletto heels. The character's signature [[spandex|lycra]] [[catsuit]] was replaced with slashed leather trousers and matching [[bra]], and a mask that also acts as a hat. She also has a different name, Patience Phillips, to the established DC Catwoman character, Selina Kyle. As the movie character differs so widely from her comic book source, the character, as portrayed in this film, has been cited as \"Catwoman in Name Only\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.catwomanfan.com/en/film/2004/index.php |title=Catwoman (2004) |accessdate=2009-05-22}}</ref> The film was the result of various rewrites by a total of 28 different screenwriters, though only four were credited after arbitration with the WGA. It has a 9% rating at [[Rotten Tomatoes]],<ref>{{rotten-tomatoes|id=catwoman|title=Catwoman}}</ref> and was declared \"arguably the worst superhero film ever made\" by the ''[[Orlando Sentinel]]''. Jean Lowerison of the ''[[San Diego Metropolitan]]'' said in her review that ''Catwoman'' \"goes on my 'worst' list for the year, and quite possibly for all time\".<ref>{{cite web|author=Jean Lowerison |url=http://sandiegometro.archives.whsites.net/reel/index.php?reelID=713 |title='Catwoman' The cat and the Bratt |publisher=San Diego Metropolitan |accessdate=2011-01-17 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724130824/http://sandiegometro.archives.whsites.net/reel/index.php?reelID=713 |archivedate=2011-07-24 }}</ref> Sadaf Ahsan of the ''[[National Post]]'' went further, calling it the worst movie ever made.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://nationalpost.com/entertainment/movies/writer-of-the-worst-movie-of-all-time-agrees-that-it-was-indeed-the-worst-movie-of-all-time |title=Writer of the worst movie of all time agrees that it was, indeed, the worst movie of all time|last=Ahsan|first=Sadaf|date=February 27, 2018 |accessdate=March 19, 2018}}</ref> ''[[The Village Voice]]'' summed up reviews of the film under the title \"Me-Ouch\".<ref>{{cite news |author=Janet Kim |url=http://www.villagevoice.com/2004-07-20/film/me-ouch/1 |title=Me-Ouch \u2013 Page 1 \u2013 Movies \u2013 New York |newspaper=Village Voice |date=2004-07-20 |accessdate=2011-01-17 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110629162951/http://www.villagevoice.com/2004-07-20/film/me-ouch/1/ |archivedate=2011-06-29 }}</ref> The movie was the winner of four [[25th Golden Raspberry Awards|Razzies]] for Worst Picture, Worst Actress, Worst Director ([[Pitof]]) and Worst Screenplay.<ref name=\"twenty-five\"/> Berry arrived at the ceremony to accept her Razzie in person (with her Best Actress [[Academy Award|Oscar]] for ''[[Monster's Ball]]'' in hand), saying: \"First of all, I want to thank Warner Brothers. Thank you for putting me in a piece of shit, god-awful movie ... It was just what my career needed.\"<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=U-7s_yeQuDg Halle Berry accepts Razzie Award] official Razzie YouTube channel</ref> It is on Roger Ebert's \"most hated\" list<ref name=\"eberthated\"/> and ''[[International Business Times]]'' included it on its list of Hollywood's top 5 worst movies ever made.<ref name=\"IBT\"/>\n\n=== ''Daniel \u2013 Der Zauberer'' (''Daniel \u2013 The Wizard'') (2004) ===\nThe German film ''[[Daniel \u2013 Der Zauberer]]'' was directed by [[Ulli Lommel]] and stars pop singer and ex-''[[Deutschland sucht den Superstar]]'' contestant [[Daniel K\u00fcblb\u00f6ck]], who appeared as a fictionalized version of himself. The title is misleading as it implies that K\u00fcblb\u00f6ck is \"Der Zauberer\" (\"The Wizard\"), while the sorcerer is actually a different character (played by Ulli Lommel, the writer/director of the film). ''[[The Daily Dot]]'' wrote that it is considered to be the worst German film,<ref name=\"DailyDot\">{{cite web|url=https://www.dailydot.com/upstream/worst-movies-on-imdb/|title=Diving into the worst-rated movies on IMDb|date=December 11, 2015|work=[[The Daily Dot]]|accessdate=March 14, 2018}}</ref> while [[n-tv]] said it was \"possibly the worst movie ever made\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.n-tv.de/leute/Filmemacher-Ulli-Lommel-erliegt-Herzinfarkt-article20165706.html|title=Filmemacher Ulli Lommel erliegt Herzinfarkt|date=December 4, 2017|publisher=[[n-tv]]|accessdate=March 14, 2018|language=German}}</ref> The website ''filmstarts.de'' states that ''Daniel \u2013 Der Zauberer'' was \"unbearable for non-fans of K\u00fcblb\u00f6ck\", adding that \"the performances of the actors were some of the worst in the history of German cinema\", and alleging that Ulli Lommel and producer Peter Schamoni had \"damaged their reputation\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.filmstarts.de/kritiken/37527-Daniel-Der-Zauberer.html |title=Daniel \u2013 Der Zauberer \u2013 Film 2004 |publisher=Filmstarts.De |accessdate=2013-11-18}}</ref> \n\nThe film also [[Box-office bomb|performed extremely poorly at the box office]], having only 13.834 viewers altogether, which led to it being withdrawn from screening at most cinemas within the first week,<ref>{{Cite book|last=Astinus|first=A. D.|url=https://books.google.de/books?id=mucWDAAAQBAJ&pg=PT9&lpg=PT9&dq=daniel+der+zauberer+13.834&source=bl&ots=uEmugZlcAu&sig=ACfU3U3o7eW1w18qHQjHnlQPXSU7hBChTw&hl=de&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjX1p6GvZ_oAhUDDewKHRzoABwQ6AEwBHoECAoQAQ#v=onepage&q=daniel%20der%20zauberer%2013.834&f=false|title=Die neun schlechtesten Filme der Kinogeschichte: Die ganze Welt der schlechtesten Kinofilme - Von Daniel, der Zauberer bis Kartoffelsalat \u2013 Nicht fragen!|date=2015-09-30|publisher=neobooks|isbn=978-3-7380-4159-0|language=de}}</ref> with ''[[Rheinische Post|RP Online]]'' referring to it as a \"super-flop\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://rp-online.de/kultur/musik/kueblboeck-als-super-flop_aid-16831093|title=Kinos setzen \"Daniel der Zauberer\" ab: K\u00fcblb\u00f6ck als Super-Flop|last=ONLINE|first=RP|website=RP ONLINE|language=de|access-date=2019-10-04}}</ref> It is consistently listed at IMDb's Bottom 100 list and became the lowest rated film at one point.<ref name=\"NYDN\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/worst-movies-made-gallery-1.3678697|title=The worst movies ever made|last=Lisi|first=Brian|work=[[New York Daily News]]|accessdate=March 14, 2018}}</ref> ''[[Total Film]]'' listed it as the third worst film of all time, after ''[[Superbabies: Baby Geniuses 2]]'' and the direct-to-video animated [[mockbuster]] ''[[Titanic: The Legend Goes On]]'',<ref name=\"TotalFilm\" /> and ''[[New York Daily News]]'' listed it among the seven worst films ever made.<ref name=\"NYDN\" /> In an interview conducted several years after its release, Daniel K\u00fcblb\u00f6ck admitted that, in retrospect, \"[Y]ou have to say this is the worst movie of all time really\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fr-online.de/wiesbaden/ex-dsds-star-daniel-kueblboeck-ist-jetzt-wiesbadener,1472860,3195326.html|title=Daniel K\u00fcblb\u00f6ck ist jetzt Wiesbadener|date=15 February 2009|work=[[Frankfurter Rundschau]]|accessdate=13 September 2013|language=German}}</ref> ''Filmstarts.de'' ranked it #4 in its list of the 25 worst movies ever made,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.filmstarts.de/nachrichten/18494996.html?page=22|title=Die 25 schlechtesten Filme aller Zeiten|last=Filmstarts|website=FILMSTARTS.de|access-date=2019-03-08}}</ref> and on the German movie rating site ''[[Moviepilot.de]]'', it is the lowest-rated film with an average rating of 0.4/10.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.moviepilot.de/filme/schlechteste|title=Die schlechtesten Filme {{!}} moviepilot.de|website=www.moviepilot.de|language=de|access-date=2019-03-08}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Superbabies: Baby Geniuses 2'' (2004) ===\n\nThe family-oriented comedy ''[[Superbabies: Baby Geniuses 2]]'' was the last film directed by [[Bob Clark]] before his death. It is a sequel to the 1999 film ''[[Baby Geniuses]]'' and like its predecessor, it received negative reviews from film critics, becoming the 6th worst reviewed film of the decade on [[Rotten Tomatoes]] with a [[List of films with a 0% rating on Rotten Tomatoes|0% rating]].<ref name=\"rtbg2\">{{cite web|url=https://rottentomatoes.com/m/super_babies_baby_geniuses_2/|title=Rotten Tomatoes|accessdate=3 May 2012}}</ref> Following the plot of the first film, four babies can communicate with each other using 'baby talk', and have knowledge of many secrets. The \"baby geniuses\" become involved in a scheme by media mogul Bill Biscane ([[Jon Voight]]), a notorious kidnapper of children, who intends to use a satellite system to brainwash the world's population and force them to watch television for the rest of their lives. The film was a box office bomb, only receiving $9 million from its $20 million budget. David Cornelius at efilmcritic wondered \"Why would anyone want to make a follow-up to what is universally viewed as one of the very worst movies ever produced is a mystery for the ages.\"<ref name=\"efcsb\">{{cite news|url=http://www.efilmcritic.com/review.php?movie=10542&reviewer=392|title=SuperBabies: Baby Geniuses 2|last=Cornelius|first=David|date=December 15, 2004|work=efilmcritic.com|accessdate=3 May 2012}}</ref> ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' writer Joshua Rivera stated that it was the worst movie he had ever sat through,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://ew.com/article/2015/01/16/popwatch-confessional-worst-kids-movies/|title=PopWatch Confessional: The worst movie a kid has made you sit through|date=January 16, 2015|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|accessdate=April 3, 2018}}</ref> and Tom Long of ''The Deseret News'' said \"It is perhaps the most incompetent and least funny comic film ever made.\"<ref name=\"dnsb\">{{cite news|url=http://www.deseretnews.com/article/700003619/SuperBabies-Baby-Geniuses-2.html|title=SuperBabies: Baby Geniuses 2|last=Long|first=Tom|date=Nov 17, 2004|work=Deseret News|accessdate=3 May 2012}}</ref> It was nominated for four Golden Raspberry Awards including Worst Picture, Worst Director ([[Bob Clark]]), Worst Supporting Actor ([[Jon Voight]]) and Worst Screenplay ([[Steven Paul]] (story) & Gregory Poppen).<ref name=\"dtsb\">{{cite news|url=http://www.dailytimes.com.pk/default.asp?page=story_26-1-2005_pg9_6|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131111023112/http://www.dailytimes.com.pk/default.asp?page=story_26-1-2005_pg9_6|url-status=dead|archive-date=November 11, 2013|title='Catwoman' battles President Bush for worst acting prize|date=January 26, 2005|work=Daily Times|accessdate=3 May 2012}}</ref> ''[[Total Film]]'' named it the runner-up to ''[[Titanic: The Legend Goes On]]'' in its list of the worst films ever made,<ref name=\"TotalFilm\" /> and ''[[Mental Floss]]'' selected it as the second worst movie ever made after ''[[Ballistic: Ecks vs. Sever]]''.<ref name=\"Mental Floss\"/> It also briefly unseated ''Manos: The Hands of Fate'' from the top spot on IMDb's bottom 100 list.<ref name=\"smbg\">{{cite news|url=https://www.slantmagazine.com/film/review/superbabies-baby-geniuses-2/1318|title=Superbabies: Baby Geniuses 2|last=Henderson|first=Eric|date=January 31, 2005|work=Slant Magazine|accessdate=3 May 2012}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Alone in the Dark'' (2005) ===\n[[File:UweBollRampage3SHORTREVIEW1.jpg|thumb|[[Uwe Boll]] won a [[Stinkers Bad Movie Awards|Stinkers Awards]] for Worst Director and received the [[Golden Raspberry Awards#Worst Career Achievement|Worst Career Achievement]] award at the [[29th Golden Raspberry Awards]]]]\nLoosely based on a [[Alone in the Dark|series of video games]] by [[Infogrames]] and directed by [[Uwe Boll]], the German-Canadian-American film ''[[Alone in the Dark (2005 film)|Alone in the Dark]]'' was panned by critics for a multitude of reasons, including poor script and production values, quick cuts to optimize the gory content, almost no connection to the game, and bad acting. The movie has received a 1% rating at [[Rotten Tomatoes]],<ref>{{rotten-tomatoes|id=alone_in_the_dark|title=Alone in the Dark}}</ref> and was included in their Top 100 worst reviewed movies of the 2000s at number two.<ref name=\"rottenworst\"/> It appeared on Metacritic's list of the all-time lowest-scoring films,<ref name=\"Metacritic\"/> is on the MRQE's 50 Worst Movies list,<ref name=\"MRQE50\"/> and is one of the few films to have received an [[CinemaScore#List of F films|F rating]] on [[CinemaScore]].<ref name=\"CinemaScore\">{{cite news |last=Lincoln |first=Kevin |title=What the 19 Movies to Ever Receive an 'F' CinemaScore Have in Common |url=https://www.vulture.com/2017/09/here-are-the-only-19-movies-to-ever-receive-an-f-cinemascore.html |work=[[https://vulture.com|Vulture]] |date=September 20, 2017 |accessdate=January 17, 2019}}</ref>  Roger Moore of ''The [[Orlando Sentinel]]'' stated: \"''Alone in the Dark'' shows just how tenuous ''[[Plan 9 from Outer Space]]'' 's hold on that 'worst movie ever' title really is.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.orlandosentinel.com/entertainment/movies/orl-db-moviereviews-searchresults,0,3279701,results.formprofile?turbine_cdb_lib__cdb_01_txt=Alone%20in%20the%20Dark&Find+it!=Submit+Query |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110629101527/http://www.orlandosentinel.com/entertainment/movies/orl-db-moviereviews-searchresults,0,3279701,results.formprofile?turbine_cdb_lib__cdb_01_txt=Alone%20in%20the%20Dark&Find+it!=Submit+Query |url-status=dead |archive-date=2011-06-29 |title=Alone in the Dark |newspaper=The Orlando Sentinel |date=2005-01-28 |accessdate=2014-06-13 |first=Roger |last=Moore }}</ref> Likewise, Peter Hartlaub, the ''[[San Francisco Chronicle]]'''s pop culture critic, called the film \"the best Ed Wood movie ever made ... a film so mind-blowingly horrible that it teeters on the edge of cinematic immortality\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sfgate.com/movies/article/FILM-CLIPS-Also-opening-today-2702523.php#alone |title=Film Clips / Also opening today |newspaper=San Francisco Chronicle |date=2005-01-28 |accessdate=2013-11-18 |first=Ruthe |last=Stein}}</ref> In 2009, he named it the worst film of the decade.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2010/01/01/MV9A1BAHMM.DTL&type=movies | work=The San Francisco Chronicle | title=Decade in review: Hartlaub's movie choices | date=2010-07-30}}</ref> Jeffrey Lyles of ''The Gazette'' considered it so bad that \"other legendary bad films ... await a film of this magnitude because it gets awfully lonely on the island of misfit movies\",<ref>{{cite news|url=http://ww2.gazette.net/gazette_archive/2005/200505/entertainment/moviefeat/258216-1.html |title='Dark' is dreary |newspaper=[[The Gazette (Maryland)]] |date=2005-02-02 |accessdate=2013-11-18}}</ref> while Scott Nash of ''Three Movie Buffs'' dubbed it \"one of the worst movies ever made\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://rottentomatoes.com/m/alone_in_the_dark/reviews/ |title=Alone in the Dark |website=Rotten Tomatoes |accessdate=2014-06-13}}</ref> Screenwriter Blair Erickson wrote about his experience dealing with Boll and his original script, which was closer to the actual game itself, and Boll's script change demands on the comedy website ''[[Something Awful]]''.<ref>{{cite news | title = Behind the Scenes: Uwe Boll and Uwe Boll's Alone In the Dark | url = https://somethingawful.com/feature-articles/behind-scenes-uwe/1/ | first = Blair | last = Erickson | date = 2005-02-02 | publisher = Something Awful}}</ref> It received two [[2005 Golden Raspberry Awards]] nominations for Worst Director (Uwe Boll) and Worst Actress ([[Tara Reid]]), and won three 2005 [[Stinkers Bad Movie Awards|Stinkers Awards]], for Worst Picture, Worst Director, and Worst Special Effects.<ref name=\"2005stinkers\">{{cite web|last=Weinberg |first=Scott |url=https://rottentomatoes.com/news/1646425/2005_stinker_awards_announced |title=2005 Stinker Awards Announced! |website=Rotten Tomatoes |date=2006-03-03 |accessdate=2011-01-17}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Aag'' (2007) ===\n\n''[[Aag (2007 film)|Aag]]'' is a remake of one of the most successful [[Bollywood]] films, ''[[Sholay]]'', directed by [[Ram Gopal Varma]]. [[Rajeev Masand]] gave it a zero out of five.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ibnlive.in.com/news/review-rgv-ki-aag-is-rgv-ka-daag/47834-8.html|title=Review: RGV Ki Aag is RGV ka daag}}</ref> ''[[Times of India]]'' stated that ''Aag'' \"destroyed Bollywood's greatest film\" and acknowledged that some \"consider it the world's worst film\".<ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2010-12-31/news-interviews/28236351_1_rakhi-sawant-salman-khan-vivek-oberoi |title=A Decade of decadence |newspaper=[[Times of India]] |date=2010-12-31 |accessdate=2013-08-25}}</ref> ''[[Hindustan Times]]'' awarded it the \"Lifetime's Worst Ever Movie Award\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/Entertainment/Reviews/Review-Ram-Gopal-Varma-Ki-Aag/Article1-245543.aspx |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111117015847/http://www.hindustantimes.com/Entertainment/Reviews/Review-Ram-Gopal-Varma-Ki-Aag/Article1-245543.aspx |url-status=dead |archive-date=2011-11-17 |title=Review: Ram Gopal Varma Ki Aag |newspaper=[[Hindustan Times]] |date=2007-08-31 |accessdate=2013-08-25 }}</ref> It came in first in a ''[[FHM (India)|FHM India]]'' list of the 57 worst movies ever made.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fhmindia.com/57-worst-films-ever-ii/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120912012157/http://www.fhmindia.com/57-worst-films-ever-ii/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=2012-09-12 |title=57 Worst Films Ever \u2013 II |publisher=[[FHM (India)]] |accessdate=2013-08-25 }}</ref> ''[[Total Film]]'' included it in their list of the 66 worst films of all time.<ref name=TotalFilm/> [[Amitabh Bachchan]], who appeared in the original film and returned for the remake, later admitted that the film was \"a mistake\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.digitalspy.com/bollywood/news/a329312/amitabh-bachchan-ram-gopal-varma-ki-aag-a-mistake.html |title= Amitabh Bachchan: 'Ram Gopal Varma Ki Aag a mistake' |website=[[Digital Spy]]|accessdate=2013-08-25}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Epic Movie'' (2007) ===\n\n''[[Epic Movie]]'' is a [[parody film]] by [[Jason Friedberg and Aaron Seltzer]] that mainly parodies [[Epic film|epic]] and [[Fantasy film|fantasy movies]], most notably ''[[The Chronicles of Narnia: The Lion, the Witch and the Wardrobe]]'' and the ''[[Harry Potter (film series)|Harry Potter]]'' films, but also contains references to all kinds of other then-popular films. Like most works of Frieberg and Seltzer, it received extremely negative reviews, holding an approval rating of 2% on [[Rotten Tomatoes]],<ref>{{Citation|title=Epic Movie (2007)|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/epic_movie|language=en|access-date=2019-02-25}}</ref> and a [[Metacritic]] score of 17/100, indicating \"overwhelming dislike\".<ref>{{Citation|title=Epic Movie|url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/epic-movie|access-date=2019-02-25}}</ref> Harry Fletcher of the ''[[Evening Standard|Standard]]'' said: \"Filmmakers and trash-peddlers Jason Friedberg and Aaron Seltzer have been responsible for some of the most pointless, lazy and unforgivable movies of the past decade and frankly, they need to be stopped. ''[[Disaster Movie]]'', ''[[300 (film)|300]]'' spoof ''[[Meet the Spartans]]'' and awful ''[[The Hunger Games (film)|Hunger Games]]'' mickey-take ''[[The Starving Games]]'' could easily have made this list of the worst movies ever made, but ''Epic Movie'' might be the worst of the lot. It offers the most uninspired, unfunny film pastiches imaginable, sometimes repeating entire sections of dialogue verbatim from the movies they\u2019re supposedly satirising.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/go/london/film/the-12-worst-films-ever-made-a3838756.html|title=The 12 worst films ever made|date=2018-05-15|website=Evening Standard|language=en|access-date=2019-02-25}}</ref> [[Nathan Rabin]] gave it an F score and said, \"''Epic Movie'' [...] strays so far from the solid fundamentals of filmmaking that it calls the very foundation of humor into question.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://film.avclub.com/epic-movie-1798202359|title=Epic Movie|last=Rabin|first=Nathan|website=Film|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-25}}</ref> Josh Rosenblatt of ''[[The Austin Chronicle]]'' said: \"I\u2019ve rarely seen a movie as hostile as this one, both to its audience and to its protagonists, and I don\u2019t think I realized before just how mean-spirited comedy can get (and I was raised on the Three Stooges).\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.austinchronicle.com/events/film/2007-01-26/438452/|title=Movie Review: Epic Movie|website=www.austinchronicle.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-25}}</ref> Jamie Russell of the [[BBC]] called it \"the most excruciating, unfunny film you'll see this year\u2026 if not your entire lifetime.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/films/2007/02/05/epic_movie_2007_review.shtml|title=BBC - Movies - review - Epic Movie|website=www.bbc.co.uk|access-date=2019-02-25}}</ref> At the [[28th Golden Raspberry Awards]], it received three nominations, for ''Worst Remake or Rip-off'', ''Worst Screenplay'' and ''Worst Supporting Actress'' ([[Carmen Electra]]). It is included in ''[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]''<nowiki/>'s and ''[[Flavorwire]]''<nowiki/>'s lists of the 50 worst movies ever made,<ref name=\"The 50 Worst Movies Ever\" /><ref name=\"Flavorwire\" /> ''[[Evening Standard|Standard]]''<nowiki/>'s list of the 12 worst films ever made, [[Movie Review Query Engine|MRQE]]'s 50 worst movies list<ref name=\"MRQE50\" /> and ''[[Newsweek]]''<nowiki/>'s list of the 50 worst comedy movies of all time.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/worst-comedy-movies-all-time-ranked-1071735|title=The worst comedy films of all time, from 'Scary Movie 5' to 'The Hottie & the Nottie'|last=Sim|first=David|last2=AM|first2=Eve Watling On 8/14/18 at 8:08|date=2018-08-14|website=Newsweek|language=en|access-date=2019-02-25}}</ref>\n\n=== ''I Know Who Killed Me'' (2007) ===\n''[[I Know Who Killed Me]]'' is a [[psychological thriller]] film directed by [[Chris Sivertson]] and starring [[Lindsay Lohan]] as identical twins, one of whom insists her identity is that of another woman after being abducted by a [[serial killer]]. At the [[28th Golden Raspberry Awards]], it set a record for most awards won in a single year by winning eight awards and it received two further nominations at the [[30th Golden Raspberry Awards]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2008/SHOWBIZ/Movies/02/23/razzie.awards/|title=Lohan's 'Killed Me' sets worst-film record - CNN.com|publisher=[[CNN]]|author=Leopold, Todd|date=February 23, 2008|accessdate=February 12, 2019}}</ref> The ''[[How Did This Get Made?]]'' podcast questioned, \"Is this the worst movie Lindsay Lohan has ever been in or flat out the worst movie ever?\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.earwolf.com/episode/i-know-who-killed-me/ |title= I Know Who Killed Me |publisher=[[Earwolf]]|work=[[How Did This Get Made?]]|date=October 18, 2011|accessdate=February 12, 2019}}</ref> [[Richard Roeper]] selected the film as the worst of the 2000s.<ref>{{cite book |first=Croft |last=Ally |url=https://books.google.com/?id=XOMzAgAAQBAJ&pg=PT87&dq=I+know+who+killed+me+richard+roeper#v=onepage&q=I%20know%20who%20killed%20me%20richard%20roeper&f=false|title= The Lindsay Lohan Story |publisher=[[Orion Publishing Group]] |year=2012 |isbn=978-1409136378}}</ref> Gabe Delahaye of ''[[Stereogum]]'' reviewed ''I Know Who Killed Me'' as part of his search for the worst movie ever made, writing that: \"Out of all the possible Worst Movies of All Time so far, none has been as painful to actually watch as I Know Who Killed Me\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.stereogum.com/1779984/the_hunt_for_the_worst_movie_o_10/vg-loc/videogum/|title=The Hunt For The Worst Movie Of All Time: I Know Who Killed Me|work=[[Stereogum]]|last=Delahaye|first=Gabe|date=June 23, 2008|accessdate=February 12, 2019}}</ref> It was named the 34th worst movie ever made in ''[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]''{{'}}s ''50 Worst Movies Ever'' poll<ref name=\"The 50 Worst Movies Ever\"/> and [[AfterEllen.com and TheBacklot.com|After Ellen]] named it the second worst ever made, after ''[[Gigli]]''.<ref name=\"afterellen\"/> MRQE includes it on its 50 Worst Movies list,<ref name=\"MRQE50\"/> and it has a rare [[CinemaScore#List of F films|F rating]] on [[CinemaScore]].<ref name=\"CinemaScore\"/>\n\n=== ''Meet the Spartans'' (2008) ===\nAnother 2008 parody movie by [[Jason Friedberg and Aaron Seltzer]], ''[[Meet the Spartans]]'' mainly parodied the movie ''[[300 (film)|300]]'', but contained numerous other pop cultural references as well. Like most Friedberg and Seltzer projects, it received extremely negative reviews, holding an approval rating of 2% on Rotten Tomatoes, with the consensus reading: \"A tired, unfunny, offensive waste of time, ''Meet the Spartans'' scrapes the bottom of the cinematic barrel.\",<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/meet_the_spartans|title=Meet the Spartans (2008)|last=|first=|date=|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango]]|access-date=April 17, 2019}}</ref> and a Metacritic score of 9/100, indicating \"overwhelming dislike\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/meet-the-spartans|title=Meet the Spartans|last=|first=|date=|website=[[Metacritic]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|access-date=April 17, 2019}}</ref> [[Josh Levin]] of ''[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]'' called it the worst movie he had ever seen.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://slate.com/culture/2008/01/meet-the-spartans-another-terrible-spoof-movie-from-the-nongeniuses-who-brought-you-date-movie-and-epic-movie.html|title=Meet the Spartans: another terrible spoof movie from the nongeniuses who brought you Date Movie and Epic Movie.|last=Levin|first=Josh|date=2008-01-30|website=Slate Magazine|language=en|access-date=2019-03-04}}</ref> It is included in ''[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]''<nowiki/>'s<ref name=\"The 50 Worst Movies Ever\" /> and ''[[Flavorwire|Flavorwire'<nowiki/>]]''s<ref name=\"Flavorwire\" /> lists of the 50 worst movies ever made, ''[[News.com.au]]''<nowiki/>'s list of the 15 worst films of all time,<ref name=\":1\" /> Metacritic's list of the all-time lowest-scoring films<ref name=\"Metacritic\" /> and [[Movie Review Query Engine|MRQE]]'s 50 Worst Movies list.<ref name=\"MRQE50\" /> At the [[29th Golden Raspberry Awards]], it received five nominations, including Worst Picture.\n\n<nowiki/>''[[Flavorwire|<nowiki/>]]''<nowiki/>''[[Flavorwire|<nowiki/>]]''<nowiki/><nowiki/>''[[Flavorwire|<nowiki/>]]''<nowiki/>''[[Flavorwire|<nowiki/>]]''<nowiki/>''[[Flavorwire|<nowiki/>]]''<nowiki/>''[[Flavorwire|<nowiki/>]]''\n\n=== ''Disaster Movie'' (2008) ===\n\n''[[Disaster Movie]]'' is a [[parody film]] written and directed by [[Jason Friedberg and Aaron Seltzer]], spoofing films in the [[Disaster films|disaster film]] genre. The film, like most films by Friedberg and Seltzer, received extremely negative reviews, and has a 1% rating on [[Rotten Tomatoes]] based on 73 reviews. The site's consensus states: \"Returning to their seemingly bottomless well of flatulence humor, racial stereotypes, and stale pop culture gags, Friedberg and Seltzer have produced what is arguably their worst ''Movie'' yet\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://rottentomatoes.com/m/disaster_movie/|title=Disaster Movie \u2013 Rotten Tomatoes|website=Rotten Tomatoes|accessdate=June 3, 2013}}</ref> It was ranked by Rotten Tomatoes as one of the worst reviewed films of the 2000s.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.cnn.com/2009/SHOWBIZ/Movies/09/25/decades.worst.movies.tomatoes/ | title = Site picks worst movies of the decade | work=[[CNN]] | date= 2009-09-25 | accessdate = 2013-04-17}}</ref> [[Jason Solomons]] of ''[[The Guardian]]'' stated that \"Nothing can convey the grimness of ''Disaster Movie'', which would be the Worst Movie Ever Made were it actually a movie at all.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Solomons|first=Jason|title=Disaster Movie|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2008/sep/07/comedy|work=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=June 3, 2013 | date=September 6, 2008|location=London}}</ref> Adam Tobias of ''[[Watertown Daily Times]]'' claimed that \"I just don't see how anyone could not find ''Disaster Movie'' one of the worst films of all time.\" Tobias went on to write that the title was appropriate because the film is \"a disaster\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Tobias|first=Adam|title=Disaster Movie one of the worst films of all time|url=http://www.wdtimes.com/features/screen_scenes/article_a665de71-6454-5ce5-9454-d13b9ad9ee18.html|work=[[Watertown Daily Times]]|accessdate=June 3, 2013|date=September 5, 2008}}</ref> It was featured in [[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]'s ''50 Worst Movies Ever'' poll,<ref name=\"The 50 Worst Movies Ever\"/> [[Total Film]]'s ''66 Worst Movies Ever'' list<ref name=TotalFilm /> Metacritic's list of the all-time lowest-scoring films,<ref name=\"Metacritic\"/> and the MRQE's 50 Worst Movies list (where it holds a score of 17, the lowest score on the site).<ref name=\"MRQE50\"/> ''Disaster Movie'' became the lowest ranked film on [[Internet Movie Database|IMDb]]'s Bottom 100 list days after its premiere<ref name=\"vh1.com\">{{cite web | url = http://www.vh1.com/celebrity/2008-09-05/update-disaster-movie-is-the-worst-collection-of-things-posing-as-a-movie-of-all-time | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20130927040609/http://www.vh1.com/celebrity/2008-09-05/update-disaster-movie-is-the-worst-collection-of-things-posing-as-a-movie-of-all-time | url-status = dead | archive-date = 2013-09-27 | title = Disaster Movie is the worst [Collection of things posing as a] movie of all time | work=[[VH1]] | date= 2008-09-05 | accessdate = 2013-04-17}}</ref><ref name=\"Byrnes\">{{cite news|last=Byrnes|first=Paul|title=Disaster Movie|url=https://www.smh.com.au/news/entertainment/film/film-reviews/disaster-movie/2008/10/02/1222651235778.html|work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|accessdate=June 3, 2013|date=October 2, 2008}}</ref> and it received a rare [[CinemaScore#List of F films|F rating]] on [[CinemaScore]].<ref name=\"CinemaScore\"/> The film is also notable for being the motion picture debut of [[Kim Kardashian]], whose performance garnered a nomination for [[Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Supporting Actress|Worst Supporting Actress]] at the [[29th Golden Raspberry Awards]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Fleeman|first=Mike|title=Kim Kardashian: Thanks for the Razzie Nomination! |url=http://www.peoplestylewatch.com/people/stylewatch/redcarpet/2009/article/0,,20249205_20254091,00.html|work=[[People (magazine)|People]]|accessdate=June 3, 2013|date=January 21, 2009}}</ref> It received five additional Razzie nominations.\n\n=== ''The Hottie and the Nottie'' (2008) ===\n\nThe romantic comedy ''[[The Hottie and the Nottie]]'' starring [[Paris Hilton]], [[Joel Moore]], [[Christine Lakin]], and [[The Greg Wilson]] opened to poor box-office takings and strongly negative reviews with a 5% rating on [[Rotten Tomatoes]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/hottie_and_the_nottie|title=The Hottie and the Nottie (2008)|last=|first=|date=|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango]]|access-date=12 July 2018}}</ref> The British newspaper ''[[The Sunday People|The People]]'', reviewing ''The Hottie and the Nottie'', claimed \"Paris Hilton is the world's worst actress and she's starring in the worst movie ever made.\"<ref name=\"tp\">{{cite news|title=The Hottie and the Nottie Review|date=March 23, 2008|newspaper=The People|location=London, England|quote=Disaster Of Paris; Bimbo is worst actress ever}}</ref> Nathan Lee of ''[[The Village Voice]]'' called it \"crass, shrill, disingenuous, tawdry, mean-spirited, vulgar, idiotic, boring, slapdash, half-assed, and very, very unfunny\".<ref>{{cite web|author=Nathan Lee |url=http://www.villagevoice.com/2008-01-29/film/the-hottie-and-the-nottie |title=Village Voice Review |publisher=Villagevoice.com |date=2008-01-29 |accessdate=2012-12-06}}</ref> Online film critic [[James Berardinelli]] described the film's comedy as \"about as funny as the anal [[rape]] scene in ''[[The War Zone]]''\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.reelviews.net/movies/h/hottie_nottie.html |title=James Berardinelli review |publisher=Reelviews.net |date=2007-05-13 |accessdate=2012-12-06}}</ref> [[Richard Roeper]] called it \"excruciatingly, painfully, horribly, terribly awful\", and argued that \"nobody in this movie really should have a career in movies\".<ref name=\"thatn\">{{cite web |url=https://rottentomatoes.com/m/hottie_and_the_nottie/ |website=Rotten Tomatoes |title=The Hottie and The Nottie |accessdate=25 October 2014 }}</ref> Connie Ogle in the ''[[Miami Herald]]'' described ''The Hottie and the Nottie'' thus: \"Imagine the worst movie you've ever seen. Got it? Now try to think of something worse. That something is this movie \u2013 wretched, embarrassing and a waste of the time and energy of everyone involved.\"<ref name=\"thatn\"/> The film appears on Metacritic's list of the all-time lowest-scoring films,<ref name=\"Metacritic\"/> and the MRQE's 50 Worst Movies list.<ref name=\"MRQE50\"/>\n\n== 2010s ==\n\n=== ''Birdemic: Shock and Terror'' (2010) ===\n[[File:Rifftrax_live_show_birdemic.jpg|thumb|right|[[Bill Corbett]], [[Michael J. Nelson|Mike Nelson]], and [[Kevin Murphy (actor)|Kevin Murphy]] during the live [[Rifftrax]] of [[Birdemic: Shock and Terror|''Birdemic'']]]]\nAn independently produced film that is an apparent homage to [[Alfred Hitchcock]]'s ''[[The Birds (film)|The Birds]]'', ''[[Birdemic: Shock and Terror]]'' tells the story of a romance between the two leading characters, played by Alan Bagh and Whitney Moore, as their small town is attacked by birds (which do not appear until 47 minutes into the film). Written, directed, and produced by James Nguyen, it was intended as a \"romantic thriller\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.viceland.com/blogs/en/2010/02/12/james-nguyens-birdemic-is-the-new-best-worst-movie-ever/ |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120914135451/http://www.viceland.com/blogs/en/2010/02/12/james-nguyens-birdemic-is-the-new-best-worst-movie-ever/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=2012-09-14 |title=Birdemic Has Romance and Suspense and All That |publisher=Viceland Today |date=2010-02-12 |accessdate=2011-04-16}}</ref> but is notable due to its poor quality, with reviewers calling out its wooden acting, bad dialogue, amateurish sound and editing, nonsensical plot and, in particular, its special effects, consisting primarily of poorly rendered computer generated eagles and vultures that perform physically awkward aerial maneuvers and explode upon impact with the ground. The film, which cost $10,000 to make,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/8604858.stm |title=Is Birdemic worst film ever made? |work=BBC News |date=2010-04-06 |accessdate=2011-04-16}}</ref> was called by the ''[[Huffington Post]]'' \"truly, one of the worst films ever made\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/review-embirdemic-shock-a_b_491140|first=Fabio|last=Periera |title=Review: Birdemic: Shock and Terror |work=HuffPost |date=2010-03-09 |accessdate=2019-12-03}}</ref> and by ''[[The Village Voice]]'' as \"one more in the pantheon of beloved trash-terpieces\".<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.villagevoice.com/2010-03-30/film/birdemic-shock-and-terror-one-more-for-the-trash-terpiece-heap/ |title=Birdemic: Shock and Terror, One More for the Trash-terpiece Heap |newspaper=The Village Voice |date=2010-03-30 |accessdate=2011-04-16 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110320100812/http://www.villagevoice.com/2010-03-30/film/birdemic-shock-and-terror-one-more-for-the-trash-terpiece-heap/ |archivedate=2011-03-20 }}</ref> ''[[Flavorwire]]'' ranked it #1 in its list of the 50 worst films ever made.<ref name=\"Flavorwire\"/> ''[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]'' deemed it among the worst movies ever made,<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.slate.com/id/2249870/pagenum/all/#p2 |title=The Worst Movies Ever Made |magazine=Slate |last1=Weiner|first1=Jonah|date=2010-04-06 |accessdate=2011-04-16}}</ref> while ''[[Salon (magazine)|Salon]]'' referred to it as \"a cult hit among bad-movie fans\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.salon.com/entertainment/movies/film_salon/2011/02/25/birdemic_review |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110228043216/http://www.salon.com/entertainment/movies/film_salon/2011/02/25/birdemic_review |url-status=dead |archive-date=2011-02-28 |title=\"Birdemic\": The magic of atrocious CGI, confirmed |work=Salon |date=2011-02-25 |accessdate=2011-05-06 }}</ref> and ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' stated that the film displayed \"all the revered hallmarks of hilariously bad filmmaking\".<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://variety.com/review/VE1117942491?refcatid=31 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110629203625/https://variety.com/review/VE1117942491?refcatid=31 |url-status=dead |archive-date=2011-06-29 |title=Variety Reviews \u2013 Birdemic: Shock and Terror |magazine=Variety |date=2010-03-29 |accessdate=2011-05-06 |first=Ronnie |last=Scheib}}</ref> Following the home media release of ''Birdemic'', [[Michael J. Nelson]], [[Kevin Murphy (actor)|Kevin Murphy]], and [[Bill Corbett]] of ''[[Mystery Science Theater 3000]]'' fame produced an audio commentary track to accompany the movie through [[Rifftrax]]. They later riffed upon the film again theatrically.<ref>{{cite web|author=eas106 |url=http://www.fandango.com/rifftraxlive:birdemic_157390/movieoverview |title=RiffTrax Live: Birdemic (2012) Movie Tickets, Reviews, and Photos |work=Fandango.com |date=2012-10-25 |accessdate=2013-11-18}}</ref> In response to the cult status of the first film, a sequel\u2014''[[Birdemic 2: The Resurrection]]''\u2014was released in 2013, and included many returning members of the cast and crew.\n\n=== ''The Last Airbender'' (2010) ===\n\n''[[The Last Airbender]]'' is a fantasy/adventure film written, produced, and directed by [[M. Night Shyamalan]] and is based on the [[Nicktoon]] ''[[Avatar: The Last Airbender]]''. Upon release, the film received extremely negative reviews, with critics panning the bad acting, numerous [[plot hole]]s, screenplay, poor special effects (despite its reported $150 million budget), and especially Shyamalan's directing. It was also ridiculed for the poor quality of its [[2D to 3D conversion|post-converted 3-D]], and the casting of white and Indian actors to portray characters who were East Asian or [[Inuit]] in the source material triggered accusations of racism and [[whitewashing in film|whitewashing]].<ref>{{cite news|author=Graeme McMillan|title=Avatar Casting Makes Fans See... White|accessdate=2008-12-19|date=2008-12-17|url=http://io9.com/5111680/avatar-casting-makes-fans-see-white| work=[[io9]]| publisher=[[Gawker Media]]}}</ref> Further criticism came from fans of the original cartoon series, who said the film differed tremendously from its critically acclaimed source material. David Onda of [[Comcast]] wrote that it \"has been called one of the worst ever made. The movie was universally panned by critics and failed to make back its production budget domestically.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Onda|first=David|title=The Last Airbender|url=http://xfinity.comcast.net/slideshow/entertainment-franchiseflops/10/|work=Comcast|accessdate=22 December 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131224104351/http://xfinity.comcast.net/slideshow/entertainment-franchiseflops/10/|archivedate=24 December 2013}}</ref> It garnered nine nominations at the [[31st Golden Raspberry Awards]], and won five, including Worst Picture and Worst Director.<ref>{{cite journal | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-12589752 | journal=BBC News | date= 27 February 2011 | title=M Night Shyamalan's Last Airbender wins Razzie Awards | accessdate=2011-02-27 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=The 31st Annual Razzie Awards|url=http://razzies.com/history/11winners.asp|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130103033553/http://razzies.com/history/11winners.asp|archivedate=2013-01-03}}</ref> [[Roger Ebert]] wrote, \"''The Last Airbender'' is an agonizing experience in every category I can think of and others still waiting to be invented. The laws of chance suggest that something should have gone right. Not here. It puts a nail in the coffin of low-rent 3D, but it will need a lot more coffins than that.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Ebert|first=Roger|title=The Last Airbender|url=https://rogerebert.com/reviews/the-last-airbender-2010|work=Chicago Sun-Times|accessdate=22 December 2013}}</ref> When asked if ''Last Airbender'' had been the worst film he has ever seen, Mike Ryan of ''[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]'' answered, \"Yes\".<ref>{{cite web|last=Ryan|first=Mike|title=25 Questions You May Have About The Last Airbender|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/online/oscars/2010/07/25-questions-you-may-have-about-the-last-airbender|work=Vanity Fair|date=July 1, 2010|accessdate=22 December 2013}}</ref> ''[[Hi (magazine)|Hi]]'' highlighted the film in their \"Worst Films Ever\" series,<ref>{{cite web|last1=Wilson|first1=Natasha|title=The Worst Films Ever: The Last Airbender|url=http://www.hihimag.com/hi/ents/film/2013/08/the-worst-films-ever-the-last-airbender/|website=Hi! Magazine|accessdate=29 June 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140808051629/http://www.hihimag.com/hi/ents/film/2013/08/the-worst-films-ever-the-last-airbender/|archive-date=2014-08-08|url-status=dead}}</ref> and [[Screen Rant]] and ''[[Digital Trends]]'' included it in their worst film lists.<ref name=\"Screen Rant\"/><ref name=\"digitaltrends\"/>\n\n=== ''Bucky Larson: Born to Be a Star'' (2011) ===\n''[[Bucky Larson: Born to Be a Star]]'' was produced by [[Adam Sandler]]'s [[Happy Madison Productions]] and featured [[Nick Swardson]] in the titular role as a small-town manchild who pursues a career in the [[pornographic film]] industry after learning that his parents were [[Pornographic film actor|porn star]]s in the 1970s. On [[Rotten Tomatoes]], ''Bucky Larson'' has a [[List of films with a 0% rating on Rotten Tomatoes|0% rating]] based on 35 reviews.<ref name=\"BuckyRotten\">{{cite news| title=Bucky Larson: Born to Be a Star (2011)|website=Rotten Tomatoes|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/bucky_larson_born_to_be_a_star/reviews/| accessdate= August 11, 2017 }}</ref> Linda Cook of the ''[[Quad-City Times]]'' described the film as \"the worst of the worst\",<ref>{{cite news|url=http://qctimes.com/entertainment/columnists/linda-cook/bucky-is-the-worst-of-the-worst/article_77c4eeea-dd6b-11e0-93fe-001cc4c03286.html|title='Bucky' is the worst of the worst|newspaper=[[Quad-City Times]]|last=Cook|first=Linda|date=September 12, 2011|accessdate=August 11, 2017}}</ref> while ''hollywoodchicago.com'' called it \"one of the worst comedies of all time\".<ref name=\"BuckyRotten\"/> In listing it as one of the ten worst comedies ever, [[Michael Musto]] stated that ''Bucky Larson'' was \"a badness the world had forgotten was capable of existing\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theblot.com/10-worst-film-comedies-ever-made-7720429|title=The 10 worst comedies ever made|last=Musto|first=Michael|work=The Blot Magazine|date=June 12, 2014|accessdate=August 11, 2017}}</ref> [[Screen Rant]] included it in its list of the 25 worst movies in film history and [[Mental Floss]] named it the fifth worst movie ever.<ref name=\"Screen Rant\">{{cite news|url=https://screenrant.com/worst-movies-list-all-time/|title=25 Worst Movies in Film History|last=Kendrick|first=Ben|work=[[Screen Rant]]|date=November 13, 2015|accessdate=August 11, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Mental Floss\">{{cite news|url=http://mentalfloss.com/article/503248/15-worst-movies-ever-made|title=The 15 Worst Movies Ever Made|last=Wood|first=Jennifer M|work=[[Mental Floss]]|date=August 10, 2017|accessdate=August 11, 2017}}</ref> ''Bucky Larson'' also appears on MRQE's 50 Worst Movies list,<ref name=\"MRQE50\"/> and Metacritic's list of the all-time lowest-scoring films.<ref name=\"Metacritic\"/> The film earned six nominations at the [[32nd Golden Raspberry Awards]], but lost in every category to ''[[Jack and Jill (2011 film)|Jack and Jill]]'', which was also produced by Happy Madison Productions.<ref name=RazzieWin/>\n\n=== ''Jack and Jill'' (2011) ===\n[[File:Adam Sandler 2011 (Cropped).jpg|thumb|[[Adam Sandler]] starred in ''[[Jack and Jill (2011 film)|Jack and Jill]]'' and ''[[That's My Boy (2012 film)|That's My Boy]]''. He also produced these films, as well as ''[[The Master of Disguise]]'' and ''[[Bucky Larson: Born to Be a Star]]''.]]\n''[[Jack and Jill (2011 film)|Jack and Jill]]'' is a comedy film starring [[Adam Sandler]] as Jack, a commercial director, who is visited by his \"identical\" twin sister, Jill (played by Sandler, in [[drag (clothing)|drag]]), during the holidays. ''[[Salon (magazine)|Salon]]'' stated that ''Jack and Jill'' \"received some of the worst reviews of any movie ever\" upon its release.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.salon.com/2011/11/14/the_tragedy_of_adam_sandler/|title=The tragedy of Adam Sandler|work= [[Salon (magazine)|Salon]] |last1=Eggers|first1=Toph|date=2011-11-14|accessdate=2013-08-23}}</ref> In the film, Jill is wooed by [[Al Pacino]], whom Jack wants to be in his [[Dunkin' Donuts]] commercial. [[Richard Roeper]] of the ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'' noted the irony of Pacino's presence, as the actor is best known for playing [[Michael Corleone]] in ''[[The Godfather]]'', which is widely considered [[list of films considered the best|one of the best films ever made]], in this film, which he called \"one of the worst movies in the history of cinema!\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.richardroeper.com/reviews/footlooselikecrazyandjackandjill.aspx|title=Footloose, Like Crazy, and Jack and Jill|publisher=Richard Roeper & The Movies|last1=Roeper|first1=Richard|accessdate=2013-04-25}}</ref> Ramin Setoodeh of ''[[The Daily Beast]]'' and [[Peter Travers]] of ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' reviewed it together in an article entitled \"Adam Sandler's 'Jack and Jill' Is the Worst Movie Ever Made\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2011/11/11/movie-review-adam-sandler-s-jack-and-jill-is-the-worst-movie-ever-made.html|title=Movie Review: Adam Sandler's 'Jack and Jill' Is the Worst Movie Ever Made|website=The Daily Beast|last1=Setoodeh|first1=Ramin|date=2011-11-11|accessdate=2013-04-25}}</ref> After an hour-long critique, [[RedLetterMedia]] claimed that it was \"so egregious that it ceased to be a film\", and the site also later called it \"the worst thing in the world\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://redlettermedia.com/half-in-the-bag-jack-and-jill/|title=Half in the Bag: Jack and Jill|publisher=RedLetterMedia|author=Mike Stoklasa, Jay Bauman|date=2011-11-20|accessdate=2013-04-25}}</ref> Mike McGranaghan wrote, on his website ''The Aisle Seat'': \"''[[Howard the Duck (film)|Howard the Duck]]'', ''[[Gigli]]'', ''[[Showgirls]]'', ''[[From Justin to Kelly]]''. What do they all have in common? They're all widely considered among the worst big studio movies ever made. You know what else they have in common? They're all better than ''Jack and Jill''.\"<ref name=\"JackandJill\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://aisleseat.com/jackandjill.htm |title=Jack and Jill |publisher=The Aisle Seat |last1=McGranaghan|first1=Mike|date=2011-11-01 |accessdate=2013-11-18}}</ref> ''Jack and Jill'' won a record 10 awards at the [[32nd Golden Raspberry Awards]], sweeping every category. It broke the record previously held by ''[[Battlefield Earth (film)|Battlefield Earth]]'' for having the most Razzies earned by a single film and is the only film to win every possible award.<ref name=RazzieWin>{{cite news |title=Adam Sandler movie Jack and Jill sweeps Razzie awards |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-17582458 |work=[[BBC News]] |date=April 2, 2012 |accessdate=May 17, 2012}}</ref> The film holds a 3% rating on [[Rotten Tomatoes]] based on 110 reviews.<ref name=\"JackandJill\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/jack_and_jill_2011|title=Jack and Jill (2011)|last=|first=|date=|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango]]|accessdate=June 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== ''That's My Boy'' (2012) ===\n\nAnother comedy film starring Adam Sandler, ''[[That's My Boy (2012 film)|That's My Boy]]'' concerns a middle school student named Donny Berger who has sex with his teacher, gets her pregnant, and in turn, earns a lifestyle of a minor celebrity, something he never intended to happen. Years later, Donny (played by Sandler) crashes his now-adult son's ([[Andy Samberg]]) wedding and bachelor party to get his money so he can pay his taxes, therefore avoiding prison. The film has been widely panned due to its comedic portrayal of [[incest]], [[hebephilia]], [[statutory rape]], and [[gerontophilia]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.foxnews.com/entertainment/2012/04/30/comedy-about-middle-school-statutory-rape-does-adam-sandlers-thats-my-boy-go/|title=Comedy about middle school statutory rape? Does Adam Sandler's ''That's My Boy'' go too far?|last=McKay|first=Hollie|date=April 30, 2012|work=|accessdate=April 17, 2019|publisher=[[Fox News]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://live.drjays.com/index.php/2012/05/21/is-adam-sandler-serious-with-thats-my-boy/ |title=Is Adam Sandler Serious With That's My Boy? &#124; DrJays.com Live &#124; Fashion. Music. Lifestyle |work=Live.drjays.com |date=2012-05-21 |accessdate=2013-12-19 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131212060031/http://live.drjays.com/index.php/2012/05/21/is-adam-sandler-serious-with-thats-my-boy/ |archive-date=2013-12-12 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://ncfm.org/2012/05/news/discrimination-against-men-news/adam-sandlers-new-movie-thats-my-boy-exploits-child-victims-of-sexual-assault-please-boycott-the-movie/ |title=Adam Sandler's new movie ''That's My Boy'' exploits child victims of sexual assault. Please boycott the movie. &#124; National Coalition For Men |publisher=NCFM |accessdate=2013-12-19}}</ref> with film critic Andrew O'Hehir of ''Salon'' stating, \"[Sandler's] new movie about a rape survivor and his estranged son is supposed to be funny, but radiates pain and rage.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.salon.com/2012/06/16/sympathy_for_adam_sandler/ |title=Adam Sandler hates you |work=Salon.com |date=2012-06-16 |accessdate=2013-12-19}}</ref> [[Richard Roeper]] of the ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'' proclaimed, \"To say ''That's My Boy'' is one of the worst movies of the year is to insult 2012. This is one of the worst movies I've ever seen\",<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.suntimes.com/entertainment/movies/13146305-421/pervs-will-be-pervs-in-thats-my-boy.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120617062159/http://www.suntimes.com/entertainment/movies/13146305-421/pervs-will-be-pervs-in-thats-my-boy.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=2012-06-17 |title=Pervs will be pervs in ''That's My Boy'' \u2013 Chicago Sun-Times |work=Suntimes.com |accessdate=2013-12-19 }}</ref> while Richard Haridly of ''[[Quickflix]]'' called it \"one of the saddest and most exhausting\" films he has ever seen.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.quickflix.com.au/news/reviews/thatsmyboy |title=That's My Boy review by Richard Haridy |publisher=Quickflix |accessdate=2013-12-19}}</ref> MaryAnn Johanson of ''Flick Filosopher'' outright panned the film for its inability to generate laughs as well as its depraved content, calling it \"a disgusting excuse for a comedy\" and possibly \"the most repulsive movie I've ever seen\",<ref name=\"myboy\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/thats_my_boy/reviews/|title=That's My Boy - Movie Reviews|last=|first=|date=|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango]]|accessdate=April 17, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.flickfilosopher.com/2013/01/thats-my-boy-review.html |title=That's My Boy (review) |work=FlickFilosopher.com |accessdate=2013-12-19}}</ref> and Jonathan Lack of ''We Got This Covered'' declared, \"''That's My Boy'' isn't just the worst film of 2012, it's one of the most morally reprehensible comedies of all time, a disgusting movie you should stay far, far away from.\"<ref name=\"myboy\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://wegotthiscovered.com/movies/boy-review/|title=That's My Boy Review|last=Lack|first=Jonathan R.|date=June 15, 2012|work=Wegotthiscovered.com|accessdate=April 17, 2019}}</ref> Furthermore, Ed Whitfield of ''The Ooh Tray'' stated, \"It may be the worst film, in any genre, ever made\".<ref name=\"myboy\"/><ref>{{cite web|author=The Ooh Tray |url=http://www.theoohtray.com/2012/09/09/film-review-thats-my-boy/ |title=Film Review: That's My Boy |publisher=The Ooh Tray |date=2012-10-02 |accessdate=2013-12-19}}</ref> In addition to the movie's overwhelmingly negative reviews, ''That's My Boy'' earned eight nominations at the [[33rd Golden Raspberry Awards]], such as Worst Picture and Worst Director, and won the awards for Worst Actor (Sandler) and Worst Screenplay.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.razzies.com/history/13winners.asp |title=Razzie Winners |work=Razzies.com |accessdate=2013-12-19 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130227010807/http://www.razzies.com/history/13winners.asp |archivedate=2013-02-27 }}</ref> It holds a 20% rating on [[Rotten Tomatoes]] {{as of|2019|April|17|lc=y|df=US}} based on 115 reviews.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/thats_my_boy/|title=That's My Boy|last=|first=|date=|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango]]|accessdate=April 17, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Run for Your Wife'' (2012) ===\n\nA British comedy film based on the [[Run for Your Wife (play)|stage farce]] of the same name, ''[[Run for Your Wife (2012 film)|Run for Your Wife]]'' starred [[Danny Dyer]] as John Smith, a bigamist, and [[Denise van Outen]] and [[Sarah Harding]] as his wives. ''Run for Your Wife'' was directed by the author of the play, [[Ray Cooney]] (who also makes an uncredited cameo appearance). Upon release, ''Run for Your Wife'' was savaged by film critics, with the South African newspaper ''Daily News'' saying \"''Run for Your Wife'' could be the worst film in history\",<ref>\"Movie may be the biggest Turkey ever\", ''Daily News'', South Africa, February 21, 2013.</ref> the [[Studio Briefing]] website reporting that \"Some writers are making the case that the British comedy may be 'the worst film ever{{'\"}},<ref name=\"studiobriefing\">[http://www.studiobriefing.net/2013/02/the-worst-film-in-history/#sthash.xFKOr9e6.dpuf The Worst Film in History?] ''Studio Briefing'', February 21, 2013. Retrieved February 13, 2015.</ref> and ''[[The Daily Mirror]]'' claiming ''Run For Your Wife'' \"was branded the worst British film ever\".<ref>[https://www.mirror.co.uk/tv/tv-news/danny-dyers-film-company-old-2343670 Danny Dyer's film company went bust with debt to taxpayer of \u00a325,000] ''Daily Mirror'', 6 October 2013. Retrieved 30 January 2015.</ref> ''Run for Your Wife'' met with such overwhelmingly negative reviews upon release that the reviews themselves were widely reported in the UK media.<ref name=\"studiobriefing\" /><ref>[http://uk.movies.yahoo.com/-run-for-your-wife----is-this-the-worst-movie-ever-filmed--114048296.html 'Run for Your Wife' \u2013 Is this the worst movie ever filmed?] ''Yahoo Movies \u2013 UK & Ireland'', 16 February 2013.</ref> The film was variously described as \"a catastrophe\", \"as funny as leprosy\" and \"30 years past its sell-by-date\", with ''[[The Guardian]]'' reviewer [[Peter Bradshaw]] saying that it \"makes ''[[The Dick Emery Show]]'' look edgy and contemporary\".<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/film/2013/feb/14/run-for-your-wife-review Run for Your Wife \u2013 review] ''The Guardian'', 14 February 2013. Retrieved 30 January 2015.</ref> ''[[The Independent (London)|The Independent]]'s'' Anthony Quinn wrote, \"The stage play ran for nine years \u2013 it [the film] will be lucky to run for nine days. Perhaps never in the field of light entertainment have so many actors sacrificed so much dignity in the cause of so few jokes ... From the look of it, Cooney hasn't been in a cinema for about 30 years\".<ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/reviews/film-review-run-for-your-wife-12a-8495806.html Film review: Run for Your Wife] ''The Independent (London)'', 30 January 2015.</ref> The cast featured numerous British celebrities in cameo roles, which was commented upon by several reviewers. The ''[[Metro (British newspaper)|Metro]]'' commented that \"no one emerges unscathed among the cameo-packed cast that reads largely like a roll-call for Brit TV legends you'd previously suspected deceased\".<ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/features/run-for-your-wife--as-funny-as-leprosy-8496873.html Run for Your Wife \u2013 'As funny as leprosy'] ''The Independent (London)'', 30th January 2015.</ref> The ''[[Daily Record (Scotland)|Daily Record]]'' described the film as \"an exasperating farce containing not one single, solitary laugh. {{sic|Comprised|hide=y| of}} people losing their trousers and falling over, the film looks like a pilot for a (mercifully) never-commissioned 70s sitcom\".<ref>\"[http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/entertainment/movies/movie-dvd-reviews/movie-review-run-your-wife-1711076 Movie Review: Run for your wife]\". ''Daily Record'', 30 January 2015.</ref> An article in the ''Independent'' described ''Run for Your Wife'' (along with the similarly panned ''[[Movie 43]]'') as contenders for the title of the \"worst film in history\".<ref>\"[https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/news/run-for-your-wife-is-this-movie-the-biggest-turkey-ever-filmed-8497478.html?origin=internalSearch Run For Your Wife: Is this movie the biggest turkey ever filmed?]\" ''The Independent''. 15 February 2013. Retrieved 30 January 2015.</ref> ''[[Hemel Hempstead Gazette|The Berkhamsted & Tring Gazette]]'' reported \"critics have being queuing up to batter recent release ''Run for Your Wife'', with general agreement that it ranks among the worst British comedies of all time\".<ref>\"Run for Your Wife\", ''Berkhamsted & Tring Gazette'', 11 March 2013.</ref> ''Run for Your Wife'' was also a [[box office bomb]], earning only \u00a3602 in its opening weekend at the British box office to its \u00a3900,000 budget.<ref>\"[http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2013-02-20/danny-dyers-run-for-your-wife-takes-just-602-at-the-box-office Danny Dyer's Run For Your Wife takes just \u00a3602 at the box office]\". ''[[Radio Times]]'', 20 February 2013. Retrieved 30 January 2015.</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/movies/news/a460182/danny-dyers-run-for-your-wife-flops-with-gbp602-at-the-box-office.html | title=Danny Dyer's 'Run For Your Wife' flops with \u00a3747 at the box office | website=Digital Spy|accessdate=30 January 2015}}</ref> ''Run for Your Wife'' has a [[List of films with a 0% rating on Rotten Tomatoes|0% rating]] on [[Rotten Tomatoes]] {{as of|2015|July|29|lc=y|df=US}} based on 15 reviews.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/run_for_your_wife_2013/|title=Run For Your Wife (2013)|last=|first=|date=|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango]]|access-date=April 17, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Movie 43'' (2013) ===\n\nProduced and co-directed by [[Peter Farrelly]] among others, ''[[Movie 43]]'' is a comedy film consisting of several vignettes each by a different director and a sizable cast of recognizable actors and actresses including [[Dennis Quaid]], [[Greg Kinnear]], [[Hugh Jackman]], [[Kate Winslet]], [[Liev Schreiber]], [[Naomi Watts]], [[Anna Faris]], [[Emma Stone]], [[Richard Gere]], [[Uma Thurman]], [[Chlo\u00eb Grace Moretz]], [[Gerard Butler]], [[Halle Berry]], [[Stephen Merchant]], [[Kristen Bell]], [[Terrence Howard]], [[Elizabeth Banks]], [[Kate Bosworth]], [[Johnny Knoxville]], [[Justin Long]], [[Chris Pratt]], [[Josh Duhamel]], and [[Jason Sudeikis]]. Several critics have called it one of the worst films ever made, including Peter Howell of the ''[[Toronto Star]]'', who said \"There's just one use for ''Movie 43'', apart from it being ground into the landfill that it deserves to become sooner rather than later. It provides me with a handy new answer to a question I'm often asked: 'What's the worst film you've ever seen?{{'\"}}<ref name=\"TS3\">{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com/entertainment/movies/2013/01/25/movie_43_review_the_worst_film_ever_gets_zero_stars.html|title=Movie 43 review: The worst film ever gets zero stars|last=Howell|first=Peter|date=January 25, 2013|work=[[Toronto Star]]|access-date=April 17, 2019}}</ref> Elizabeth Weitzman of the [[Daily News (New York)|New York ''Daily News'']] also considered it the worst movie she ever saw.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/tv-movies/movie-review-movie-43-article-1.1248520|title=Movie Review: Movie 43|last=Weitzman|first=Elizabeth|date=January 26, 2013|work=[[Daily News (New York)|Daily News]]|accessdate=April 17, 2019|location=New York}}</ref> Brady Murphy of Murphy Reviews wrote, \"A world where a film like this can exist only reminds me of the other contemptible acts performed by human kind since the dawn of time, and is rather eye-opening in that respect. That probably wasn't intentional, though\"; he went on to say that \"The idea that anyone could think that this would be in any way humorous is simply unbelievable.\" He concluded his review by saying the movie \"had no heart\", and gave it the site's first zero out of ten rating.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.murphyreviews.com/movie-43.html |title=Movie 43 |publisher=Murphy Reviews |date=2013-01-30 |accessdate=2013-11-18 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131020021708/http://www.murphyreviews.com/movie-43.html |archivedate=2013-10-20 }}</ref> [[Richard Roeper]] of the ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'' voiced similar hatred, calling it \"aggressively tasteless\" and \"the ''[[Citizen Kane]]'' of awful\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.suntimes.com/entertainment/17804431-421/theres-awful-and-then-theres-movie-43.html|title=There's awful and THEN there's ''Movie 43''|date=2013-01-25|work=Chicago Sun-Times|accessdate=2013-11-18|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130129011636/http://www.suntimes.com/entertainment/17804431-421/theres-awful-and-then-theres-movie-43.html|archive-date=2013-01-29|url-status=dead}}</ref> [[Lou Lumenick]] of the ''[[New York Post]]'' stated, \"If you mashed-up the worst parts of the infamous ''Howard the Duck'', ''Gigli'', ''Ishtar'' and every other awful movie I've seen since I started reviewing professionally in 1981, it wouldn't begin to approach the sheer soul-sucking badness of the cringe-inducing ''Movie 43''.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://nypost.com/2013/01/25/wtf-beyond-sketchy/ |title=WTF! Beyond sketchy |work=[[New York Post]] |date=2013-01-25 |accessdate=2013-11-28 |first=Lou |last=Lumenick}}</ref> ''Movie 43'' is on the MRQE's 50 Worst Movies list.<ref name=\"MRQE50\"/> It holds a 5% approval rating on [[Rotten Tomatoes]] based on 88 reviews, averaging out at a 2.23/10 rating.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/movie_43/|title=Movie 43|last=|first=|date=|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango]]|accessdate=May 22, 2019}}</ref> It won three awards at the [[34th Golden Raspberry Awards]]: Worst Picture, Worst Director, and Worst Screenplay. In the Worst Director category, all 13 directors won the award.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/envelope/moviesnow/la-et-mn-movie-43-named-worst-film-of-2013-razzie-awards-20140228,0,5893779.story |title='Movie 43' is named worst film of 2013 at the 34th Razzie Awards |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=2014-03-01 |accessdate=2014-03-01 |first=Susan |last=King}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Fateful Findings'' (2013) ===\n\n''[[Fateful Findings]]'' is a 2013 independent [[techno-thriller]] written, directed and produced by [[Neil Breen]]. Breen also starred in the film and took on most of the crew roles, including film editor, sound editor, accountant, caterer, set designer, wardrobe, makeup and casting.<ref name=\"NYDN\"/> The film follows an author-turned-hacker with supernatural powers who uses his abilities to reveal government and corporate secrets while struggling with his wife's drug addiction and his attraction to his teenage neighbor, ending with an extended sequence at a press conference where politicians and business people confess to corruption and kill themselves before an applauding crowd. Writing for ''[[Film Threat]]'', reviewer Mike Hodges described it as \"the worst movie ever made\", comparing it unfavorably to ''[[#Troll 2 (1990)|Troll 2]]'' and ''[[#The Room (2003)|The Room]]''.<ref>{{cite web|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222032832/https://filmthreat.com/reviews/66453/|url=https://filmthreat.com/reviews/66453/|first=Mike|last=Hodges|website=Film Threat|date=27 May 2013|archive-date=22 February 2014|accessdate=1 February 2018|url-status=dead|title=Fateful Findings}}</ref> [[Nathan Rabin]], writing for [[Rotten Tomatoes]], said ''Fateful Findings'' threatens ''The Room''{{'}}s position as \"best worst movie\",<ref>{{cite web|url=https://editorial.rottentomatoes.com/article/why-fateful-findings-deserves-cult-status/|title=Why Fateful Findings Deserves Cult Status|first=Nathan|last=Rabin|date=8 December 2015|website=Rotten Tomatoes|accessdate=1 February 2018}}</ref> while reviewers of the podcast ''[[The Flop House]]'' said \"Move over ''The Room'', move over ''[[#Birdemic: Shock and Terror (2008)|Birdemic]]''\" and ''Mystery Science Theater 3000'' head writer [[Elliott Kalan]] described it as the \"good-est bad movie, maybe, I've ever seen\".<ref>{{Cite AV media|url=https://soundcloud.com/the-flop-house/ep-187-fateful-findings|title=Ep. #187 - Fateful Findings|first1=Elliot|last1=Kalan|first2=Dan|last2=McCoy|first3=Stuart|last3=Wellington|date=19 September 2015|publisher=[[The Flop House]]|accessdate=1 February 2018|time=50:22 to 50:55}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Humshakals'' (2014) ===\nA [[Bollywood]] comedy film directed by [[Sajid Khan (director)|Sajid Khan]], ''[[Humshakals]]'' featured Indian actors [[Saif Ali Khan]], [[Ram Kapoor]] and [[Riteish Deshmukh]]. On [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film has an [[List of films with a 0% rating on Rotten Tomatoes|approval rating of 0%]], based on six reviews, with an average rating of 2/10.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/humshakals/ |title=Humshakals (2014) |website=Rotten Tomatoes |accessdate=July 10, 2017}}</ref> Mihir Fadnavis wrote in his ''[[Firstpost]]'' review, \"sexual tomfoolery, shrieking and hamming aside, there's much more to hate about this 'family movie'. It's disturbing to see such an atrocious, regressive, misogynistic, sexist, homophobic cinematic product force-fed to paying audiences. I can understand that a comedy need not be 'safe', but what goes on in ''Humshakals'' is simply too horrifying to bear.\"<ref name=\"Fadnavis\">{{cite news|url=http://www.firstpost.com/blogs/humshakals-review-saif-ali-khan-riteish-deshmukh-team-up-to-give-you-brain-damage-1580181.html |title=Humshakals review: How Saif, Riteish teamed up to give your brain damage |work=Firstpost |last1=Fadnavis|first1=Mihir|date=2014-06-22 |accessdate=2014-07-22}}</ref> Saurabh Dwivedi of ''[[India Today]]'' stated \"I can only say that ''Humshakals'' will be listed in one of the worst films of the century.\"<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/humshakals-movie-review-sajid-khan-riteish-deshmukh-saif-ali-khan/1/367688.html |title=Movie review: Humshakals is three times trash |last1=Dwivedi|first1=Saurabh|date=June 20, 2014|magazine=[[India Today]]}}</ref> Writing in ''[[Emirates 24/7]]'', Sneha May Francis said that it succeeded Khan's previous endeavor, ''[[Himmatwala (2013 film)|Himmatwala]]'', in becoming the worst Bollywood film ever.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.emirates247.com/entertainment/films-music/saif-ali-khan-s-humshakals-act-could-make-kareena-insecure-2014-06-19-1.553579 |title=Saif Ali Khan's 'Humshakals' act could make Kareena insecure |last1=Francis|first1=Sneha May|publisher=Emirates 24/7 |date=2014-06-29 |accessdate=2014-10-22}}</ref> Fadnavis went further, writing that it displaced ''Himmatwala'' as the \"worst possible product any film industry in the world can offer\".<ref name=\"Fadnavis\"/> Itrath Syed of ''[[The Georgia Straight]]'' stated that ''Humshakals'' was \"the absolute bottom of the cinematic barrel\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.straight.com/movies/673511/humshakals-redefines-dreadfulness|title=Humshakals redefines dreadfulness|work=The Georgia Straight|last1=Syed|first1=Itrath|date=June 25, 2014 |accessdate=July 10, 2017}}</ref> The film received five [[Golden Kela Awards|Golden Kela Award]] nominations,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/entertainment/humshakals-lead-nominations-list-at-golden-kela-awards/article6905214.ece |title=Humshakals' leads nominations list at Golden Kela Awards |newspaper=The Hindu |author=PTI|date=February 17, 2015 |accessdate=2014-10-22 |location=Chennai, India}}</ref> and won the \u201caward\u201d for Worst Film.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenational.ae/arts-lifestyle/from-holly-to-bolly/sonakshi-and-arjun-grab-top-golden-kela-awards |title=Sonakshi and Arjun grab top Golden Kela awards |newspaper=The National |author=IANS|date=March 15, 2015 |accessdate=August 17, 2015}}</ref> It also won two [[Ghanta Awards]]; the film won Worst Picture and Ram Kapoor, Saif Ali Khan and Riteish Deshmukh shared the Worst Actor award.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ibtimes.co.in/ghanta-awards-2015-complete-winners-list-sonakshi-sinha-ajay-devgn-win-worst-actor-awards-farah-625675 |title=Ghanta Awards 2015 Complete Winners List: Sonakshi Sinha, Ajay Devgn Win Worst Actor Awards; Farah Khan Worst Director |work=International Business Times|last1=Mehta|first1=Ankhita|date=March 9, 2015 |accessdate=August 17, 2015}}</ref>\n\nSeveral of the cast members also lamented their involvement in the film. Despite being the film's leading actress, [[Bipasha Basu]] did not participate in the film's promotions because she was \"extremely disturbed by the end result\" and stated that \"''Humshakals'' was the worst experience of my life\".<ref>{{cite news |date=August 8, 2014 |title=Sajid Khan's Humshakals left me disturbed: Bipasha Basu |newspaper=Hindustan Times |url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/entertainment/tabloid/sajid-khan-s-humshakals-left-me-disturbed-bipasha-basu/article1-1249663.aspx |author=IANS|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140809060246/http://www.hindustantimes.com/entertainment/tabloid/sajid-khan-s-humshakals-left-me-disturbed-bipasha-basu/article1-1249663.aspx |url-status=dead |archive-date=August 9, 2014 |location=Mumbai}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/slide-show/slide-show-1-bipasha-humshakals-was-the-worst-experience-of-my-life/20140826.htm |title=Bipasha: Humshakals was the worst experience of my life |publisher=Rediff.com |date=August 26, 2014}}</ref> Another cast member, actress [[Esha Gupta]], warned her family to not watch the film.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/Humshakals-I-asked-my-father-not-to-watch-the-film-says-Esha-Gupta/articleshow/37616095.cms |title=Humshakals: I asked my father not to watch the film, says Esha Gupta |newspaper=Times of India |date= Jul 2, 2014 }}</ref> After the release of the film, leading actor Saif Ali Khan lamented that \"I've been introspecting a lot and will never repeat a mistake that was ''Humshakals''.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/Saif-Ali-Khan-Humshakals-was-a-mistake/articleshow/38590378.cms |title=Saif Ali Khan: Humshakals was a mistake |newspaper=Times of India |date= Jul 18, 2014 }}</ref>\n\n=== ''Kidnapping, Caucasian Style!'' (2014) ===\n''[[Kidnapping, Caucasian Style!]]'' is a 2014 Russian comedy film.<ref>[https://letterboxd.com/film/kidnapping-caucasian-style-2014/ Kidnapping, Caucasian Style (2014)-Letterboxd]</ref> It is a remake of [[Leonid Gaidai]]'s 1967 Soviet film, ''[[Kidnapping, Caucasian Style]]'', and was harshly criticized for how closely it copied the original, essentially being a frame by frame reproduction with few modern references. ''[[Gazeta.ru]]'' described it as \"probably the worst film in the history of Russian cinema\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.gazeta.ru/culture/2014/08/21/a_6185217.shtml |script-title=ru:\u0428\u0443\u0440\u0438\u043a \u0432 \u0417\u0430\u043f\u0440\u0435\u0434\u0435\u043b\u044c\u0435|language=Russian|work=[[Gazeta.ru]]|date= August 22, 2014|accessdate=February 19, 2019}}</ref> ''[[Mail.Ru]]'' said it was the worst remake, while critic Maxim Shilimanov wrote that \"The film is so bad that it seems that it was shot badly on purpose so that film critics had something to write about.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.kritikanstvo.ru/movies/kavkazskajaplennica/|script-title=ru:\u041a\u0430\u0432\u043a\u0430\u0437\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u043f\u043b\u0435\u043d\u043d\u0438\u0446\u0430!|language=Russian|publisher=Kritikanstvo|date= November 28, 2017|accessdate=February 19, 2019}}</ref> In listing it as one of the worst remakes of Soviet cinema, ''[[Cosmopolitan Russia]]'' opted to quote from a user review from [[KinoPoisk]] that called it \"the worst film I've ever seen\" rather than describe the plot.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cosmo.ru/stars/krupnim-planom/veselye-rebyata-kavkazskaya-plennica-i-drugie-hudshie-remeyki-sovetskogo-kino/|script-title=ru:\"\u0412\u0435\u0441\u0435\u043b\u044b\u0435 \u0440\u0435\u0431\u044f\u0442\u0430\", \"\u041a\u0430\u0432\u043a\u0430\u0437\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u043f\u043b\u0435\u043d\u043d\u0438\u0446\u0430!\" \u0438 \u0434\u0440\u0443\u0433\u0438\u0435 \u0445\u0443\u0434\u0448\u0438\u0435 \u0440\u0435\u043c\u0435\u0439\u043a\u0438 \u0441\u043e\u0432\u0435\u0442\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u043a\u0438\u043d\u043e|language=Russian|work=[[Cosmopolitan Russia]]|date= November 18, 2018|accessdate=February 19, 2019}}</ref> It is the lowest rated film on KinoPoisk,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.aif.ru/culture/movie/proval_na_million_hudshie_rossiyskie_filmy_soglasno_reytingu_zriteley|script-title=ru:\u041f\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043b \u043d\u0430 \u043c\u0438\u043b\u043b\u0438\u043e\u043d. \u0425\u0443\u0434\u0448\u0438\u0435 \u0440\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0435 \u0444\u0438\u043b\u044c\u043c\u044b \u0441\u043e\u0433\u043b\u0430\u0441\u043d\u043e \u0440\u0435\u0439\u0442\u0438\u043d\u0433\u0443 \u0437\u0440\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u0435\u0439|language=Russian|work=[[Argumenty i Fakty]]|date= December 1, 2017|accessdate=February 19, 2019}}</ref> appears on [[review aggregator]] Kritikanstvo's all-time lowest-scoring films,<ref name=\"Kritikanstvo\"/> and [[RIA Novosti]] listed it as the second worst film after ''[[Guardians (2017 film)|Guardians]]''.<ref name=\"RIA\">{{cite news|url=https://ria.ru/20171128/1509765632.html?referrer_block=index_daynews3_1|script-title=ru:\u0421\u0430\u043c\u044b\u0439 \u0445\u0443\u0434\u0448\u0438\u0439 \u0444\u0438\u043b\u044c\u043c: \u043a\u0430\u043a\u0438\u0435 \u043a\u0430\u0440\u0442\u0438\u043d\u044b \u043f\u043e\u0441\u043b\u0435\u0434\u043d\u0438\u0445 \u043b\u0435\u0442 \u0440\u0430\u0437\u043e\u0447\u0430\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043b\u0438 \u0437\u0440\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u0435\u0439\n|language=Russian|publisher=[[RIA Novosti]]|date= November 28, 2017|accessdate=February 19, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Saving Christmas'' (2014) ===\n[[File:Kirk Cameron by Gage Skidmore.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Kirk Cameron]]'s plea for fans to support ''[[Saving Christmas]]'' backfired, resulting in it being the lowest rated film on [[IMDB]]]]\n''[[Saving Christmas]]'' is a [[Christian film industry|faith-based]] [[List of Christmas films|Christmas]] [[comedy film]] starring [[Kirk Cameron]], who plays a fictionalized version of himself attempting to convince his brother-in-law (played by the film's director, [[Darren Doane]]) that Christmas is still a Christian holiday.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=g1om1mtv5ZM The Troubling Philosophy of Kirk Cameron's Saving Christmas-Renegade Cut on YouTube]</ref> On [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film received a [[List of films with a 0% rating on Rotten Tomatoes|0% rating]], based on 13 reviews, with an average rating of 1.7/10.<ref name=\"savingrotten\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/kirk_camerons_saving_christmas/reviews/|title=Kirk Cameron's Saving Christmas|website=Rotten Tomatoes|accessdate=July 28, 2017}}</ref> Critic David Keyes described ''Saving Christmas'' as \"The worst holiday movie ever made\",<ref name=\"savingrotten\"/> ''[[Billings Gazette]]'' selected the film as the worst Christmas movie of all time,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://billingsgazette.com/entertainment/movies/the-worst-christmas-movies-of-all-time/collection_b50903c8-f2cf-54ce-8fea-90fac279d391.html|title=The 25 Worst Christmas Movies of All Time|work=Billings Gazette|date=December 12, 2016|accessdate=July 28, 2017}}</ref> and Will Nicol of ''Digital Trends'' included it on his list of the ten worst movies ever made.<ref name=\"digitaltrends\">{{cite web|url=https://www.digitaltrends.com/movies/worst-movies-ever-made/|title=10 Worst Movies You Can Watch|work=Digital Trends|last=Nicol|first=Will|date=May 10, 2017|accessdate=July 28, 2017}}</ref> [[Christy Lemire]] picked ''Saving Christmas'' as the worst film she has ever reviewed and called it  \"[[The Room (2003 film)|''The Room'']] of Christmas movies\" (while adding that she found ''The Room'' to be more enjoyable) and gave it a score of zero stars out of four.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://indiewire.com/2017/06/critics-worst-movies-ever-reviewed-1201843846/|title=Critics Pick the Worst Movies They've Ever Reviewed|work=Indiewire|last=Kohn|first=Eric|date=June 19, 2017|accessdate=July 28, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://christylemire.com/kirk-camerons-saving-christmas/|title=Kirk Cameron's Saving Christmas - Christy Lemire|date=2014-11-21|work=Christy Lemire|access-date=2018-09-09|language=en-US}}</ref> Bill Zwecker of the ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'' said: \"This may be one of the least artful holiday films ever made.\"<ref name=\"savingrotten\" /> In response to the criticism, Cameron asked fans to give the film positive reviews on Rotten Tomatoes.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.christianpost.com/news/kirk-cameron-urges-fans-to-improve-saving-christmas-rating-help-me-storm-the-gates-of-rotten-tomatoes-130072/ |title=Kirk Cameron Urges Fans to Improve ''Saving Christmas'' Rating, 'Help Me Storm the Gates of Rotten Tomatoes' |author=Koonse, Emma |newspaper=The Christian Post |date=November 21, 2014 |accessdate=July 28, 2017}}</ref> This resulted in a backlash in which Internet users traveled to the Rotten Tomatoes page and condemned the film.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://cinemablend.com/new/Kirk-Cameron-Tried-Cheat-Rotten-Tomatoes-It-Did-Go-68399.html | title=Kirk Cameron Tried To Cheat Rotten Tomatoes, It Did Not Go Well | work=CinemaBlend | date=November 25, 2014 | accessdate=July 28, 2017}}</ref> Three weeks after its release, ''Saving Christmas'' became the lowest-rated film on IMDb's bottom 100 list. Cameron blamed the low rating on a [[Reddit]] campaign by \"haters and [[Atheism|atheists]]\" to purposely lower the film's ratings.<ref>{{cite news|last1=O'Neal|first1=Sean|date=December 5, 2014|title=Kirk Cameron Is Crucified at the Hands of IMDb Users, Rises with Jesus Coffee|url=https://avclub.com/article/kirk-cameron-crucified-hands-imdb-users-rises-jesu-212677|newspaper=The A.V. Club|accessdate=9 December 2014}}</ref> The film won four awards, including Worst Picture, at the [[35th Golden Raspberry Awards]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=King|first1=Susan|date=February 21, 2015|title=Kirk Cameron's Saving Christmas'' Dominates the 35th Razzie Awards|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/moviesnow/la-et-mn-kirk-cameron-35th-razzie-awards-20150220-story.html |newspaper=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=July 28, 2017}}</ref> ''[[MSN Entertainment]]'' ranked it #2 in its list of the 100 worst films of all time and ''Digital Trends'' included it in its worst film list.<ref name=\"digitaltrends\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/movies/gallery/100-worst-movies-of-all-time/ss-BBS3EmT#image=100|title=100 Worst Movies of All Time|website=www.msn.com|access-date=2019-09-25}}</ref>\n\n=== ''United Passions'' (2014) ===\n\nA 2014 English-language French [[Drama (film and television)|drama film]] about the origins of the soccer world governing body [[FIFA|F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association]] (FIFA), ''[[United Passions]]'' starred [[Tim Roth]] (as FIFA President [[Sepp Blatter]]), [[G\u00e9rard Depardieu]] and [[Sam Neill]], and was directed by [[Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Auburtin]]. ''United Passions''{{'}} release in the U.S. occurred simultaneously with the [[2015 FIFA corruption case]], in which several current and former members of FIFA's executive committee were arrested for charges of corruption,<ref name=\"Scheck\">{{cite news |last=Scheck |first=Frank |title='United Passions': Film Review |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/united-passions-film-review-799879 |newspaper=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |accessdate=4 June 2015}}</ref> and Blatter himself resigned following repeated accusations of corruption at FIFA under his leadership.<ref>{{cite news |last=Parker |first=Graham |date=2 June 2015 |title=Sepp Blatter: A history of scandal |url=http://america.aljazeera.com/articles/2015/6/2/sepp-blatter-a-history-of-scandal.html |publisher=[[Al Jazeera]] |access-date=4 June 2015}}</ref> ''United Passions'' was accused of ignoring these long-running claims.<ref name=\"Scheck\"/><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.goal.com/en/news/1717/editorial/2015/06/09/12556292/is-united-passions-the-worst-movie-of-all-time-fifa%E2%80%93|title=Is United Passions the worst movie of all time? Fifa propaganda film paints Blatter as a bastion of morality|last=Koylu|first=Enis|date=|website=Goal.com|access-date=April 17, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"field\">{{cite news |last=Field |first=Paul |date=3 June 2015 |title=United Passions review: FIFA's hideous \u00a316 million movie is unintentional comedy gold |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/football/news/united-passions-review-fifas-hideous-5817599 |newspaper=[[Daily Mirror]] |access-date=25 June 2015}}</ref> ''[[London Evening Standard]]''{{'}}s [[Des Kelly]] wrote that ''United Passions'' was \"the worst movie ever made\" and \"the most extraordinary vanity exercise; a vile, self-aggrandizing, sugar-coated pile of manure where Blatter and Co. manage to make North Korea's [[Kim Jong-un]] look self-effacing\".<ref>[https://www.standard.co.uk/sport/football/des-kelly-sugarcoated-fifa-film-is-spreading-around-europe-like-a-virus-9820165.html Sugar-coated FIFA film is spreading around Europe like a virus] Des Kelly, ''London Evening Standard'', 27 October 2014. Retrieved 25 June 2015.</ref> Daniel Gold of ''The New York Times'' claimed ''United Passions'' is \"one of the most unwatchable films in recent memory, a dishonest bit of corporate-suite sanitizing that's no good even for laughs\",<ref>Daniel M. Gold. \"[https://www.nytimes.com/2015/06/05/movies/review-in-united-passions-a-fictionalized-fifa-underwritten-by-the-soccer-group.html Review: In 'United Passions', a Fictionalized FIFA, Underwritten by the Soccer Group]\". ''New York Times'', June 4, 2015. Retrieved 25 June 2015.</ref> later stating it would make the top three of his list of all time bad films.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/videos/world/2015/06/14/exp-new-film-about-fifa-opens-in-the-u-s-.cnn|title='United Passions' not getting good reviews|publisher=CNN|date=June 14, 2015|accessdate=September 4, 2015}}</ref> Several critics noted the irony of the film's depiction of Blatter as an anti-corruption campaigner. Paul Field of the ''[[Daily Mirror]]'' said that this created \"unintentional comedy gold\",<ref name=\"field\"/> while Sara Stewart of the ''[[New York Post]]'' described it as \"hilariously ill-timed\".<ref>{{cite news |last=Stewart |first=Sara |date=3 June 2015 |title=Lame 'United Passions' an ironic ode to glory of FIFA |url=https://nypost.com/2015/06/03/lame-united-passions-an-ironic-ode-to-glory-of-fifa/ |newspaper=[[New York Post]] |access-date=25 June 2015}}</ref> On [[Rotten Tomatoes]], ''United Passions'' has [[List of films with a 0% rating on Rotten Tomatoes|an approval rating of 0%]] based on 16 reviews,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/united_passions|title=United Passions (2015)|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango Media]]|access-date=September 28, 2019}}</ref> while on [[Metacritic]], the film holds a score of 1 out of 100, based on 9 critics, and is tied for the lowest scoring film on the site.<ref name=\"Metacritic\"/>\n\n''United Passions'' was also a [[box office bomb]],<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2X1AU1ArE0k Top 10 Worst Movies of 2015-WatchMojo on YouTube]</ref> becoming the lowest-grossing film ever in American history with a total take of $918,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://avclub.com/article/fifa-vanity-project-united-passions-breaks-box-off-221084|title=FIFA vanity project ''United Passions'' breaks box-office record (not the good kind)|last=Rife|first=Katie|date=June 19, 2015|work=[[The A.V. Club]]|publisher=[[The Onion]]|accessdate=April 17, 2019}}</ref><ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=vDGp2_6iEe4 Another Top 10 Movies So Bad They Were Pulled From Theatres-WatchMojo on YouTube]</ref> which surpassed the previous record held by ''[[I Kissed a Vampire]]'' ($1,380) in 2012. The film additionally went [[Direct-to-video|directly to DVD]] in France and was not distributed in a number of other European countries.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/sports/sportsnow/la-sp-sn-fifa-movie-united-passions-bombs-20150608-story.html|title='United Passions,' which cost FIFA $29 million, has $607 box-office take|author=Austin Knoblauch|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|publisher=([[Tribune Publishing]])|date=25 June 2015|accessdate=8 June 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Ikav\">{{cite web|url=http://www.espnfc.com/fifa-world-cup/story/2496658/fifa-film-united-passions-among-worst-in-us-history|title=FIFA film 'United Passions' one of worst in U.S. box office history|author=ESPN Staff|work=[[ESPN FC]]|publisher=([[ESPN]])|date=25 June 2015|accessdate=21 June 2015}}</ref> Several of the people involved in ''United Passions'' later expressed regret over the film. Director Auburtin called ''United Passions'' \"a disaster\" and added: \"Now I'm seen as bad as the guy who brought AIDS to Africa or the guy who caused the financial crisis ... apparently I am a propaganda guy making films for corrupt people.\"<ref name=\"Ikav\"/><ref name=\"r&r\">{{cite news|url=https://hollywoodreporter.com/news/fifa-movie-director-breaks-silence-802760|title=FIFA Movie Director Breaks Silence on Bomb: \"It's a Disaster; My Name Is All Over [This Mess]\"|author1=Scott Roxborough |author2=Rhonda Richford |lastauthoramp=yes|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|publisher=([[Prometheus Global Media]])|date=17 June 2015|accessdate=25 June 2015}}</ref> Tim Roth apologized for taking part in the film and admitted that he took the job in ''United Passions'' for the money.<ref name=\"r&r\"/>\n\n===''Dirty Grandpa'' (2016)===\n''[[Dirty Grandpa]]'', a 2016 comedy movie starring [[Robert De Niro]] and [[Zac Efron]] as a grandfather and grandson going to [[Florida]] during [[Spring break]], received negative reviews for its [[Off-color humor|gross-out]] and [[Shock humour|shock humor]] that was also considered as [[Sexism|sexist]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://sassymamainla.com/2016/01/how-dirty-grandpa-made-my-feminism-hurt/.html|title=How DIRTY GRANDPA Made My Feminism Hurt: An Expos\u00e9|last=Howard|first=Courtney|date=January 22, 2016|website=Sassy Mama in LA|language=en-US|access-date=September 28, 2019}}</ref> [[Homophobia|homophobic]] and [[Racism|racist]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://slate.com/human-interest/2016/02/comedies-like-dirty-grandpa-get-hard-are-horribly-homophobic.html|title=Some of Hollywood's Most Successful Comedies Have a \"Hipster Homophobia\" Problem|last=Lang|first=Nico|date=February 10, 2016|website=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate Magazine]]|language=en|access-date=September 28, 2019}}</ref> Mike Ryan of [[Uproxx]] said: \"''Dirty Grandpa'' is the worst movie I\u2019ve ever seen in a movie theater. Burn it.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiewire.com/2016/01/reviews-is-dirty-grandpa-robert-deniros-worst-movie-ever-124909/|title=Reviews: Is 'Dirty Grandpa' Robert DeNiro's Worst Movie Ever?|last=Murthi|first=Vikram|last2=Murthi|first2=Vikram|date=2016-01-22|website=IndieWire|language=en|access-date=2018-12-26}}</ref> He later also picked it as the worst film he had ever both reviewed<ref>{{cite news|last1=Kohn|first1=Eric|title=Critics Pick the Worst Movies They've Ever Reviewed|url=https://indiewire.com/2017/06/critics-worst-movies-ever-reviewed-1201843846/|accessdate=January 16, 2018|work=[[IndieWire]]|date=June 19, 2017}}</ref> and seen.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ryan|first1=Mike|title='Dirty Grandpa': The Most Important Movie Ever Made|url=http://uproxx.com/movies/dirty-grandpa-review/|accessdate=January 16, 2018|publisher=[[Uproxx]]|date=January 21, 2016}}</ref> Pete Hammond of [[Deadline Hollywood]] said: \"... ''Dirty Grandpa,'' is not just the worst movie [De Niro] has ever been in, but it may be the worst movie ''anyone'' has ever been in.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2016/01/dirty-grandpa-review-zac-efron-robert-de-niro-worst-ever-1201688276/|title='Dirty Grandpa' Review: The Worst Film Of Robert De Niro's Career (Or Maybe Anybody's)|last=Hammond|first=Pete|last2=Hammond|first2=Pete|date=2016-01-22|website=Deadline|language=en|access-date=2018-12-26}}</ref> Glenn Mcdonald of [[Indy Week]] said: \"The awful, ugly ''Dirty Grandpa'' is the comedy equivalent of torture porn ... In fact, in the dizzying moments after being bludgeoned by this miserable specimen, I was convinced it's among the worst movies ever made.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://indyweek.com/api/content/5adaaa95-3951-5e39-8f24-20d058c698b4/|title=Movie review: The awful, ugly Dirty Grandpa is the comedy equivalent of torture porn|last=McDonald|first=Glenn|date=2016-01-22|website=INDY Week|language=en-us|access-date=2018-12-26}}</ref> [[Richard Roeper]] gave the film zero stars, writing, \"If ''Dirty Grandpa'' isn't the worst movie of 2016, I have some serious cinematic torture in my near future.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://chicago.suntimes.com/entertainment/dirty-grandpa-robert-de-niro-deserves-better-than-this-dreck/|title='Dirty Grandpa': Robert De Niro deserves better than this dreck|website=Chicago Sun-Times|language=en|access-date=2018-12-26}}</ref> On his YouTube channel, Roeper also said: \"I'm not ready to say ''Dirty Grandpa'' is the worst movie I've ever seen, but I'm also not ready to say it's ''not'' the worst movie I've ever seen.\"<ref>{{Citation|title=Richard Roeper Reviews \"Dirty Grandpa\"|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=XOu2gzJiaCg|language=en|access-date=2019-09-29}}</ref> [[Mark Kermode]], on his [[BBC Radio 5 Live]] show (''[[Kermode and Mayo's Film Review]]''), said that he found the film \"truly, genuinely horrible\" and went on to say, \"after ''Dirty Grandpa'' I did feel genuinely unclean, I wanted to go and have a shower, because it's just so revolting. Somewhere in hell there is a multiplex playing this on a double bill, with ''[[Movie 43]]'' and ''[[Entourage (film)|Entourage]]''.\"<ref>{{Citation|last=kermodeandmayo|title=Dirty Grandpa reviewed by Mark Kermode|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=05GwDHYXlmI|access-date=2018-12-27}}</ref> He would later go on to brand it his least favorite film of 2016.<ref>{{Citation|last=kermodeandmayo|title=The Ten Worst Films of 2016: Part Two|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4NwzBUjeMl0|access-date=2018-12-27}}</ref> Glenn Kelly of ''[[RogerEbert.com]]'' said: \"The actor [[Bela Lugosi]] appeared in some landmark, perhaps even great, films at the beginning of his Hollywood career in the 1930s. ... Lugosi's final film was 1959's ''[[Plan 9 from Outer Space]]'', frequently cited as the worst film ever made. The cinematic landmarks of De Niro's career include films such as [[Francis Ford Coppola|Coppola]]'s ''[[The Godfather Part II]]'' and [[Martin Scorsese|Scorsese]]'s ''[[Raging Bull]]''. He has been featured in a good number of very bad films in the years since. But this? This might just be his own ''Plan 9''\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/dirty-grandpa-2016|title=Dirty Grandpa Movie Review & Film Summary (2016) {{!}} Roger Ebert|last=Kenny|first=Glenn|website=www.rogerebert.com|language=en|access-date=2019-02-17}}</ref> The film has an approval rating of 11% at [[Rotten Tomatoes]] based on 133 reviews, with an average rating of 2.76/10,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/dirty_grandpa/|title=Dirty Grandpa (2016)|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango Media]]|access-date=September 28, 2019}}</ref> while on [[Metacritic]] it has a score of 21 out of 100 based on 27 critics, indicating \"generally unfavorable reviews\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/dirty-grandpa|title=Dirty Grandpa Reviews|website=[[Metacritic]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|access-date=September 28, 2019}}</ref> At the [[37th Golden Raspberry Awards]] it received five nominations, for Worst Picture, Worst Actor (De Niro), Worst Supporting Actress ([[Julianne Hough]] and [[Aubrey Plaza]], respectively) and Worst Screenplay, but did not win in any category.\n\n=== ''Guardians'' (2017) ===\n''[[Guardians (2017 film)|Guardians]]'' is a Russian [[superhero film]]<ref>[https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/guardians-movie-trailer-2017-russian-923229 'Guardians' Movie Trailer 2017: Russian Superheroes Unite|Hollywood Reporter]</ref><ref>[https://mubi.com/films/guardians-2017 Guardians (2017)-MUBI]</ref> about a team of Soviet superheroes created during the [[Cold War]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://letterboxd.com/film/guardians-2017/|title=Guardians (2017)|last=|first=|date=|website=Letterboxd|access-date=April 17, 2019}}</ref> It was criticized for having a derivative plot, bad acting and direction, cheap CGI, [[plot hole]]s and overall low quality. ''Kg-portal.ru'' wrote that \"''Guardians'' is a film from which Russian cinema should be protected. It's like a sequel to ''Plan 9 from Outer Space'', filmed by [[Uwe Boll]], with the screenplay by [[Tommy Wiseau]] and with him in the lead role\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://kg-portal.ru/movies/zaschitniki/reviews/5269/|script-title=ru:\u0414\u0435\u0440\u044c\u043c\u043e \u043d\u0430 \u044d\u043a\u0441\u043f\u043e\u0440\u0442\n|language=Russian|work=kg-portal.ru|date=October 23, 2017|accessdate=February 19, 2019}}</ref> ''[[Rossiyskaya Gazeta]]'' commented that the film was \"Worse than you can imagine.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://rg.ru/2017/02/24/zashchitniki-sarika-andreasiana-naskolko-eto-ploho.html|script-title=ru:\u041e\u0441\u043b\u0438\u043a, \u0441\u0443\u0441\u043b\u0438\u043a, \u0410\u043d\u0434\u0440\u0435\u0430\u0441\u044f\u043d\n|language=Russian|work=[[Rossiyskaya Gazeta]]|date=February 24, 2017|accessdate=February 23, 2019}}</ref> ''[[Meduza]]'' compared the film's director, [[Sarik Andreasyan]], to ''Plan 9 from Outer Space''{{'}}s director, [[Ed Wood]], and said that ''Guardians'' \"is a convincing answer to the eternal question of why we can never catch up with Hollywood even in our own box office\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://meduza.io/feature/2017/02/23/filmy-na-nedelyu-patrioticheskie-i-uzhasayuschie-zaschitniki-a-takzhe-dzheki-toni-erdmann-i-slishkom-svobodnyy-chelovek|script-title=ru:\u0424\u0438\u043b\u044c\u043c\u044b \u043d\u0430 \u043d\u0435\u0434\u0435\u043b\u044e: \u043f\u0430\u0442\u0440\u0438\u043e\u0442\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0435 (\u0438 \u0443\u0436\u0430\u0441\u0430\u044e\u0449\u0438\u0435) \"\u0417\u0430\u0449\u0438\u0442\u043d\u0438\u043a\u0438\", \u0430 \u0442\u0430\u043a\u0436\u0435 \"\u0414\u0436\u0435\u043a\u0438\", \"\u0422\u043e\u043d\u0438 \u042d\u0440\u0434\u043c\u0430\u043d\u043d\" \u0438 \"\u0421\u043b\u0438\u0448\u043a\u043e\u043c \u0441\u0432\u043e\u0431\u043e\u0434\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0447\u0435\u043b\u043e\u0432\u0435\u043a\"|language=Russian|work=[[Meduza]]|date=October 23, 2017|accessdate=February 19, 2019}}</ref> ''[[Afisha]]'' said that it was the Russian answer to ''[[Howard the Duck (film)|Howard the Duck]]'',<ref>{{cite news|url=https://daily.afisha.ru/cinema/4639-zaschitniki-nash-otvet-govardu-utke/|script-title=ru:\"\u0417\u0430\u0449\u0438\u0442\u043d\u0438\u043a\u0438\" \u0421\u0430\u0440\u0438\u043a\u0430 \u0410\u043d\u0434\u0440\u0435\u0430\u0441\u044f\u043d\u0430: \u043d\u0430\u0448 \u043e\u0442\u0432\u0435\u0442 \u0413\u043e\u0432\u0430\u0440\u0434\u0443-\u0443\u0442\u043a\u0435|language=Russian|work=[[Afisha]]|date=October 23, 2017|accessdate=February 19, 2019}}</ref> and [[Ivi, Inc.]] commented that \"a more talentless film is hard to imagine\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ivi.tv/watch/143155/reviews/44706|script-title=ru:\u0417\u0430\u0449\u0438\u0442\u0438\u0442\u0435 \u043d\u0430\u0441 \u043e\u0442 \"\u0417\u0430\u0449\u0438\u0442\u043d\u0438\u043a\u043e\u0432\"|language=Russian|work=[[Ivi, Inc.]]|date=October 23, 2017|accessdate=February 19, 2019}}</ref> [[RIA Novosti]] placed it at the top of their worst film list,<ref name=\"RIA\"/> and it appears on Kritikanstvo's all-time lowest-scoring films.<ref name=\"Kritikanstvo\">{{cite news|url=http://www.kritikanstvo.ru/top/movies/worst/alltime/|script-title=ru:\u0425\u0443\u0434\u0448\u0438\u0435 \u0444\u0438\u043b\u044c\u043c\u044b|language=Russian|publisher=Kritikanstvo|accessdate=February 19, 2019}}</ref> Critics outside of Russia generally panned the film but were not as harsh, as it has a 30% rating on Rotten Tomatoes based on 10 reviews.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/guardians_2017|title=Guardians (Zashchitniki)|last=|first=|date=|work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango]]|accessdate=February 23, 2019}}</ref> A sequel was planned,<ref>{{cite web |url= https://hollywoodreporter.com/news/russian-superhero-film-china-release-868671|title= Russian Cold War Superhero Film to Get China Release Under Import Quota|first= Vladimir|last= Kozlov|date= February 23, 2016|accessdate= February 23, 2019|work= [[The Hollywood Reporter]]}}</ref> but the film was a box office bomb, which resulted in the film's production company, [[Enjoy Movies]], subsequently filing for bankruptcy, and the [[Cinema Foundation of Russia]], which provided part of the budget, suing the company and demanding a return of the investment.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://lenta.ru/news/2017/07/05/zashitniki/ |script-title=ru:\u0424\u043e\u043d\u0434 \u043a\u0438\u043d\u043e \u043f\u043e\u0442\u0440\u0435\u0431\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043b 51 \u043c\u0438\u043b\u043b\u0438\u043e\u043d \u0440\u0443\u0431\u043b\u0435\u0439 \u0443 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0434\u044e\u0441\u0435\u0440\u043e\u0432 \"\u0417\u0430\u0449\u0438\u0442\u043d\u0438\u043a\u043e\u0432\"|language=Russian|work=[[Lenta.ru]]|date=July 5, 2017|accessdate=February 19, 2019}}</ref><!-- Please do not add The Emoji Movie or Holmes & Watson. They have already been submitted many times but do not meet the inclusion criteria for this list and will be deleted. Generally, before submitting a film, please check the talk page and the list of removed films to see if the movie has already been rejected in the past.  -->\n\n=== ''Death Of A Nation'' (2018) ===\n''[[Death of a Nation]]:Can We Save America a Second Time?\"'' is a 2018 American political documentary film by Dinesh D'Souza a convicted felon and a US conservative provocateur, comparing the political climate surrounding the 45th President of the United States Donald Trump to that of the 16th President, Abraham Lincoln. The film argues that the Democratic Party from both eras was critical of the presidents of the time and that the Democrats have similarities to fascist regimes, including the Nazi Party. The film was written and directed by Dinesh D'Souza and Bruce Schooley, and produced by Gerald R. Molen. It was produced on a budget of $6 million.\n\nOwen Gleiberman of [[Variety]] noted that \"D\u2019Souza\u2019s bogus conflation of liberalism and Nazism is really his way of denying the white-supremacist appeal that runs right down the middle of the Trump presidency....In \u201cDeath of a Nation,\u201d Dinesh D\u2019Souza is no longer preaching to the choir; he\u2019s preaching to the mentally unsound\" <ref>https://variety.com/2018/film/reviews/death-of-a-nation-review-dinesh-dsouza-1202890451/</ref>Review aggregator Metacritic ranked it as the worst film of all time out of almost 12,000 films on its website. <ref>https://www.metacritic.com/movie/death-of-a-nation</ref> [[Rotten Tomatoes]] gave it a reading of zero on its Tomatometer<ref>https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/death_of_a_nation</ref> [[Indiewire]] wrote that \"Dinesh D\u2019Souza\u2019s \u201cDeath of a Nation\u201d has the dubious distinction of coming in at #1, but it isn\u2019t just the worst film of 2018 \u2014 it\u2019s the worst film in the site\u2019s history: \u201cOut of the 11,819 films for which we have Metascores,\u201d the list reads, \u201c\u2018Nation\u2019 ranks as #11,819.\u201d <ref>https://www.indiewire.com/2018/12/worst-movies-2018-metacritic-death-of-a-nation-1202030220/</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{portal|Film|Lists}}\n* [[List of films considered the best]]\n* [[Box office bomb]]\n* [[List of box office bombs]]\n* [[List of films with a 0% rating on Rotten Tomatoes]]\n* [[CinemaScore#List of F films]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|20em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://rottentomatoes.com/ Rotten Tomatoes]\n* [http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20050811/COMMENTARY/50808002 Ebert's Most Hated]\n* [http://www.razzies.com/ Golden Raspberry Awards]\n* [https://metacritic.com/film/lowscores.shtml Metacritic: Worst-Reviewed Movies]\n* [http://www.mrqe.com/movies/special/50_worst_movies Movie Review Query Engine's 50 Worst]\n* [https://www.imdb.com/chart/bottom IMDb Bottom 100] (user scores)\n\n{{Worst works}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:List Of Films Considered The Worst}}\n[[Category:Lists of films by type|Worst]]\n[[Category:Lists of worsts|Films]]\n[[Category:Film and video fandom]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Wikimedia list article}}\n{{for|the 2011 American action comedy|The Worst Movie Ever!}}\n{{pp-protected|reason=Persistent [[WP:Disruptive editing|disruptive editing]]|small=yes}}\n</noinclude>[[File:Reefer Madness (1936).jpg|220px|thumb|''[[Reefer Madness]]'', one of the earliest films to garner particularly negative contemporary reviews<ref name=\"psmag\">{{cite news|last1=Lincoln|first1=Kevin|title=The Benefits of Being the Worst Movie Ever Made|url=https://psmag.com/economics/benefits-worst-movie-ever-made-84813|accessdate=October 23, 2017|work=[[Pacific Standard]]|date=July 2, 2014|language=en}}</ref>]]\nThe [[film]]s listed below have been cited by a variety of notable critics in varying media sources as being among the '''worst films ever made'''. Examples of such sources include [[Metacritic]], [[Roger Ebert]]'s list of most-hated films, ''[[The Golden Turkey Awards]]'', ''[[Leonard Maltin's Movie Guide]]'', [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the [[Stinkers Bad Movie Awards]], the cult TV series ''[[Mystery Science Theater 3000]]'', and the [[Golden Raspberry Awards]] (aka the \"Razzies\"). Films on these lists are generally [[feature film|feature-length films]] that are [[commerce|commercial]]/[[art film|artistic]] in nature (intended to turn a profit and/or to express personal statements), professionally or independently produced (as opposed to [[amateur]] productions), and released in theaters, then on television, or more recently through on-demand [[streaming media|streaming services]].\n\n== 1930s ==\n\n=== ''Maniac'' (1934) ===\n''[[Maniac (1934 film)|Maniac]]'', also known as ''Sex Maniac'', is an [[exploitation film|exploitation]]/[[horror film]] directed by [[Dwain Esper]]. The story is a loose adaptation of the [[Edgar Allan Poe]] story \"[[The Black Cat (short story)|The Black Cat]]\" and follows a [[vaudeville]] impersonator who becomes an assistant to a [[mad scientist]]. [[Danny Peary]] believes that ''Maniac'' is the worst film ever made, Charlie Jane Anders of [[Gawker Media]]{{'}}s [[io9]] described it as \"possibly the worst movie in history\" and ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'' critic Michael Wilmington wrote that it may be the worst film he had ever seen, writing: \"There are some voyages into ineptitude, like Dwain Esper's anti-classic ''Maniac,'' that defy all reason.\"<ref>{{Cite book|last1=Peary|first1=Danny|authorlink=Danny Peary|title=Cult Midnight Movies: Discover the 37 Best Weird, Sleazy, Sexy, and Crazy Good Cinema Classics|publisher=[[Workman Publishing Company]]|url=https://books.google.com/?id=TTsPBAAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=Maniac+(1934)#v=snippet&q=Maniac%20(1934)%20Dwain%20Esper&f=false|year=2014|isbn=9780761181699}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://io9.gizmodo.com/did-the-worst-movie-of-all-time-come-out-75-years-ago-5161275 |title=Did The Worst Movie Of All Time Come Out 75 Years Ago? |publisher=[[io9]] |last=Anders|first=Charlie Jane |date=February 26, 2009|accessdate=February 18, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-2005-08-12-0508120290-story.html| work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|title='Chaos' a loathsome exercise in horror\n|last =Wilmington|first=Michael|date=August 12, 2005|accessdate=February 18, 2019}}</ref> [[Rotten Tomatoes]] placed ''Maniac'' on their list of movies \"So Bad They're Unmissable\",<ref name=\"sobad\"/> the Italian ''[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]'' included the film on its list of the 20 worst movies ever, and it is featured in ''[[The Official Razzie Movie Guide]]''.<ref name=italianvanity>{{cite news|url=https://www.vanityfair.it/show/cinema/2018/02/25/20-film-piu-brutti-di-sempre| work=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]|title=I 20 film pi\u00f9 brutti di sempre|last =Pellegrini|first=Francesca|language=Italian|date=25 February 2018|accessdate=February 18, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Reefer Madness'' (1936) ===\n[[File:ReeferMadness 12.JPG|thumb|upright|Originally titled ''Tell Your Children'', ''[[Reefer Madness]]'' was called \"the grand-daddy of all 'Worst' movies\" by [[Leonard Maltin]]]]\n''[[Reefer Madness]]'' (originally released as ''Tell Your Children'' and sometimes titled or subtitled as ''The Burning Question'', ''Dope Addict'', ''Doped Youth'', and ''Love Madness'') is a 1936 American [[exploitation film]] and [[propaganda|propaganda work]] revolving around the melodramatic events that ensue when high school students are lured by pushers to try [[cannabis (drug)|marijuana]]\u2014from a [[Hit and run (vehicular)|hit and run accident]], to [[manslaughter]], suicide, attempted rape, and descent into madness. ''[[Pacific Standard]]'' wrote that ''Reefer Madness'' was \"one of the first films ever to be considered transcendentally bad\"<ref name=\"psmag\"/> and [[Leonard Maltin]] has called it \"the grand-daddy of all 'Worst' movies\".<ref name=\"Maltin01211\">{{cite book |last=Maltin |first=Leonard |authorlink=Leonard Maltin |title=Leonard Maltin's Movie and Video Guide 2004 |publisher=Signet |year=2003 |isbn=0-451-20940-0 |url=https://archive.org/details/leonardmaltinsmo00leon }}</ref> ''[[Las Vegas CityLife]]'' named it the \"worst ever\" runner-up to ''[[Plan 9 from Outer Space]]'',<ref>{{cite news |url=http://archives.lasvegascitylife.com/articles/2009/09/24/ae/stage/iq_31362594.txt |date=September 24, 2009 |last=McKee |first=David |work=Las Vegas CityLife |accessdate=November 17, 2013 |title=What's the Worst Movie Ever? |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130903051856/http://archives.lasvegascitylife.com/articles/2009/09/24/ae/stage/iq_31362594.txt |archivedate=September 3, 2013 }}</ref> and [[AMC (TV channel)|AMC]] described it as \"one of the worst movies ever made\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://movies.amctv.com/movie/1936/Reefer+Madness|work=[[AMC (TV channel)]] |accessdate=November 17, 2013 |title= Reefer Madness (1936)}}</ref> [[News.com.au]] considered it a \"disastrous flop turned cult classic\" due to its \"terrible acting and exaggerated drug-addicted stereotypes\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.news.com.au/national/nsw-act/when-hollywoods-worst-films-become-cult-classics/news-story/792f3f09aba66809245d65328c73921c|title=When Hollywood's worst films become cult classics|work=[[News.com.au]]|first=Troy|last=Lennon|date=December 7, 2017|accessdate=January 20, 2019}}</ref> The film has inspired a number of parodies, including an [[off-Broadway]] [[Reefer Madness (musical)|musical satire]] and a [[Reefer Madness (2005 film)|2005 film]] based on the musical.<ref>[http://www.tcm.com/tcmdb/title/546510/Reefer-Madness/ Reefer Madness (2005)-Overview-TCM.com]</ref>\n\n=== ''The Terror of Tiny Town'' (1938)===\n''[[The Terror of Tiny Town]]'', directed by [[Sam Newfield]] and produced by [[Jed Buell]], remains the only [[musical film|musical]] [[Western (genre)|Western]] with an all-[[Dwarfism|dwarf]] cast. The film was pulled from obscurity as a [[camp (style)|camp classic]] after appearing in college and [[midnight film|midnight screenings]] in the early 1970s.<ref>[http://www.tcm.com/tcmdb/title/92598/The-Terror-of-Tiny-Town/articles.html The Terror of Tiny Town (1938) - Articles - TCM.com]</ref> In 1978, it was included in ''[[The Fifty Worst Films of All Time]]''<ref name=\"tinyterror\">{{cite web|url=https://filmthreat.com/uncategorized/the-terror-of-tiny-town-dvd/|title=The Terror of Tiny Town (DVD)|work=Film Threat|date=June 17, 2005|accessdate=March 23, 2020}}</ref> and has since been listed as one of the worst films ever made by ''[[Flavorwire]]'',<ref name=\"Flavorwire\"/> Rotten Tomatoes,<ref name=\"sobad\"/>  and ''[[The Golden Turkey Awards]]''.<ref name=\"tinyterror\"/> [[Melvin Defleur]] referred to it as \"Perhaps the worst film of all time\",<ref>{{Cite book|last1=Defluer|first1=Melvin|authorlink=Melvin Defleur|title=Understanding Mass Communication: A Liberal Arts Perspective|publisher=[[Houghton Mifflin Harcourt]]|edition=6|year=1998|page=160}}</ref> and critic Gabriel Ricard listed it as the worst film ever made; stating,\"not only is it pretty terrible, but ''Tiny Town'' is also pretty endearing.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://culturedvultures.com/best-worst-movies/|title=20 Best Worst Movies Of All Time|work=Cultured Vultures|last=Richard|first=Gabriel|date=June 5, 2019|accessdate=March 23, 2020}}</ref> In 1986, ''The Terror of Tiny Town'' was the first film featured on ''[[Canned Film Festival]]'', a [[late night television]] show featuring the worst movies ever made.<ref name=\"cannedfilm\">{{cite web|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-1986-06-20-8602140300-story.html|title=A 'Terror' Kicks Off World's Worst Film Festival|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|last=Terry|first=Clifford|date=June 20, 1989|accessdate=March 23, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== 1940s ==\n\n=== ''No Orchids for Miss Blandish'' (1948) ===\n\n''[[No Orchids for Miss Blandish (film)|No Orchids for Miss Blandish]]'', a British gangster film adapted from the 1939 [[No Orchids for Miss Blandish (novel)|novel]] by [[James Hadley Chase]], received a very hostile reception from the press. This was mainly due to the film's high (for the time) level of sexual and violent content, but also because its attempt to portray Americans using a largely British cast (including an early role for [[Sid James]])<ref name=\"goodwin\">{{cite book |first=Cliff |last=Goodwin |title=Sid James: A Biography |publisher=Random House |year=2011 |isbn=978-0-7535-4682-6 |pages=67\u201368 }}</ref> was seen as unconvincing.<ref name=\"bmc\">{{cite book |last=McFarlane |first=Brian |year=1999 |chapter=Outrage: No Orchids for Miss Blandish |title=British Crime Cinema |editor-first1=Steve |editor-last1=Chibnall |editor-first2=Robert |editor-last2=Murphy |publisher=Routledge |isbn=0-415-16870-8 |pages=37\u201350 }}</ref> The British film journal ''[[Monthly Film Bulletin]]'' called it \"the most sickening exhibition of brutality, perversion, sex and sadism ever to be shown on a cinema screen\".<ref name=\"bmc\" /> The ''[[Sunday Express]]'' film reviewer called ''No Orchids for Miss Blandish'' \"the worst film I have ever seen\".<ref name=\"hfg\">{{cite book |title=Halliwell's Film Guide |publisher=HarperPerennial |year=1994 |isbn=978-0-06-273318-4 |page=781 }}</ref> The Australian newspaper ''[[The Age]]'' also gave a harsh review: \"''No Orchids for Miss Blandish'' is not only a disgrace to the studio that made it, but it also reflects on the British industry as a whole ... the entire production is unpardonable.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=The Chiel's Film Review |newspaper=The Age |date=November 27, 1948 |page=5 }}</ref> Cliff Goodwin, discussing ''No Orchids For Miss Blandish's'' initial reception, notes it was \"unanimously dubbed 'the worst film ever made{{'\"}}.<ref name=\"goodwin\" /> Later reviews of the film were equally antipathetic. ''No Orchids for Miss Blandish'' was described by British film reviewer [[Leslie Halliwell]] as a \"hilariously awful gangster film ... one of the worst films ever made\".<ref name=\"hfg\" /> ''Leonard Maltin's Classic Movie Guide'' states that ''No Orchids for Miss Blandish'' \"aspires to be a Hollywood film noir and misses by a mile.\"<ref>{{cite book |last=Maltin |first=Leonard |year=2011 |title=Leonard Maltin's Classic Movie Guide: From The Silent Era Through 1965 |edition=Second |publisher=Penguin |isbn=978-0-452-29577-3 |page=474 }}</ref>\n\n=== ''The Babe Ruth Story'' (1948) ===\n\n''[[The Babe Ruth Story]]'' is a 1948 baseball film biography of [[Babe Ruth]], starring [[William Bendix]], [[Claire Trevor]] and [[Sam Levene]].<ref>{{Citation|last=Del Ruth|first=Roy|title=The Babe Ruth story|date=2010|publisher=Warner Home Video|language=English|oclc=694103117|last2=Considine|first2=Bob|last3=Callahan|first3=George|last4=Bendix|first4=William|last5=Trevor|first5=Claire|last6=Bickford|first6=Charles|last7=Frawley|first7=William|last8=Levene|first8=Sam|last9=Allied Artists Productions}}</ref> ''[[The New York Times]]'' describes it as \"the ''[[Plan 9 from Outer Space]]'' of baseball biopics\".<ref>{{cite news |title=The Babe Ruth Story (1948)|newspaper=The New York Times |url=https://www.nytimes.com/movies/movie/3535/The-Babe-Ruth-Story/overview |accessdate=30 November 2013}}</ref> It was rushed into release while Ruth was still alive. In the final scene, Ruth delivers on a promise he made to a young cancer patient that he would hit a [[home run]]. Not only does Ruth succeed in fulfilling the promise, but also the child is subsequently cured of his cancer. [[Dan Shaughnessy]] of ''[[The Boston Globe]]'' claimed the film was the worst he had ever seen,<ref>{{cite news |title=Duke as Williams? A Prince of an Idea |author=Dan Shaughnessy |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=XscSAAAAIBAJ&sjid=vvkDAAAAIBAJ&pg=7230,788739&dq=babe+ruth+story+worst+film |newspaper=Spokane Chronicle |date=Apr 3, 1986 |accessdate=30 November 2013}}</ref> while ''[[The Washington Times]]'' stated that it \"stands as possibly the worst movie ever made\".<ref>{{cite news |last=Heller |first=Dick |title=Clinic and reception in the works to honor NBA pioneer Lloyd |newspaper=The Washington Times |date=July 23, 2000 |url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=WT&p_theme=wt&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EB08BFA289BE4FB&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D |accessdate=30 November 2013}}{{subscription required}}</ref> The film has been called one of the worst sports films ever by ''[[Newsday]]'' and ''[[The A.V. Club]]'',<ref>{{cite news |last=Isaacs |first=Stan |title=Out ofLeft Field \u2013 The 10 Worst Sports Movies Of All Time |newspaper=Newsday |date=Feb 26, 1989 |url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/newsday/doc/278087041.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Feb%2026,%201989&author=Stan%20Isaacs&pub=Newsday%20%28Combined%20editions%29&edition=&startpage=&desc=OUT%20OF%20LEFT%20FIELD%20The%2010%20Worst%20Sports%20Movies%20Of%20All%20Time |accessdate=30 November 2013}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://film.avclub.com/the-home-run-that-cured-cancer-16-amazing-movie-sports-1798214998|title=The home run that cured cancer: 16 Amazing Movie Sports Feats|last=Mincher|first=Chris|last2=Bahn|first2=Christopher|date=October 6, 2008|website=[[The A.V. Club]]|language=en-US|access-date=April 16, 2019|last3=Modell|first3=Josh|last4=Gillette|first4=Amelie|last5=Tobias|first5=Scott|last6=Murray|first6=Noel|last7=Pierce|first7=Leonard}}</ref> and called one of the worst biopics by [[Moviefone]] and [[Spike (TV network)|Spike]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.moviefone.com/2009/11/05/worst-movie-biopics/|title=Worst Movie Biopics: Real-Life Catastrophes|date=November 5, 2009|accessdate=30 November 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203031806/http://news.moviefone.com/2009/11/05/worst-movie-biopics/|archive-date=3 December 2013|url-status=dead|publisher=[[Moviefone]]|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.spike.com/articles/td0rkp/all-access-weekly-blockbuster-hollywood-bios-the-good-the-bad-and-the-jobs|title=Blockbuster Hollywood Bios: The Good, the Bad, and the \"Jobs\"|last=Marshall|first=Kevin|date=August 16, 2013|website=[[Spike (TV network)|Spike]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203195640/http://www.spike.com/articles/td0rkp/all-access-weekly-blockbuster-hollywood-bios-the-good-the-bad-and-the-jobs|archive-date=December 3, 2013|url-status=dead|access-date=April 16, 2019}}</ref> Michael Sauter included it in his book ''The Worst Movies of All Time'' and Leonard Maltin called it \"perfectly dreadful\".<ref name=\"Maltin01211\"/>\n\n== 1950s ==\n\n=== ''Glen or Glenda'' (1953) ===\n[[File:Ed wood glen or glenda.jpg|thumb|[[Ed Wood]] appears in a scene from ''[[Glen or Glenda]]''. He directed ''Glen or Glenda'' and  ''[[Plan 9 from Outer Space]]'' and was named the Worst Director of All Time in ''[[The Golden Turkey Awards]]''.]]\nA semi-[[Autobiography|autobiographical]] quasi-[[Documentary film|documentary]] about [[transvestism]], ''[[Glen or Glenda]]'' starred and was directed by [[Ed Wood]]. After a nightmarish [[dream sequence]], Glen undergoes psychotherapy to help cure his affliction. [[Bela Lugosi]] appears in this film, as he did in several other Wood films toward the end of his career. Leonard Maltin insists this was far worse than Wood's later ''[[Plan 9 from Outer Space]]'' and considers it \"possibly the worst movie ever made\".<ref name=\"Maltin01211\"/> Richard Barrios describes ''Glen or Glenda'' as \"one of the funniest and worst movies ever made\".<ref>Richard Barrios, ''Screened Out: Playing Gay in Hollywood from Edison to Stonewall'', Psychology Press, 2003, {{ISBN|0-415-92328-X}}, Page 235.</ref> In his book ''Cult Movies 3'', [[Danny Peary]] suggests this is actually a radical, if ineptly made, film that presents a far more personal story than is contained in films by more well-respected [[auteur theory|auteurs]], and it was taken seriously and seen as a significant work by Steve Jenkins, writing for ''[[The Monthly Film Bulletin]]'' when the film was finally released in the UK in 1981.<ref>{{cite book |last=Peary |first=Danny |authorlink=Danny Peary |title=Cult Movies 3: 50 More of the Classics, the Sleepers, the Weird and the Wonderful |publisher=Simon & Schuster |year=1988 |isbn=978-0-671-64810-7}}</ref> In 1994, [[Tim Burton]] directed ''[[Ed Wood (film)|Ed Wood]]'', which includes some material about the trials and tribulations of making ''Glen or Glenda''.\n\n=== ''Robot Monster'' (1953) ===\n\n''[[Robot Monster]]'', a [[science-fiction film]] originally shot and exhibited in [[3-D film|3D]], features an actor dressed in a gorilla suit and what looks almost like a [[diving helmet]]. The film, produced and directed by [[Phil Tucker]], is listed in Michael Sauter's book ''The Worst Movies of All Time'' among \"The Baddest of the Bs\". It is also featured in ''[[The Book of Lists]]''' 10 worst movies list, and in ''[[The Fifty Worst Films of All Time]]''. ''[[The Golden Turkey Awards]]'' confers on its main character the title of \"Most Ridiculous Monster in Screen History\" and, listing director Tucker among the runners-up to \"Worst Director of All Time\" (the winner being Ed Wood), states, \"What made ''Robot Monster'' ineffably worse than any other low-budget sci-fi epic was its bizarre artistic pretension\". It was featured in an episode of the movie-mocking television show ''[[Mystery Science Theater 3000]]'',<ref>{{cite web |title=Mystery Science Theater 3000 \u2013 Robot Monster |work=TV.com |url=http://www.tv.com/mystery-science-theater-3000/robot-monster/episode/46805/summary.html?tag=ep_list;title;6/ |accessdate=2011-03-07}}</ref> and was fondly remembered by author [[Stephen King]], who quotes, and agrees with, a review in ''[[Castle of Frankenstein]]'' magazine (\"certainly among the finest terrible movies ever made\", \"one of the most laughable [[Poverty Row|poverty row]] quickies\").<ref>{{cite book |first=Stephen |last=King |title=Danse Macabre |year=1981 |publisher=Everest House |location=New York |isbn=978-0-89696-076-3|title-link=Danse Macabre (book) }}</ref>\n\n=== ''The Conqueror'' (1956) ===\n\n[[Howard Hughes]] funded ''[[The Conqueror (1956 film)|The Conqueror]]'', an [[epic film]] featuring [[John Wayne]] as [[Mongolia]]n chieftain [[Genghis Khan]] and the redheaded [[Susan Hayward]] as a [[Tatars|Tatar]] princess. The movie was filmed near [[St. George, Utah]], downwind from a [[nuclear testing]] range in [[Nevada]], and is often blamed for the [[cancer]] deaths of many of the cast and crew, including Hayward, Wayne, [[Agnes Moorehead]], [[Pedro Armend\u00e1riz]], and director [[Dick Powell]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Adams |first=Cecil |title=Did John Wayne die of cancer caused by a radioactive movie set? |publisher=The Straight Dope |date=October 26, 1984 |url=http://www.straightdope.com/classics/a2_016.html |accessdate=2011-03-07}}</ref> In addition to filming near the testing range, truckloads of the red sands were transported back to the studios for interior scenes. The film made the ten-worst list in ''[[The Book of Lists]]'', appears in Michael Sauter's book ''The Worst Movies of All Time'', and was among those listed in [[Michael Medved]]'s book ''[[The Fifty Worst Films of All Time]]''. Originally written for [[Marlon Brando]], ''[[The Guardian]]'' called the choice of Wayne for Khan \"one of the worst casting decisions of all time\".<ref name=geng/> ''[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]'' listed ''The Conqueror'' as the worst biopic ever made.<ref>{{cite web |last=Barone |first=Matt |title=The 10 Worst Biopic Movies Of All Time |work=Complex |date=November 12, 2012 |url=http://www.complex.com/pop-culture/2012/11/10-worst-biopic-movies-of-all-time/ |accessdate=July 7, 2017}}</ref>\n\nHughes, one of the world's wealthiest people at the time, had previously produced the successful dramatic films ''[[Hell's Angels (film)|Hell's Angels]]'', ''[[Scarface (1932 film)|Scarface]]'', and ''[[The Outlaw]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/april/5/newsid_4739000/4739940.stm |title=BBC On THis Day &#124; 5 &#124; 1976: Billionaire Howard Hughes dies |work=BBC News |date=1976-04-07 |accessdate=2013-11-18}}</ref> After seeing ''The Conqueror'' himself, Hughes bought every existing print for $12 million and refused to let the film be seen on television until 1974, reportedly out of guilt over the decision to shoot at such a hazardous location.<ref>{{cite book |title=My Year of Flops |last=Rubin |first=Nathan |year=2010 |publisher=[[Charles Scribner's Sons|Scribner]] |location= |isbn=978-1-4391-5312-3 |page= |pages= |url=https://archive.org/details/myyearofflopsavc0000rabi |accessdate= }}</ref> By 1980, 91 of the 220 cast and crew members had been diagnosed with cancer, over 41%.<ref name=geng>{{cite news|last=von Tunzelmann|first=Alex|title=The Conqueror: Hollywood gives Genghis Khan a kicking he won't forget|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/filmblog/2013/may/03/the-conqueror-hollywood-genghis-khan|newspaper=The Guardian|date=3 May 2013|location=London}}</ref> This was the last film Hughes produced.\n\n=== ''Fire Maidens from Outer Space'' (1956) ===\n\n''[[Fire Maidens from Outer Space]]'', a low-budget British [[space opera]] film (known in the US as ''Fire Maidens of Outer Space''), is about a group of astronauts visiting an all-female society on a moon of [[Jupiter]]. This film developed a negative reputation for its poor special effects (including a scene on the alien planet in which an automobile is visible driving past).<ref name=\"dt\">[https://www.dvdtalk.com/reviews/61441/fire-maidens-of-outer-space/ Fire Maidens Of Outer Space]. ''DVD Talk'', August 13, 2013. Retrieved January 21, 2014.</ref> Leslie Halliwell described ''Fire Maidens from Outer Space'' as \"a strong contender for the title of the worst movie ever made, with diaphanously clad English gals striking embarrassed poses against cardboard sets\".<ref>John Walker (ed.) ''Halliwell's Film and Video Guide 2000'', London and New York; HarperCollins, 1999, {{ISBN|0-06-273645-0}} (p.287).</ref> British film historian I.Q. Hunter included it in his list of candidates for \"the worst British film ever made\".<ref name=\"iqh\">I. Q Hunter, \"From Window Cleaner to Potato Man\" in ''British Comedy Cinema'', edited by I.Q. Hunter and Laraine Porter. Routledge, 2012. {{ISBN|0-415-66667-8}}. (p.154)</ref> The [[Internet Brands|DVD Talk]] website's review claimed it \"may be among the worst-ever professionally produced science fiction films\".<ref name=\"dt\" /> In November 1992, the film was featured in an episode of ''Mystery Science Theater 3000''.\n\n=== ''Plan 9 from Outer Space'' (1959) ===\n[[File:Plan 9 Alternative poster.jpg|thumb|''[[Plan 9 from Outer Space]]'' has been named the worst movie ever made by ''[[The Golden Turkey Awards]]'' and other sources]]\n[[Ed Wood]]'s ''[[Plan 9 from Outer Space]]'' was labeled the \"Worst Film Ever\" by ''[[The Golden Turkey Awards]]''. This movie marked the final film appearance of [[Bela Lugosi]]. Wood shot only a small amount of test footage featuring his idol Lugosi before the actor's death. Afterwards, the character was played by [[Tom Mason]], the [[chiropractic|chiropractor]] of Wood's wife (Kathy O'Hara) at the time, who played his scenes holding the character's cape in front of his face.\n\nWood was apparently undeterred by the numerous physical differences that distinguished Mason from Lugosi {{spaced ndash}} such as height and build, and the fact that Mason was nearly bald while Lugosi retained a full head of hair until he died.  Worst of all, Mason may have been the only man in the world who couldn't do an impression of Lugosi's accent. Years later, video distributors such as Avenue One DVD began to make light of this, adding such blurbs as \"Almost Starring Bela Lugosi\" to the cover art. Numerous critics also pointed out the cheap, hardly believable special effects and [[wikt:kitschy|kitschy]] dialogue.\n\nShot in 1956, the film was not released until 1959 because of difficulty in finding a distributor. It has played at the New Orleans Worst Film Festival. In 1994, [[Tim Burton]] directed ''[[Ed Wood (film)|Ed Wood]]'', which includes some material about the trials and tribulations of making ''Plan 9''. Phil Hall of ''Film Threat'' calls it \"far too entertaining to be considered as the very worst film ever made\".<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/plan-9-from-outer-space/reviews/|title=Plan 9 from Outer Space - Movie Reviews|last=|first=|date=|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|access-date=April 16, 2019}}</ref> Likewise, John Wirt of ''The Advocate'' goes as far as to call it \"the ultimate cult flick\",<ref name=\":2\" /> and ''Videohound's Complete Guide to Cult Flicks and Trash Pics'' states, \"In fact, the film has become so famous for its own badness that it's now beyond criticism.\"<ref>{{cite book |last=Schwartz |first=Carol |title=Videohound's Complete Guide to Cult Flicks and Trash Pics |publisher=Visible Ink Press |year=1995 |isbn=978-0-7876-0616-9}}</ref> Ian Berriman of ''[[SFX (magazine)|SFX]]'' commented about the unintentional comedy, \"Some things are best watched at 3 am, wrapped in the warm glow of drunkenness ... ''Plan 9 From Outer Space'' is one of them.\" ''The [[Radio Times]] Guide to Films'' described ''Plan 9'' as \"the worst film ever made\" and \"tediously depressing\".<ref>''Radio Times Guide to Films 2014''. Radio Times, London, 2013. {{ISBN|0-9567523-6-5}} (p.947).</ref>\n\n== 1960s ==\n\n=== ''The Beast of Yucca Flats'' (1961) ===\n\n''[[The Beast of Yucca Flats]]'' by [[Coleman Francis]], shot silently with added narration, concerns a scientist ([[Tor Johnson]]) who is exposed to radiation from an atomic blast, which turns him into a monster. The film opens with a scene of implied [[necrophilia]] that has nothing to do with the remainder of the movie and does not fit anywhere into the film's chronology. ''Leonard Maltin's TV and Movie Guide'' calls it \"one of the worst films ever made\".<ref>{{cite book| first=Leonard |last=Maltin |edition=2007 |title=Leonard Maltin's Movie and Video Guide |publisher=Plume |location=New York |isbn=978-0-452-28893-5 |page=94|year=2007 }}</ref> [[Bill Warren (film historian and critic)|Bill Warren]] said, \"It may very well be the worst non-[[pornographic film|porno]] science fiction movie ever made.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.monstershack.net/sp/index.php/the-beast-of-yucca-flats-1961/ |title=Full Movie Walk-throughs |publisher=Monster Shack |date=2009-02-10 |accessdate=2011-01-17}}</ref> It was featured on ''Mystery Science Theater 3000'', where members of the cast state it is one of the worst films they have seen up to that point.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.castleforrester.com/media/guide/0621.htm |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080907155815/http://www.castleforrester.com/media/guide/0621.htm |url-status=dead |archive-date=2008-09-07 |title=Experiment Guide |publisher=Castle Forrester |accessdate=2011-01-17}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Eegah'' (1962) ===\n\nThe low-budget shocker ''[[Eegah]]'' features [[Richard Kiel]] as a prehistoric caveman emerging in early 1960s California who clumsily finds love with a teenage girl. [[Arch Hall Jr.]] performs musical numbers, with lyrics widely considered terrible. The film's notoriety was enhanced as a result of being featured on episodes of ''[[Canned Film Festival]]'' and ''Mystery Science Theater 3000'',<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.castleforrester.com/media/guide/0506.htm |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080829141244/http://www.castleforrester.com/media/guide/0506.htm |url-status=dead |archive-date=2008-08-29 |title=Experiment Guide |publisher=Castle Forrester |accessdate=2011-01-17}}</ref> where the cast of the show stated in ''The Mystery Science Theater 3000 Amazing Colossal Episode Guide'' ({{ISBN|0-553-37783-3}}), that they consider the shaving scene (where Eegah lolls his tongue around and laps up shaving cream) one of the most disgusting things they have seen. It was also one of the films listed in Michael Medved's book ''The Fifty Worst Films of All Time''.<ref>{{cite book|last=Medved|first=Michael|title=The Fifty Worst Films Of All Time|year=1980|publisher=Random House|isbn=0-449-04139-5}}</ref>\n\n=== ''The Creeping Terror'' (1964) ===\n\nThe science-fiction/horror film ''[[The Creeping Terror]]'' was directed, produced, and edited by Vic Savage (under the pseudonym A.J. Nelson, but he keeps his name when credited as an actor). The movie is about a large slug-like alien that lands on Earth and terrorizes an American town.<ref>Medved, Harry and Michael (1986). ''Son of Golden Turkey Awards''. New York: Random House/Villard Books. {{ISBN|0-394-74341-5}}. p. 197.</ref> The film is memorable for its use of some bargain-basement effects: stock footage of a rocket launch played in reverse to depict the landing of an alien spacecraft, and the \"monster\" appears to be composed of a length of shag carpet draped over several actors. Notably, the creature's victims inexplicably stand perfectly still as the slow-moving monster approaches them. Scott Weinberg of efilmcritic.com simply summarizes the movie with \"You've seen clips of this one in those 'awful, awful movies' documentaries.\" The movie was featured in the sixth season of ''Mystery Science Theater 3000''.<ref>{{cite web |title=\"Mystery Science Theater 3000\" The Creeping Terror |work=imdb.com |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0770613/ |accessdate=2013-05-24}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://rottentomatoes.com/m/the-creeping-terror-dangerous-charter-the-crawling-monster/ |title=The Creeping Terror (Dangerous Charter) (The Crawling Monster) |website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |accessdate=2013-11-18}}</ref>\n\n=== ''The Horror of Party Beach'' (1964) ===\n\n''Mystery Science Theater 3000'' featured ''[[The Horror of Party Beach]]'' in 1997, and the film was listed in ''[[The Fifty Worst Films of All Time]]''. [[Del Tenney]] directed it, and the plot mainly consists of sea monsters attacking young women at slumber parties on a beach, who keep returning even after a few murders. ''[[The New York Times]]'' film review stated, \"The most to be said for him is that he has not stinted on the gore.\"<ref>[https://movies.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9A06E1D61138E13ABC4850DFB266838F679EDE New York Times Movie Review] April 30, 1964</ref> Thomas Lisanti in ''Hollywood Surf and Beach Movies: The First Wave, 1959\u20131969'' called it \"by far the worst of the sixties beach films\", and [[Stephen King]] called it \"an abysmal little wet fart of a film\".<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=eBvMFuHle2kC&pg=RA1-PA1925&dq=%22the+horror+of+party+beach%22+worst#v=onepage&q=%22the%20horror%20of%20party%20beach%22%20worst Hollywood Surf and Beach Movies: The First Wave, 1959\u20131969] By Thomas Lisanti, number 8</ref> Joe Meyers in the [[Hearst Publishing|Hearst]] newspaper blog for the ''[[Stamford Advocate]]'' said on Del Tenney's passing: \"Connecticut had its own Ed Wood, an actor, director and entrepreneur named Del Tenney who made a series of truly awful pictures in the Stamford area during the 1960s, the most notorious of which is ''Horror of Party Beach'', a 1964 drive-in quickie about an atomic mutation that terrorizes [[Stamford, Connecticut|Stamford]] ('Party Beach' was actually [[Shippan Point]]).\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.ctnews.com/meyers/2013/03/01/the-passing-of-the-b-movie-king-of-connecticut-%E2%80%94-del-tenney/|title=The passing of the B-movie king of Connecticut \u2014 Del Tenney|date=1 March 2013|website=ctnews.com}}</ref> It is also listed in Michael Sauter's book ''The Worst Movies of All Time''.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=H2FZAAAAMAAJ&q=sauter+%22horror+of+party+beach%22&dq=sauter+%22horror+of+party+beach%22 The worst movies of all time, or, What were they thinking?] Michael Sauter; Carol Pub. Group, 1999 358 pages, page 306</ref>\n\n=== ''The Incredibly Strange Creatures Who Stopped Living and Became Mixed-Up Zombies'' (1964) ===\n\n''[[The Incredibly Strange Creatures Who Stopped Living and Became Mixed-Up Zombies]]'' (sometimes billed as ''The Incredibly Strange Creatures'') is a 1964 American monster movie written and directed by [[Ray Dennis Steckler]]. Steckler also starred in the film, billed under the pseudonym \"Cash Flagg\". In the film, three friends visit a carnival and stumble into a group of occultists and disfigured monsters. Produced on a $38,000 budget, much of it takes place at The Pike amusement park in [[Long Beach, California]], which resembles [[Brooklyn]]'s [[Coney Island]]. The film was billed as the first \"monster musical\", beating out ''The Horror of Party Beach'' by a mere month in release date. The 2004 DVD ''The 50 Worst Movies Ever Made'' listed this film as the worst film of all time.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0449786/movieconnections|title=The 50 Worst Movies Ever Made (Video 2004)|publisher=|via=www.imdb.com}}</ref> The [[Music journalism|rock critic]] [[Lester Bangs]] wrote an appreciative 1973 [[essay]] about ''Incredibly Strange Creatures'' in which he tries to explain and justify the movie's value: \"This flick doesn't just rebel against, or even disregard, standards of taste and art. In the universe inhabited by ''The Incredibly Strange Creatures Who Stopped Living and Became Mixed-Up Zombies'', such things as standards and responsibility have never been heard of. It is this lunar purity which largely imparts to the film its classic stature. Like ''[[Beyond the Valley of the Dolls]]'' and a very few others, it will remain as an artifact in years to come to which scholars and searchers for truth can turn and say, '''This'' was trash!{{'\"}}<ref name=\"Bangs\">{{cite book\n | author =Lester Bangs\n | authorlink = Lester Bangs\n | editor = Greil Marcus\n | title = Psychotic Reactions and Carburetor Dung\n | year = 1987\n | publisher = Random House\n | location = New York\n | isbn = 0-394-53896-X\n | chapter = The Incredibly Strange Creatures Who Stopped Living and Became Mixed-Up Zombies, or, The Day The Airwaves Erupted\n | page = 122\n}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Santa Claus Conquers the Martians'' (1964) ===\n\nThe sci-fi movie ''[[Santa Claus Conquers the Martians]]'' was the creation of [[Nicholas Webster]]. Because [[Martian]] children only get to see Santa Claus on TV signals beamed from Earth, their parents decide to abduct Santa to make them happy. The film was initially criticized for its oddity and poor special effects. It is also known for starring a very young [[Pia Zadora]].<ref name=\"ft1111\">{{cite web|url=https://filmthreat.com/features/1295/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121130200629/https://filmthreat.com/features/1295/|url-status=dead|archive-date=30 November 2012|title=Film Threat \u2013 The Bootleg Files: \"Santa Claus Conquers The Martians\"|work=Filmthreat.com|accessdate=4 May 2012}}</ref> [[BBC]] critic Nick Cramp described it as \"possibly the worst film ever made\".<ref>{{cite web |title=Santa Claus Conquers the Martians (1964) |publisher=[[BBC]] |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/films/2000/12/11/santa_claus_conquers_the_martians_1964_review.shtml |last=Cramp|first=Nick|date= December 11, 2020 |accessdate=March 25, 2020}}</ref> The film is cited on a 10-worst list in ''The Book of Lists'' and in ''The Fifty Worst Films of All Time''. Like many others in this category, it has been featured in ''Mystery Science Theater 3000'',<ref>{{cite web |title=Mystery Science Theater 3000 \u2013 Santa Claus Conquers the Martians |work=TV.com |url=http://www.tv.com/mystery-science-theater-3000/santa-claus-conquers-the-martians/episode/46920/summary.html?tag=ep_list;title;47/ |accessdate=2011-03-07}}</ref> and ''[[Cinematic Titanic]]'' (a spin-off of ''MST3K'') revisited the film in 2008.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://cinematictitanic.twinvision.com/products/ |title=Cinematic Titanic &#124; The Store |work=Cinematictitanic.twinvision.com |date=2012-10-11 |accessdate=2013-11-18 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131015034626/https://cinematictitanic.twinvision.com/products/ |archivedate=2013-10-15 }}</ref> \n\nA remake was rumoured with [[David Zucker (filmmaker)|David Zucker]] as producer, and [[Jim Carrey]] attached to play Dropo. An estimated release date was announced as 2002, though it was then believed to have been in [[development hell]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Santa Claus Conquers the Martians |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0058548/ |publisher=imdb.com |accessdate=May 16, 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050206013433/http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0158916/ |archivedate=February 6, 2005 |date=February 6, 2005 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n=== ''Monster a Go-Go!'' (1965) ===\n\n''[[Monster a Go-Go|Monster a Go-Go!]]'' began as ''Terror at Halfday'' by [[Bill Rebane]]. The production ran out of money and the film was abandoned. [[Herschell Gordon Lewis]], who reportedly needed a second feature to comprise a double bill, purchased and completed it for a minimal amount of money. Several of the film's actors were unable to return, so Lewis simply replaced their parts with new characters who mysteriously appear and fill the roles of the missing characters. One of the actors Lewis managed to rehire had gained weight, gone bald, and grown a goatee, so Lewis recast him as the brother of the original character.<ref name=\"agony\">{{cite web |date=June 16, 2003 |url=http://www.agonybooth.com/monster_a_go_go/default.asp?Page=5 |title=Recap: Monster A-Go Go (1965)|work=The Agony Booth |accessdate=2007-01-21}}</ref> The picture consists mostly of lengthy dialogue sequences concerning the apparent mutation of an astronaut into a monster portrayed by the giant [[Henry Hite]]. Poor audio quality makes much of the dialogue unintelligible, and when the film is overexposed, several characters' faces appear as bright white, glowing circles. At one point, when a phone supposedly rings, the sound effect is obviously a person making a noise with their mouth.<ref>{{youtube|5dKiaRUKgmA|MST3K \u2013 421 \u2013 Human Phone Ring}}</ref> During the climax of the movie, as soldiers prepare to confront the mutated astronaut, he abruptly vanishes and the narrator informs the audience, \"there was no monster\", and that the astronaut has, in fact, been in the [[Atlantic Ocean]] the entire time. [[Allmovie|All Movie Guide]] calls the film a \"surreal anti-masterpiece\".<ref>{{cite web |last=Beldin |first=Fred |title=Monster A Go-Go! |work=Allmovie.com |url=https://allmovie.com/movie/monster-a-go-go%21-v33169/review |accessdate=2012-09-12}}</ref> It was also featured on ''Mystery Science Theater 3000'', where writer [[Paul Chaplin]] called the dialogue \"garbled beyond recognition\".<ref>{{cite web |title=Mystery Science Theater 3000 \u2013 Monster A Go-Go |publisher=Castle Forrester |url=http://www.castleforrester.com/media/guide/0421.htm |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081120215055/http://www.castleforrester.com/media/guide/0421.htm |url-status=dead |archive-date=2008-11-20 |accessdate=2011-03-07}}</ref> The entire cast of the show later stated it was officially the worst movie they have ever seen.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.angelfire.com/ga/hikeeba/mst3kguide.html |title=Hi-keeba!'s MST3K Episode Guide |work=Angelfire.com |date=2001-03-01 |accessdate=2011-01-17}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Manos: The Hands of Fate'' (1966) ===\n[[File:Manosposter.jpg|thumb|''[[Manos: The Hands of Fate]]'' was featured in ''[[Mystery Science Theater 3000]]'''s most popular episode]]\nThe low-budget horror film ''[[Manos: The Hands of Fate]]'', made by [[El Paso, Texas|El Paso]] insurance and fertilizer salesman Hal P. Warren, concerns a vacationing family kidnapped by a [[polygamy|polygamous]] cult of [[paganism|pagans]]. The film was conceived after Warren bet Academy Award-winning screenwriter [[Stirling Silliphant]] that anyone could make a horror movie.<ref name=\"EW2\">{{cite news |url=https://ew.com/article/2005/06/06/worst-movie-ever-made/|title=The Worst Movie Ever Made |page=2 |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |date=June 6, 2005 |accessdate=December 3, 2019|first=Dalton |last=Ross}}</ref> Warren was convinced by the film's cinematographer and stunt coordinator that most of its glaring mistakes could be fixed in a [[Dallas]] post-production studio, when in reality the two wanted to quickly wrap the production because they were not being paid.<ref name=\"EW2\"/> Several technical gaffes made it into the film, including scenes filmed out of focus, a marking slate being seen in one shot, the scarf on the female lead's head disappearing and reappearing, and an insect bumping the camera lens.<ref name=\"EW2\"/><ref name=\"ma\">{{cite book |first=Michael |last=Adams |title=Showgirls, Teen Wolves, and Astro Zombies: a film critic's year-long quest to find the worst movie ever made |location=New York |publisher=Itbooks |year=2010 |isbn=978-0-06-180629-2 |pages=91\u20132 }}</ref> The film was shot with a camera that could not record sound and had a 32-second maximum shot length. All dialogue was later dubbed by Warren and four others, including a grown woman who dubbed the voice for a seven-year-old girl.<ref name=\"ma\"/><ref name=\"NBC\">{{cite web |url=http://entertainment.nbcnews.com/_news/2012/08/13/12645253-torgo-lives-mystery-science-alums-revisit-worst-movie-ever-manos-the-hands-of-fate |title=Torgo lives! 'Mystery Science' alums revisit worst movie ever, 'Manos: The Hands of Fate' |last1=Fashingbauer Cooper |first1=Gael |date=August 13, 2012 |work=[[NBC News]] |accessdate=March 4, 2013}}</ref> It opens with a nine-minute driving scene that the filmmakers intended to use for cast and crew credits, but failed to do so.<ref name=\"NBC\"/> The movie includes dialogue spoken while all characters are facing away from the camera, a character complaining about it getting dark while the sun is brightly shining, and the character Torgo, a [[satyr]] with overly large thighs, that three women attempt to massage to death.<ref name=\"EW2\"/><ref name=\"NBC\"/><ref name=\"ElPaso\">{{cite news |title=Hero Massaged to Death in 'Manos-- The Hands of Fate' |author=Betty Pierce |url=http://www.mst3ktemple.com/images/manos_review-post-x.jpg |newspaper=[[El Paso Herald-Post]] |date= November 11, 1966|accessdate=March 1, 2013}}</ref> The film gained notoriety and cult popularity by being featured on ''Mystery Science Theater 3000'',<ref>{{cite web |title=Mystery Science Theater 3000 \u2013 Manos: The Hands of Fate |work=TV.com |url=http://www.tv.com/mystery-science-theater-3000/manos-the-hands-of-fate/episode/46947/summary.html?tag=ep_list;title;74/ |accessdate=2011-03-07}}</ref> and was the show's most popular episode.<ref name=\"EW2\"/> The film has a 7% on [[Rotten Tomatoes]],<ref>{{rotten-tomatoes|id=manos_the_hands_of_fate|title=Manos \u2013 the Hands of Fate |accessdate=July 2, 2018}}</ref> and ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' says the movie is \"widely regarded as, quite simply, the worst movie ever made\".<ref name=\"EW2\"/> Even Warren himself would later admit his film was one of the worst ever, suggesting it might make a passable comedy if redubbed.<ref>{{cite news |first=Richard |last=Brandt |url=http://www.jophan.org/mimosa/m18/brandt.htm |title=The Hand That Time Forgot |work=Mimosa |date=May 1996 |accessdate=2006-08-17 |pages=35\u201338}}</ref> The film was later restored <ref>[https://www.npr.org/2011/12/12/143573040/manos-the-hands-of-fate-carefully-restoring-the-opposite-of-a-masterpiece 'Manos: The Hands of Fate': Carefully Restoring The Opposite Of A Masterpiece : NPR]</ref> and released on Blu-ray in 2015.<ref>[https://news.avclub.com/read-this-the-battle-over-the-infamous-cult-classic-ma-1798284742 Read this: The battle over the infamous cult classic Manos: The Hands of Fate|AV Club]</ref><ref>[https://synapse-films.com/synapse-films/manos-the-hands-of-fate-special-edition-blu-ray/ Synapse Films]</ref>\n\n=== ''A Place for Lovers'' (1968) ===\n\n''[[A Place for Lovers]]'' is a French-Italian [[romantic film]] directed by [[Vittorio De Sica]], starring [[Faye Dunaway]] as a terminally ill American fashion designer in [[Venice, Italy]], and [[Marcello Mastroianni]] as a race car driver who has a whirlwind affair with her. [[Roger Ebert]] of the ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'' called it the \"most godawful piece of pseudo-romantic slop I've ever seen!\"<ref>{{cite news |last=Ebert |first=Roger |title=A Place for Lovers |newspaper=[[Chicago Sun-Times]] |date=December 16, 1969 |url=https://rogerebert.com/reviews/a-place-for-lovers-1969 |accessdate=2013-10-19}}</ref> and [[Charles Champlin]] of the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' referred to it as \"the worst movie I have seen all year and possibly since 1926\".<ref>{{cite news |title=A Place For Lovers Film 'Worst' One Critic's Seen |author=Charles Champlin|author-link=Charles Champlin |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=FmlkAAAAIBAJ&sjid=5HwNAAAAIBAJ&pg=1127,904508&dq=a+place+for+lovers+dunaway+worst |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=18 December 1969|accessdate=19 August 2013}}</ref> Leonard Maltin noted Ebert's comments in his review and offered that the film was \"low points for all concerned\".<ref name=\"Maltin01211\"/> ''A Place for Lovers'' was included as one of the choices in ''The Fifty Worst Films of All Time'' and the Italian ''[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]'' listed it as one of the 20 worst movies ever made.<ref name=italianvanity/>\n\n=== ''They Saved Hitler's Brain'' (1968) ===\n''[[They Saved Hitler's Brain]]'' is a [[science fiction film]] directed by [[David Bradley (director)|David Bradley]].\n<ref>[http://www.tcm.com/tcmdb/title/92846/They-Saved-Hitler-s-Brain/ They Saved Hitler's Brain (1964) - TCM.com]</ref> It was [[made-for-TV movie|adapted for television]] from a shorter 1963 theatrical [[feature film]], ''Madmen of Mandoras'',<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0057273/ The Madmen of Mandoras (1963) - IMDb]</ref> and was lengthened by about 20 minutes with additional footage shot by [[University of California, Los Angeles|UCLA]] students at the request of the distributor. In the film, [[Adolf Hitler]]'s head was severed from his body at the end of [[World War II]] and the head plans to rule over a new [[Third Reich]] from [[South America]]. It has a [[List of films with a 0% rating on Rotten Tomatoes|rare rating of 0%]] on Rotten Tomatoes, based on 5 reviews from critics, with an average rating of 1.3/10.<ref name=\"hitlersbrain\">{{cite web | url = http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/they_saved_hitlers_brain/ | title = They Saved Hitler's Brain | work = [[Rotten Tomatoes]]  | accessdate = March 26, 2020 }}</ref> ''[[TV Guide]]'' called it \"One of the all-time worst\",<ref name=\"hitlersbrain\"/> while Danny Peary said it was \"A legitimate candidate for Worst Film Ever Made title.\"<ref>{{Cite book|last1=Peary|first1=Danny|authorlink=Danny Peary|title=Guide for the Film Fanatic|publisher=[[Simon & Schuster]]|page=430|year=1986|isbn=0671610813}}</ref> In 1979, it won the World's Worst Film Festival in [[Ottawa, Canada]], which reportedly delighted Bradley.<ref name=\"aslide\">{{Cite book|last1=Slide|first1=Anthony|authorlink=Anthony Slide|title=Magnificent Obsession: The Outrageous History of Film Buffs, Collectors, Scholars, and Fanatics|publisher=[[University Press of Mississippi]]|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ep9GDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT105&dq=they+saved+hitler%27s+brain+worst&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiqudvQ_7joAhVCn-AKHZy9BSUQ6AEwAHoECAEQAg#v=onepage&q=they%20saved%20hitler's%20brain%20&f=false|year=2018|isbn=1496810538}}</ref> It has been featured in ''The Golden Turkey Awards'', ''Canned Film Festival'',<ref name=\"cannedfilm\"/> and has been spoofed on ''[[The Simpsons]]'' multiple times.<ref name=\"aslide\"/>\n\n== 1970s ==\n\n=== ''Myra Breckinridge'' (1970) ===\n\nThe comedy ''[[Myra Breckinridge (film)|Myra Breckinridge]]'', based on the [[Myra Breckinridge|book of the same name]] by [[Gore Vidal]], directed by [[Mike Sarne|Michael Sarne]] and starring [[Raquel Welch]], [[Rex Reed]], [[Mae West]], [[John Huston]] and [[Farrah Fawcett]], provoked controversy due to a scene in which Welch [[rape|forcibly]] [[Pegging (sexual practice)|sodomizes]] a bound man while clips from various classic films play onscreen. The film was initially [[X-rated|rated X]] before edits and an appeal to the [[Motion Picture Association of America|MPAA]] brought it down to an R. It also used the technique of inserting clips from [[Classical Hollywood cinema|Golden Age]] movies in such a way that the dialogue took on sexual undertones. Several stars whose films were featured objected to the gimmick, and some (such as [[Loretta Young]]) sued to remove the footage. The film was a critical failure, with ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine saying \"''Myra Breckinridge'' is about as funny as a child molester\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Cinema:Some Sort of Nadir |work=time.com |date=July 6, 1970 |url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,878382,00.html |accessdate=2011-03-07}}</ref> Leonard Maltin gave it a BOMB (the lowest score possible) and stated that it was \"as bad as any movie ever made\".<ref name=\"Maltin01211\"/> The ''[[Miami News]]'' critic Herb Kelly nominated ''Myra Breckinridge'' as the worst film ever made.<ref>{{cite news |title='Breckinridge' Worst Ever |author=Herb Kelly |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=4QxgAAAAIBAJ&sjid=E-oFAAAAIBAJ&pg=2413,4500090&dq=myra+breckinridge+worst+ever |newspaper=The Miami News |date=29 August 1970 |accessdate=17 August 2013}}</ref> The film is also cited in ''The Fifty Worst Films of All Time''. It also was included in ''The Book of Lists''{{'}} worst movies of all time, claiming there was something in the movie to offend absolutely everyone. Gore Vidal disowned it, calling it \"an awful joke\",<ref>{{cite book |last1=Hoberman |first1=J. |authorlink1=J. Hoberman |last2=Rosenbaum |first2=Jonathan |authorlink2=Jonathan Rosenbaum |title=Midnight Movies |publisher=Da Capo Press |year=1991 |isbn=0-306-80433-6 |page=268}}</ref> and blamed the movie for a decade-long drought in the sale of the original book.<ref>{{cite book |last=Conner |first=Floyd |title=Hollywood's Most Wanted: The Top 10 Book of Lucky Breaks, Prima Donnas, Box Office Bombs, and Other Oddities |publisher=Brassey's |year=2002 |isbn=1-57488-480-8 |page=[https://archive.org/details/hollywoodsmostwa0000conn/page/65 65] |url=https://archive.org/details/hollywoodsmostwa0000conn/page/65 }}</ref>\n\n=== ''Zaat'' (1971) ===\n\nDirected by Don Barton, ''[[Zaat]]'' was also known under various titles including ''Hydra'', ''Attack of the Swamp Creatures'', ''Legend of the Zaat Monster'', and ''The Blood Waters of Dr. Z'' (the name under which it was lampooned on ''Mystery Science Theater 3000''). The film follows a Nazi [[mad scientist]] who injects himself with a formula that turns him into a mutated catfish. ''[[Florida Times-Union]]'' critic Matt Soergel quipped that ''Zaat'' \"could very well be the best film ever made about a mutated catfish\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://jacksonville.com/tu-online/stories/061201/enm_zaat.html|title=Locally made sci-fi thriller is all 'Zaat' and then some|date=2001-06-12|accessdate=2013-09-30}}</ref> Critic Jeffrey Kauffman said, \"this is the sort of film Ed Wood, Jr. might have made\u2014on a bad day\" and added, \"Lovers of fantastically bad films rate ''Zaat'' one of the worst\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blu-ray.com/movies/Zaat-Blu-ray/35923/#Review|title=Zaat Blu Ray|date=2012-02-21|last=Kauffman|first=Jeffrey |accessdate=2013-09-30}}</ref> Patrick Naugle of [[DVD Verdict]] stated, \"The acting in ''Zaat'' is below subpar. Actors seem to be whispering their lines and trying hard not to fully comprehend that they're in one of the worst films ever made\", while Michael Rubino of DVD Verdict also claimed, \"''Zaat'' may be one of the worst films ever created\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://dvdverdict.com/printer/zaatbluray.php|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131002180849/https://dvdverdict.com/printer/zaatbluray.php|url-status=dead|archive-date=2013-10-02|title=DVD Verdict Review \u2013 Zaat (Blu Ray)|date=2012-02-12|last=Naugle|first=Patrick|work=[[DVD Verdict]]|accessdate=2013-09-30}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://dvdverdict.com/reviews/mst3kxvii.php |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100225160816/https://dvdverdict.com/reviews/mst3kxvii.php |url-status=dead |archive-date=2010-02-25 |title=DVD Verdict Review \u2013 Mystery Science Theater 3000 |date=2010-02-22 |last=Rubino |first=Michael |work=[[DVD Verdict]] |accessdate=2013-09-30 }}</ref> [[NPR]] called it a \"sci-fi fiasco\" when it became \"the winner \u2014 er, loser \u2014\" on IMDb's Bottom 100.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=101056819|title=10 Reasons Why We Love Making Lists|date=2009-02-24|last=Weeks|first=Linton|work=[[NPR]]|accessdate=2013-09-30}}</ref> ''Zaat'' appeared on ''Mystery Science Theater 3000'', which gave it significant exposure,<ref>{{cite web|author=Sampo, on May 20th, 2010 |url=http://www.mst3kinfo.com/?p=5866 |title=Season 10 Episode Guide! |publisher=MST3Kinfo |date=2010-05-20 |accessdate=2013-12-19}}</ref> and was also featured on [[RedLetterMedia]] show ''Half in the Bag'' where they called it one of their favorite \"[[so bad it's good]]\" films.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://redlettermedia.com/half-in-the-bag-zaat/|title=Half in the Bag:Zaat!|date=2012-04-30|work=[[RedLetterMedia]]|accessdate=2013-09-30}}</ref> ''[[Total Film]]'' included it in their list of the 66 worst films of all time.<ref name=TotalFilm/>\n\n=== ''An American Hippie in Israel'' (1972) ===\n\nThe Israeli ''[[An American Hippie in Israel]]'' is about an American hippie traveling to [[Israel]] after being involved with the [[Vietnam War]], befriending Israeli flower children, and encountering \"menacing\" [[Mime artist|mimes]] along the way. The film was presumed [[Lost film|lost]], but after resurfacing 38 years after its production, it became a \"midnight sensation\" in [[Tel Aviv]] and developed a cult following akin to ''[[The Rocky Horror Picture Show]]''. It was then released internationally on home video by [[Grindhouse Releasing]]. Gil Shefler of ''[[The Jewish Daily Forward]]'' described it as \"perfectly awful\", offering that it \"probably is the worst Israeli movie ever made, and a serious candidate for the worst movie of all time\".<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=[[The Jewish Daily Forward]] |url=http://forward.com/articles/134946/finding-new-life-as-a-cult-classic/ |date=January 26, 2011 |last=Shefler |first=Gil |accessdate=August 14, 2013 |title=Finding New Life As a Cult Classic}}</ref> Ben Hartman of ''[[The Jerusalem Post]]'' stated the film was \"surely one of the worst films ever made in Israel, or beyond\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.jpost.com/Arts-and-Culture/Entertainment/Horrendous-Israeli-70s-film-becomes-a-cult-favorite |date=January 9, 2011 |last=Harman|first=Ben|work=[[The Jerusalem Post]] |accessdate=August 29, 2013 |title= 'Horrendous' Israeli '70s film becomes a cult favorite}}</ref> ''[[Nana 10]]'' said it claims the title of \"worst Israeli film and most amusing\".<ref>{{in lang|he}} [http://news.nana10.co.il/Article/?ArticleID=766710 News article from Nana 10] (Last accessed August 26, 2013).</ref>\n\n=== ''Bat Pussy'' (unknown, possibly 1973) ===\n\nA loose spoof of the 1966 ''[[Batman (TV series)|Batman]]'' television series cited as one of the earliest examples of a [[pornographic parody film]], the presumably-1970s [[pornographic film]] ''[[Bat Pussy]]'' has been \"widely described\" as the worst pornographic film ever made, on account of \"some incredibly unarousing sex and a general attitude of awfulness\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/men/the-filter/11395280/The-rise-of-parody-porn-the-Chaucer-of-our-times.html |title=The rise of parody porn, 'the Chaucer of our times' |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |author=Merz, Theo |date=February 23, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"BP73io9\">{{cite web |url=http://io9.gizmodo.com/5914178/the-bizarre-history-of-superhero-porn-nsfw |title=The Bizarre History of Superhero Porn [NSFW] |author=Anders, Charlie Jane |date=May 30, 2012 |publisher=[[io9]]}}</ref> Possessing no credits or copyright information, there is no known record of ''Bat Pussy''{{'}}s existence prior to the mid-1990s, when it was discovered in the storeroom of an adult movie theater in [[Memphis, Tennessee]], and subsequently released on home video by [[exploitation film]] distributor [[Something Weird Video]]. [[Gawker Media]]{{'}}s [[io9]] proclaimed the film to be \"the absolute nadir of pornography, period. Not just Batman-themed pornography. ALL pornography\", deriding its \"obese redneck\" cast as rendering the film \"[[masturbation|wank]]-proof\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://io9.gizmodo.com/5545416/a-brief-history-of-batman-themed-pornography-nsfw |title=A brief history of Batman-themed pornography (NSFW) |publisher=[[io9]] |author=Lamar, Cyriaque |date=May 22, 2010}}</ref> ''PornParody.com'', a website dedicated to pornographic parody films, acknowledged its status as \"the worst adult movie of all time\", describing ''Bat Pussy'' as \"renowned for its technical ineptness and anti-eroticism\" due to its \"physically unappealing\" actors.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://pornparody.com/2014/10/bat-pussy-the-first-superhero-porn-parody/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141008174205/http://pornparody.com/2014/10/bat-pussy-the-first-superhero-porn-parody/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=October 8, 2014 |title=Bat Pussy \u2013 the first superhero porn parody? |date=October 6, 2014 |publisher=PornParody.com}}</ref> ''AV Maniacs'' contested ''Bat Pussy''{{'}}s categorization as pornography on the grounds of the lead actor's visible [[erectile dysfunction|impotence]] and instead labeled the film \"anti-porn\", asking \"How else do you categorize an adult film that completely and utterly fails to elicit even the minutest amount of arousal in its viewers?\"<ref name=\"BPAVClub\">{{cite web |url=http://avmaniacs.com/features/bat_pussy.html |title=Deep Inside Bat Pussy |author=Allison, Matthew |publisher=AV Maniacs}}</ref> The book ''The Many More Lives of Batman'' by [[William Uricchio]] and [[Will Brooker]] also labeled ''Bat Pussy'' \"the worst porn film ever made\", criticizing its poor adaptation of the source material,<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0hZ5CgAAQBAJ&pg=PA115&dq=%22Bat+Pussy%22#v=onepage&q=%22Bat%20Pussy%22 |title=The Many More Lives of Batman |author1=Pearson, Rebecca |author2=Brooker, Will |author3=Uriccho, William |date=2015 |isbn=978-1844577644 |publisher=[[British Film Institute]]}}</ref> while Tim Lewis, the general manager of Something Weird Video, selected ''Bat Pussy'' as the one film \"so nuts it has to be seen to be believed\" out of the company's entire catalog, saying it was \"only for the truly jaded adult film viewer\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://atomiclegdropzine.wordpress.com/2014/03/04/something-weird-video/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140727143331/https://atomiclegdropzine.wordpress.com/2014/03/04/something-weird-video/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=July 27, 2014 |title=Something Weird Video |date=March 4, 2014 |publisher=The Atomic Leg Drop Zine!}}</ref>\n\n=== ''At Long Last Love'' (theatrical version, 1975) ===\n\n''[[At Long Last Love]]'' was renowned director [[Peter Bogdanovich]]'s musical homage to great 1930s Hollywood musicals. It features songs by [[Cole Porter]] and stars [[Cybill Shepherd]] and [[Burt Reynolds]]. Upon release, it received very negative reviews. [[CNN]] noted it was once considered \"the worst musical extravaganza in Hollywood history\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2013/07/10/showbiz/movies/big-bombs-revisited|title=Picking up the pieces on Hollywood's biggest bombs|date=2013-07-11|accessdate=2013-08-23|work=CNN}}</ref> ''[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]]'' film critic [[John Simon (critic)|John Simon]] said, \"it may be the worst movie musical of this \u2013 or any \u2013 decade\".<ref name=PictureShows>{{cite book | last =Yule | first =Andrew | title =Picture shows: the life and films of Peter Bogdanovich | publisher =[[Hal Leonard Corporation]] | year =1992 | location = | page =[https://archive.org/details/pictureshowslife00yule/page/90 90] | isbn =0-87910-153-9 | url =https://archive.org/details/pictureshowslife00yule/page/90 }}</ref> ''[[Buffalo News]]'' film critic Jeff Simon wrote, \"About 45 minutes in, it became apparent to one and all that this was one of the worst and most embarrassing major-talent turkeys of all time.\"<ref name=\"BufNews\">{{cite news |title=Wisecrack Addicts Laughing at the Not-So-Bad |url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=BN&p_theme=bn&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EAF994638769706&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D |newspaper= [[The Buffalo News]] |date= May 24, 1996| author =Simon, Jeff }}</ref> Film critic [[Jay Cocks]] has said the film was \"regarded as the great [[white elephant]] catastrophe of its time\".<ref name=SinginANewTune>{{cite book | last =Muir | first =John Kenneth | title =Singing a new tune:the rebirth of the modern film musical, from Evita to De-lovely and beyond | publisher =[[Hal Leonard Corporation]] | year =2005 | location = | page =[https://archive.org/details/singingnewtunere0000muir/page/58 58] | isbn =1-55783-610-8 | url =https://archive.org/details/singingnewtunere0000muir/page/58 }}</ref> [[Hollis Alpert]] stated, \"This failure is so dismal that it goes beyond failure.\"<ref>{{cite book | last =Tookey | first =Christopher | title =Named and Shamed: The World's Worst and Wittiest Movie Reviews from Affleck to Zeta-Jones | publisher =Troubador Publishing | year =2010 | location = | page =34 | isbn =978-1-84876-560-3}}</ref> It was included in the book ''The Fifty Worst Films of All Time'' and Michael Sauter's book ''The Worst Films of All Time''.<ref name=50worst>{{cite book | last =Medved | first =Harry | title =The fifty worst films of all time: (and how they got that way) | publisher =[[Popular Library]] | year =1978 | location = | page =37 | isbn =0-445-04139-0}}</ref> It is also included in the ''Golden Turkey Awards Nominees and Winners, the Worst Achievements in Hollywood History''.<ref name=Goldenturkeys>{{cite book | last =Medved | first =Michael | title =The Golden Turkey Awards | publisher =[[G. P. Putnam's Sons]] | year =1980 | location = | page =209 | isbn =0-399-50463-X| title-link =The Golden Turkey Awards }}</ref> Bogdanovich, who was also the screenwriter, sent press releases to newspapers across the country apologizing for this film.<ref name=SinginANewTune/>\n\nOne defender of the film was Roger Ebert, who stated, \"The movie's no masterpiece, but I can't account for the viciousness of some of the critical attacks against it.\" He continued, \"It's a light, silly, impeccably stylish entertainment ... if [Bogdanovich] doesn't go spectacularly right, at least he provides small pleasures and great music.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Sobczynski |first=Peter |url=https://rogerebert.com/reviews/at-long-last-love-1975 |title=At Long Last Love Movie Review (1975) |publisher=Roger Ebert |date=1975-01-01 |accessdate=2014-03-05}}</ref> In a recent documentary on his career, Bogdanovich lamented being influenced by studio previews to cut the film before its theatrical release. He subsequently recut it again before it debuted on [[cable TV]] the next year. A fan of the film, a studio editor who preferred the director's first cut, secretly saved that original version and quietly put it in place of the others. When news of this version streaming on [[Netflix]] reached Bogdanovich, he contacted Fox and made a few finishing touches, resulting in a critically acclaimed director's cut that debuted on [[home video]] in 2013.<ref>{{cite web|last=McWeeny |first=Drew |url=http://www.hitfix.com/blogs/motion-captured/posts/peter-bogdanovich-screens-new-cut-of-at-long-last-love-and-tells-story-behind-it |title=Peter Bogdanovich screens new cut of At Long Last Love and tells story behind it |work=Hitfix.com |date=2012-01-09 |accessdate=2014-03-05}}</ref>\n\n=== ''HaMal'ach Haya Satan'' (''The Angel Was a Devil'') (1976) ===\n\n''The Angel Was a Devil'' (filmed in 1971, released in 1976) is an Israeli [[horror film]] about a young woman fleeing a murderer<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mubi.com/films/the-angel-was-a-devil|website=MUBI|title=The Angel Was a Devil|access-date=4 May 2019}}</ref> that has been described by Meir Schnitzer, a leading authority on [[Israel]]i [[Film|cinema]] and by others, as \"the worst film ever made in Israel.\"<ref name=haaretz>{{cite newspaper|first=Nirit|last=Anderman|url=http://www.haaretz.co.il/gallery/television/1.1522771 |title=\u05d1\u05de\u05d0\u05d9 \"\u05d4\u05e1\u05e8\u05d8 \u05d4\u05d9\u05e9\u05e8\u05d0\u05dc\u05d9 \u05d4\u05d2\u05e8\u05d5\u05e2 \u05d1\u05d9\u05d5\u05ea\u05e8\" \u05d3\u05d5\u05e8\u05e9 \u05db\u05d1\u05d5\u05d3|trans-title=Director of the \"worst Israeli film\" demands respect|newspaper=[[Haaretz]]|date=14 October 2011|access-date=4 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|journal=Moznayim|volume=70|page=62|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=g0k_AQAAIAAJ|via=[[Google Books]]|quote=\u05e1\u05d9\u05e4\u05d5\u05e8 \u05e2\u05dd \u05de\u05d5\u05e1\u05e8 \u05d4\u05e9\u05db\u05dc: \u05d0\u05dc \u05e0\u05d7\u05e6\u05f3\u05d4 \u05e9\u05de\u05e8, \u05de\u05d6\u05db\u05d9\u05e8 \u05e7\u05d9\u05d1\u05d5\u05e5 \u05f3\u05e2\u05d9\u05df \u05e0\u05d9\u05e6\u05e0\u05d9\u05dd\u05f3 \u05e9\u05d1\u05e0\u05d2\u05d1, \u05d4\u05d2\u05d9\u05e2 \u05d1\u05d0\u05d5\u05e4\u05df \u05de\u05d7\u05ea\u05e8\u05ea\u05d9 \u05d4\u05de\u05d9\u05d3\u05e2 \u05e2\u05dc \u05d4\u05d4\u05db\u05ea\u05e8\u05d4 \u05d4\u05e4\u05d5\u05de\u05d1\u05d9\u05ea \u05e9\u05dc \u05d4\u05e1\u05e8\u05d8 \u05d4\u05d9\u05e9\u05e8\u05d0\u05dc\u05d9 \u05d4\u05d2\u05e8\u05d5\u05e2 \u05d1\u05d9\u05d5\u05ea\u05e8 \u05d1\u05db\u05dc \u05d4\u05d6\u05de\u05e0\u05d9\u05dd, \u05f4\u05d4\u05de\u05dc\u05d0\u05da \u05d4\u05d9\u05d4 \u05e9\u05d8\u05df\u05f4 \u05e9\u05dc \u05de\u05e9\u05d4 \u05d2\u05d6, \u05d5\u05e2\u05dc \u05d4\u05d4\u05e7\u05e8\u05e0\u05d4 \u05d4\u05d7\u05d2\u05d9\u05d2\u05d9\u05ea \u05d4\u05d7\u05d3\u05be\u05e4\u05e2\u05de\u05d9\u05ea \u05e9\u05ea\u05d9\u05e2\u05e8\u05da \u05dc\u05d5 \u05d1\u05e1\u05d9\u05e0\u05de\u05d8\u05d9\u05e7 \u05ea\u05dc \u05d0\u05d1\u05d9\u05d1.|access-date=4 May 2019|year=1995|script-title=he:\u05d4\u05e1\u05e8\u05d8 \u05d4\u05d9\u05e9\u05e8\u05d0\u05dc\u05d9 \u05d4\u05d2\u05e8\u05d5\u05e2 \u05d1\u05d9\u05d5\u05d7\u05e8 \u05d1\u05db\u05dc \u05d4\u05d6\u05de\u05d2\u05d9\u05dd|trans-title=The worst Israeli film of all times|language=he}}</ref> Moshe Guez was the [[film director]], [[scriptwriter]], [[movie star|star]], [[cinematographer]], recorder, [[film editor|editor]] and the [[composer]] of some of its [[film score|original music]].<ref name=haaretz/><ref>[https://mubi.com/cast/moshe-guez Moshe Guez-MUBI]</ref> Due to the high concentration of crew positions, the production missed out on the subsidy for full-length Israeli movies that is almost automatically given to local productions. The production and distribution were plagued by many additional problems, including impacts of the [[Yom Kippur War]], script and actor changes, and the instant bankruptcy of its final distributor.<ref name=haaretz/> In 2011, Avida Livny released the documentary ''[[Looking for Moshe Guez]]'', describing the film and a search after its director in Israel and the US.<ref name=haaretz/> The creator released a slightly improved digital version of his movie in 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5pJEcXlmTts|website=[[YouTube]]|title=The Angel was a Devil Trailer 277 MP4|accessdate=4 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite newspaper|url=https://www.ynet.co.il/articles/0,7340,L-4781180,00.html|title=\u05e1\u05d9\u05e4\u05d5\u05e8\u05d5 \u05e9\u05dc \u05d4\u05e1\u05e8\u05d8 \u05d4\u05d9\u05e9\u05e8\u05d0\u05dc\u05d9 \u05d4\u05d2\u05e8\u05d5\u05e2 \u05d1\u05d9\u05d5\u05ea\u05e8|trans-title=The story of the worst Israeli film|quote=\"\u05d4\u05de\u05dc\u05d0\u05da \u05d4\u05d9\u05d4 \u05e9\u05d8\u05df\", \u05de\u05d5\u05ea\u05d7\u05df \u05d0\u05d9\u05de\u05d4 \u05d9\u05e9\u05e8\u05d0\u05dc\u05d9 \u05e9\u05e0\u05d5\u05e6\u05e8 \u05dc\u05e4\u05e0\u05d9 40 \u05e9\u05e0\u05d4, \u05d9\u05e8\u05d3 \u05de\u05d4\u05de\u05e1\u05db\u05d9\u05dd \u05d1\u05de\u05d4\u05d9\u05e8\u05d5\u05ea \u05e9\u05d9\u05d0 \u05d5\u05d4\u05d5\u05d2\u05d3\u05e8 \u05db\"\u05e1\u05e8\u05d8 \u05d4\u05d9\u05e9\u05e8\u05d0\u05dc\u05d9 \u05d4\u05d2\u05e8\u05d5\u05e2 \u05d1\u05d9\u05d5\u05ea\u05e8 \u05d1\u05db\u05dc \u05d4\u05d6\u05de\u05e0\u05d9\u05dd\". \u05d0\u05d9\u05da \u05d6\u05db\u05d4 \u05dc\u05ea\u05d5\u05d0\u05e8 \u05d4\u05de\u05e9\u05de\u05d9\u05e5 \u05d5\u05de\u05d4 \u05d2\u05e8\u05dd \u05dc\u05d1\u05de\u05d0\u05d9 \u05de\u05e9\u05d4 \u05d2\u05d6 \u05dc\u05d9\u05e6\u05d5\u05e8 \u05d2\u05e8\u05e1\u05d4 \u05d7\u05d3\u05e9\u05d4 \u05e9\u05ea\u05d5\u05e7\u05e8\u05df \u05d1\u05e7\u05e8\u05d5\u05d1?|newspaper=[[Yediot Ahronot]]|first=Idan|last=Rozen}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timeout.co.il/%d7%97%d7%90%d7%a4%d7%a8%d7%95%d7%95%d7%93-%d7%a1%d7%99%d7%a4%d7%95%d7%a8%d7%9d-%d7%a9%d7%9c-%d7%94%d7%a1%d7%a8%d7%98%d7%99%d7%9d-%d7%94%d7%9b%d7%99-%d7%97%d7%90%d7%a4%d7%a8%d7%99%d7%9d-%d7%91%d7%aa/|title=\u05d7\u05d0\u05e4\u05e8\u05d5\u05d5\u05d3: \u05e1\u05d9\u05e4\u05d5\u05e8\u05dd \u05e9\u05dc \u05d4\u05e1\u05e8\u05d8\u05d9\u05dd \u05d4\u05db\u05d9 \u05d7\u05d0\u05e4\u05e8\u05d9\u05dd \u05d1\u05ea\u05d5\u05dc\u05d3\u05d5\u05ea \u05d4\u05e7\u05d5\u05dc\u05e0\u05d5\u05e2 \u05d4\u05d9\u05e9\u05e8\u05d0\u05dc\u05d9|last=\u05e8\u05d9\u05e0\u05d2\u05dc|first=\u05de\u05d0\u05ea \u05e9\u05d9|date=2016-03-24|website=\u05d8\u05d9\u05d9\u05dd \u05d0\u05d0\u05d5\u05d8|language=he-IL|access-date=2020-02-22}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Exorcist II: The Heretic'' (1977) ===\n\n''[[Exorcist II: The Heretic]]'' is the sequel to [[William Friedkin]]'s [[Academy Award]]-winning [[The Exorcist (film)|1973 film]], directed by [[John Boorman]]. While British film critic [[Mark Kermode]] called the original film his favourite film of all time, he believes the sequel to be the worst film ever made.<ref name=\"guardianworst\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2004/jul/02/1 |title= 'If I'd made that, I'd change my name' |accessdate=2013-12-01 |newspaper=The Guardian}}</ref> The ''Golden Turkey Awards'' named it the second-worst film ever made, after ''Plan 9 from Outer Space''. Critic Bill Chambers stated it was \"Possibly the worst film ever made and surely the worst sequel ever made.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/exorcist_ii_the_heretic/reviews/|title=Exorcist II \u2013 The Heretic Reviews|last=|first=|date=|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango]]|accessdate=April 16, 2019}}</ref> It also appeared in ''[[The Official Razzie Movie Guide: Enjoying the Best of Hollywood's Worst]]'' book. Friedkin believes the sequel diminished the value of the original film and called it \"the worst piece of shit I've ever seen\" and \"a fucking disgrace.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cinemablend.com/news/2464836/original-exorcist-director-says-the-sequel-was-the-worst-movie-hes-ever-seen|title=Original Exorcist Director Says The Sequel Was The Worst Movie He's Ever Seen |publisher=CinemaBlend|date=January 9, 2019|accessdate=January 20, 2019|last=Libbey|first=Dirk}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.blastr.com/2013-4-15/exorcist-director-says-sequel-one-worst-films-ive-ever-seen |title= Exorcist director says sequel is 'one of the worst films I've ever seen' |accessdate=December 1, 2013|date=April 15, 2013 |author=Don Kaye |publisher=[[Blastr]]}}</ref> Eventually, the film garnered so much hate that Boorman disowned it. In an interview with Bob McCabe for the book ''The Exorcist: Out of the Shadows'', he confessed, \"The sin I committed was not giving the audience what it wanted in terms of horror.\"<ref>John Boorman, cited in Bob McCabe, ''The Exorcist: Out of the Shadows'' (Omnibus Press, 1999), p.164</ref>\n\n=== ''The Swarm'' (1978) ===\n\n''[[The Swarm (film)|The Swarm]]'' is a horror film about a [[Africanized bee|killer bee]] invasion of [[Texas]], directed and produced by [[Irwin Allen]]. Despite its all-star cast (including [[Michael Caine]], [[Henry Fonda]], [[Richard Widmark]] and [[Olivia de Havilland]]), it was a box-office failure and was excoriated by reviewers.<ref name=\"ts\">''Halliwell's film and video guide 2002'' edited by John Walker. London. HarperCollins Entertainment, 2001. {{ISBN|0-00-712265-9}} (p. 804).</ref> On its UK release, ''[[The Sunday Times]]'' described ''The Swarm'' as \"simply the worst film ever made\".<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2001/apr/26/artsfeatures2 The worst movie ever?] ''The Guardian'', 26 April 2001. Retrieved 29 March 2014.</ref> [[Leslie Halliwell]] described it as a \"very obvious disaster movie with risible dialogue\".<ref name=\"ts\" /> ''[[The Guardian]]'' article on ''The Swarm'' stated, \"You could pass it all off as a sick joke, except it cost twelve million dollars, twenty-two million bees, and several years of someone's life.\"<ref name=\"ts\" /> [[Barry Took]], reviewing it for ''[[Punch (magazine)|Punch]]'', stated, \"the story is of a banality matched only by the woodenness of the acting\".<ref name=\"ts\" /> ''[[Time Out (magazine)|Time Out]]'' magazine called ''The Swarm'' a \"risibly inadequate disaster movie\".<ref>[https://www.timeout.com/london/film/the-swarm \"The Swarm\"] Retrieved 29 March 2014.</ref> ''The Swarm'' is included in several \"worst movie\" books, including the Medved brothers' ''The Golden Turkey Awards'',<ref>Mikel J. Koven, ''Film, Folklore and Urban Legends''. Scarecrow Press, 2008 {{ISBN|0-8108-6025-2}} (p. 91)</ref> and John Wilson's book ''The Official Razzie Movie Guide'', as one of the 100 Most Enjoyably Bad Movies Ever Made.<ref name=\"Wilson 2005\">{{cite book|last=Wilson|first=John|title=The Official Razzie Movie Guide: Enjoying the Best of Hollywood's Worst |year=2005|publisher=Grand Central Publishing|isbn=0-446-69334-0}}</ref> It soon gained a cult status (enough so that [[Warner Archive]] released the extended version on [[Blu-ray]]).<ref>[https://bloody-disgusting.com/home-video/3517106/warner-archive-releasing-extended-version-1978s-swarm-blu-ray/ Warner Archive Releasing Extended Version of 1978\u2019s \u2018The Swarm\u2019 on Blu-ray-Bloody Disgusting]</ref><ref>[https://addictedtohorrormovies.com/2017/07/14/on-this-day-in-horror-history-the-mind-boggling-the-swarm-hit-theaters/ On This Day in Horror History: The Mind Boggling \u2018The Swarm\u2019 Hit Theaters-Addicted to Horror]</ref>\n\n=== ''I Spit on Your Grave'' (1978) ===\n\n''[[I Spit on Your Grave]]'' became controversial for its graphic violence and lengthy depictions of gang rape. It was initially unable to find a distributor until 1980, when it received a wider release. Luke Y. Thompson of the ''[[New Times LA|New Times]]'' stated, \"Defenders of the film have argued that it's actually pro-woman, due to the fact that the female lead wins in the end, which is sort of like saying that cockfights are pro-rooster because there's always one left standing\".<ref name=\"Spiton\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/i_spit_on_your_grave|title=I Spit on Your Grave (Day of the Woman)|last=|first=|date=|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango]]|accessdate=April 16, 2019}}</ref> Critic David Keyes named it the worst film of the 1980s.<ref name=\"Spiton\"/> Scott Tobias of ''The A.V. Club'' called it \"one of the era's most abhorrent pieces of exploitation trash\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://avclub.com/article/emi-spit-on-your-graveem-2010-53367 |title=I Spit On Your Grave (2010) |author=Scott Tobias |date=March 21, 2011 |newspaper=[[The A.V. Club]]}}</ref> and Patrick Naugle of DVD Verdict stated, \"It's one of the most soulless, vile, and morally reprehensible things I've ever had to sit through.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://dvdverdict.com/reviews/dontmesssister.php |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040426083712/https://dvdverdict.com/reviews/dontmesssister.php |url-status=dead |archive-date=April 26, 2004 |title=Don't Mess With My Sister |author=Patrick Naugle |date=February 15, 2002 |publisher=[[DVD Verdict]] }}</ref> Roger Ebert gave the film no stars, referring to it as \"a vile bag of garbage ... without a shred of artistic distinction,\" adding, \"Attending it was one of the most depressing experiences of my life.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/19800716/REVIEWS/7160301/1023 |title=Review of ''I Spit on Your Grave'' |accessdate=2007-03-20 |author=Roger Ebert|author-link=Roger Ebert |date=July 16, 1980 |newspaper=[[Chicago Sun-Times]] }}</ref> Ebert also included it on his \"most hated\" list<ref name=\"eberthated\"/> and considered it the worst movie ever made.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://beaconnews.suntimes.com/news/2247859-418/ebert-movie-chaz-roger-writer.html |title=Movie, journalism fans queue up to see Ebert |accessdate=2007-03-20 |author=Steve Lord |date=November 7, 2010 |newspaper=[[Chicago Sun-Times]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101111153312/http://beaconnews.suntimes.com/news/2247859-418/ebert-movie-chaz-roger-writer.html |archivedate=November 11, 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Video Q&A |author=Roger Ebert|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=0U9IAAAAIBAJ&sjid=NP0DAAAAIBAJ&pg=2655,5621128&dq=roger+ebert+i+spit+on+your+grave+worst+ever |newspaper=[[The Ledger]] |date=28 May 1998 |accessdate=3 November 2013}}</ref> [[Gene Siskel]] also considered it one of the worst films ever made.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/chicagotribune/doc/175977821.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:AI&type=historic&date=Aug%2017,%201983&author=&pub=Chicago%20Tribune&edition=&startpage=&desc=Tempo |title= 'Man Who Wasn't There' would best be left unseen |accessdate=2013-10-02 |author=Gene Siskel|author-link=Gene Siskel |date=1983-08-17|newspaper=Chicago Tribune }}{{subscription required}}</ref> Author James Livingston wrote in ''The World Turned Inside Out'' that ''I Spit on Your Grave'' was the second worst movie ever made,<ref>James Livingston, ''The World Turned Inside Out: American Thought and Culture at the End of the 20th Century'', Rowman & Littlefield Publishers, 2011, {{ISBN|978-0742535428}}, Page 189.</ref> ''Film Racket'' featured it as their first entry in to their \"Worst Movie Ever?\" series,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://filmracket.com/worst-movie-ever-i-spit-on-your-grave/ |title=Worst Movie Ever? I Spit On Your Grave |author=Pete Croatto |date= May 1, 2013 |publisher=Film Racket}}</ref> and ''Flavorwire'' named it the eleventh worst movie ever made.<ref name=\"Flavorwire\">{{cite web|url=http://flavorwire.com/477608/the-50-worst-movies-ever-made/view-all |title=The 50 Worst Movies Ever Made|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190330132846/https://www.flavorwire.com/477608/the-50-worst-movies-ever-made/view-all|author=Jason Bailey |date= September 17, 2014 |archivedate=March 30, 2019 |work=[[Flavorwire]]}}</ref> Despite the intense negative reception from some critics, the film has a 55% rating on [[Rotten Tomatoes]], with critics arguing that \"It shows us the raw, shocking reality of rape, in all its bloody viciousness.\"<ref name=\"Spiton\"/>\n\n=== ''Caligula'' (1979) ===\n[[File:Caligula8.jpg|thumb|[[Teresa Ann Savoy]] and [[Malcolm McDowell]] appear in ''[[Caligula (film)|Caligula]]'', which was panned for its explicit sex scenes]]\nThe erotic/historical drama ''[[Caligula (film)|Caligula]]'', directed by [[Tinto Brass]], about the infamous [[Caligula|Roman Emperor]] was in part financed by ''[[Penthouse magazine|Penthouse]]'' founder [[Bob Guccione]]. The film, featuring a prestigious cast ([[Malcolm McDowell]], [[Helen Mirren]], [[Peter O'Toole]], and [[John Gielgud]]) is notable for its explicit scenes of sex and violence, including six minutes of hardcore porn footage filmed by Guccione and another editor. ''Caligula'' earned some prerelease controversy after [[Gore Vidal]], who had written the script, distanced himself from the film. When ''Caligula'' was released, it received strongly hostile reviews, reviewers criticizing its extreme scenes of sex and violence and lack of narrative coherence.<ref name=\"ebert19800922\">{{cite news |url=http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/19800922/REVIEWS/9220301/1023 |title=Caligula |newspaper=[[Chicago Sun-Times]] |author=Roger Ebert|author-link=Roger Ebert |date=22 September 1980 |accessdate=7 January 2014}}</ref> [[Rex Reed]] of ''[[New York (magazine)|New York]]'' magazine called the film \"a trough of rotten swill\".<ref>Thomas Vinciguerra, \"[https://nymag.com/nymetro/movies/features/1407/ Porn Again: \"Caligula\" is remastered in all its gross glory]\".</ref> Roger Ebert gave ''Caligula'' a zero stars rating, dubbing it \"sickening, utterly worthless, shameful trash\", accusing it of being artistically vulgar in its depiction of sex and violence, and of having technically incompetent direction and structure.<ref name=\"ebert19800922\"/> ''Caligula'' was one of the few films Ebert ever walked out on (two hours into its 170-minute running time), after describing himself as feeling \"disgusted and unspeakably depressed\",<ref>{{cite news|url=http://blogs.suntimes.com/ebert/2008/10/dont_read_me_first.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081018181430/http://blogs.suntimes.com/ebert/2008/10/dont_read_me_first.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=18 October 2008 |title=Don't read me first! |author=Roger Ebert |date=16 October 2008 |work=blog.suntimes.com |accessdate=9 June 2012 }}</ref> and he also placed it on his \"Most Hated\" list.<ref name=\"eberthated\"/> [[Jay Scott]], reviewing ''Caligula'' for ''[[The Globe and Mail]]'', stated, \"''Caligula'' doesn't really work on any level\" and the film and its production \"constitute a boondoggle of landmark proportions\".<ref>Jay Scott, ''The Globe and Mail'', February 7th, 1980.</ref> So negative was its initial reception, Australian newspaper ''[[The Age]]'' stated that ''Caligula'' was being \"billed by critics everywhere as one of the worst films ever made\".<ref>''News Diary'', ''The Age'' June 8, 1981 (p.2).</ref> Leslie Halliwell dubbed it \"a vile curiosity of interest chiefly to sadomasochists\".<ref>''Photoplay Magazine'', Volume 38, 1987 (p.38)</ref> ''[[The Hamilton Spectator]]'' later referred to ''Caligula'' as \"possibly the worst movie ever made\".<ref>\"Lowest:100 Really Bad Moments in 20th Century Entertainment\". ''The Hamilton Spectator'', July 24, 1999 (p. W17).</ref> Joe Holleman, in an article in the ''[[St. Louis Post-Dispatch]]'' discussing historical films set in Ancient Rome, argued, \"two of the worst movies made in the 20th century were ancient Rome pieces ... ''[[Cleopatra (1963 film)|Cleopatra]]'' and ''Caligula''\".<ref>Joe Holleman, \"Roman Warriors roam the big screen again\". ''St. Louis Post-Dispatch'' May 5th, 2000 (p. E1).</ref> Christopher Armstead, reviewing ''Caligula'' for the website Film Critics United, stated, \"Dollar for dollar, this could very well be the worst movie ever made.\"<ref>[http://filmcriticsunited.com/caligula.html \"Caligula\" by Christopher Armstead] Film Critics United. Retrieved 10 January 2014.</ref>\n\n== 1980s ==\n\n=== ''Heaven's Gate'' (theatrical version, 1980) ===\n\nThe [[Western (genre)|Western]] epic ''[[Heaven's Gate (film)|Heaven's Gate]]'', loosely based on the [[Johnson County War]] in 1890s [[Wyoming]], was plagued by massive cost and time overruns, largely due to director [[Michael Cimino]]'s extreme attention to detail. He demanded 50 takes of at least one scene, and refused to start shooting for another until a cloud he liked rolled across the sky. It cost over $44 million, but brought in only $3.5 million at the box office.<ref>[https://www.cnbc.com/id/38815985?slide=9 \"The 15 Biggest Box Office Bombs -> ''Heaven's Gate'' #8\"]. CNBC. Retrieved 2011-09-07.</ref> The original version ran at nearly four hours, but was yanked from release after only one week due to scathing reviews. It later resurfaced in a 149-minute version, but by then the damage was done. [[Vincent Canby]] called it \"an unqualified disaster\", among other things. Roger Ebert called it \"the most scandalous cinematic waste I've ever seen\".<ref>[[Roger Ebert|Ebert, Roger]] (1981). [http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/19810101/REVIEWS/101010302/1023 \"''Heaven's Gate''\"]. ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]''. Retrieved 2011-09-07.</ref>\n\nAfter word of his grandiose spending and defiant nature toward studio [[United Artists]] got out (detailed in ''Final Cut'' by [[Steven Bach]], a studio executive involved with the film from the beginning).<ref>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/finalcutartmoney00bach|url-access=registration|page=[https://archive.org/details/finalcutartmoney00bach/page/6 6]|quote=heaven's gate april 16 1979.|isbn=9781557043740|title=Final Cut: Art, Money, and Ego in the Making of Heaven's Gate, the Film that Sank United Artists|year=1999|publisher=Newmarket Press|last=Bach|first=Steven}}</ref> Cimino was awarded the 1980 [[Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Director]], and the film was nominated for four more Razzies, including Worst Picture.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://razzies.com/asp/content/XcNewsPlus.asp?cmd=view&articleid=21 |title=Summary of 1981 Razzies |work=Razzies.com |accessdate=2013-12-19 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140116032635/http://razzies.com/asp/content/XcNewsPlus.asp?cmd=view&articleid=21 |archivedate=2014-01-16 }}</ref> In 1999, ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' placed the film on a list of the 100 worst ideas of the 20th century.<ref name=\"worstideas\"/> In February 2010, the readers of ''[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]'' voted it the sixth-worst film of all time.<ref name=\"The 50 Worst Movies Ever\"/> That same year, [[Joe Queenan (author)|Joe Queenan]] of ''[[The Guardian]]'' also called it the worst film ever made, saying that it \"defies belief\".<ref name=\"queenan\"/> Cimino was initially considered a director on the rise after directing ''[[The Deer Hunter]]'' (which won five Oscars, including Best Picture and Best Director), but his reputation never recovered after ''Heaven's Gate''. The production is also notorious for the cruelty to animals that occurred both on screen and on site, including deliberately killing a horse with explosives.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0080855/trivia|title=Heaven's Gate (1980)|work=IMDb|accessdate=1 October 2014}}</ref> The film effectively ended not only the existence of [[United Artists]] as an independent Hollywood studio (its parent firm sold the company to [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer]], where it still operates), but also, largely, Cimino's career \u2014 he would not direct again until 1985's ''[[Year of the Dragon (film)|Year of the Dragon]]''.\n\nDespite the vicious reviews, the film's reputation improved over time.<ref>[https://www.newyorker.com/culture/richard-brody/movie-of-the-week-heavens-gate Movie of the Week: \"Heaven's Gate|The New Yorker]</ref> In fall 2012, the [[New York Film Festival]], the venue for its infamous opening, premiered the restored director's cut. In stark contrast, ''The Times'' (London) called the restored version \"a modern masterpiece\" and its 1980 cut \"one of the greatest injustices of cinematic history\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/arts/film/article3554129.ece |title=Heaven's Gate: box office turkey that sank a studio is a modern masterpiece |newspaper=The Times |date=2012-10-01 |accessdate=2013-11-18}}</ref> The film has also been released on Blu-ray and DVD by the [[Criterion Collection]].<ref>[https://www.criterion.com/films/28036-heaven-s-gate Heaven's Gate (1980)-The Criterion Collection]</ref> Manohla Dargis of ''[[The New York Times]]'' said that the film \"has been called a disaster and a disgrace, yet also anointed a masterpiece.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/03/17/movies/michael-ciminos-heavens-gate-returns-to-film-forum.html|title=The Second Coming of 'Heaven's Gate'|last=Dargis|first=Manohla|date=March 15, 2013|accessdate=June 13, 2013|work=The New York Times}}</ref>\n\n=== ''The Apple'' (1980) ===\n\n''[[The Apple (1980 film)|The Apple]]'' (also called ''Star Rock'') is a 1980 [[Science fiction film|science fiction]] [[Musical film|musical]] [[comedy film]] written and directed by [[Menahem Golan]]. It stars [[Catherine Mary Stewart]] as a young singer named Bibi, who, in a futuristic 1994, signs to an evil label named Boogalow International Music. It deals with themes of conformity versus rebellion, and makes use of [[Bible#Christian Bibles|Biblical allegory]]<ref name = \"Flavorwire2\">Bailey, Jason (10 July 2017). [http://flavorwire.com/607226/bad-movie-night-the-distinctive-disco-cheese-of-the-apple \"Bad Movie Night: The Distinctive Disco Cheese of \u2018The Apple\u2019\"]. ''[[Flavorwire]]''. Retrieved 9 December 2017.</ref> including the tale of [[Adam and Eve]].\n\nOn Rotten Tomatoes, the film has a 20% score based on 10 reviews, with an average rating of 3.99/10.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/1001131-apple/ | title=The Apple (1980) | work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] | publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango Media]] | accessdate=July 7, 2019}}</ref> Common criticism from both reviews that appeared in trade publications and major news outlets and the audience were a lack of originality,<ref name=\"afi\" /> a weak script,<ref name=\"afi\">{{cite web|url=http://www.afi.com/members/catalog/DetailView.aspx?s=&Movie=56362|publisher=[[American Film Institute]]|title=The Apple|accessdate=January 31, 2016}}</ref> uninspired music,<ref name=\"afi\" /> poor execution,<ref name=\"afi\" /> and Golan's inexperienced take on the 1960s hippie movement.<ref name = \"SlashFilm2\"/> At the 1980 [[Montreal World Film Festival]], some watchers threw [[vinyl records]] of music from the film at the screen.<ref name = \"SlashFilm2\">Harris p. [http://www.slashfilm.com/the-apple-oral-history/2/ 2]</ref> ''The Apple'' was nominated for Worst Picture at the [[1980 Stinkers Bad Movie Awards]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://theenvelope.latimes.com/extras/lostmind/year/1980/1980st.htm|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070815004414/http://theenvelope.latimes.com/extras/lostmind/year/1980/1980st.htm|url-status=dead|archive-date=August 15, 2007|title=Past Winners Database|date=August 15, 2007}}</ref> The ballot was revised and re-released in 2006, where the Worst Picture results remained the same. In addition, the film received six more nominations, two of which were wins: Worst Director (Golan) and Least \u201cSpecial\u201d Special Effects.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://theenvelope.latimes.com/extras/lostmind/year/1980/1980st.htm|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070815004414/http://theenvelope.latimes.com/extras/lostmind/year/1980/1980st.htm|url-status=dead|archive-date=August 15, 2007|title=Past Winners Database|date=August 15, 2007}}</ref> Sean Burns in the ''[[Philadelphia Weekly]]'' gave the film a scathing review: \"''The Apple'' isn't just the worst disco musical ever made; it could very well be the worst movie ever made, period.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Summer Camp |first=Sean |last=Burns |newspaper=Philadelphia Weekly |date=July 12, 2006 }}</ref> In 2004, after a poor transfer on VHS that lead years of fans rediscovering it ala midnight screenings at sci-fi conventions while also becoming a staple at film festivals and art houses, the cult film was finally released on DVD.<ref>[http://www.mtv.com/news/1579735/american-idol-executive-producers-secret-flop-the-apple/ 'American Idol' Executive Producer's Secret Flop: 'The Apple' - MTV]</ref>\n\n=== ''Inchon'' (1981) === <!-- This qualifies as a 1981 film, for it made its world premiere a year prior to its general release, a few months before \"Mommie Dearest\". -->\n\nThe [[war film]] ''[[Inchon (film)|Inchon]]'', directed by [[Terence Young (director)|Terence Young]] and starring [[Laurence Olivier]] as General [[Douglas MacArthur]],<ref>[http://www.tcm.com/tcmdb/title/3139/Inchon/ Inchon (1982)-TCM.com]</ref> was meant to depict the [[Battle of Inchon]] during the [[Korean War]]. Producer Mitsuharu Ishii was a senior member of the Japanese branch of the [[Unification Church]], whose leader, [[Sun Myung Moon]],<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wiWctDyWhDI Slate's Bad Movies: Oscar Slumming - Slate on YouTube]</ref> claimed he had the film made to show MacArthur's spirituality and connection to God and the Japanese people.<ref>[[s:U.S. v. Sun Myung Moon 532 F.Supp. 1360 (1982)]]</ref> Its eventual production cost of $46 million resulted in a $5 million box office gross, and ''[[The New York Times]]'' review written by [[Vincent Canby]] calls the movie \"the most expensive B-movie ever\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Inchon (1981) \u2013 'Inchon,' At Last |author=Vincent Canby |url=https://movies.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9A03E0D8123BF934A2575AC0A964948260 |work=The New York Times |date=1982-09-17}}</ref> ''[[The Washington Post]]'' described ''Inchon'' as \"one of the biggest commercial disasters in film history\".<ref>{{cite news | last =The Washington Post staff | title =Terence Young dies \u2013 Directed Bond movies | work =[[The Washington Post]] | page =B6 | publisher =[[The Washington Post Company]] | date =September 9, 1994}}</ref> Every conceivable kind of problem plagued production, including labor issues, the U.S. military withdrawing support due to the film's Unification Church connection, weather and natural disasters, customs difficulties, expensive directorial blunders, and the original director ([[Andrew McLaglen]]) quitting before the start of production. Olivier's performance was criticised, and he was awarded the [[3rd Golden Raspberry Awards|1982 Golden Raspberry award]] for Worst Actor.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.razzies.com/forum/forum_posts.asp?TID=332&PN=3 |title=1982 Razzie Nominees & \"Winners\" \u2013 The Official Razzie Forum |work=Razzies.com |accessdate=2011-01-17 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160820075540/http://www.razzies.com/forum/forum_posts.asp?TID=332&PN=3 |archive-date=2016-08-20 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The film itself took the 1982 Razzies for Worst Picture and Worst Screenplay, and Young's direction earned him a tie for Worst Director of 1982. A number of reviewers at various media outlets described ''Inchon'' as the worst film ever made, including ''The Washington Post'',<ref>{{cite news | last =Mayo | first =Mike | title =Hollywood's untapped resources \u2013 worthwhile movies don't always make it to video | work =[[The Washington Post]] | publisher =[[The Washington Post Company]] | date =April 13, 1997 |page=G7}}</ref> ''Newsweek'',<ref>{{cite news | last =Boedeker | first =Hal | title =The Magic of Olivier his film legacy sets standard for all actors | work =[[The Miami Herald]] | page =36G | date =July 21, 1989 |quote=The worst of his choices was probably taking on the role of Gen. Douglas MacArthur in 1982's Inchon. ''Newsweek'' called Inchon 'the worst movie ever made, a turkey the size of Godzilla.'}}</ref> ''TV Guide'',<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://movies.tvguide.com/inchon/review/102041 |title=Inchon Review |magazine=[[TV Guide]] |date=2012-11-28 |accessdate=2013-11-18}}</ref> and the [[The Canadian Press|Canadian Press]].<ref>{{cite news | last =McKay | first =John ([[Canadian Press]]) | title =Welch fleshes out worst in film | work =The Record (Kitchener, Ontario, Canada) | page =E4 | date =March 23, 2004}}</ref> ''Inchon'' was later profiled in multiple books on worst in film, including ''[[The Hollywood Hall of Shame]]'' by Harry and Michael Medved,<ref>{{cite book |last=Medved |first=Harry |author2=Michael Medved |author2-link=Michael Medved |title=The Hollywood Hall of Shame: The Most Expensive Flops in Movie History |publisher=Perigee Books |location=[[New York City|New York]], [[New York (state)|NY]] |year=1984 |pages=[https://archive.org/details/hollywoodhallofs00medv/page/189 189\u2013197] |isbn=0-399-51060-5 |title-link=The Hollywood Hall of Shame }}</ref> and ''The Worst Movies of All Time'' by Michael Sauter.<ref name=\"sauter\">{{cite book |last=Sauter |first=Michael |title=The Worst Movies of All Time: Or, What Were They Thinking? |publisher=[[Citadel Press]] |year=1999 |page=197 |isbn=0-8065-2078-7}}</ref> To date, ''Inchon'' has never been released on home video in the United States.\n\n=== ''Tarzan, the Ape Man'' (1981) ===\n\nThe [[adventure film]] ''[[Tarzan, the Ape Man (1981 film)|Tarzan, the Ape Man]]'', loosely based on the novel ''[[Tarzan of the Apes]]'' by [[Edgar Rice Burroughs]], stars [[Miles O'Keefe]] in the [[Tarzan|title role]] and [[Bo Derek]] as his partner [[Jane Porter (Tarzan)|Jane Parker]], and is told from Jane's point of view. Despite being a box office success, it was poorly received by critics upon its release, due to its poor screenplay, bad acting, and unintentional humor. [[Leonard Maltin]], writing for his ''[[Movie Guide]]'', stated that the film \"lacks action, humor and charm\", and considered it so bad that it \"nearly forced editors of this book to devise a rating lower than BOMB\".<ref name=\"Maltin01211\"/> [[Leslie Halliwell]] was equally harsh; he described ''Tarzan, the Ape Man'' as \"certainly the worst of the Tarzan movies and possibly the most banal film so far made; even the animals give poor performances\".<ref>Leslie Halliwell, John Walker, ''Halliwell's Film Guide''. HarperPerennial, 1996 (p. 1119).</ref> Writer Thomas S. Hischak described it thus: \"Produced and directed without a shred of talent by [[John Derek]], ''Tarzan, the Ape Man'' often ranks high in the lists of the worst movies ever made.\"<ref>Thomas S. Hischak, ''American Literature on Stage and Screen: 525 Works and Their Adaptations'' McFarland, 2012. {{ISBN|0-7864-9279-1}} (p. 237)</ref> Film critic John Nesbit considered it \"my pick for worst film ever\",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://oldschoolreviews.com/rev_80/tarzan.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140304212347/http://oldschoolreviews.com/rev_80/tarzan.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=2014-03-04 |title=John Derek, Tarzan the Ape Man |publisher=Old School Reviews |accessdate=2014-03-05}}</ref> while Matt Brunson of ''[[Creative Loafing]]'' wrote, \"this cinematic atrocity truly is one of the all-time worsts\".<ref>{{cite web|last=Brunson |first=Matt |url=http://clclt.com/charlotte/view-from-the-couch/Content?oid=2354590 |title=View From The Couch &#124; View from the Couch &#124; Creative Loafing Charlotte |work=Clclt.com |date=2004-06-16 |accessdate=2014-03-05}}</ref> ''Tarzan, the Ape Man'' was nominated for six awards at the [[2nd Golden Raspberry Awards]], winning one for Worst Actress (Bo Derek). It holds an 11% rating on [[Rotten Tomatoes]] based on 19 reviews.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://rottentomatoes.com/m/1020897-tarzan_the_ape_man/|title=Tarzan, the Ape Man|last=|first=|date=|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango]]|accessdate=April 16, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Mommie Dearest'' (1981) ===\n\n''[[Mommie Dearest (film)|Mommie Dearest]]'' was based on the [[Mommie Dearest|memoir of the same name]] by [[Christina Crawford]] about her upbringing by [[Joan Crawford]].<ref>[https://mubi.com/de/films/mommie-dearest MUBI]</ref> It was the first film to sweep the Golden Raspberry Awards nominations, winning a total of five Razzies out of the nine nominations, including \"Worst Picture\" and Worst Actress ([[Faye Dunaway]], shared with Bo Derek).<ref name=SGTW>{{cite book | last =Adams | first =Michael | title =Showgirls, Teen Wolves, and Astro Zombies:A Film Critic's Year-Long Quest to Find the Worst Movie Ever Made | publisher =[[HarperCollins]] | year =2010 | location = | page =188 | isbn =978-0-06-180629-2}}</ref> The same organization also named it \"Worst Picture of the Decade\" in 1989/90, and was nominated for \"Worst Drama of Our First 25 Years\" in 2004/05.<ref name=\"GR1\">{{cite news| url=http://www.razzies.com/asp/content/XcNewsPlus.asp?cmd=view&articleid=12| title=Decade's Worst -The 80's| author=Wilson, John| publisher=[[Golden Raspberry Awards]]| date=March 15, 1990| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130511065558/http://www.razzies.com/asp/content/XcNewsPlus.asp?cmd=view&articleid=12| archivedate=May 11, 2013}}</ref> The film is part of the \"100 most awful\" in the book ''[[The Official Razzie Movie Guide: Enjoying the Best of Hollywood's Worst]]''.<ref name=\"OFMG\">{{cite news | url=https://www.usatoday.com/life/movies/movieawards/2005-02-24-razzies_x.htm| title=Razzies still knocking Hollywood down a peg after 25 years | publisher=[[Associated Press]] / [[USA Today]]| date=February 24, 2005}}</ref><ref name=ORG>{{cite book | last =Wilson | first =John | title =The official Razzie movie guide: enjoying the best of Hollywood's worst | publisher =[[Hachette (publisher)|Hachette]] | year =2005 | location = | pages = | isbn =0-446-69334-0}}</ref> Entertainment writer Michael Sauter included the film in his book ''The Worst Movies of All Time''.<ref name=WMOAT>{{cite book | last =Sauter | first =Michael. | title =The worst movies of all time, or, What were they thinking? | publisher =Carol Publishing | year =1999 | location = | pages = | isbn =0-8065-2078-7}}</ref> It earned, as film critic and television host [[Richard Crouse]] put it, \"some of the nastiest reviews ever\".<ref name=RW>{{cite book | last =Crouse | first =Richard | title =Reel Winners: Movie Award Trivia | publisher =[[Dundurn Group]] | year =2005 | location = | page =[https://archive.org/details/reelwinnersmovie0000crou/page/123 123] | isbn =1-55002-574-0 | url =https://archive.org/details/reelwinnersmovie0000crou/page/123 }}</ref> Eric Henderson of ''[[CBS Minneapolis]]'' named it at the top of his \"Best 'Worst Movies Ever{{'\"}} list.<ref name=\"WCCO\">{{cite news | url=http://minnesota.cbslocal.com/2010/07/21/movie-blog-best-worst-movies-ever/| title=Movie Blog: Best 'Worst Movies Ever' | author=Henderson, Eric | publisher=[[CBS Minneapolis]]| date=June 21, 2010}}</ref> Roger Ebert wrote of this film, \"I can't imagine who would want to subject themselves to this movie. ''Mommie Dearest'' is a painful experience that drones on endlessly, as Joan Crawford's relationship with her daughter, Christina, disintegrates from cruelty through jealousy into pathos.\"<ref>[http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/19810101/REVIEWS/101010346/1023 Mommie Dearest] Roger Ebert, Chicago Sun Times, January 1, 1981</ref> Of the performance of Faye Dunaway, ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' said \"Dunaway does not chew scenery. Dunaway starts neatly at each corner of the set in every scene and swallows it whole, co-stars and all.\"<ref>[https://variety.com/review/VE1117793196.html?categoryid=31&cs=1&p=0] Variety, Jan. 1, 1981</ref>\n\nDespite the reviews at the time,<ref>[https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2017/06/05/joan-crawfords-explosive-offscreen-life Joan Crawford's Explosive Offscreen Life-The New Yorker]</ref> the film was a box office success, grossing $39 million worldwide on a $5 million budget. It has a 50% rating on [[Rotten Tomatoes]]. The site's consensus reads, \"''Mommie Dearest'' certainly doesn't lack for conviction, and neither does Faye Dunaway's legendary performance as a wire-wielding monster; unfortunately, the movie is too campy and undisciplined to transcend guilty pleasure\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/mommie_dearest/|title=Mommie Dearest (1981)|last=|first=|date=|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango]]|access-date=June 26, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== ''D\u00fcnyay\u0131 Kurtaran Adam'' (''The Man Who Saved the World'') (1982) ===\n\nThe Turkish science-fiction adventure ''[[D\u00fcnyay\u0131 Kurtaran Adam]]'' (also commonly known as ''Turkish Star Wars'') was directed by [[\u00c7etin \u0130nan\u00e7]] and starred [[C\u00fcneyt Ark\u0131n]]. It is notorious for illegally using footage from well known science fiction films and shows, most notably ''[[Star Wars]]'', along with stealing the music score from films such as ''[[Moonraker (film)|Moonraker]]'' and ''[[Raiders of the Lost Ark]]''. The film is also criticized for its nonsensical plot, badly written dialogue, and crude special effects.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.austinchronicle.com/gyrobase/Issue/story?oid=oid%3A197912 |title=There Is No Try...: Foleyvision does the Turkish 'Star Wars' Austin Screens |publisher=AustinChronicle.com |date=2004-02-20 |accessdate=2011-01-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://filmthreat.com/reviews/2341/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100312030851/https://filmthreat.com/reviews/2341/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=2010-03-12 |title=The Turkish Star Wars |publisher=Film Threat |date=2005-05-18 |accessdate=2011-01-17 }}</ref> Jos Kirps of [[ArticlesBase]] called it \"The Worst Movie Ever\", and stated, \"There are many bad sci-fi movies, and for many years movie addicts even considered Ed Wood's ''Plan 9 From Outer Space'' the worst movie of all times. But ''Plan 9'' is still a pretty good movie when compared to ''D\u00fcnyayi Kurtaran Adam''.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.contour2002.org/article/the-worst-movie-ever-a-turkish-star-wars-clone|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140810150129/http://www.contour2002.org/article/the-worst-movie-ever-a-turkish-star-wars-clone|url-status=dead|archive-date=10 August 2014|title=Contour2002.org|accessdate=1 October 2014}}</ref> ''[[Sabah (newspaper)|Sabah]]'' called it the \"world's worst film\".<ref>{{in lang|tr}} [http://www.sabah.com.tr/Gunaydin/Magazin/2012/04/15/turkun-uzayla-imtihani-nereye-kadar-surecek News article from Sabah newspaper] (Last accessed August 29, 2013).</ref> ''[[H\u00fcrriyet]]'' described the film as \"sitting on the throne of the king\" when compared to other [[So bad it's good|\"so bad it's good\" cult films]].<ref>{{in lang|tr}} [http://www.hurriyet.com.tr/yazarlar/20291864.asp News article from H\u00fcrriyet] (Last accessed August 29, 2013).</ref> ''[[Toronto Standard]]'' called it a \"dollar-store Star Wars\" and compared it to the works of Ed Wood.<ref>{{cite news|title=Dollar-store Star Wars |publisher= [[Toronto Standard]]|date=2012-05-04|url= http://torontostandard.com/culture/dollar-store-star-wars|accessdate=2013-08-24}}</ref> After a strong worldwide cult developed around the film, a sequel, ''The Son of the Man Who Saved the World'' ([[Turks in Space|''D\u00fcnyay\u0131 Kurtaran Adam'\u0131n O\u011flu'']]), was shot in 2006 and featured many returning members of the original cast and crew.<ref>{{in lang|tr}} [http://www.sabah.com.tr/2006/04/13/gny/gny119-20060413-200.html News article from Sabah newspaper] (Last accessed July 29, 2006).</ref>\n\n=== ''The Lonely Lady'' (1983) ===\nA [[Drama (film and television)|drama film]] directed by [[Peter Sasdy]], adapted from the 1976 novel written by [[Harold Robbins]], ''[[The Lonely Lady]],'' starring [[Pia Zadora]], became a critical and commercial failure and until today is the last adaptation of a Harold Robbins story. [[Roger Ebert]] opened his review saying that \"If ''The Lonely Lady'' had even a shred of style and humor, it could qualify as the worst movie of the year. Unfortunately, it's not that good.\"''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/the-lonely-lady-1983|title=The Lonely Lady Movie Review & Film Summary (1983) {{!}} Roger Ebert|last=Ebert|first=Roger|website=www.rogerebert.com|language=en|access-date=2019-07-18}}</ref>'' [[John J.B. Wilson]] included it in ''[[The Official Razzie Movie Guide]]'' as one of the most enjoyable bad movies ever, saying: \"In rough cut, ''The Lonely Lady'' was one of the funniest bad movies ever made.\"<ref name=\"Wilson 2005\" /> Dennis Schwartz called it \"A true candidate for one of the worst films ever.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://homepages.sover.net/~ozus/lonelylady.html|title=lonelylady|website=homepages.sover.net|access-date=2019-07-18}}</ref> Zadora herself said that ''The Lonely Lady'' was \"a real turkey, done very badly\", that she \"knew it was bad all along\" and that despite being taken seriously by its director it became a \"[[Camp (style)|camp]] classic, one of those movies that's so bad it's funny.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1985-11-19-ca-7761-story.html|title=ZADORA LOOKING FOR CREDIBILITY|date=1985-11-19|website=Los Angeles Times|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-18}}</ref> The film was nominated for eleven [[Golden Raspberry Awards]] (a record at that time until being surpassed by ''[[Showgirls]]'' with 13 nominations) and won six: Worst Actress, Worst Director, Worst Musical Score, Worst Original Song (\"The Way You Do It\"), Worst Picture, and Worst Screenplay. It was the first movie to win more than five Razzies.<ref name=\"Wilson 2005\" /> It was also nominated for a [[Stinkers Bad Movie Awards]] for Worst Picture as well as for a Razzie for Worst Picture of the Decade, but lost to ''[[Mommie Dearest (film)|Mommie Dearest]]'', and for Worst Drama of the Razzies' First 25 Years, but lost to ''[[Battlefield Earth (film)|Battlefield Earth]].'' Zadora's performance in this film and ''[[Butterfly (1982 film)|Butterfly]]'' also led to her being nominated for three special Razzies: Two in 1990, for \"Worst New Star of the Decade\", which she won, and \"Worst Actress of the Decade\", where she lost against [[Bo Derek]], and \"Worst Actress of the Century\" in 2000, where she lost against [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]]. The film has a [[List of films with a 0% rating on Rotten Tomatoes|0% rating at Rotten Tomatoes]], based on 11 reviews.<ref>{{Citation|title=The Lonely Lady (1983)|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/lonely_lady|language=en|access-date=2019-07-18}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Bolero'' (1984) ===\nA 1984 American [[Romance film|romantic]] [[Drama (film and television)|drama film]], ''[[Bolero (1984 film)|Bolero]],'' starring [[Bo Derek]], written and directed by her husband [[John Derek]], became a box-office bomb and a critical failure''. [[TV Guide]]'' says: \"''BOLERO'' must rank as one of the worst major movies ever made. Many awful movies are at least funny in a [[Camp (style)|campy]] sort of way. Bo and John Derek, however, make films so sincerely bad that they offer nothing in the way of relief.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tvguide.com/movies/bolero/117489|title=Bolero {{!}} TV Guide|website=TVGuide.com|language=en|access-date=2019-11-20}}</ref> [[Alan Jones (film critic)|Alan Jones]] of ''[[Radio Times]]'' named it \"One of the funniest bad movies ever made\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.radiotimes.com/film/cjwjx/bolero/|title=Bolero \u2013 review {{!}} cast and crew, movie star rating and where to watch film on TV and online|website=Radio Times|language=en|access-date=2019-11-20}}</ref> Matt Brunson of ''[[Creative Loafing]]'' said: \"I daresay even waterboarding is less punishing than watching this.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://clclt.com/charlotte/ghosts-cant-do-it-everest-the-martian-among-new-home-entertainment-titles/Content?oid=3718575|title=Ghosts Can't Do It, Everest, The Martian among new home entertainment titles|last=Brunson|first=Matt|website=Creative Loafing Charlotte|language=en|access-date=2019-11-20}}</ref> ''[[Fade In (magazine)|Fade In]]'' included it on its list of the \"30 worst vanity projects of all time\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fadeinonline.com/the-30-worst-vanity-projects-of-all-time.html|title=The 30 worst vanity projects of all time|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=}}</ref> It was nominated for nine [[Golden Raspberry Awards]] and won six, including Worst Picture, Worst Actress, Worst Director and Worst Screenplay. It was also nominated for a [[Stinkers Bad Movie Awards]] for Worst Picture, and in 1990, the film was nominated for an additional Razzie award for \"Worst Picture of the Decade.\", but lost to ''Mommy Dearest''. It has a [[List of films with a 0% rating on Rotten Tomatoes|0% rating]] on [[Rotten Tomatoes]], based on 17 reviews.<ref>{{Citation|title=Bolero - Movie Reviews|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/bolero_1984/reviews|language=en|access-date=2019-11-20}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Howard the Duck'' (1986) ===\n\nProduced by [[George Lucas]] and based on the [[Marvel Comics]] [[Howard the Duck|character of the same name]], ''[[Howard the Duck (film)|Howard the Duck]]'' received overwhelmingly negative reviews from film critics. ''[[Orange Coast Magazine]]'' writer Marc Weinberg and Leonard Maltin criticized the decision to shoot the film in live action.<ref>{{cite journal | last = Weinberg | first = Marc | date = 1986 | title = Out-Foxed | journal = [[Orange Coast Magazine]] | volume = 12 | issue = 9 | pages = 143\u2013144 }}</ref><ref name = \"Maltin\">{{cite book | last = Maltin | first = Leonard | title = Leonard Maltin's 2009 Movie Guide | year = 2008 | publisher = Penguin Group | isbn = 978-0-452-28978-9 | page = [https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780452289789/page/641 641] | chapter = H | url = https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780452289789/page/641 }}</ref> Maltin described it as a \"hopeless mess ... a gargantuan production which produces a gargantuan headache\".<ref name = \"Maltin\" /> The appearance of Howard was criticized as being unconvincing due to his poorly functioning mouth, drunkenness, perverted tendencies, and expressionless face. Reviewers also criticized the acting and humor and found the film boring.<ref name = \"Stanley\">{{cite book | last = Stanley | first = John | title = Creature Features: The Science Fiction, Fantasy, and Horror Movie Guide | year = 2000 | publisher = Berkley Boulevard Books | page = 253 | isbn = 0-425-17517-0 | quote = For one, the duck costume and makeup are phony&nbsp;\u2014 Howard looks like a midget in a Halloween costume. }}</ref><ref name = \"Hunter\">{{cite book | last = Hunter | first = Lew | title = Lew Hunter's Screenwriting 434: The Industry's Premier Teacher Reveals the Secrets of the Successful Screenplay | year = 2004 | publisher = Perigee | isbn = 0-399-52986-1 | page = 21 | chapter = Nothing in the Mind, Please | quote = Because we all know what a duck looks like, Lucas could not get an audience to suspend their belief that Howard was a little person in a duck suit. }}</ref> Jay Carr of ''[[The Boston Globe]]'' claimed that \"They Don't Get Much Worse Than ''Howard''{{-\"}},<ref>{{cite news|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/boston/doc/294411402.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Aug%201,%201986&author=Jay%20Carr,%20Globe%20Staff&pub=Boston%20Globe%20%28pre-1997%20Fulltext%29&edition=&startpage=&desc=THEY%20DON%27T%20GET%20MUCH%20WORSE%20THAN%20%27HOWARD%27|title=They Don't Get Much Worse Than 'Howard'|work=[[The Boston Globe]]|accessdate=2013-09-30|first=Jay|last=Carr|date=1986-08-01}}{{subscription required}}</ref> Glenn Heath Jr. of ''[[Slant Magazine]]'' wrote that it \"has a rightful place in the canon of worst films ever\",<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.slantmagazine.com/house/2011/07/summer-of-86-tarred-and-feathered-howard-the-duck/|title= Summer of '86: Tarred and Feathered: Howard the Duck |work=[[Slant Magazine]]|date=2011-07-28|accessdate=2014-03-14}}</ref> and ''[[TV Guide]]'' states it is \"one of the worst big-budget movies ever made\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://movies.tvguide.com/howard-the-duck/review/101469|title= Howard the Duck |work=[[TV Guide]]|accessdate=2014-03-14}}</ref> Film website [[Rotten Tomatoes]] gives the film a score of 15% based on 48 reviews, making it the lowest-rated [[Lucasfilm]] production of those reviewed on the site. The site's consensus states: \"While it has its moments, ''Howard the Duck'' suffers from an uneven tone and mediocre performances.\"<ref name = \"Tomatoes\">{{cite web | url = https://rottentomatoes.com/m/howard_the_duck/ | title = ''Howard the Duck'' (1986) | website = [[Rotten Tomatoes]] | accessdate = March 22, 2019 }}</ref> It received seven [[Golden Raspberry Award]] nominations in 1987 including [[Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Supporting Actor|Worst Supporting Actor]] ([[Tim Robbins]]), [[Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Director|Worst Director]] ([[Willard Huyck]]) and [[Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Original Song|Worst Original Song]] (\"Howard the Duck\"). It won four trophies for [[Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Screenplay|Worst Screenplay]], [[Golden Raspberry Award for Worst New Star|Worst New Star]] (\"the six guys and gals in the duck suit\"), Worst Visual Effects, and [[Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Picture|Worst Picture]], tied with ''[[Under the Cherry Moon]]''.<ref name=\"Razzies\">{{cite web | last = Wilson | first = John | title = 1986 Archive | url = http://www.razzies.com/asp/content/XcNewsPlus.asp?cmd=view&articleid=25 | publisher = [[Golden Raspberry Award]] | accessdate = October 11, 2009 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20130602153152/http://www.razzies.com/asp/content/XcNewsPlus.asp?cmd=view&articleid=25 | archivedate = June 2, 2013 }}</ref> The movie won also a [[Stinkers Bad Movie Awards]] for Worst Picture.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://theenvelope.latimes.com/extras/lostmind/year/1986/1986st.htm|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061017172107/http://theenvelope.latimes.com/extras/lostmind/year/1986/1986st.htm|archivedate=2006-10-17|title=1986 9th Hastings Bad Cinema Society Stinkers Awards|accessdate=April 2, 2013|work=[[Stinkers Bad Movie Awards]]|publisher=[[Los Angeles Times]]}}</ref> ''Howard the Duck'' was also featured in ''[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]''{{'}}s poll of the 50 worst films ever made.<ref name=\"The 50 Worst Movies Ever\"/> The negative reaction to the film took its toll on the cast, who found themselves unable to work on other projects as a result.<ref name=\"Release-2\">{{cite video |people=Thompson, Lea; Jones, Jeffry; Gale, Ed |date=2009 |title=Releasing the Duck |medium=DVD |publisher=Universal Home Video |id=UPC 025195052306}}</ref> Since then, it had become a cult film<ref>[https://www.cinemablend.com/news/2434140/lea-thompson-is-pitching-a-howard-the-duck-movie-to-marvel Lea Thompson Is Pitching A Howard The Duck Movie To Marvel-Cinema Blend]</ref> to the point of a cameo in ''[[Guardians of the Galaxy (film)|Guardians of the Galaxy]]'' played by [[Seth Green]] in that first film.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cinemablend.com/new/Guardians-Galaxy-End-Credits-Sequence-Explained-66562.html|title=Guardians Of The Galaxy End Credits Sequence Explained|last=Eisenberg|first=Eric|date=August 1, 2014|website=CinemaBlend|access-date=April 16, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Ishtar'' (1987) ===\n\n''[[Ishtar (film)|Ishtar]]'' was written and directed by [[Elaine May]] and starred [[Academy Award]]-winning duo [[Warren Beatty]] and [[Dustin Hoffman]] as Rogers and Clarke, two untalented lounge singers who travel to [[Morocco]] in hopes of finding a gig.<ref name=\"brody\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.newyorker.com/culture/richard-brody/movie-of-the-week-ishtar|title=Movie of the Week: \"Ishtar\"|last=Brody|first=Richard|authorlink=Richard Brody|work=[[The New Yorker]]|access-date=February 11, 2019|date=August 6, 2015}}</ref> Due to unanticipated problems with filming in the desert\u2014which resulted in numerous reshoots\u2014the film ran over budget by $30 million. While its final budget cost was $55 million, ''Ishtar'' earned only $14,375,181 at the North American box office leading ''Ishtar'' to become synonymous with \"[[Box office bomb|box office flop]]\". It was also subject to harsh reviews from critics. The film was nominated for Worst Picture and Worst Screenplay in the [[8th Golden Raspberry Awards]], winning one for Worst Director. ''[[San Jose Mercury News]]'' claimed that \"Time has not improved this film's reputation as being one of the worst ever made.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mercurynews.com/movies-dvd/ci_17017300 |title=Review: 'Dinner for Schmucks' a savory comedy |newspaper=[[San Jose Mercury News]]|date=1 May 2011}}</ref> ''[[Time Out (magazine)|Time Out]]'' suggested it was \"so bad it could have been deliberate\", and called it \"one of the worst films ever made\",<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.timeout.com/london/film/ishtar |title=Ishtar |magazine=[[Time Out (magazine)|Time Out]]}}</ref> while ''[[Hot Air (news site)|Hot Air]]'' referred to it as \"The ''[[Citizen Kane]]'' of big-budget, A-list vehicular homicides.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hotair.com/archives/2009/02/22/what-were-the-worst-movies-of-all-time/ |title=What were the worst movies of all time? |first= Ed |last=Morrissey |authorlink= Ed Morrissey|date=February 22, 2009 |publisher=[[Hot Air (news site)|Hot Air]]}}</ref> It was included in Michael Sauter's ''The Worst Movies of All Time'' book<ref name=\"sauter\"/> and [[Richard Roeper]] included it on his list of the 40 worst films he had seen.<ref name=\"RichardRoeper\">Richard Roeper, 10 Sure Signs a Movie Character is Doomed and Other Surprising Movie Lists, New York: Hyperion Books, 2003, pp. 66\u201367</ref> In 1999, ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' placed the film on a list of the 100 worst ideas of the 20th century.<ref name=\"worstideas\">{{cite news|url=http://content.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,991230,00.html |title=The 100 Worst Ideas Of The Century |date=June 14, 1999 |accessdate=April 8, 2018|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |first1=Melissa |last1=August |first2=Harriet |last2=Barovick |first3=Michelle |last3=Derrow |first4=Tam |last4=Gray |first5=Daniel S. |last5=Levy |first6=Lina |last6=Lofaro |first7=David |last7=Spitz |first8=Joel |last8=Stein |first9=Chris |last9=Taylor}}{{subscription required}}</ref>\n\nHowever, the film has since become a cult classic,<ref>[https://www.filminquiry.com/10-movies-low-ratings-actually-good/ 10 Movies With Low Ratings That Are Actually Good-Film Inquiry]</ref><ref>[http://streamline.filmstruck.com/2011/05/24/hearts-and-minds/ Streamline-The Official Filmstruck Blog-An Evening with Elaine May (and ISHTAR)]</ref> and it has also seen a recent minor critical re-evaluation, with some critics, including [[Richard Brody]],<ref name=\"brody\"/> praising the film, and directors [[Quentin Tarantino]], [[Edgar Wright]] and [[Martin Scorsese]] liking it.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://whatculture.com/film/6-guilty-pleasure-films-you-wont-believe-these-famous-directors-enjoy?page=7|title=6 Guilty Pleasure Films You Won't Believe These Famous Directors Enjoy|last=Paciuszko|first=Owain|date=2012-10-19|website=WhatCulture.com|language=en|access-date=2019-01-14}}</ref> [[Joe Queenan (author)|Joe Queenan]] compared the film to another comedy film considered the worst, ''[[Gigli]]'', and wrote that although it was considered one of the worst films ever made at the time of its release, it \"has several comic moments\" and does not get worse on subsequent viewings, unlike ''Gigli''.<ref name=\"queenan\"/>\n\n=== ''Nukie'' (1987) ===\n\n''[[Nukie]]'' is a 1987 South African film directed by Sias Odendaal (credited as Sias Odendal) and Michael Pakleppa, and starring [[Steve Railsback]], Ronald France, and [[Glynis Johns]]. The plot concerns an alien, Nukie, who crash lands on earth and seeks help from two children to reunite with his brother, Miko, who has been captured by the [[United States|U.S.]] government. The film was heavily inspired by [[Steven Spielberg]]'s 1982 film ''[[E.T. the Extra-Terrestrial]]''. Simon Abrams of [[Politico]] wrote that ''Nukie'' was worse than 1988 ''E.T.'' knock-off, ''[[Mac and Me]]'', writing that it is \"probably the most incompetent ''E.T.'' ripoff of any time period ... While ''Mac and Me'' was just rotten and ill-conceived, ''Nukie'' is uniquely perplexing\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.politico.com/states/new-york/albany/story/2011/10/in-the-year-of-spielberg-a-reminder-of-his-most-shameless-imitators-067306|title=In the year of Spielberg, a reminder of his most shameless imitators|last=Abrams|first=Simon|publisher=[[Politico]]|date=October 1, 2011|accessdate=July 8, 2017}}</ref> Critic [[The Cinema Snob|Brad Jones]] has said that ''Nukie'' is the worst film he has ever reviewed.<ref>{{cite web|last = Jones|first = Brad|title = E.T. Week: Nukie|url = http://www.thecinemasnob.com/the-cinema-snob/et-week-nukie|website = TheCinemaSnob|accessdate = July 8, 2017 |date = 2011-02-11}}</ref> ''[[Total Film]]'' named ''Nukie'' the worst kids movie ever made.<ref name=\"kidsmovie\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gamesradar.com/50-worst-kids-movies/|title=50 Worst Kids Movies|last=Winning|first=Joshua|work=[[Total Film]]|publisher=[[GamesRadar]]|date=November 8, 2011|accessdate=July 8, 2017 }}</ref> They also named it one of the worst science-fiction films ever made.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamesradar.com/25-worst-science-fiction-films/|title=25 Worst Science-Fiction Films|last=Winning|first=Joshua|work=[[Total Film]]|publisher=[[GamesRadar]]|date=June 30, 2014|accessdate=July 8, 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Superman IV: The Quest for Peace'' (1987) ===\n\n''[[Superman IV: The Quest for Peace]]'' was the last film in the [[Christopher Reeve]] series of [[Superman in film|Superman]] films, and co-starred [[Mark Pillow]] as the villain Nuclear Man. Despised by fans and critics alike, it is the lowest-grossing film in the series, only taking in $15,681,020 at the North American box office. Many critics pointed out the film's poor screenplay, acting, and special effects (such as a scene in which Superman repairs the [[Great Wall of China]] with his super-vision), while some have criticized it for its lack of attention to the comic book source material. Such special effects led Rita Kempley of ''[[The Washington Post]]'' to call it \"one of the cheesiest movies ever made\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/style/longterm/movies/videos/supermanivthequestforpeacepgkempley_a0ca6d.htm |title='Superman IV: The Quest for Peace' (PG) |work=Washingtonpost.com |date=1987-07-25 |accessdate=2014-03-05}}</ref> Film critic Jeffrey Lyles voiced similar hatred, claiming that the film \"isn't just one of the worst comic book films, it's one of the worst films ever made\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://lylesmoviefiles.com/2013/06/11/review-superman-iv-the-quest-for-peace/ |title=Review: Superman IV \u2013 The Quest for Peace &#124; Jeffrey K. Lyles' Movie Files |work=Lylesmoviefiles.com |date=2013-06-11 |accessdate=2014-03-05}}</ref> ''Superman IV'' holds a 11% rating on [[Rotten Tomatoes]] based on 44 reviews.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://rottentomatoes.com/m/superman_iv_the_quest_for_peace/ |title=Superman IV: The Quest for Peace |website=Rotten Tomatoes |accessdate=2019-07-17}}</ref> It appears on ''[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]'''s list of the 50 worst movies of all time,<ref name=\"The 50 Worst Movies Ever\"/> as well as the MRQE's 50 Worst Movies list.<ref name=\"MRQE50\"/> The film was nominated for two Razzies at the [[8th Golden Raspberry Awards]]: Worst Supporting Actress ([[Mariel Hemingway]]) and Worst Visual Effects.\n\n=== ''The Garbage Pail Kids Movie'' (1987) ===\n\n''[[The Garbage Pail Kids Movie]]'' is a [[live-action]] adaptation of the then-popular [[Garbage Pail Kids|trading card series of the same name]], itself a gross-out parody of the [[Cabbage Patch Kids]] dolls. The title characters are depicted by dwarf actors in low-budget costumes, with poorly functioning mouths and expressionless faces. The film is often criticized for its [[gross-out humor]], nonsensical plot, poor explanations, bad acting, and the unsettling appearance of the Garbage Pail Kids. It has a [[List of films with a 0% rating on Rotten Tomatoes|0% rating]] on [[Rotten Tomatoes]].<ref>{{rotten-tomatoes|id=garbage_pail_kids_movie|title=The Garbage Pail Kids Movie}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film holds a score of 1, making it tied for the lowest scoring film on the site.<ref name=\"Metacritic\"/> Caryn James of ''[[The New York Times]]'' said the movie is \"too repulsive for children or adults of any age\"<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-e8f3vgi-iQ Top 10 Movies So Bad They Were Pulled From Theatres-WatchMojo on YouTube]</ref> and is \"enough to make you believe in strict and faraway boarding schools\".<ref>{{cite news |first=Caryn |last=James |url=https://movies.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9B0DE1D81030F931A1575BC0A961948260 |title=Movie Review \u2013 The Garbage Pail Kids Movie |newspaper=[[New York Times]] |accessdate=6 Jun 2010 |date=1987-08-28}}</ref> Carlos Coto of the ''[[Sun-Sentinel]]'' called it \"one of the worst ever made\".<ref>{{cite news |url =http://articles.sun-sentinel.com/1987-09-05/features/8703110946_1_garbage-pail-kids-cabbage-patch-kids-kids-show |title=Trashy 'Garbage Pail Kids' Has No Value |newspaper=[[Sun-Sentinel]] |accessdate=29 Sep 2010 |date=1987-09-05}}</ref> Much of its content is said to be inappropriate for children, its intended audience. Throughout the movie, the Garbage Pail Kids steal, get in fights, bite toes off people, flatulate in people's faces, threaten others with [[switchblade]]s, urinate upon themselves, and run over cars. In addition to scatological behavior, the movie has several scenes that feature sexual images, violence, and drinking. Offended parents launched a nationwide protest of the movie that successfully resulted in the movie being withdrawn from circulation.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://allmovie.com/work/the-garbage-pail-kids-movie-19217 |title=The Garbage Pail Kids Movie > Overview |publisher=[[AllMovie]] |accessdate=6 Jun 2010}}</ref> The shortened release contributed to the movie's poor gross of only $1,576,615.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=garbagepailkids.htm |title=The Garbage Pail Kids Movie (1987) \u2013 Box Office Mojo |work=Boxofficemojo.com |accessdate=7 March 2011}}</ref> It was nominated for three Razzies at the [[8th Golden Raspberry Awards]]: Worst Visual Effects, Worst New Star for the Garbage Pail Kids collectively, and Worst Original Song.<!-- Doug Walker (\"The Nostalgia Critic\") is a comedian, not a movie critic. Please do NOT use his views. -->\n\n=== ''Leonard Part 6'' (1987) ===\n[[File:Bill cosby 1969.JPG|thumb|upright|[[Bill Cosby]] became the first person to [[List of people who have accepted Golden Raspberry Awards|accept a Golden Raspberry Award]] for ''[[Leonard Part 6]]'', which he said was the worst movie ever made]]\n''[[Leonard Part 6]]'', starring (as well as written and produced by) [[Bill Cosby]], was intended as a parody of spy movies. Leonard Parker, a former [[Central Intelligence Agency|CIA]] spy, is brought out of retirement to save the world from an evil vegetarian who brainwashes animals to kill people. Rita Kempley at ''[[The Washington Post]]'' noted the large number of Coca-Cola product placements and said \"The only good thing about Bill Cosby's ''Leonard Part 6'' is that we didn't have to see Parts 1 through 5.\"<ref name=\"wprk\">{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/style/longterm/movies/videos/leonardpart6pgkempley_a0ca2f.htm|title=Leonard Part 6 (PG)|last=Kempley|first=Rita|date=December 19, 1987|work=Washington Post|accessdate=27 June 2012}}</ref> Scott Weinberg at DVD Talk noted the film as \"truly one of the worst movies you'll ever see ... movies this bad should be handled with Teflon gloves and a pair of tongs\".<ref name=\"weinberglp6\">{{cite web|url=https://www.dvdtalk.com/reviews/15632/leonard-part-6/|title=Leonard Part 6|last=Weinberg|first=Scott|date=April 26, 2005|work=DVD Talk|accessdate=27 June 2012}}</ref> By 1990, Dennis King of ''[[Tulsa World]]'' wrote that the film had \"become synonymous with 'bomb.'\"<ref>{{cite news|last=King|first=Dennis|title=Ghost Dad|date=July 6, 1990|newspaper=[[Tulsa World]]|url=http://www.tulsaworld.com/archives/ghost-dad/article_5b0372e5-e91b-5570-b2c7-c9edabbfae0a.html|accessdate=January 27, 2019}}</ref> ''Total Film'' included ''Leonard Part 6'' on their list of the \"66 Worst Films of all Time\".<ref name=TotalFilm/> Cosby himself disowned the film, and when it was released to theaters he publicly advised people not to see it. It earned [[Golden Raspberry]]s for Worst Actor (Cosby), Worst Picture, and Worst Screenplay. It was also nominated for two more Razzie Awards, for Worst Supporting Actress and Worst Director.<ref name=LATimes>{{cite news|title= Leonard RIP?|newspaper= [[The Los Angeles Times]]|date=1987-12-20|url= https://articles.latimes.com/1987-12-20/entertainment/ca-29856_1_leonard-part|accessdate=2010-12-26|first=Pat H.|last=Broeske}}</ref> Cosby became the first person to [[List of people who have accepted Golden Raspberry Awards|accept a Golden Raspberry Award]],<ref name=\"feran\">{{Cite news | last = Feran | first = Tim | title = Section: Features - Accent & Arts - Intermission | newspaper = [[Columbus Dispatch]] | location = [[Columbus, Ohio]] | page = 01F | publisher = The Dispatch Printing Co. | date = April 26, 1992}}</ref> and said \"It was the worst movie I ever made - the worst movie anyone ever made\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Stars take critics with a grain of salt |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=waFEAAAAIBAJ&sjid=6bUMAAAAIBAJ&pg=1013,2816922&dq=leonard+part+6+worst+ever&hl=en |newspaper=[[The Daily Union]] |date=May 12, 1991 |accessdate=April 1, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Hobgoblins'' (1988) ===\n\n''[[Hobgoblins (film)|Hobgoblins]]'', by [[Rick Sloane]], is widely considered a low-budget [[Mockbuster|knock-off]] that capitalizes on the popularity of the 1984 film ''[[Gremlins]].''<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://brokehorrorfan.com/post/152859915403/blu-ray-review-hobgoblins|title=Blu-ray Review: Hobgoblins|last=DiVincenzo|first=Alex|date=|website=Broke Horror Fan|language=en|access-date=April 16, 2019}}</ref> It gained popularity in 1998 after being featured on an episode of ''[[Mystery Science Theater 3000]]''. ''MST3K'' writer [[Paul Chaplin]] later commented on ''Hobgoblins'', saying, \"Oh, man. You have no idea the torture it was to watch this movie several times in the space of a week. It shoots right to the top of the list of the worst movies we've ever done.\" Specific points of the film that were lampooned was the extreme misogyny and atrocious treatment of women, the film's technical incompetence and repetitive scenes, its moronic, very poorly conceived plot, its dreadful acting, its ugly look and its preference towards rather needless vulgarity, particularly in regards to its characters and subject matter.<ref>[http://www.castleforrester.com/media/guide/0907.htm] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081013042500/http://www.castleforrester.com/media/guide/0907.htm |date=October 13, 2008 }}</ref> Greg Muskewitz at Efilmcritic.com called it \"[[Jim Henson]]'s worst nightmare\",<ref>{{cite web |url=http://efilmcritic.com/review.php?movie=4694&reviewer=172&highlight=hobgoblins |title=Movie Review \u2013 Hobgoblins |publisher=eFilmCritic |date=1987-06-02 |accessdate=2011-01-17}}</ref> while David Cornelius of DVD Talk stated, \"There's not one aspect of this movie that isn't the Worst Thing Ever.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dvdtalk.com/reviews/38236/mad-monster-rally/ |title=Mad Monster Rally : DVD Talk Review of the DVD Video |work=Dvdtalk.com |accessdate=2014-03-05}}</ref> After seeing the ''MST3K'' episode himself, Sloane was inspired to direct [[Hobgoblins 2|a sequel]], which was released in 2009.\n\n=== ''Mac and Me'' (1988) ===\n\n''[[Mac and Me]]'' is about a young boy in a wheelchair who meets and befriends an alien who has crash-landed on Earth. A box office failure,<ref>{{cite news|title=Advertising is so much a part of life that it's understandable to find familiar products in films. But sometimes it goes too far.|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=August 29, 1999|url=https://articles.latimes.com/1999/aug/29/entertainment/ca-4591/3|access-date=May 17, 2012}}</ref> the film grossed $6,424,112 in the United States<ref>{{mojo title|macandme|Mac and Me}}</ref> on a $13 million budget.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://catalog.afi.com/Catalog/MovieDetails/58827|title=Mac and Me|website=[[AFI Catalog of Feature Films]]|access-date=April 27, 2018}}</ref> It has a [[List of films with a 0% rating on Rotten Tomatoes|0% rating]] on [[Rotten Tomatoes]], whose critical consensus notes that it is \"duly infamous\" as both an imitation of ''[[E.T. the Extra-Terrestrial]]'' (1982), and a marketing vehicle for [[McDonald's]] and [[Coca-Cola]]<ref name=\"rottentomatoes1\">{{rotten-tomatoes|id=mac_and_me|title=Mac and Me}}</ref> (the filmmakers had admitted a profit-sharing arrangement with the former).<ref>{{cite news|title= Movie Review Mac and Me Takes a Big McBite Out of E.T.|newspaper=[[The Los Angeles Times]]|url= https://articles.latimes.com/1988-08-15/entertainment/ca-300_1_big-mac|accessdate=2010-12-05}}</ref> One scene features a large, impromptu dance-off with the alien (dressed in a teddy bear costume), a football team, [[Ronald McDonald]], and various other people inside and outside of a McDonald's restaurant. [[Leonard Maltin]] described the film as being \"more like a TV commercial than a movie\",<ref name=\"Maltin01211\"/> and Marjorie Baumgarten of the ''[[Austin Chronicle]]'' called it a \"shameless ''E.T.'' knockoff\".<ref name=\"rottentomatoes1\"/> ''Mac and Me'' is widely regarded as one of the worst films ever made,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://screenrant.com/movies-with-bizarre-weird-source-material/|title=15 Movies With Bizarre Source Material|last=McGranaghan|first=Mike|date=March 21, 2017|website=[[Screen Rant]]|access-date=June 23, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://movieweb.com/mac-and-me-movie-alternate-ending-video/|title=Alternate Mac and Me Ending Unearthed and It's Insane|last=Millican|first=Josh|date=August 8, 2018|work=[[MovieWeb]]|access-date=December 15, 2018}}</ref> with ''[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]'' reporting that it is \"frequently pulled out in 'worst film of all time' arguments\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/films/2016/07/18/top-aliens-in-the-movies/mac-and-me/|title=Top 20 aliens in the movies|date=December 19, 2017|website=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]|access-date=April 27, 2018}}</ref> Filmmaker [[Morgan Spurlock]] (responsible for the 2004 Oscar-nominated ''[[Super Size Me]]'') declared it the \"worst thing you'll ever see in your entire life\", as well as the most egregious example of [[product placement]] in cinema history.<ref name=\"crow\">{{cite news|url=https://movies.yahoo.com/blogs/movie-talk/morgan-spurlock-dubs-mac-worst-movie-ever-sold-060910653.html|date=April 22, 2011|last=Crow|first=Jonathan|work=[[Yahoo! Movies]]|accessdate=August 29, 2013|title=Morgan Spurlock Dubs 'Mac and Me' the Worst Film Ever Sold|url-status=bot: unknown|archiveurl=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20130829025758/https://movies.yahoo.com/blogs/movie-talk/morgan-spurlock-dubs-mac-worst-movie-ever-sold-060910653.html|archivedate=August 29, 2013}}</ref> The film was also named the worst ever in the ''[[San Francisco Chronicle]]'',<ref>{{cite journal|date=January 22, 2017|title=Mac and Me|journal=[[San Francisco Chronicle]]|publisher=[[Hearst Communications]]|quote=McDonald's created an 'E.T.' rip-off called 'Mac and Me' in 1988... It's the worst movie ever made.}}</ref> as well as by broadcaster [[Simon Mayo]]<ref name=\"mayo\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p03slrls|title=Paul Rudd and Chris Evans interviewed by Simon Mayo|date=April 29, 2016|publisher=[[BBC Radio 5 Live]]|access-date=April 27, 2018|time=10 minutes|quote=''Mac and Me''... we're talking about the worst film ever made.}}</ref> and writer/producer [[Damon Lindelof]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gq.com/story/damon-lindelof-paul-alien-comedy|title=Damon Lindelof's Open Letter to Paul the Alien|last=Lindelof|first=Damon|authorlink=Damon Lindelof|date=March 14, 2011|website=[[GQ]]|access-date=April 27, 2018}}</ref> Michael Hayden of ''[[GQ (Indian edition)|GQ India]]'' referred to it as \"hands down the worst family movie in Hollywood history\".<ref name=\"gqindia\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gqindia.com/content/6-best-bad-films/#s-cust0|title=The 6 best bad films|last=Hayden|first=Michael|date=November 10, 2011|website=[[GQ (Indian edition)|GQ India]]|access-date=May 11, 2018}}</ref> The film was nominated for four Razzie Awards including Worst Picture and Worst Screenplay, and won two trophies: Worst Director for [[Stewart Raffill]] (tied with [[Blake Edwards]] for ''[[Sunset (1988 film)|Sunset]]'') and Worst New Star for Ronald McDonald in a cameo. ''Mac and Me'' has however [[Mac and Me#Legacy|gained a cult following]] and was featured on the second season of the ''[[Mystery Science Theater 3000]]'' revival (the only Razzie-winning film ever to be riffed in the history of the show).<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thrillist.com/entertainment/nation/mcdonalds-mac-and-me-paul-rudd-movie-et-spinoff|title=How McDonald's Bizarre 'E.T.' Knockoff Got Made|last=Patches|first=Matt|date=2017-04-03|publisher=[[Thrillist]]|access-date=2017-12-11}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://nerdist.com/mac-and-me-bottleneck-gallery-figure-pins/|title=Mac and Me Finally (?) Gets Figure and Pin Collection|last=McNally|first=Victoria|date=April 24, 2017|publisher=[[Nerdist Industries|Nerdist]]|access-date=May 11, 2018}}</ref><ref>[https://uproxx.com/tv/mystery-science-theater-3000-mac-and-me-season-2/ \u2018Mystery Science Theater 3000\u2019 Will Tackle \u2018Mac And Me\u2019 In Season 2 - UPROXX]</ref>\n\n=== ''Things'' (1989) ===\n\n''Things'', a Canadian [[low budget]], [[independent film|independent]], horror [[exploitation film]], was written and produced by Andrew Jordan & Barry J. Gillis. It cost approximately $35,000 in total to make<ref name=\"CANUX\">{{cite web |url=http://www.canuxploitation.com/review/things.html|title=''Things'' review |publisher=Canuxploitation|accessdate=}}</ref> and marked the [[mainstream]] film debut of [[porn star]] [[Amber Lynn]]. It was ostensibly made as [[Homage (arts)|homage]] to horror icons and films, such as [[George A. Romero]] and his ''[[Night of the Living Dead]]''.<ref name=\"CO1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.critcononline.com/films_on_the_fringe.htm|title=Films on the Fringe: Things (1989)|publisher=Critic Online|accessdate=June 7, 2009}}</ref> ''[[Cinema Sewer]]'' magazine has repeatedly proclaimed that \"this is the worst movie ever made\".<ref name=sew>[http://www.cinemasewer.com/?p=35 \"''Things'' on DVD!!\"], ''[[Cinema Sewer]]'', 12 September 2008</ref> Robin Bougie, its founder and editor, wrote \"I don't mean [\"bad\"] like the way [[Troma Entertainment|Troma]] makes bad movies. I'm talking about bad with the best of intentions, like all of the best \"bad\" movies. You like tormenting yourself with hilariously trashy, moronic, gory, ''idiotic'' bad films? ''Things'' is the fucking ''king'' of bad movies. This is the movie you put on when you have a get together of pals \u2014 and just blow them away. Trust me, you have never seen anything like this in your life. It's absolutely astonishing in how it is able to ''mentally wreck'' anyone who watches it.\"<ref name=sew/> Jeff Kirschner of [[Dread Central]] has also named it the worst movie ever made.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://dreadcentral.com/news/142337/things-worst-movie-ever-made/|title=Things: The Worst Movie Ever Made|author=Jeff Kirschner|date=December 10, 2015|publisher=[[Dread Central]]|accessdate=March 21, 2016}}</ref> ''Things'' was covered in an episode of [[RedLetterMedia]] show ''Half in the Bag''; during the discussion Jay Bauman stated that ''Things'' was \"probably one of the worst movies ever made\", to which Mike Stoklasa replied \"I would remove 'probably'.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://redlettermedia.com/half-in-the-bag-the-conjuring-only-god-forgives-blue-jasmine-and-things/|title=Half in the Bag: The Conjuring, Only God Forgives, Blue Jasmine, and THINGS|date=October 7, 2013|publisher=[[RedLetterMedia]]|accessdate=March 15, 2014}}</ref>\n\n== 1990s ==\n\n=== ''Troll 2'' (1990) ===\n\nDespite its title, ''[[Troll 2]]'' does not feature any trolls (the antagonists are actually goblins) and has no relation to the [[Troll (film)|original film]], which was also poorly reviewed.<ref>Janet Maslin, ''The New York Times'', January 17, 1986; Patricia Smith, ''The Chicago Sun-Times'', January 20, 1986; Alan Carter, ''The New York Daily News'', January 17, 1986; Rex Reed, January 17, 1986</ref> Released in relative obscurity, it was re-taken by the public in later years. [[NPR]] claims that it is \"known as the worst movie of all time\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=105420828 |title=The Beauty Of The 'Best Worst Movie' |work=NPR |accessdate=2009-06-15}}</ref> while ''[[The A.V. Club]]'' calls it \"a popular candidate for the worst film ever made\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://avclub.com/article/ibest-worst-movie-iuncovers-the-heartbreaking-psyc-95807 |title=Best Worst Movie uncovers the heartbreaking psychodrama in a memorably insane B-movie |work=The A.V. Club |accessdate=2013-03-29}}</ref> Rumsey Taylor of ''[[Not Coming to a Theater Near You]]'' opined that it was \"one of the worst films I've ever seen\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.notcoming.com/reviews/troll2/ |title= Troll 2 |work=Not Coming to a Theater Near You |date=2009-03-23}}</ref> Ken Hanke of ''[[Mountain Xpress]]'' gave it one-half star out of five, and stated in his review, \"There are movies that are bad. There are movies that are so-bad-they're-good. And then there's ''Troll 2''\u2014a movie that's so bad that it defies comprehension.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mountainx.com/movies/review/troll_2 |title=Movie Review: Troll 2 &#124; Mountain Xpress |work=mountainx.com |accessdate=2014-03-05}}</ref> In addition, ''[[TV Guide]]'' proclaimed that \"''Troll 2'' is really as bad as they come.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tvguide.com/movies/troll-2/review/129231 |title=Troll 2 Review |work=Tvguide.com |accessdate=2014-03-05}}</ref> Nearly twenty years after its release, the movie's child star, Michael Stephenson, made a documentary about its production and fanbase titled ''[[Best Worst Movie]]'', released to critical success in 2009.\n\n=== ''Highlander 2: The Quickening'' (1991) ===\n\nThe French-British film ''[[Highlander II: The Quickening|Highlander 2: The Quickening]]'' is a sequel to the cult film ''[[Highlander (film)|Highlander]],'' which transitions the [[fantasy]] of the original film into [[science fiction]], and [[retcons]] the mystical warriors of the first film into [[Extraterrestrial life|aliens]]. It was met with harsh criticism by both critics and audiences. Based on 23 reviews collected by [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film holds a [[List of films with a 0% rating on Rotten Tomatoes|0% \"Rotten\" rating]]. Common criticisms included the lack of motivation for the characters, the blatant disregard for established characters and background set forth in the first film (such as the new and seemingly incongruent origin for the Immortals), the massive number of gigantic plot holes, the film's messy, nonsensical story structure, the filmmaker's inability to balance the rather unrelated plots and subplots involved, the unexplained resurrection of Ramirez, and rampantly apparent contradictions in the film's internal logic.<ref>[https://www.ign.com/articles/2000/06/16/highlander-2-renegade-version Highlander 2: Renegade Version-IGN]</ref> Roger Ebert named it the worst film of 1991, stating: \"If there is a planet somewhere whose civilization is based on the worst movies of all time, ''Highlander 2: The Quickening'' deserves a sacred place among their most treasured artifacts.\"<ref>[http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/19911101/REVIEWS/111010305/1023 \"''Highlander II: The Quickening'' review\"], Roger Ebert, ''Chicago Sun-Times'', November 1, 1991</ref> An [[IGN]] review said: \"How bad is this movie? Well, imagine if [[Ed Wood]] were alive today, and someone gave him a multi-million dollar budget. See his imagination running rampant, bringing in aliens from outer space with immensely powerful firearms, immortals who bring each other back to life by calling out their names, epic duels on flying skateboards, and a blatant disregard for anything logical or previously established\u2014now you are starting to get closer to the vision of ''Highlander II''.\"<ref>[http://dvd.ign.com/articles/037/037360p1.html \"Highlander 2: Renegade Version Review\"], IGN, June 16, 2000</ref> \n\nIn 1995, the film's director [[Russell Mulcahy]]<ref>[https://mubi.com/films/highlander-ii-the-quickening Highlander II: The Quickening (1991)-MUBI]</ref>\nmade a [[director's cut]] version known as ''Highlander 2: Renegade Version'' and then later released another version simply known as ''Highlander 2: The Special Edition'' for its 2004 DVD release. The film was reconstructed on both occasions largely from existing material, with certain scenes removed and others added back in, and the entire sequence of events changed. The reconstructed film's reception was far better than the original's; it was elevated to a mixed reception.<ref>{{cite web| url = https://joblo.com/horror-movies/news/highlander-ii-there-can-be-only-four-cuts---part-2| title = Highlander II: There can be only four cuts!| work = JoBlo Movie Network| accessdate = 2013-03-16}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Cattive ragazze (Bad Girls)'' (1992) ===\n\nThe [[Italian language|Italian]] erotic thriller ''[[Cattive ragazze]] (Bad Girls)'' was directed by gossip columnist [[Marina Ripa di Meana]], and stars [[Eva Grimaldi]] as a recently divorced woman falling in love with a male stripper, alongside a cast of big names such as [[Anita Ekberg]] and [[Burt Young]]. The production received bad publicity, as it was made using money from the country's [[Ministry of Cultural Heritage and Activities (Italy)|Ministry of Cultural Heritage and Activities]]. Paolo Mereghetti in his film encyclopedia ''Dizionario dei Film'' described the film as a \"vapid mess that can only serve those incapable of understanding what cinema is\", and considered it able to \"compete for the title of worst film in cinema history and win!\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.mymovies.it/dizionario/recensione.asp?id=4831 | title=Cattive ragazze MYMovies \u2013 Morandini |journal=MyMovies |giorno= |year= |access-date=2014-07-29}}</ref> G. Giraud wrote in ''Il Lavoro'' that ''Cattive ragazze'' \"does not resemble anything in a real movie, or even recall anything previously seen at the cinema, even in its worst\". Film critic Marco Giusti refers to it as \"one of the pillars of Italian trash cinema\".<ref name=stracult>{{cite book|last=Marco Giusti|title=Dizionario dei film italiani stracult|year=1999|publisher=Sperling & Kupfer|isbn=8820029197}}</ref> While ''Cattive ragazze'' was Ripa Di Meana's directorial debut, she never made another film.<ref>{{cite web |title=Marina Ripa di Meana filmography |work=imdb.com |url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0224079/ |accessdate=2014-07-29}}</ref>\n\n=== ''North'' (1994) ===\nThe [[Rob Reiner]] film ''[[North (1994 film)|North]]'' is an adaptation of the novel ''North: The Tale of a 9-Year-Old Boy Who Becomes a Free Agent and Travels the World in Search of the Perfect Parents'' by [[Alan Zweibel]], who also wrote the screenplay and has a minor role in the film. ''North'', which was also [[Scarlett Johansson]]'s film debut, was a critical and commercial failure, earning only $7,138,449 worldwide despite its budget of over $40 million. It was widely criticized for its plot, its all-star cast of insensitive characters, lack of humor and portrayal of numerous ethnic stereotypes. It has a 14% approval rating at [[Rotten Tomatoes]].<ref>{{cite web |title=North Movie Reviews, Pictures \u2013 Rotten Tomatoes |work=Rottentomatoes.com |url=https://rottentomatoes.com/m/north/ |accessdate=2011-03-07}}</ref> Roger Ebert gave it zero stars and, in his review, infamously wrote \"I hated this movie. Hated, hated, hated, hated, ''hated'' this movie. Hated it. Hated every simpering stupid vacant audience-insulting moment of it. Hated the sensibility that thought anyone would like it. Hated the implied insult to the audience by its belief that anyone would be entertained by it.\" He continued saying \"''North'' is a bad film \u2013 one of the worst movies ever made\",<ref>{{cite news| url=http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/19940722/REVIEWS/407220302/1023 | work=Chicago Sun-Times | title=North | date=1994-07-22}}</ref> and it is also on his list of most hated films.<ref name=\"eberthated\"/> Both Ebert and [[Gene Siskel]] named ''North'' as the worst film of 1994.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Official Site of Gene Siskel |work=Cmgww.com |url=http://www.cmgww.com/stars/siskel/screening_room/thumbs_down.htm |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090226070236/http://www.cmgww.com/stars/siskel/screening_room/thumbs_down.htm |url-status=dead |archive-date=2009-02-26 |accessdate=2011-03-07 }}</ref> Mick LaSalle of the ''San Francisco Chronicle'' said in his review that \"''North'' is director Rob Reiner's first flat-out failure, a sincerely wrought, energetically made picture that all the same crashes on takeoff. It's strange and oddly distasteful, at its best managing to be bad in some original and unexpected ways.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/1995/01/06/dd59113.dtl |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20031113141403/http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=%2Fc%2Fa%2F1995%2F01%2F06%2Fdd59113.dtl |url-status=dead |archive-date=2003-11-13 |work=The San Francisco Chronicle |title=Rob Reiner's 'North' Is Distastefully Bad |date=2011-01-08 }}</ref> [[Richard Roeper]] named ''North'' as one of the 40 worst movies he has ever seen, saying that, \"Of all the films on this list, ''North'' may be the most difficult to watch from start to finish.\"<ref name=\"RichardRoeper\" /> The film was nominated for the following awards at the [[15th Golden Raspberry Awards]]: Worst Picture, Worst Actor ([[Bruce Willis]], also for ''[[Color of Night]]''), Worst Supporting Actress ([[Kathy Bates]]), Worst Supporting Actor ([[Dan Aykroyd]], also for ''[[Exit to Eden (film)|Exit to Eden]]''), Worst Director, and Worst Screenplay ([[Andrew Scheinman]] and [[Alan Zweibel]]).\n\n=== ''Dis \u2013 en historie om kj\u00e6rlighet'' (''A Story About Love'') (1995) ===\n\nThe Norwegian [[romantic film]] ''[[A Story About Love|Dis \u2013 en historie om kj\u00e6rlighet]]'' was directed by Aune Sand. The film follows different couples and their love stories around the world, in [[Cairo]], [[Normandy]], [[Oslo]] and [[New York City]]. ''Dis'' received universally poor reviews by critics, and has been called the most poorly reviewed Norwegian film in history.<ref>{{cite news|last=Kristoffersen|first=Marius Vartdal|title=Hva Var I Veien Med Dis?|url=http://znett.com/2011/05/hva-var-i-veien-med-dis/|date=3 May 2011|accessdate=14 July 2014|newspaper=Z Filmtidsskrift|language=Norwegian}}</ref><ref name=\"osloby.no\" /> Critic Harald Kolstad of ''[[Dagsavisen]]'' gave it a score of zero, refused to acknowledge ''Dis'' as a film, and claimed to have never seen anything worse.<ref>{{cite news|last=Pedersen |first=Brent Erik |title=Hedrer Dagsavisens kritiker |url=http://www.dagsavisen.no/kultur/hedrer-dagsavisens-kritiker/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140617125554/http://www.dagsavisen.no/kultur/hedrer-dagsavisens-kritiker/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=17 June 2014 |accessdate=14 July 2014 |newspaper=Dagsavisen |language=Norwegian }}</ref> ''[[Aftenposten]]'' referred to the film as \"the largest turkey\" and \"the most reviled film\",<ref name=\"osloby.no\">{{cite news|title=Norges st\u00f8rste kalkun flyr igjen|url=http://www.osloby.no/article199599_2.ece|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120814005215/http://www.osloby.no/article199599_2.ece|url-status=dead|archive-date=14 August 2012|date=28 June 2012|accessdate=14 July 2014|newspaper=Aftenposten|language=Norwegian}}</ref> and ''[[Total Film]]'' included it on its list of the 66 worst films ever made.<ref name=\"TotalFilm\" /> Despite being a critical disaster it became a commercial success, gaining [[cult film]] status with a following akin to ''[[The Rocky Horror Picture Show]]'', with fans embracing its \"so bad it's good\" qualities.<ref name=\"osloby.no\" /> Director Aune Sand insists that ''Dis'' is a masterpiece.<ref>{{cite news|title= Slakter norsk film|url=http://www.dagbladet.no/kultur/2005/07/20/437937.html|accessdate=14 July 2014|newspaper=Dagbladet|language=Norwegian}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Showgirls'' (1995) ===\n[[File:SHOWGIRLS.png|thumb|''[[Showgirls]]'' holds the record for number of [[Golden Raspberry Award]] nominations]]\nA large amount of hype of ''[[Showgirls]]'' was put behind promoting the sex and nudity in this [[Motion Picture Association of America film rating system#Commercial viability of the NC-17 rating|NC-17]] French-American film with a $45 million budget, but the final result was critically derided. Most of the hype revolved around the film's star, [[Elizabeth Berkley]], who only two years before had been one of the stars of the Saturday morning teen [[situation comedy|sitcom]] ''[[Saved by the Bell]]''. The film won seven [[Golden Raspberry Award|Razzie Awards]], a record at that time, and received 13 nominations, a record that still stands. It received an additional award at the [[20th Golden Raspberry Awards]], where it was awarded Worst Picture of the Decade. Kenneth Turan of the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' called it, \"a film of thunderous oafishness that gives adult subject matter the kind of bad name it does not need or deserve\",<ref>{{cite web|url=https://rottentomatoes.com/m/showgirls/reviews/#page=2&sort=source |title=Showgirls \u2013 Movie Reviews |website=Rotten Tomatoes |accessdate=2014-03-05}}</ref> while Rob Gonsalves of eFilmCritic.com stated, \"Even the grossest porn is more cheerfully sexual than this movie.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.efilmcritic.com/review.php?movie=1247&reviewer=416 |title=Movie Review \u2013 Showgirls |publisher=eFilmCritic |accessdate=2013-11-18}}</ref> Michael Dequina of TheMovieReport.com also criticized the film, claiming that it was \"the best bad filmmaking Hollywood has to offer\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://themoviereport.com/movierpt1.html#showgirls |title=The Movie Report Archive, Volume 1 |work=TheMovieReport.com |accessdate=2013-11-18}}</ref> Stephen Lynch of the ''[[Knight Ridder|Knight Ridder/Tribune]]'' named it the worst movie ever made, calling it \"so bad it may be brilliant\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Critic picks worst movies of all time |author=Stephen Lynch|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=398&dat=20011003&id=oGhOAAAAIBAJ&sjid=vj4DAAAAIBAJ&pg=6912,5443994|newspaper=Bartow Press |date=October 3, 2001 |accessdate=12 June 2014}}</ref> [[Rotten Tomatoes]] selected it as one of 25 movies that are so bad they're unmissable while ''[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]'' featured it on its poll of the worst films ever made.<ref name=\"sobad\"/><ref name=\"The 50 Worst Movies Ever\"/> ''Showgirls'' was also featured in Michael Sauter's ''The Worst Movies of All Time'' book as well as ''[[The Official Razzie Movie Guide: Enjoying the Best of Hollywood's Worst]]''. The edited R-rated version, which director [[Paul Verhoeven]] developed for video outlets that would not carry NC-17 films, deletes about three minutes of the more graphic sex scenes. [[TBS (TV network)|TBS]] has broadcast the film on television in its prime time schedule, but this version adds digitally animated solid black underwear to hide breasts and genitalia. This version has also been broadcast by [[VH1]] as part of its ''Movies That Rock'' series. It holds a 22% rating on [[Rotten Tomatoes]] based on 54 reviews.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://rottentomatoes.com/m/showgirls/ |title=Showgirls |website=Rotten Tomatoes |accessdate=2019-07-06}}</ref> Despite a negative theatrical and critical consensus, ''Showgirls'' enjoyed much bigger success on the [[home video]] market, generated more than $100 million from home video market and became one of [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer|MGM]]'s top 20 all-time bestsellers.<ref>[http://www.rollingstone.com/culture/culture-news/showgirls-paul-verhoeven-on-the-greatest-stripper-movie-ever-made-54740/\u2018Showgirls\u2019: Paul Verhoeven on the Greatest Stripper Movie Ever Made-Rolling Stone]</ref>\n\n=== ''Striptease'' (1996) ===\n\nA comedy-drama directed by [[Andrew Bergman]], based on a [[Strip Tease (novel)|novel]] by [[Carl Hiaasen]], ''[[Striptease (film)|Striptease]]'' centers on a woman ([[Demi Moore]]) who becomes a stripper in order to fund an appeal for custody of her daughter. The film was criticized as boring and humourless, and was also accused of being a vanity project for Moore.<ref name=\"bdj\">Brian D. Johnson, \"A Demi-talented actor bares all\", ''[[Maclean's]]'' 7/08/96, Vol. 109 Issue 28, page 49.</ref> Daniel P. Franklin, discussing ''Striptease'' in his book ''Politics and Film: The Political Culture of Film in the United States'' stated \"This is the worst film ever made.\"<ref>Daniel P. Franklin, ''Politics and Film: The Political Culture of Film in the United States''. Lanham, [[Rowman & Littlefield|Rowman and Littlefield]], 2006, {{ISBN|0742538095}}, (p. 203).</ref> [[Joe Queenan (author)|Joe Queenan]] cited ''Striptease'' as an example of what he considered the poor quality of contemporary Hollywood cinema: \"One thing that I admire about films like ''Striptease'' is that they serve as powerful reminders that on any given day, Hollywood has the potential to release the worst film in history.\"<ref>Joe Queenan, ''Red Lobster, White Trash, and the Blue Lagoon: Joe Queenan's America'' Hyperion Books, 1999 {{ISBN|0786884088}}, (p.50 )</ref> [[Richard Schickel]] in ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'', also criticized the film: \"Bergman ... misses Hiaasen's strength: setting mean-funny characters spinning through lowlife milieus ... the crazy, nothing-to-lose anarchy of people living below the margin and beyond the fringe is not within Bergman's fastidious reach.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Schickel|first=Richard|title=Cinema: Only the Bare Essentials \"Striptease isn't raunchy, but it isn't witty either|url=http://content.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,984828,00.html|date=July 8, 1996|work=Time Magazine|accessdate=June 9, 2014}}</ref> [[Leonard Maltin]] stated that ''Striptease'' was \"Not funny enough, or dramatic enough, or sexy enough, or bad enough, to qualify as entertainment in ''any'' category.\"<ref>Leonard Maltin, ed., ''Leonard Maltin's 2002 Movie & Video Guide''. A Signet Book, 2001, page 1323.</ref> Brian D. Johnson of ''[[Maclean's]]'' stated \"While ''[[Showgirls]]'' was honestly sleazy, ''Striptease'' is tacky, pretentious \u2013 and boring. Trying to be a comedy, a morality tale and a titillating sideshow, ''Striptease'' fails on all counts.\"<ref name=\"bdj\" /> ''Striptease'' was awarded six [[1996 Golden Raspberry Awards|Golden Raspberry]] awards, for Worst Picture, Worst Director, Worst Screenplay, Worst Actress (Moore), Worst Original Song (\"(Pussy Pussy Pussy) Whose Kitty Cat Are You?\"), and Worst Screen Couple (Moore and [[Burt Reynolds]]).<ref>\"Moore, ''Striptease'' get blasted with Razzie for Worst Picture, 5 others\". ''[[Milwaukee Journal Sentinel]]'', March 24, 1997, (p. 66).</ref>\n\n=== ''Le Jour et la Nuit'' (''Day and Night'') (1997) ===\n\nThe French [[romance film]] ''[[Day and Night (1997 film)|Le Jour et la Nuit]]'' was directed by philosopher [[Bernard-Henri L\u00e9vy]]. It follows a French author who fled to Mexico for a quiet life and an actress who is willing to seduce him to get a part in a film adapted from one of his books. Before its release, ''Le Jour et la Nuit'' was heavily promoted in many French newspapers and magazines.<ref name=\"ti\">Jade Lindgaard and Xavier De La Porte, ''The Imposter: BHL in Wonderland'' (Translated by John Howe) London; Verso, 2012. {{ISBN|978-1-84467-748-1}} (p. 48-9).</ref> When the film premiered at the [[Berlin International Film Festival]] in 1997, hundreds of journalists walked out of the screening and those that stayed audibly ridiculed it.<ref name=Plato>{{cite news |last=Dahlburg |first=John-Thor |title=The Film That Plato Didn't Make |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |date=March 28, 1997 |url=https://articles.latimes.com/1997-03-28/entertainment/ca-42798_1_european-film |accessdate=2013-10-14}}</ref> Following its release, ''Le Jour et la Nuit'' was very harshly criticized by the French media. G\u00e9rard Lefort of ''[[Lib\u00e9ration]]'' described the film as \"BHL pedalling through guacamole\", and it was also panned by ''[[Le Monde]]'' and ''[[Le Nouvel Observateur]]''.<ref name=\"ti\" /> The film also did poorly commercially, with only 73,147 seats for ''Le Jour et la Nuit'' having been sold two months after its release.<ref name=\"ti\" /> ''Le Jour et la Nuit'' was considered the worst French film since 1945 by film magazine ''[[Cahiers du cin\u00e9ma]]'', and considered as a possible \"worst film in history\" by the French version of ''[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.slate.fr/story/27925/pire-film-du-monde-bhl-concurrence |title=\"Le Jour et la Nuit\", pire film de l'histoire ... Vraiment? |publisher=Slate.fr |accessdate=2013-12-19}}</ref> ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' said the film was {{nowrap|\"[l]augh}}-out-loud awful without touching the cult realm of 'so bad it's good{{'\"}}, [[Fran\u00e7oise Giroud]] stated that {{nowrap|\"[i]t's}} a bad movie, there's no question\",<ref name=Plato/> and ''[[L'Humanit\u00e9]]'' called it an \"Absolute debacle\".<ref>{{cite news |title=The volcano a molehill |newspaper=[[L'Humanit\u00e9]] |date=February 19, 1997 |url=https://www.humanite.fr/node/154931 |accessdate=2013-10-14}}</ref> An original documentary, ''Anatomy of a Massacre'', was released with the ''Le Jour et la Nuit'' DVD, and focused on its intense negative reception and failure.<ref>{{cite news |title=BHL et la critique cin\u00e9, c'\u00e9tait le jour et la nuit |newspaper=[[20 minutes (France)]] |date=October 11, 2010 |url=http://www.20minutes.fr/medias/607145-media-bhl-critique-cine-jour-nuit |accessdate=2013-10-14}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Batman & Robin'' (1997) ===\n[[File:Btrjpg.jpg|thumb|''[[Batman & Robin (film)|Batman & Robin]]'' was named the worst movie ever made by ''[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]'']]\n''[[Batman & Robin (film)|Batman & Robin]]'' is a [[superhero film]] based on the [[DC Comics|DC]] character [[Batman]] and is the fourth and final installment of the [[Burton/Schumacher Batman film series]]. It is directed by [[Joel Schumacher]] and stars [[George Clooney]] as [[Batman]]/[[Bruce Wayne]], [[Arnold Schwarzenegger]] as [[Mr. Freeze]], [[Uma Thurman]] as [[Poison Ivy (comics)|Poison Ivy]], [[Chris O'Donnell]] as [[Robin (comics)|Robin]]/[[Dick Grayson]], [[Alicia Silverstone]] as [[Batgirl]]/[[Barbara Gordon|Barbara Wilson]] and [[Michael Gough]] as [[Alfred Pennyworth]]. This film was largely criticized for its [[toyetic]] and [[camp (style)|camp]] approach, Mr. Freeze's approach and [[one-line joke]]s, as well as its possible homosexual innuendo. {{as of|2017|June|}}, [[review aggregator]] [[Rotten Tomatoes]] reports that 11% of critics have given the film a positive review based on 89 reviews, certifying it \"Rotten\" with an average rating of 3.7/10, and the critics consensus: \"Joel Schumacher's tongue-in-cheek attitude hits an unbearable limit in ''Batman & Robin'', resulting in a frantic and mindless movie that's too jokey to care much for.\"<ref>{{cite web | url = https://rottentomatoes.com/m/1077027-batman_and_robin/ | title = Batman & Robin | website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] | accessdate = 2019-07-06}}</ref> By comparison [[Metacritic]] collected an average score of 28/100, based on 21 reviews.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://metacritic.com/movie/batman-robin | title = Batman & Robin (1997): Reviews | work=[[Metacritic]] | publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=2010-04-17}}</ref> ''[[International Business Times]]'' included it on its list of Hollywood's top five worst movies ever made.<ref name=\"IBT\"/> [[Michael J. Nelson]], of ''Mystery Science Theater 3000'' fame, wrote of the movie in his book, ''Movie Megacheese'', \"''Batman & Robin'' is not the worst movie ever. No, indeed. It's the worst thing ever. Yes, it's the single worst thing that we as human beings have ever produced in recorded history.\"<ref>{{Cite book | url = https://archive.org/details/mikenelsonsmovie00nels | url-access = registration | page = [https://archive.org/details/mikenelsonsmovie00nels/page/79 79] | title = Mike Nelson's Movie Megacheese | publisher = Harper Collins | isbn = 978-0-380-81467-1 | last1 = Nelson | first1 = Michael J | date = 2000-06-20}}</ref> ''Batman & Robin'' also came in first in an ''[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]'' poll of the 50 worst films ever.<ref name=\"The 50 Worst Movies Ever\"/> Joel Schumacher apologized to disappointed fans on the 2005 DVD release of ''Batman & Robin''.<ref>{{cite AV media | people = Joel Schmacher | title = \"Making of\" Introduction | medium = DVD | publisher = Warner Bros. | year = 2005 }}</ref>\n\n=== ''The Avengers'' (1998) ===\nAn adaptation of the popular 1960s [[The Avengers (TV series)|British series]] of the same name, ''[[The Avengers (1998 film)|The Avengers]]'' starred [[Ralph Fiennes]] as John Steed and [[Uma Thurman]] as [[Emma Peel]], with [[Sean Connery]] as their antagonist, Sir August de Wynter. It was directed by [[Jeremiah S. Chechik]]. ''The Avengers'' began to receive negative publicity after [[Warner Bros.]], the film's distributor, refused to allow any early press-screenings for movie reviewers.<ref>{{cite journal |authorlink=Godfrey Cheshire III |first=Godfrey |last=Cheshire |url=https://variety.com/review/VE1117913229.html?categoryid=31&cs=1 |title=The Avengers \u2013 Sputtering Spies: Steed and Peel Lack Appeal |journal=Variety |date=August 17, 1998 |accessdate=January 27, 2015 }}</ref> After early test screenings, ''The Avengers'' was heavily edited by the studio.<ref name=NYTreview2>{{cite news |first=Janet |last=Maslin |authorlink=Janet Maslin |url=https://www.nytimes.com/library/film/081598avengers-film-review.html |title='The Avengers': Shh! They're Trying Not to Be Noticed |newspaper=The New York Times |date=August 15, 1998 |accessdate=January 27, 2015 }}</ref> On its release, ''The Avengers'' was savaged by film critics, with the ''[[Birmingham Post]]'' stating \"''The Avengers'' is being slated by critics as the worst film ever made\" and adding that one reviewer had joked the film was such a \"turkey\" that the makers should have handed distribution to the poultry chain [[Bernard Matthews Farms|Bernard Matthews]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Film-''The Avengers'' |newspaper=The Birmingham Post |date=August 19, 1998 }}</ref> Several reviewers disparaged ''The Avengers'' for lacking the wit and excitement of its source material.<ref name=rt2>{{cite journal |url=http://www.radiotimes.com/film/cjykx/the-avengers |title=Review: The Avengers |first=Alan |last=Jones |journal=Radio Times |accessdate=27 January 2015 }}</ref><ref name=\"db\">{{cite news |url=http://www.nydailynews.com/archives/entertainment/not-so-excellent-avengers-insults-old-series-awful-film-debases-tv-inspiration-article-1.807212 |title=Not So Excellent Avengers |first=David |last=Bianculli |newspaper=[[New York Daily News]] |date=August 18, 1998 |accessdate=January 27, 2015 }}</ref> [[Janet Maslin]] strongly criticised ''The Avengers'': \"With pseudo-suave repartee that would make [[Austin Powers (character)|Austin Powers]] blush and with so many shades of ''[[Howard the Duck (film)|Howard the Duck]]'' that one scene depicts man-size pastel teddy bears sitting around a conference table, it's a film to gall fans of the old television series and perplex anyone else. I can't remember another Friday morning show where I heard actual cries of \"Ugh!\" on the way out the door\" and finished her review with, \"At a pared-down, barely rational 100 minutes, ''The Avengers'' is short but not short enough.\"<ref name=NYTreview2 /> David Bianculli said \"This ''Avengers'' film is so horrendously, painfully and thoroughly awful, it gives other cinematic clunkers like ''[[Ishtar (film)|Ishtar]]'' and ''Howard the Duck'' a good name.\"<ref name=\"db\" /> Alan Jones in ''[[The Radio Times]]'' stated \"The cult 1960s TV series gets royally shafted by Hollywood in this stunningly designed blockbuster that's stunningly awful in every other department ... Terrible special effects and zero chemistry between Fiennes and Thurman make this notorious disaster a total waste of everyone's time and energy.\"<ref name=rt2 /> ''The Avengers'' also shared a [[Razzie Award]] for \"Worst Remake or Sequel\" with the 1998 adaptations of ''[[Psycho (1998 film)|Psycho]]'' and ''[[Godzilla (1998 film)|Godzilla]]'' at the [[19th Golden Raspberry Awards]]. ''[[Total Film]]'' magazine later voted Fiennes and Thurman in ''The Avengers'' as \"The Worst Movie Double Act Of All Time\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Double disasters make it to top of the flops |newspaper=[[Western Mail (Wales)|The Western Mail]] |location=Cardiff |date=December 1, 2003 }}</ref> The film also appeared on Metacritic's list of the all-time lowest-scoring films.<ref name=\"Metacritic\"/>\n\n=== ''Cinderela Baiana'' (''Bahian Cinderella'') (1998) ===\n\nThe Brazilian film ''[[Cinderela Baiana]]'' was directed by Conrado Sanchez and stars former [[\u00c9 o Tchan!]] dancer [[Carla Perez]] in the lead role. It is a heavily fictionalized biographical account of Perez's early life and how she came into fame. Despite an all-star cast, including [[Alexandre Pires]], Perez's then-boyfriend and a very popular singer in Brazil at the time, the movie was criticized for its campy dialogue, badly written script, numerous plot holes and ludicrous acting, to the point of Perez herself disowning the film years later.<ref>[http://www.meionorte.com/noticias,--Eu-era-uma-crianca-sem-maldade----diz-dancarina-Carla-Perez-sobre-E-o-Tchan,47976.html \"'Eu era uma crian\u00e7a sem maldade', diz dan\u00e7arina Carla Perez sobre \u00c9 o Tchan!\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080516051117/http://www.meionorte.com/noticias%2C--Eu-era-uma-crianca-sem-maldade----diz-dancarina-Carla-Perez-sobre-E-o-Tchan%2C47976.html |date=2008-05-16 }} \u2013 ''Meio Norte'', May 14, 2008 {{in lang|pt}}</ref> It was a [[box office bomb]], and it was some time later banned from circulation by request of Perez herself. It was also the debut of a then-unknown [[L\u00e1zaro Ramos]], who used his salary to pay for acting classes. On March 15, 2010, Brazilian magazine ''[[Veja (magazine)|Veja]]'' made a Top 10 list of the worst Brazilian movies of all time, and ''Cinderela Baiana'' was featured in first place. The reviewer, Pollyane Lima e Silva, called the film \"a shame\".<ref>[http://veja.abril.com.br/blog/10-mais/cinema/os-10-piores-filmes-da-historia-do-cinema-brasileiro/ Os Piores 10 Filmes da Hist\u00f3ria do Cinema Brasileiro] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160428071504/http://veja.abril.com.br/blog/10-mais/cinema/os-10-piores-filmes-da-historia-do-cinema-brasileiro/ |date=2016-04-28 }}, Pollyane Lima e Silva; ''Veja'', March 15, 2010 {{in lang|pt}}</ref> Author Renzo Mora included it in his ''25 Movies That Can Ruin Your Life'' book, while Luis Nassif claimed that, \"For me this is the worst of all.\"<ref>[http://www.advivo.com.br/comentario/re-o-pior-filme-do-mundo-50 Os 25 Piores Filmes do Mundo], Luis Nassif; ''Avido.com.br'', May 20, 2011 {{in lang|pt}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Fatal Deviation'' (1998) ===\n''[[Fatal Deviation]]'' is often credited as being the first [[martial arts film]] to be filmed in Ireland. It stars martial artist James Bennett and [[Michael Graham (singer)|Michael Graham]], who is best known for being a member of the boy band [[Boyzone]]. ''[[The Irish Post]]'' and ''[[Den of Geek]]'' write that it is a mainstay of worst film lists.<ref name=\"irishpost\"/><ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.denofgeek.com/movies/fatal-deviation/looking-back-at-fatal-deviation-irelands-only-martial-arts-film|title=Meet Fatal Deviation, Ireland's only martial arts film|last=Lines|first=Craig|date=November 4, 2015|accessdate=June 7, 2019|work=[[Den of Geek]]}}</ref> Luke McKinney of [[Cracked.com]] called it the worst film ever made, writing: \"There are so many things about making a movie that Jimmy doesn't know, that you could replace film school with this movie alone--just screening it once for students and asking them to list all the things it did wrong. Anyone who doesn't write 'everything' instantly fails.\"<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.cracked.com/article_18632_irelands-only-kung-fu-movie-is-worst-film-ever-made.html|title=Ireland's Only Kung Fu Movie (Is The Worst Film Ever Made)|last=McKinney|first=Luke|date=July 3, 2010|accessdate=March 9, 2019|work=[[Cracked.com]]}}</ref> ''The Irish Post'' named it the worst Irish film of all time,<ref name=\"irishpost\">{{cite web |url= https://www.irishpost.com/entertainment/definitive-ranking-7-worst-irish-films-time-158594|title= A definitive ranking of the 7 worst Irish films of all-time|first= Aidan|last=Lonergan|date= August 16, 2018|accessdate= March 9, 2019|work= [[The Irish Post]]}}</ref> and the ''[[Irish Independent]]'' wrote that it is \"regarded as one of the worst films ever made\".<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.independent.ie/lifestyle/westlife-what-next-26785226.html|title=Westlife: what next?|date= October 22, 2011|accessdate=March 9, 2019|work=[[Irish Independent]]}}</ref> [[Entertainment.ie]] placed it on its list of \"10 So Bad They're Good Movies You Need To See Before You Die\" and it was covered in ''[[Paste (magazine)|Paste]]''{{'}}s ''Bad Movie Diaries'' column.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://entertainment.ie/cinema/movie-news/10-so-bad-theyre-good-movies-you-need-to-see-before-you-die-227463/|title=10 So Bad They're Good Movies You Need To See Before You Die|last=Lloyd|first=Bryan|accessdate=March 9, 2019|work=[[entertainment.ie]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2018/07/bad-movie-diaries-fatal-deviation-1998.html |title=Bad Movie Diaries: Fatal Deviation (1998)|last1=Vorel|first1=Jim|last2=Lowe|first2=Kenneth|accessdate=June 7, 2019|work=[[Paste (magazine)|Paste]]}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Parting Shots'' (1999) ===\n\nThe British [[black comedy]] ''[[Parting Shots]]'' was the last film directed by [[Michael Winner]]. It starred rock musician [[Chris Rea]] as a man who, told he has only six months to live, begins murdering people who have wronged him. ''Parting Shots'' was accused of being poorly acted, filmed and scripted, as well as treating [[murder]] flippantly.<ref name=\"tookey\">Christopher Tookey, \"Michael Winner's latest film is his most offensive yet.\" ''[[The Daily Mail]]'', May 11, 1999, (p.11).</ref> [[Andrew Collins (broadcaster)|Andrew Collins]] took a very negative view of the film: \"''Parting Shots'' ... is going to set the course of British film-making back 20 years. It is not only the worst British film produced in this country since ''[[Carry On Emmannuelle]]'' (quite a feat in itself), it is a thoroughbred contender for the crown of Worst Film Ever Made.\"<ref>Andrew Collins, \"How to Shoot a Real Turkey\" ''[[The Observer]]'', March 28, 1999. ''Observer Screen'', p.6.</ref> [[Christopher Tookey]] was even more harsh, stating: \"''Parting Shots'' is not only the most horrible torture for audiences that Winner has ever devised. It is also profoundly offensive, even by Winner standards\" and later called ''Parting Shots'' \"the most tasteless, abysmal comedy of all time\".<ref name=\"tookey\"/> Tookey also stated that Winner had \"established himself, over his last dozen films, as beyond doubt the worst director of all time\".<ref name=\"tookey\"/> In an interview about the film, Charlotte O'Sullivan, [[The Independent|the ''Independent'']]'s film editor, claimed ''Parting Shots'' was \"the worst film I've ever seen\". O'Sullivan also criticised it for glorifying vigilantism: \"It's Michael Winner and you know, he doesn't have any sense of irony. He seems to be saying it is okay to go and kill people.\"<ref>\"Winner's Turkey has a bad aftertaste\". ''[[The Sunday Herald]]'', May 2, 1999 (p.7)</ref> The journalist [[Miles Kington]] later claimed \"''Parting Shots'' ... was directed by Michael Winner and despite the glittering cast, was possibly the worst film ever made.\"<ref>Miles Kingston, \"One or two plots to occupy my declining years\". ''[[The Independent]]'', May 3, 2005, (p.30).</ref> I. Q. Hunter listed ''Parting Shots'' as one of the candidates for \"the Worst British film ever made\".<ref name=\"iqh\" /> ''Parting Shots'' was also featured in a poll of ''[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]'' magazine readers' \"50 Worst Movies Ever\" poll.<ref name=\"The 50 Worst Movies Ever\"/>\n\n=== ''The Underground Comedy Movie'' (1999) ===\n\nThe comedy ''[[The Underground Comedy Movie]]'' is based on a [[cable access]] show from 1988. Director and lead actor [[Vince Offer]] constructed the film out of a series of tasteless, [[low culture|lowbrow skits]] (including [[Gena Lee Nolin]] loudly using the restroom and a superhero named ''Dickman'' who dresses in a giant penis costume and defeats his enemies by squirting them with semen). In 1999, Offer filed a suit against [[20th Century Fox]] and the co-directors of ''[[There's Something About Mary]]'', Bobby and Peter Farrelly, claiming that 14 scenes in ''Mary'' were stolen from his film.<ref name=\"ewol\">{{cite magazine|url=https://ew.com/article/1999/06/11/underground-comedy-movie-2/|title=Movie Review Underground Comedy Movie |date=June 11, 1999|accessdate=December 3, 2019|magazine=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|last=Gleiberman|first=Owen}}</ref> The Farrellys released this statement: \"We've never heard of him, we've never heard of his movie, and it's all a bunch of baloney.\"<ref name=\"ewx\">{{cite magazine|url=https://ew.com/article/1998/10/16/monitor-269/|title=Monitor: Celebrity news for October 16, 1998|last=Karger|first=Dave|first2=Suna|last2=Chang|date=October 16, 1998|magazine=Entertainment Weekly|accessdate=December 3, 2019}}</ref> [[Lawrence Van Gelder]] of ''[[The New York Times]]'' referred to it as a \"wretched film\" and stated that \"'The Underground Comedy Movie' stands as a monument to ineptitude and self-delusion.\"<ref name=\"nytvangelder\">{{cite news|url=https://archive.nytimes.com/www.nytimes.com/library/film/052899comedy-film-review.html|title=Lawrence Van Gelder's review of ''The Underground Comedy Movie'' |work=New York Times|date=1999-05-28 |accessdate=2013-12-19}}</ref> [[Rod Dreher]] of the ''[[New York Post]]'' said it \"may be the least amusing comedy ever made\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Dreher|first=Rod|title='Comedy' is Really Buried by Its Trash|work=New York Post|date=May 28, 1999}}</ref> [[Nathan Rabin]] covered the film in his column detailing terrible films and stated that: \"nothing I\u2019ve covered for this column was quite as soul-crushingly, brain-meltingly terrible as ... ''The Underground Comedy Movie''.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nathanrabin.com/happy-place/2018/9/4/this-looks-terrible-the-underground-comedy-movie-1999|title=This Looks Terrible! The Underground Comedy Movie (1999)|last=Rabin|first=Nathan|authorlink=Nathan Rabin|work=www.nathanrabin.com|date=September 4, 2018|accessdate=February 23, 2019}}</ref> Thom Bennett at ''[[Film Journal International]]'', wrote \"Anyone offended by unbearably bad films, jokes that are not funny and wasting 90 minutes of their lives is, as promised, guaranteed to be offended. In fact, to even call this mess a comedy is giving it far too much credit\", and \"''The Underground Comedy Movie'' may well be the worst film I have ever seen.\"<ref name=\"fji\">{{cite web|url=http://www.filmjournal.com/filmjournal/esearch/article_display.jsp?vnu_content_id=1000697847|title=Underground Comedy Movie, The|last=Bennett|first=Thom|work=Film Journal International|accessdate=7 March 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131105184223/http://www.filmjournal.com/filmjournal/esearch/article_display.jsp?vnu_content_id=1000697847|archive-date=5 November 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> Writing in ''[[Central Western Daily]]'', Peter Young said, \" I am pretty sure that I can declare this The Worst Film I Have Ever Seen\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.centralwesterndaily.com.au/story/1386763/comedy-film-best-kept-underground/|title=Comedy film best kept underground|last=Young|first=Peter|work=[[Central Western Daily]]|date=March 26, 2013|accessdate=March 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== 2000s ==\n\n=== ''Battlefield Earth'' (2000) ===\n[[File:John Travolta Battlefield Earth signing.jpg|thumb|[[John Travolta]] during ''[[Battlefield Earth (film)|Battlefield Earth]]'''s pomotional tour]]\n''[[Battlefield Earth (film)|Battlefield Earth]]'' is based on the first half of [[L. Ron Hubbard]]'s [[Battlefield Earth (novel)|novel of the same name]], and stars [[John Travolta]], [[Barry Pepper]] and [[Forest Whitaker]]. Although a sequel covering the second half of the book was planned, the panning from critics, poor box office performance, and financial ruin of [[Franchise Pictures]] killed off such plans. It was criticized for a poor script, hammy acting, overuse of [[Dutch angle]]s, repetitive dialogue, and several inconsistencies and plot holes. The movie's producer, Franchise Pictures, was later forced out of business after it emerged that it had fraudulently overstated the film's budget by $31 million. It has a 3% rating at [[Rotten Tomatoes]],<ref>{{rotten-tomatoes|id=battlefield_earth|title=Battlefield Earth}}</ref> and it was included in their Top 100 worst-reviewed movies of the 2000s.<ref name=\"rottenworst\">{{cite web|url=https://rottentomatoes.com/guides/worst_of_the_worst/ |title=The worst of the worst pictures |website=Rotten Tomatoes |date=2009-09-21 |accessdate=2011-01-17}}</ref> [[Roger Ebert]] predicted that the film, \"for decades to come will be the punch line of jokes about bad movies\".<ref name=\"BEarth\">{{cite news |url=http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20000512/REVIEWS/5120301/1023 |work=Chicago Sun-Times |title=Battlefield Earth | date=2000-05-12}}</ref> Ebert also wrote, \"the director, [[Roger Christian (filmmaker)|Roger Christian]], has learned from better films that directors sometimes tilt their cameras, but he has not learned why\".<ref name=\"BEarth\" /> It is also on his \"most hated\" list.<ref name=\"eberthated\">{{cite news|url=http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20050811/COMMENTARY/50808002/ |title=Ebert's Most Hated |work=Rogerebert.suntimes.com |accessdate=2011-01-17}}</ref> [[Nathan Rabin]] of [[The A.V. Club]] called it \"a fiasco that occupies a distinguished place high atop the pantheon of widely reviled crap\" and said, \"A legendary disaster well before it finished completion, ''Battlefield Earth'' hit theaters with a \"Kick Me\" sign on it so massive it could be detected from outer space.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://film.avclub.com/my-year-of-flops-case-file-66-battlefield-earth-1798212540|title=My Year OF Flops Case File #66: Battlefield Earth|last=Rabin|first=Nathan|website=Film|language=en-US|access-date=2019-01-27}}</ref> It won seven [[Golden Raspberry Award]]s, including Worst Picture and Worst Screen Couple (John Travolta and \"anyone on the screen with him\").<ref>{{cite web |url=http://razzies.com/asp/content/XcNewsPlus.asp?cmd=view&articleid=44/ |title=It's official \u2013 \"Battlefield Earth\" ties with \"Showgirls\" |work=Razzies.com |date=2000-02-03 |accessdate=2011-01-17 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110715160151/http://razzies.com/asp/content/XcNewsPlus.asp?cmd=view&articleid=44%2F |archive-date=2011-07-15 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In 2005, an eighth Razzie (for Worst \"Drama\" of Our First 25 Years) was awarded to the film,<ref>{{cite web |title=Awards for Battlefield Earth |work=Internet Movie Database |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0185183/awards |accessdate=2008-06-27}}</ref> and in 2010 it won a ninth Razzie at the [[30th Golden Raspberry Awards]] for ''Worst Picture of the Decade'',<ref name=\"30thRazzies\">{{cite web |title=Razzie Noms for Worst Picture of the Decade |work=Razzies.com |url=http://www.razzies.com/history/09NomPOD.asp |accessdate=2010-02-02}}</ref> the most of any film in the history of the awards at the time,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.razzies.com/history/07release.asp |title=Golden Raspberry Award Foundation |work=Razzies.com |accessdate=2013-11-18 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130321103846/http://www.razzies.com/history/07release.asp |archivedate=2013-03-21 }}</ref> before ''[[Jack and Jill (2011 film)|Jack and Jill]]'' surpassed its record with ten wins in 2012.<ref name=RazzieWin/> The movie appeared on Metacritic's list of the all-time lowest-scoring films,<ref name=\"Metacritic\">{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/browse/movies/score/metascore/all?sort=asc|title=Movie Releases By Score|last=|first=|date=|work=[[Metacritic]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|accessdate=April 17, 2019}}</ref> and is on the MRQE's 50 Worst Movies list.<ref name=\"MRQE50\">{{cite web|url=https://www.mrqe.com/lists/50_worst_movies|title=50 Worst Movies|last=|first=|date=|work=[[Movie Review Query Engine]]|accessdate=April 17, 2019}}</ref> ''[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]'' named it the second worst movie ever made after ''[[Batman & Robin (film)|Batman & Robin]]'' and ''[[The Register]]'' listed it as the worst movie ever made.<ref name=\"The 50 Worst Movies Ever\"/><ref name=\"battlefieldregister\">{{cite web |title=Battlefield Earth ruled worst film Ever|work=[[The Register]]|last=Haines|first=Lester|url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2012/04/20/worst_movie/|accessdate=April 5, 2018|date=April 20, 2012}}</ref> ''Battlefield Earth'' screenwriter [[J. David Shapiro]] later apologized for making \"the suckiest movie ever\".<ref name=\"battlefieldregister\"/>\n\n=== ''Honest'' (2000) ===\n\n''[[Honest (film)|Honest]]'' is the directorial debut of [[Eurythmics]] member [[David A. Stewart]], and starring three members of the British/Canadian [[girl group]] [[All Saints (group)|All Saints]] ([[Melanie Blatt]], [[Nicole Appleton|Nicole]] and [[Natalie Appleton]]). It received a large amount of media criticism following its release.<ref name=\"dr\">\"Honest, it's the worst movie ever; All Saints' film debut is holy awful, say critics\". ''The Daily Record'', May 26, 2000</ref> The Scottish newspaper ''[[Daily Record (Scotland)|Daily Record]]'' described ''Honest'' thus: \"This turgid tale of Sixties London isn't just bad \u2013 it's quite probably the worst film ever.\"<ref name=\"dr\" /> [[Peter Bradshaw]] noted that ''Honest'' \"subscribes to the usual credulous fictions about the charm, glamour and wit of violent criminals, and leaves out these qualities in spades\" and added \"However silly and implausible, it would be all right if there was the slightest hint of brio or fun in the script, written by comedy giants [[Dick Clement]] and [[Ian La Frenais]]. But there isn't.\"<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/film/2000/may/26/culture.reviews \"Honest\"] Peter Bradshaw, ''The Guardian'', 26 May 2000. Retrieved 2 October 2014.</ref> [[Alexander Walker (critic)|Alexander Walker]] called ''Honest'' \"An ugly, ratty-looking load of jazzy cliches buried in flashy has-been styles, including slowmo frolicking in the Trafalgar Square fountains, strobe-lit druggy sessions and accelerated action on the mattress.\"<ref>Alexander Walker, ''The Evening Standard'', 26 May 2000.</ref> British film historian I.Q. Hunter later listed ''Honest'' as one of the candidates for the title of \"Worst British film ever made\".<ref name=\"iqh\" />\n\n=== ''Freddy Got Fingered'' (2001) ===\n\nThe comedy film ''[[Freddy Got Fingered]]'' stars [[Tom Green]], who also wrote and directed it, featuring largely [[gross-out comedy|gross-out]] and [[shock humor]] similar to that featured in ''[[The Tom Green Show]]''. In the film, Green stars as a 28-year-old slacker and cartoonist who falsely accuses his father of [[child molestation]] when he questions his son's life goals. ''Freddy Got Fingered'' received overwhelmingly negative reviews, with [[CNN]] critic [[Paul Clinton]] declaring it \"quite simply the worst movie ever released by a major studio in Hollywood history\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Clinton |first=Paul |title='Freddy Got Fingered' is a bad, bad film |publisher=CNN |date=April 19, 2011 |url=http://archives.cnn.com/2001/SHOWBIZ/Movies/04/19/Freddy.Fingered/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061230080518/http://archives.cnn.com/2001/SHOWBIZ/Movies/04/19/Freddy.Fingered/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=December 30, 2006 |accessdate=February 9, 2011 }}</ref> Warren Epstein of ''[[The Gazette (Colorado Springs)|The Gazette]]'' described ''Freddy Got Fingered'' as \"the worst movie ever made\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-5965104.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180319151405/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-5965104.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=19 March 2018 |title='Freddy Got Fingered' is but the latest in a long line of stinkers |author=Warren Epstein |newspaper=[[The Gazette (Colorado Springs)|The Gazette]] |date=26 April 2001|via=HighBeam Research}}</ref> A review in ''[[The Washington Post]]'' said: \"If ever a movie testified to the utter creative bankruptcy of the Hollywood film industry, it is the abomination known as ''Freddy Got Fingered''.\"<ref>{{cite news |last=Hughes |first=Scott |title=The worst movie ever? |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=April 26, 2001 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2001/apr/26/artsfeatures2 |accessdate=February 9, 2011 |location=London}}</ref> Robert Koehler of ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' called it, \"One of the most brutally awful comedies ever to emerge from a major studio.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Freddy Got Fingered |work=[[Metacritic]] |url=https://metacritic.com/movie/freddy-got-fingered/critic-reviews |accessdate= March 17, 2014}}</ref> Film reviewer [[Roger Ebert]] included the film on his \"most hated\" list,<ref name=\"eberthated\" /> gave it zero out of four stars, and wrote: \"This movie doesn't scrape the bottom of the barrel. This movie isn't the bottom of the barrel. This movie isn't below the bottom of the barrel. This movie doesn't deserve to be mentioned in the same sentence with barrels.\"<ref>{{cite news |last=Ebert |first=Roger |author-link=Roger Ebert |title=Freddy Got Fingered |work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]] |date=April 20, 2011 |url=http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20010420/REVIEWS/104200304/1023 |accessdate=February 9, 2011}}</ref> ''Freddy Got Fingered'' was nominated for eight awards at the [[22nd Golden Raspberry Awards|2001 Razzies]], and won for Worst Picture, Worst Actor, Worst Director, Worst Screenplay, and Worst On-Screen Couple.<ref name=\"BBC0211\">{{cite news |title=Freddy heads Razzies nominations |work=BBC News |date=February 11, 2002 |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/1814018.stm |accessdate=February 9, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"BBC0323\">{{cite news |last=Waters |first=Darren |title=Green gets fingered for Razzies |work=BBC News |date=March 23, 2002 |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/in_depth/entertainment/2002/oscars_2002/1889555.stm |accessdate=February 9, 2011}}</ref> Razzies founder [[John J. B. Wilson]] called it \"offensive, stupid and obnoxious\" and said it had \"no redeeming value\".<ref name=\"BBC0211\"/> Green accepted his awards in person, traveling to the ceremony in a white [[Cadillac]], wearing a tuxedo and rolling out his own [[red carpet]] to the presentation. The movie has an 11% rating on [[Rotten Tomatoes]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://rottentomatoes.com/m/freddy_got_fingered/ |title=Freddy Got Fingered |website=Rotten Tomatoes |accessdate=2013-11-18}}</ref> In 2010, the film was nominated at the [[30th Golden Raspberry Awards]] for ''Worst Picture of the Decade'',<ref name=\"30thRazzies\"/> though it lost to ''Battlefield Earth''.<ref>{{cite news |last=Masters |first=Tim |title=Sandra Bullock wins worst actress award at Razzies |work=BBC News |date=March 7, 2010 |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/8554035.stm |accessdate=February 9, 2011}}</ref> ''Freddy Got Fingered'' also appeared on Metacritic's list of the all-time lowest-scoring films,<ref name=\"Metacritic\"/> was featured in ''[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]'''s list of the \"50 Worst Movies Ever\" poll,<ref name=\"The 50 Worst Movies Ever\">{{cite web | url = https://www.empireonline.com/movies/features/50-worst-movies-ever-2/ |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200201223813/https://www.empireonline.com/movies/features/50-worst-movies-ever-2/ | title = The 50 Worst Movies Ever | work=[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]] | date=February 4, 2010 |archivedate=February 1, 2020 | accessdate = March 17, 2014}}</ref> and is on the MRQE's 50 Worst Movies list.<ref name=\"MRQE50\"/>\n\n=== ''Glitter'' (2001) ===\nStarring [[Mariah Carey]] in the lead role as an aspiring singer, the romantic musical drama ''[[Glitter (film)|Glitter]]'' was intended to be her breakthrough role but was a critical failure and a box office bomb. ''[[Hindustan Times]]'' claimed that ''Glitter'' \"was slammed by almost all critics for being the worst film ever\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Mariah Carey's flop movie 'Glitter' almost killed her |newspaper= Hindustan Times |date=November 4, 2009 |quote=Carey, 39, had to be hospitalised due to an emotional breakdown after Glitter was slammed by almost all critics for being the worst film ever.}}</ref> ''[[Fade In (magazine)|Fade In]]'' stated that \"''Glitter'' isn't just one of the worst music-themed films ever \u2014 it's one of the worst films ever made, period.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=The 30 worst Vanity Projects of all time|url=http://fadeinonline.com/the-30-worst-vanity-projects-of-all-time.html|website=Fadeinonline.com|publisher=[[Fade In (magazine)|Fade In]]|accessdate=August 23, 2015}}</ref> Author Bob McCann wrote in ''Encyclopedia of African American Actresses in Film and Television'' that it's \"rightfully in the running as one of the worst films ever made\".<ref>{{cite book |first=McCann |last=Bob |title=Encyclopedia of African American Actresses in Film and Television |location=New York |publisher=Performing Arts |year=2009 |isbn=9780786458042 |page=70 }}</ref> [[News.com.au]],<ref name=\":1\">{{cite news|url=https://www.news.com.au/entertainment/movies/absolute-stinkers-the-15-worst-movies-of-all-time/news-story/0023085ea96fa3f2c581778a070f1308|title=Absolute stinkers: The 15 worst movies of all time|last=Stephenson|first=Alison|date=November 13, 2013|work=|accessdate=April 17, 2019|website=[[News.com.au]]}}</ref> ''[[Hi (magazine)|Hi]]'',<ref>{{cite web|title=Worst Films Ever: Glitter|url=http://www.hihimag.com/hi/ents/film/2013/07/worst-films-ever-glitter/|website=[[Hi (magazine)|Hi]]|accessdate=August 23, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924030115/http://www.hihimag.com/hi/ents/film/2013/07/worst-films-ever-glitter/|archive-date=2015-09-24|url-status=dead}}</ref> ''[[Flavorwire]]'',<ref name=\"Flavorwire\"/> Metacritic,<ref name=\"Metacritic\"/> and ''[[Empire (magazine)|Empire]]'' are amongst those who have listed it as one of the worst films ever made.<ref name=\"The 50 Worst Movies Ever\"/> ''Glitter'' received six Razzie nominations and Carey won for Worst Actress.<ref>{{cite news|title=Tom Green, Estella Warren are Razzie ''winners'' |url=https://www.ew.com/article/2002/03/25/tom-green-estella-warren-are-razzie-winners |newspaper=Entertainment Weekly |accessdate=August 23, 2015 |first=Brian |last=Hiatt |date=2002-03-25}}</ref> It was also featured in John Wilson's ''The Official Razzie Movie Guide'', and in 2005, it was nominated for \"Worst Musical of Our First 25 Years\", but lost to ''[[From Justin to Kelly]]''. In an interview in 2010, Carey stated that she believed that the film's failure at the box office was largely due to the soundtrack being released the same day as the [[September 11 attacks]].<ref name=\"digitalspy\">{{cite web|title=Carey Blames 9/11 For 'Glitter' Flop|work=[[Digital Spy]]|publisher=[[Hachette Filipacchi M\u00e9dias]]|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/movies/news/a199302/carey-blames-911-for-glitter-flop.html|last=Reynolds|first=Simon|date=January 26, 2010|accessdate=August 23, 2015}}</ref> It has a 7% rating on [[Rotten Tomatoes]] based on 87 reviews.<ref>{{cite web|title=Glitter (2001)|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/glitter|website=Rotten Tomatoes|accessdate=3 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Swept Away'' (2002) ===\nA remake of [[Swept Away (1974 film)|a 1974 Italian film of the same name]], the [[romantic comedy]] film ''[[Swept Away (2002 film)|Swept Away]]'' was directed by [[Guy Ritchie]] and starred his then-wife [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]] and [[Adriano Giannini]]. It received mostly extremely negative reviews, with most of the criticism going towards Madonna's bad acting, the original film being considered superior and the remake being considered just a star vehicle for Madonna.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/northamerica/usa/1410000/Madonna-and-Guy-swept-away-on-tide-of-criticism.html|title=Madonna and Guy swept away on tide of criticism|last=Poole|first=Oliver|date=2002-10-11|access-date=2018-12-28|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref> [[Rotten Tomatoes]] holds a 5% rating, based on 79 reviews, with an average rating of 2.76/10. The site's consensus states: \"Muddled and lacking the political context of the original, ''Swept Away'' offers further proof that Madonna can't act.\"<ref>{{Citation|title=Swept Away|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/1116774-swept_away/|language=en|access-date=2018-12-28}}</ref> [[Metacritic]] reports an 18 out of 100 rating, based on 27 critics, indicating \"overwhelming dislike\".<ref>{{Citation|title=Swept Away|url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/swept-away|access-date=2018-12-28}}</ref> Rex Reed of ''[[The Observer]]'' said: \"If there is one thing worse than a Guy Ritchie movie, it's a Guy Ritchie movie with Madonna in it.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://observer.com/2002/10/not-swept-away-by-madonna/|title=Not Swept Away By Madonna|date=2002-10-21|website=Observer|language=en|access-date=2018-12-28}}</ref> [[Joe Queenan (author)|Joe Queenan]] of ''[[The Guardian]]'' discussed the movie in an article on what makes a movie the worst of all time and said, \"[...] ''[[Showgirls]]'' has a certain campy allure that grows a bit each time I see it. Madonna's ''Swept Away'' doesn't; it seems more amateurish on each viewing, like a morass that starts out as a quagmire, then morphs into a cesspool and finally turns into a slime pit on the road to its ultimate destination in the bowels of Hell.\"<ref name=\"queenan\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2008/mar/21/1|title=Joe Queenan on the worst movie of all time|last=Queenan|first=Joe|authorlink=Joe Queenan (author)|date=March 21, 2008|work=The Guardian|access-date=December 28, 2018|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> [[Julie Burchill]], also from ''The Guardian'', selected it as her pick for the worst film ever made.<ref name=\"guardianworst\"/> John Anderson of ''[[Newsday]]'' said, \"New ways of describing badness need to be invented to describe exactly how bad it is.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/1116774-swept_away/reviews/?page=2&sort=|title=Swept Away - Movie Reviews - Rotten Tomatoes|website=www.rottentomatoes.com|access-date=2018-12-28}}</ref> ''Swept Away'' was also a [[box office bomb]]; against a $10 million budget, it grossed $598,645 in the United States and around $437,875 from foreign territories for a worldwide total gross of $1,036,520.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=sweptaway.htm|title=Swept Away (2002) - Box Office Mojo|website=www.boxofficemojo.com|access-date=2018-12-28}}</ref> The film was awarded five awards at the [[23rd Golden Raspberry Awards|2002 Golden Raspberry Awards]], for Worst Picture, Worst Actress (Madonna), Worst Screen Couple (Madonna and Giannini), Worst Remake or Sequel and Worst Director (Ritchie), while also being nominated for Worst Actor (Giannini) and Worst Screenplay. It was the first film to win both Worst Picture and Worst Remake or Sequel. At the [[25th Golden Raspberry Awards]], it was nominated for ''Worst \"Drama\" of Our First 25 Years'', and at the [[30th Golden Raspberry Awards]], it was nominated for ''Worst Picture of the Decade'', but in both cases lost to ''[[Battlefield Earth (film)|Battlefield Earth]]''. [[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]] ranked it #20 in its list of \"The 50 Worst Movies Ever\",<ref name=\"The 50 Worst Movies Ever\" /> and [[AfterEllen.com and TheBacklot.com|After Ellen]] ranked it #7 in its list of \"The worst movies ever to grace the screen\".<ref name=\"afterellen\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.afterellen.com/movies/58522-the-worst-movies-ever-to-grace-the-screen|title=The worst movies ever to grace the screen|date=2009-09-08|website=AfterEllen|access-date=2019-01-30}}</ref>\n\n=== ''The Master of Disguise'' (2002) ===\n\nThe comedy film ''[[The Master of Disguise]]'' was produced in part by [[Adam Sandler]] and stars [[Dana Carvey]] as Pistachio Disguisey, an undercover Italian waiter who must save his father Fabbrizio ([[James Brolin]]) from the evil Devlin Bowman ([[Brent Spiner]]) by using his inherent skills in disguise. Although the film was a box office success, it received scathing reviews from critics upon its release, many of which pointed out its sophomoric plot, unfunny humor (in particular, its [[flatulence]] gags) and disguises that would clearly not be recognized by children (such as [[Tony Montana]] from ''[[Scarface (1983 film)|Scarface]]''). Many critics also pointed out the short running time, consisting of 72 minutes of the film itself and over ten minutes of end credits juxtaposed with outtakes. [[Roger Ebert]] gave it one star out of four, claiming, \"The movie is a desperate miscalculation. It gives poor Dana Carvey nothing to do that is really funny, and then expects us to laugh because he acts so goofy all the time.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Fragoso |first=Sam |url=https://rogerebert.com/reviews/the-master-of-disguise-2002 |title=The Master Of Disguise Movie Review (2002) |publisher=Roger Ebert |date=2002-08-02 |accessdate=2014-03-05}}</ref> Alan Morrisson, writing for the film magazine ''[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]'', proclaimed that ''The Master of Disguise'' was \"the worst film ever made: a film about idiots, made by idiots, for idiots\",<ref name=\"The 50 Worst Movies Ever\"/> while Matthew Turner of ''ViewLondon'' remarked, \"This is a serious contender for the title of The Worst Film Ever Made.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.viewlondon.co.uk/films/the-master-of-disguise-film-review-3673.html |title=The Master of Disguise Film Review \u2013 The Master of Disguise Film Pictures, The Master of Disguise Film Trailer |work=Viewlondon.co.uk |date=2006-10-16 |accessdate=2014-03-05}}</ref> In addition, Chris Parry of eFilmCritic.com stated, \"Quite honestly, I've never seen anything less competent. And I mean that.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.efilmcritic.com/review.php?movie=6017&reviewer=1 |title=Movie Review \u2013 Master of Disguise, The |publisher=eFilmCritic |accessdate=2014-03-05}}</ref> The film holds a 1% rating on [[Rotten Tomatoes]] based on 104 reviews,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://rottentomatoes.com/m/master_of_disguise/ |title=The Master of Disguise |website=Rotten Tomatoes |accessdate=2014-07-24}}</ref> and was featured on the site's list of the top 100 worst-reviewed films of the 2000s.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://rottentomatoes.com/guides/worst_of_the_worst/9/ |title=Worst of the Worst 2009 \u2013 Crossover |website=Rotten Tomatoes |accessdate=2014-03-05}}</ref> It also appears on Metacritic's list of the all-time lowest-scoring films,<ref name=\"Metacritic\"/> and is on the MRQE's 50 Worst Movies list.<ref name=\"MRQE50\"/> A cameo appearance by [[Bo Derek]] landed her a nomination for Worst Supporting Actress at the [[23rd Golden Raspberry Awards]], but she lost to [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]] for ''[[Die Another Day]]''.\n\n=== ''Ballistic: Ecks vs. Sever'' (2002) ===\n\nThe action film ''[[Ballistic: Ecks vs. Sever]]'' stars [[Antonio Banderas]] and [[Lucy Liu]] as opposing secret agents. Critics panned it, generally regarding it as having no redeeming features, not even the unintentional comedic value normally associated with bad films. They variously described the film as \"A picture for idiots\", \"Boring to an amazing degree\", \"A fine achievement in stupidity and dullness\", \"Dreadful\", \"[Giving] new meaning to the word incoherent\", and \"bad on just about every level\". One critic suggested an alternative title as \"''Simplistic: Bullets Vs. Humans''\".<ref>[https://hollywoodreporter.com/hr/search/article_display.jsp?vnu_content_id=1689821/ ''Ballistic: Ecks vs. Sever''] at ''The Hollywood Reporter''</ref> [[Stephen Hunter]] of ''[[The Washington Post]]'' wrote, \"You could run this film backward, soundtrack included, and it would make no less sense.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/ac2/wp-dyn/A42115-2002Sep19 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110628231426/http://www.washingtonpost.com/ac2/wp-dyn/A42115-2002Sep19 |url-status=dead |archive-date=2011-06-28 |title=''Goosey Lucy: 'Ballistic,' a Lot of Noisy Dumdum'' |work=Washingtonpost.com |date=2002-09-20 |accessdate=2011-01-17}}</ref> [[Roger Ebert]], who included the film in his \"most hated list\", called the movie \"a chaotic mess, overloaded with special effects and explosions, light on continuity, sanity and coherence\".<ref>[http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=%2F20020920%2FREVIEWS%2F209200302%2F1023&AID1=%2F20020920%2FREVIEWS%2F209200302%2F1023&AID2= Roger Ebert \u2013 Ballistic: Ecks vs. Sever]. Retrieved 2009-10-09.</ref> In addition to being lambasted by critics, it was a disaster financially, recouping just over $19.9 million of its $70 million budget. ''[[International Business Times]]'' included it on its list of Hollywood's top 5 worst movies ever made.<ref name=\"IBT\"/> In March 2007, the movie review site [[Rotten Tomatoes]] ranked it #1 among \"The Worst of the Worst\" movie list,<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20090303154232/https://rottentomatoes.com/features/special/2007/wotw/?r=1&mid=1116131 \"The Worst of the Worst\"], rottentomatoes.com (archived at Wayback Machine)</ref> with 108 \"rotten\" reviews and no \"fresh\" ones. ''[[Mental Floss]]'' also listed it as the worst movie ever made.<ref name=\"Mental Floss\"/>\n\n=== ''Ben and Arthur'' (2002) ===\nA low-budget 2002 American romantic drama film about the titular gay couple who come into conflict with Arthur's religious brother, ''[[Ben and Arthur]]'' was written, directed, produced, edited, and scored by Sam Mraovich, who also played the character Arthur. ''Ben and Arthur'' received strong criticism (especially from the LGBT community) for its low budget and poor plotting. [[BuzzFeed]] described it as the \"worst gay movie of all time\".<ref name=\"peitzman\">{{cite news|url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/louispeitzman/the-man-behind-the-worst-gay-movie-of-all-time-doesnt-care-i |title=The Man Behind The \"Worst Gay Movie Of All Time\" Doesn't Care If You Hate It |first=Louis |last=Peitzman |publisher=[[BuzzFeed]] |date=September 5, 2014 |accessdate=March 15, 2018}}</ref> The gay popular culture site [[Queerty]] described ''Ben and Arthur'' as \"unintelligible\" and ended its review by calling it the \"Worst. Movie. Ever.\"<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://www.queerty.com/ben-arthur-the-worst-gay-movie-of-all-time-20090220 |title=Ben & Arthur: The Worst Gay Movie of All Time |first=Japhy |last=Grant |journal=[[Queerty]] |date=February 20, 2009 |accessdate=January 25, 2015 }}</ref> The gay movie review site Cinemaqueer likewise stated: \"''Ben and Arthur'' is so terrible that it has awoken the dormant Bette Davis in me. It is so painfully bad that it wouldn't even make good fodder on ''[[Mystery Science Theater 3000]]''. This just might possibly be the worst movie I have ever seen ... Unless you get a kick out of mocking bad films, avoid this one at all costs.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cinemaqueer.com/review%20pages/9deadgayguysben.html |title=9 dead gay guys/ben & arthur |first=Michael D. |last=Klemm |website=Cinemaqueer |date=July 2004 |accessdate=January 25, 2015 }}</ref> Michael Adams, reviewing the film for his book ''Showgirls, Teen Wolves, and Astro Zombies'', describes it thus: \"''Ben & Arthur'' is as over-the-top insane as it is ludicrously executed ... the production values, from biscuits on plates comprising the main course of a candlelit dinner to a church literally having a cardboard cross and a cartoon Jesus on the wall, are as bad as anything I've seen.\"<ref>{{cite book |first=Michael |last=Adams |title=Showgirls, Teen Wolves, and Astro Zombies: a film critic's year-long quest to find the worst movie ever made |location=New York |publisher=Itbooks |year=2010 |isbn=978-0-06-180629-2 |page=301 }}</ref> A [[Rotten Tomatoes]] article placed ''Ben and Arthur'' on their list of \"Films So Bad They're Unmissable\", saying \"If [[Tommy Wiseau]]'s ''[[The Room (2003 film)|The Room]]'' is the over-wrought, melodramatic and self-pitying heterosexual camp classic of choice, then Sam Mraovich's ''Ben & Arthur'' is its gay equivalent.\" Rotten Tomatoes also stated \"Every scene, every line, every hissy fit is simultaneously hilariously amateur and hysterically fever-pitched.\"<ref name=\"sobad\">{{cite web |url=https://editorial.rottentomatoes.com/article/25-movies-so-bad-theyre-unmissable/|title=25 Movies So Bad They're Unmissable |website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |date=January 30, 2010 |accessdate=January 25, 2015 }}</ref> ''[[Total Film]]'' ranked ''Ben and Arthur'' at #58 in their list of the 66 worst films of all time.<ref name=TotalFilm>{{cite web|url=http://www.totalfilm.com/features/66-worst-movies-of-all-time|title=66 Worst Movies Of All Time|date=February 15, 2012 |work=[[Total Film]]|publisher=[[GamesRadar]]|accessdate=September 30, 2013 }}</ref> Mraovich finds ''Ben and Arthur''{{'}}s placement among the canon of worst films to be a blessing as the film has received more attention than he ever anticipated.<ref name=\"peitzman\"/>\n\n=== ''Pinocchio'' (US dub, 2002) ===\n''[[Pinocchio (2002 film)|Pinocchio]]'', a 2002 Italian [[Fantasy film|fantasy]] [[comedy-drama]] film based on ''[[The Adventures of Pinocchio]]'' by [[Carlo Collodi]], directed by and starring [[Roberto Benigni]], garnered largely negative reviews mostly for Benigni's poor portrayal of [[Pinocchio]]. It received an English-language dub in the United States in December 2002, released by [[Miramax]], which was universally panned and further contributed to the negative reception. Bob Grimm of ''[[News & Review]]'' called it \"quite possibly the worst movie-going experience in all of my 34 years\" and said, \" ''Pinocchio'' garners Benigni the dubious distinction of having directed one of the worst movies ever unleashed upon an unsuspecting public.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsreview.com/reno/monstrous-terrifying/content?oid=19474|title=Pinocchio - Monstrous and terrifying - Film Reviews - Film - January 2, 2003|website=Reno News & Review|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> Elvis Mitchell of ''[[The New York Times]]'' called it \"a movie so bad that it quickly enters the pantheon of wreckage that includes ''Battleship Earth'' [sic] and ''Showgirls''.<nowiki>''</nowiki><ref>{{Cite news|last=Mitchell|first=Elvis|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/12/26/movies/film-review-how-many-actors-does-it-take-to-make-a-log-talk.html|title=FILM REVIEW; How Many Actors Does It Take to Make a Log Talk?|date=2002-12-26|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-12|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Keith Phillips of ''[[The A.V. Club]]'' said that it \"could have become a ''Howard The Duck-'' or ''Battlefield Earth''-like synonym for cinematic miscalculation, were its title not already so familiar.\" <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://film.avclub.com/pinocchio-1798198162|title=Pinocchio|website=Film|language=en-us|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> ''[[News.com.au]]'' included it in its list of the 15 worst films of all time.<ref name=\":1\" /> It was the fist non-English-language-film to get nominated for the Golden Raspberry Awards, earning six nominations, for Worst Picture, Worst Director, Worst Screenplay, Worst Actor, Worst Remake or Sequel and Worst Screen Couple (Roberto Benigni and Nicoletta Braschi), with Benigni winning one for Worst Actor. The film has a [[List of films with a 0% rating on Rotten Tomatoes|0% rating]] at Rotten Tomatoes and it is on Metacritic's list of the all-time lowest-scoring films.<ref name=\"Metacritic\"/><ref>{{Citation|title=Pinocchio (2002)|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/1119026_pinocchio|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>  Despite this, Benigni starred in [[Pinocchio (2019 film)|another Pinocchio film]] in 2019, this time playing [[Mister Geppetto|Gepetto]].\n\n=== ''From Justin to Kelly'' (2003) ===\n\nThe romantic-comedy musical ''[[From Justin to Kelly]]'' stars [[Kelly Clarkson]] and [[Justin Guarini]], the winner and runner-up, respectively, of the [[American Idol (season 1)|first season]] of ''[[American Idol]]''. The film was a critical and commercial disaster, earning only $4.9 million at the North American box office and achieving a 10% rating on [[Rotten Tomatoes]] based on 63 reviews.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://rottentomatoes.com/m/from_justin_to_kelly/ |title=From Justin To Kelly |website=Rotten Tomatoes |accessdate=2014-07-24}}</ref> [[Josh Tyrangiel]] of ''[[Time Magazine]]'' described ''From Justin to Kelly'' as \"a monstrous ''Idol'' movie musical that in the most generous light is the worst film so far this century\",<ref name=\"kc\">[http://content.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,1156616,00.html \"Miss Independent\"] Josh Tyrangiel. ''Time Magazine''  February 5, 2006 (Subscription Required).</ref> while ''[[The Free Lance\u2013Star]]'' referred to it as \"the world's worst movie\".<ref>\"Dishing it!\" ''The Free Lance\u2013Star'', July 9th, 2003, (p.56).</ref> [[Nathan Rabin]] of ''[[The A.V. Club]]'', reviewing the film for his \"My Year of Flops\" series, stated, \"All films require suspension of disbelief. ''From Justin To Kelly'' requires something more like a temporary lobotomy. Nothing about the main characters or their relationships makes sense.\"<ref name=\"fjtk\">[https://avclub.com/article/contest-winning-case-file-150-ifrom-justin-to-kell-35221 Contest-Winning Case File #150: From Justin To Kelly] Nathan Rabin, ''[[The A.V. Club]]'', November 11th, 2009. Retrieved 28 January 2014.</ref> It won a special [[Razzie]]\u2014\"Governor's Award \u2013 Distinguished Under-Achievement in Choreography\"\u2014at the [[24th Golden Raspberry Awards]].<ref>\"Gigli Takes Razzie Dishonors as Year's Worst\", ''[[Reading Eagle]]'', March 1st, 2004 (p.20)</ref> It was nominated for eight additional Razzies (including a second special award, \"Worst Excuse for an Actual Movie\"), and a year later it won for [[25th Golden Raspberry Awards|Worst \"Musical\" of Our First 25 Years]]. ''[[Total Film]]'' included ''From Justin to Kelly'' on their list of \"The 66 Worst Films of All Time\",<ref name=TotalFilm/> and ''[[International Business Times]]'' included the film on its list of Hollywood's top 5 worst movies ever made.<ref name=\"IBT\"/> In a later interview, Clarkson expressed regret over ''From Justin to Kelly'', stating she only did it because she was contractually obligated to do so: \"I knew when I read the script it was going to be real, real bad, but when I won, I signed that piece of paper, and I could not get out of it.\"<ref name=\"kc\" />\n\n=== ''The Room'' (2003) ===\n[[File:Tommy-Wiseau-1.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Tommy Wiseau]] in a promotional picture for ''[[The Room (2003 film)|The Room]]'']]\nThe independently produced ''[[The Room (2003 film)|The Room]]'', about an amiable banker whose friends betray him one by one, has been called \"the ''[[Citizen Kane]]'' of bad movies\" by some critics.<ref name=\"ew1\">{{cite magazine |url=https://ew.com/article/2008/12/12/crazy-cult-room/|title=The Crazy Cult of 'The Room'|date=July 20, 2009 |magazine=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |accessdate=December 3, 2019|first=Clark |last=Collis}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/features/the-couch-surfer-it-may-be-sublimely-rubbish-but-the-room-makes-audiences-happy-1752708.html |title=The Couch Surfer: 'It may be sublimely rubbish, but The Room makes audiences happy' |date=2009-07-20 |work=Independent.co.uk |accessdate=23 November 2009 |location=London}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://ew.com/article/2008/12/30/the-room-postsc/ |title='The Room': Worst movie ever? Don't tell that to its suddenly in-demand star |last=Collis |first=Clark |date=December 30, 2008 |work=Entertainment Weekly |accessdate=December 3, 2019}}</ref> ''[[The Guardian]], [[Vox (website)|Vox]], [[The Washington Post]], [[Australian Broadcasting Corporation|ABC Australia]]'' and ''[[S\u00fcddeutsche Zeitung]]'' called it the worst film ever made.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Rose|first=Steve|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/filmblog/2009/sep/10/cinema-the-room-cult|title=Is this the worst movie ever made?|date=2009-09-09|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-03-18|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/culture/2017/12/2/16720012/the-room-tommy-wiseau-backstory-explained|title=The Room: how the worst movie ever became a Hollywood legend as bizarre as its creator|last=Romano|first=Aja|date=2017-12-02|website=Vox|language=en|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/entertainment/the-room-is-the-worst-movie-ever-made-but-ive-seen-it-a-hundred-times--without-irony/2017/11/30/6475b096-d3ae-11e7-b62d-d9345ced896d_story.html|title=Perspective {{!}} \u2018The Room\u2019 is the worst movie ever made, but I\u2019ve seen it a hundred times \u2014 without irony|last=ParkReporterEmailEmailBioBioFollowFollowReporter|first=Gene Park closeGene|website=Washington Post|language=en|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2017-12-05/the-room-tommy-wiseau-worst-film-ever-made-endures/9223516|title=The worst movie ever made, explained|last=Donoughue|first=pop culture reporter Paul|date=2017-12-05|website=ABC News|language=en-AU|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sueddeutsche.de/kultur/schlechtester-film-aller-zeiten-wie-eine-atombombe-die-jeden-moment-explodiert-1.1680571|title=\"The Room\", schlechtester Film aller Zeiten|last=Graff|first=Bernd|website=S\u00fcddeutsche.de|language=de|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref> Ignatiy Vishnevetsky of ''[[The A.V. Club|The A.V Club]]'' called it \"the greatest bad movie of our time\" and said, \"''The Room'' is nearly an anti-film\u2014an inane and unintentionally surreal soap opera, filled with non sequiturs, confused characters, and gratuitous, anatomically incorrect sex.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.avclub.com/the-disaster-artist-is-a-lousy-tribute-to-the-greatest-1820787988|title=The Disaster Artist is a lousy tribute to the greatest bad movie of our time|last=Vishnevetsky|first=Ignatiy|website=The A.V. Club|access-date=2019-01-04}}</ref> Though the film's star, writer, producer, and director [[Tommy Wiseau]] has claimed it is a [[black comedy]] and its numerous flaws are intentional, other actors involved in the production have denied this, saying that Wiseau intended it as a [[melodrama]]tic romance.<ref name=\"Times1\">{{cite news |title=Cult hit (Even M is a recycled sex scene) The Room is best worst film |url=http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/film/article6067024.ece |newspaper= The Times |first=Christopher |last=Goodwin |date=April 12, 2009 |location=London}}</ref> ''The Room'' has been noted for its bizarre and non-sequiturial dialogue, protracted sex scenes, various subplots that are inadequately resolved or simply disappear altogether (most notably, a character announces that she has been diagnosed with [[breast cancer]], but this is never mentioned again throughout the entire film), and infamous use of [[chroma key|green-screen]] for \"outdoor\" rooftop scenes. It made its broadcast premiere as an [[April Fools' Day]] special in 2009 on [[Cartoon Network]]'s [[Adult Swim]] block, edited down from its original R rating to a TV-14/DSLV rating. The day after its appearance, its DVD became the top-selling [[independent film]] on [[Amazon.com]]. In June 2010, ''The Room'' started playing at the [[American Film Institute]] [[AFI Silver|Silver Theatre]] in [[Silver Spring, Maryland]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Siblo |first=Matt |url=http://www.washingtoncitypaper.com/articles/39009/tommy-wiseau-and-the-room-at-afi-silver-theatre-friday |title=Tommy Wiseau and The Room at AFI Silver Theatre: Friday, June 11 through Sunday, June 13 |newspaper=Washington City Paper |date=2010-06-12 |accessdate=2011-01-17}}</ref> ''[[Mystery Science Theater 3000]]'' alumni [[Michael J. Nelson]], [[Kevin Murphy (actor)|Kevin Murphy]], and [[Bill Corbett]] produced an audio commentary track to accompany the movie through their site [[RiffTrax]].com. In 2013, the book ''[[The Disaster Artist]]'', written by [[Greg Sestero]] and [[Tom Bissell]], was published; the book is Sestero's memoir of his involvement in the production of the movie. The book was adapted into an Oscar-nominated film<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BNtvTr4hADk \"Call Me by Your Name\" wins Best Adapted Screenplay-Oscars on YouTube]</ref><ref>[https://www.oscars.org/oscars/ceremonies/2018 2018|Oscars.org]</ref> [[The Disaster Artist (film)|of the same name]], directed by and starring [[James Franco]] as Wiseau (winning a [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actor - Motion Picture Musical or Comedy|Best Actor Golden Globe Award]] for his performance)<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_81Peb7Atc4 James Franco Wins Best Actor, Musical or Comedy at the 2018 Golden Globes]</ref><ref>[https://www.goldenglobes.com/film/disaster-artist Disaster Artist, The|Golden Globes]</ref> and his brother [[Dave Franco]] as Sestero.\n\n=== ''Gigli'' (2003) ===\n\nThe [[Martin Brest]] movie ''[[Gigli]]'' features [[Jennifer Lopez]] and [[Ben Affleck]], with appearances by [[Al Pacino]] and [[Christopher Walken]]. ''Gigli'' was originally a [[black comedy]] with no romantic subplot. The producers demanded script rewrites throughout filming, hoping to cash in on the [[Jennifer Lopez#Ben Affleck|Lopez-Affleck romance]] that was big news in celebrity-watching publications of the time, such as ''[[Us Weekly|Us]]'' and ''[[People (magazine)|People]]''. This film cost $54 million to make but grossed only $6 million, making it one of the biggest box office bombs of all time. ''[[The Times]]'' gave the film a zero, making ''Gigli'' the lowest scored film review in the publication's history at that time.<ref name=\"IBT\">{{cite news|url=http://au.ibtimes.com/articles/271260/20111222/hollywood-s-5-worst-movies.htm#page1 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120110143252/http://au.ibtimes.com/articles/271260/20111222/hollywood-s-5-worst-movies.htm |url-status=dead |archive-date=2012-01-10 |title=Hollywood's Top 5 Worst Movies Ever Made |newspaper=International Business Times |accessdate=2013-06-19 }}</ref> ''[[International Business Times]]'', which included ''Gigli'' in its list of Hollywood's top five worst movies ever made, described reviewers calling it \"the ultimate turkey of all time\".<ref name=\"IBT\"/> ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'' stated that it was \"[t]he worst movie\u2014all right, the worst allegedly major movie\u2014of our admittedly young century\",<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2013/08/01/a-look-back-at-gigli-the-infamous-bennifer-starring-film-on-its-10th-anniversary.html |title=A Look Back at 'Gigli,' the Infamous Bennifer-Starring Film, on Its 10th Anniversary |website=The Daily Beast |date=2013-08-01 |accessdate=2013-09-20}}</ref> while [[Roger Friedman]] of [[Fox News]] claimed it was \"[t]he worst movie ever made\".<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/2003/07/30/gigli-is-up/ |title=The 'Gigli' Is Up |publisher=[[Fox News]]|date=2003-07-30 |accessdate=2013-09-20}}</ref> It was also the winner of seven [[Golden Raspberry Award|Razzies]] (including 2005's Worst \"Comedy\" of Our First 25 Years),<ref name=\"twenty-five\">{{cite web |url=http://www.razzies.com/asp/directory/25thWinners.htm |title=Halle's Feline Fiasco Catwoman and President's Fahrenheit Blunders Tie for 25th Razzie Dis-Honors |work=Razzies.com |accessdate=2011-03-07 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110315210719/http://www.razzies.com/asp/directory/25thWinners.htm |archive-date=2011-03-15 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and in 2010 the film was nominated at the [[30th Golden Raspberry Awards]] for \"Worst Picture of the Decade\".<ref name=\"30thRazzies\"/> It is in [[Rotten Tomatoes]]' Top 100 worst reviewed movies of the 2000s,<ref name=\"rottenworst\"/> where it has a 6% rating.<ref>{{rotten-tomatoes|id=gigli|title=Gigli}}</ref> It was also featured in ''[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]''{{'}}s poll of the 50 worst films ever made,<ref name=\"The 50 Worst Movies Ever\"/> and ''[[AfterEllen.com and TheBacklot.com|AfterEllen]]'' ranked it #1 in its list of the worst films of all time.<ref name=\"afterellen\" />\n\n=== ''Sex Lives of the Potato Men'' (2004) ===\n\nThe British [[sex comedy]] ''[[Sex Lives of the Potato Men]]'' is about a group of potato delivery men. The film received strongly hostile reviews from the British media. Reviews claimed ''Sex Lives of the Potato Men'' was unfunny, disgusting, and depressing.<ref name=\"slotpm1\">[https://web.archive.org/web/20131012015015/http://news.sky.com/story/248096/critics-pan-worst-film-ever Critics Pan \"Worst Film Ever\"] [[Sky News]], 23 February 2004. Retrieved 11 October 2013.</ref> Writing in the ''[[Daily Mirror]]'', film critic Kevin O'Sullivan called ''Sex Lives of the Potato Men'' \"one of the worst films ever made\".<ref>Kevin O'Sullivan, ''The Daily Mirror'', March 5th, 2004, (p.14)</ref> Novelist [[Will Self]], in his review for ''[[The Evening Standard]]'', called ''Sex Lives of the Potato Men'' \"mirthless, worthless, toothless, useless\".<ref name=\"slotpm1\" /> ''[[The Times]]'' reviewer James Christopher dubbed ''Sex Lives of the Potato Men'' \"one of the two most nauseous films ever made ... a masterclass in film-making ineptitude\".<ref name=\"slotpm1\" /> The ''[[Sunday Express]]'' film critic, Henry Fitzherbert, also strongly condemned the film: \"''Sex Lives'' is so awful it left me slack-jawed in disbelief ... it must be one of the worst British comedies.\"<ref>Henry Fitzherbert, ''The Sunday Express'', 22nd February 2004 (p.67).</ref> Catherine Shoard, in a critique in ''[[The Sunday Telegraph]]'', stated \"It's hard to know what to say to this \u2013 it's like finding the right words at a nasty accident ... ''Sex Lives of the Potato Men'' is probably the lewdest Brit-com since ''[[Confessions of a Window Cleaner]]'', and certainly the worst.\" Shoard also described the film as \"Less a film than an appetite suppressant.\"<ref>Catherine Shoard, ''The Sunday Telegraph'', 22nd February 2004.</ref> Alan Morrison in the Scottish ''[[Daily Record (Scotland)|Daily Record]]'' described it as \"puerile smut of the very worst kind ... ''Sex Lives of the Potato Men'' should never have been made\".<ref>\"Review:Sex Lives of the Potato Men''. ''Daily Record'', February 20th, 2004.</ref> ''[[The Irish Times]]'' later noted that \"''Sex Lives of the Potato Men'' attracted some of the worst reviews in living memory.\"<ref>Donald Clarke, \"Out of Office:Interview with Mackenzie Crook\". \"The Ticket\" Magazine, ''The Irish Times'', April 25th, 2008, (p.6).</ref> ''The [[Birmingham Post]]'' described ''Sex Lives of the Potato Men'' as \"quite possibly the worst film ever made\",<ref>Mike Davies, ''The Birmingham Post'', April 24, 2008 (p.&nbsp;13).</ref> while ''[[The Independent on Sunday]]'' stated that the film was \"a strong contender for the title of worst film of all time\".<ref>Matthew Bell, ''Independent on Sunday'', February 8, 2009, (p. 42).</ref> It was also featured in ''[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]''{{'}}s ''50 Worst Movies Ever'' poll.<ref name=\"The 50 Worst Movies Ever\"/> The film has a [[List of films with a 0% rating on Rotten Tomatoes|0% rating]] on [[Rotten Tomatoes]], based on 14 reviews.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://rottentomatoes.com/m/the-sex-lives-of-the-potato-men/ |title=Sex Lives Of The Potato Men on Rotten Tomatoes |publisher=Rottentomatoes.com |date= |accessdate=2015-01-12}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Catwoman'' (2004) ===\n\nNominally based on [[Catwoman|the DC Comics character]], ''[[Catwoman (film)|Catwoman]]'' stars [[Halle Berry]] as the title character. It bears little resemblance to the [[Batman]] antagonist: the cinematic Catwoman has [[superpower (ability)|superpowers]], unlike in the comics, and leaps from rooftop to rooftop in stiletto heels. The character's signature [[spandex|lycra]] [[catsuit]] was replaced with slashed leather trousers and matching [[bra]], and a mask that also acts as a hat. She also has a different name, Patience Phillips, to the established DC Catwoman character, Selina Kyle. As the movie character differs so widely from her comic book source, the character, as portrayed in this film, has been cited as \"Catwoman in Name Only\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.catwomanfan.com/en/film/2004/index.php |title=Catwoman (2004) |accessdate=2009-05-22}}</ref> The film was the result of various rewrites by a total of 28 different screenwriters, though only four were credited after arbitration with the WGA. It has a 9% rating at [[Rotten Tomatoes]],<ref>{{rotten-tomatoes|id=catwoman|title=Catwoman}}</ref> and was declared \"arguably the worst superhero film ever made\" by the ''[[Orlando Sentinel]]''. Jean Lowerison of the ''[[San Diego Metropolitan]]'' said in her review that ''Catwoman'' \"goes on my 'worst' list for the year, and quite possibly for all time\".<ref>{{cite web|author=Jean Lowerison |url=http://sandiegometro.archives.whsites.net/reel/index.php?reelID=713 |title='Catwoman' The cat and the Bratt |publisher=San Diego Metropolitan |accessdate=2011-01-17 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724130824/http://sandiegometro.archives.whsites.net/reel/index.php?reelID=713 |archivedate=2011-07-24 }}</ref> Sadaf Ahsan of the ''[[National Post]]'' went further, calling it the worst movie ever made.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://nationalpost.com/entertainment/movies/writer-of-the-worst-movie-of-all-time-agrees-that-it-was-indeed-the-worst-movie-of-all-time |title=Writer of the worst movie of all time agrees that it was, indeed, the worst movie of all time|last=Ahsan|first=Sadaf|date=February 27, 2018 |accessdate=March 19, 2018}}</ref> ''[[The Village Voice]]'' summed up reviews of the film under the title \"Me-Ouch\".<ref>{{cite news |author=Janet Kim |url=http://www.villagevoice.com/2004-07-20/film/me-ouch/1 |title=Me-Ouch \u2013 Page 1 \u2013 Movies \u2013 New York |newspaper=Village Voice |date=2004-07-20 |accessdate=2011-01-17 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110629162951/http://www.villagevoice.com/2004-07-20/film/me-ouch/1/ |archivedate=2011-06-29 }}</ref> The movie was the winner of four [[25th Golden Raspberry Awards|Razzies]] for Worst Picture, Worst Actress, Worst Director ([[Pitof]]) and Worst Screenplay.<ref name=\"twenty-five\"/> Berry arrived at the ceremony to accept her Razzie in person (with her Best Actress [[Academy Award|Oscar]] for ''[[Monster's Ball]]'' in hand), saying: \"First of all, I want to thank Warner Brothers. Thank you for putting me in a piece of shit, god-awful movie ... It was just what my career needed.\"<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=U-7s_yeQuDg Halle Berry accepts Razzie Award] official Razzie YouTube channel</ref> It is on Roger Ebert's \"most hated\" list<ref name=\"eberthated\"/> and ''[[International Business Times]]'' included it on its list of Hollywood's top 5 worst movies ever made.<ref name=\"IBT\"/>\n\n=== ''Daniel \u2013 Der Zauberer'' (''Daniel \u2013 The Wizard'') (2004) ===\nThe German film ''[[Daniel \u2013 Der Zauberer]]'' was directed by [[Ulli Lommel]] and stars pop singer and ex-''[[Deutschland sucht den Superstar]]'' contestant [[Daniel K\u00fcblb\u00f6ck]], who appeared as a fictionalized version of himself. The title is misleading as it implies that K\u00fcblb\u00f6ck is \"Der Zauberer\" (\"The Wizard\"), while the sorcerer is actually a different character (played by Ulli Lommel, the writer/director of the film). ''[[The Daily Dot]]'' wrote that it is considered to be the worst German film,<ref name=\"DailyDot\">{{cite web|url=https://www.dailydot.com/upstream/worst-movies-on-imdb/|title=Diving into the worst-rated movies on IMDb|date=December 11, 2015|work=[[The Daily Dot]]|accessdate=March 14, 2018}}</ref> while [[n-tv]] said it was \"possibly the worst movie ever made\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.n-tv.de/leute/Filmemacher-Ulli-Lommel-erliegt-Herzinfarkt-article20165706.html|title=Filmemacher Ulli Lommel erliegt Herzinfarkt|date=December 4, 2017|publisher=[[n-tv]]|accessdate=March 14, 2018|language=German}}</ref> The website ''filmstarts.de'' states that ''Daniel \u2013 Der Zauberer'' was \"unbearable for non-fans of K\u00fcblb\u00f6ck\", adding that \"the performances of the actors were some of the worst in the history of German cinema\", and alleging that Ulli Lommel and producer Peter Schamoni had \"damaged their reputation\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.filmstarts.de/kritiken/37527-Daniel-Der-Zauberer.html |title=Daniel \u2013 Der Zauberer \u2013 Film 2004 |publisher=Filmstarts.De |accessdate=2013-11-18}}</ref> \n\nThe film also [[Box-office bomb|performed extremely poorly at the box office]], having only 13.834 viewers altogether, which led to it being withdrawn from screening at most cinemas within the first week,<ref>{{Cite book|last=Astinus|first=A. D.|url=https://books.google.de/books?id=mucWDAAAQBAJ&pg=PT9&lpg=PT9&dq=daniel+der+zauberer+13.834&source=bl&ots=uEmugZlcAu&sig=ACfU3U3o7eW1w18qHQjHnlQPXSU7hBChTw&hl=de&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjX1p6GvZ_oAhUDDewKHRzoABwQ6AEwBHoECAoQAQ#v=onepage&q=daniel%20der%20zauberer%2013.834&f=false|title=Die neun schlechtesten Filme der Kinogeschichte: Die ganze Welt der schlechtesten Kinofilme - Von Daniel, der Zauberer bis Kartoffelsalat \u2013 Nicht fragen!|date=2015-09-30|publisher=neobooks|isbn=978-3-7380-4159-0|language=de}}</ref> with ''[[Rheinische Post|RP Online]]'' referring to it as a \"super-flop\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://rp-online.de/kultur/musik/kueblboeck-als-super-flop_aid-16831093|title=Kinos setzen \"Daniel der Zauberer\" ab: K\u00fcblb\u00f6ck als Super-Flop|last=ONLINE|first=RP|website=RP ONLINE|language=de|access-date=2019-10-04}}</ref> It is consistently listed at IMDb's Bottom 100 list and became the lowest rated film at one point.<ref name=\"NYDN\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/worst-movies-made-gallery-1.3678697|title=The worst movies ever made|last=Lisi|first=Brian|work=[[New York Daily News]]|accessdate=March 14, 2018}}</ref> ''[[Total Film]]'' listed it as the third worst film of all time, after ''[[Superbabies: Baby Geniuses 2]]'' and the direct-to-video animated [[mockbuster]] ''[[Titanic: The Legend Goes On]]'',<ref name=\"TotalFilm\" /> and ''[[New York Daily News]]'' listed it among the seven worst films ever made.<ref name=\"NYDN\" /> In an interview conducted several years after its release, Daniel K\u00fcblb\u00f6ck admitted that, in retrospect, \"[Y]ou have to say this is the worst movie of all time really\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fr-online.de/wiesbaden/ex-dsds-star-daniel-kueblboeck-ist-jetzt-wiesbadener,1472860,3195326.html|title=Daniel K\u00fcblb\u00f6ck ist jetzt Wiesbadener|date=15 February 2009|work=[[Frankfurter Rundschau]]|accessdate=13 September 2013|language=German}}</ref> ''Filmstarts.de'' ranked it #4 in its list of the 25 worst movies ever made,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.filmstarts.de/nachrichten/18494996.html?page=22|title=Die 25 schlechtesten Filme aller Zeiten|last=Filmstarts|website=FILMSTARTS.de|access-date=2019-03-08}}</ref> and on the German movie rating site ''[[Moviepilot.de]]'', it is the lowest-rated film with an average rating of 0.4/10.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.moviepilot.de/filme/schlechteste|title=Die schlechtesten Filme {{!}} moviepilot.de|website=www.moviepilot.de|language=de|access-date=2019-03-08}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Superbabies: Baby Geniuses 2'' (2004) ===\n\nThe family-oriented comedy ''[[Superbabies: Baby Geniuses 2]]'' was the last film directed by [[Bob Clark]] before his death. It is a sequel to the 1999 film ''[[Baby Geniuses]]'' and like its predecessor, it received negative reviews from film critics, becoming the 6th worst reviewed film of the decade on [[Rotten Tomatoes]] with a [[List of films with a 0% rating on Rotten Tomatoes|0% rating]].<ref name=\"rtbg2\">{{cite web|url=https://rottentomatoes.com/m/super_babies_baby_geniuses_2/|title=Rotten Tomatoes|accessdate=3 May 2012}}</ref> Following the plot of the first film, four babies can communicate with each other using 'baby talk', and have knowledge of many secrets. The \"baby geniuses\" become involved in a scheme by media mogul Bill Biscane ([[Jon Voight]]), a notorious kidnapper of children, who intends to use a satellite system to brainwash the world's population and force them to watch television for the rest of their lives. The film was a box office bomb, only receiving $9 million from its $20 million budget. David Cornelius at efilmcritic wondered \"Why would anyone want to make a follow-up to what is universally viewed as one of the very worst movies ever produced is a mystery for the ages.\"<ref name=\"efcsb\">{{cite news|url=http://www.efilmcritic.com/review.php?movie=10542&reviewer=392|title=SuperBabies: Baby Geniuses 2|last=Cornelius|first=David|date=December 15, 2004|work=efilmcritic.com|accessdate=3 May 2012}}</ref> ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' writer Joshua Rivera stated that it was the worst movie he had ever sat through,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://ew.com/article/2015/01/16/popwatch-confessional-worst-kids-movies/|title=PopWatch Confessional: The worst movie a kid has made you sit through|date=January 16, 2015|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|accessdate=April 3, 2018}}</ref> and Tom Long of ''The Deseret News'' said \"It is perhaps the most incompetent and least funny comic film ever made.\"<ref name=\"dnsb\">{{cite news|url=http://www.deseretnews.com/article/700003619/SuperBabies-Baby-Geniuses-2.html|title=SuperBabies: Baby Geniuses 2|last=Long|first=Tom|date=Nov 17, 2004|work=Deseret News|accessdate=3 May 2012}}</ref> It was nominated for four Golden Raspberry Awards including Worst Picture, Worst Director ([[Bob Clark]]), Worst Supporting Actor ([[Jon Voight]]) and Worst Screenplay ([[Steven Paul]] (story) & Gregory Poppen).<ref name=\"dtsb\">{{cite news|url=http://www.dailytimes.com.pk/default.asp?page=story_26-1-2005_pg9_6|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131111023112/http://www.dailytimes.com.pk/default.asp?page=story_26-1-2005_pg9_6|url-status=dead|archive-date=November 11, 2013|title='Catwoman' battles President Bush for worst acting prize|date=January 26, 2005|work=Daily Times|accessdate=3 May 2012}}</ref> ''[[Total Film]]'' named it the runner-up to ''[[Titanic: The Legend Goes On]]'' in its list of the worst films ever made,<ref name=\"TotalFilm\" /> and ''[[Mental Floss]]'' selected it as the second worst movie ever made after ''[[Ballistic: Ecks vs. Sever]]''.<ref name=\"Mental Floss\"/> It also briefly unseated ''Manos: The Hands of Fate'' from the top spot on IMDb's bottom 100 list.<ref name=\"smbg\">{{cite news|url=https://www.slantmagazine.com/film/review/superbabies-baby-geniuses-2/1318|title=Superbabies: Baby Geniuses 2|last=Henderson|first=Eric|date=January 31, 2005|work=Slant Magazine|accessdate=3 May 2012}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Alone in the Dark'' (2005) ===\n[[File:UweBollRampage3SHORTREVIEW1.jpg|thumb|[[Uwe Boll]] won a [[Stinkers Bad Movie Awards|Stinkers Awards]] for Worst Director and received the [[Golden Raspberry Awards#Worst Career Achievement|Worst Career Achievement]] award at the [[29th Golden Raspberry Awards]]]]\nLoosely based on a [[Alone in the Dark|series of video games]] by [[Infogrames]] and directed by [[Uwe Boll]], the German-Canadian-American film ''[[Alone in the Dark (2005 film)|Alone in the Dark]]'' was panned by critics for a multitude of reasons, including poor script and production values, quick cuts to optimize the gory content, almost no connection to the game, and bad acting. The movie has received a 1% rating at [[Rotten Tomatoes]],<ref>{{rotten-tomatoes|id=alone_in_the_dark|title=Alone in the Dark}}</ref> and was included in their Top 100 worst reviewed movies of the 2000s at number two.<ref name=\"rottenworst\"/> It appeared on Metacritic's list of the all-time lowest-scoring films,<ref name=\"Metacritic\"/> is on the MRQE's 50 Worst Movies list,<ref name=\"MRQE50\"/> and is one of the few films to have received an [[CinemaScore#List of F films|F rating]] on [[CinemaScore]].<ref name=\"CinemaScore\">{{cite news |last=Lincoln |first=Kevin |title=What the 19 Movies to Ever Receive an 'F' CinemaScore Have in Common |url=https://www.vulture.com/2017/09/here-are-the-only-19-movies-to-ever-receive-an-f-cinemascore.html |work=[[https://vulture.com|Vulture]] |date=September 20, 2017 |accessdate=January 17, 2019}}</ref>  Roger Moore of ''The [[Orlando Sentinel]]'' stated: \"''Alone in the Dark'' shows just how tenuous ''[[Plan 9 from Outer Space]]'' 's hold on that 'worst movie ever' title really is.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.orlandosentinel.com/entertainment/movies/orl-db-moviereviews-searchresults,0,3279701,results.formprofile?turbine_cdb_lib__cdb_01_txt=Alone%20in%20the%20Dark&Find+it!=Submit+Query |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110629101527/http://www.orlandosentinel.com/entertainment/movies/orl-db-moviereviews-searchresults,0,3279701,results.formprofile?turbine_cdb_lib__cdb_01_txt=Alone%20in%20the%20Dark&Find+it!=Submit+Query |url-status=dead |archive-date=2011-06-29 |title=Alone in the Dark |newspaper=The Orlando Sentinel |date=2005-01-28 |accessdate=2014-06-13 |first=Roger |last=Moore }}</ref> Likewise, Peter Hartlaub, the ''[[San Francisco Chronicle]]'''s pop culture critic, called the film \"the best Ed Wood movie ever made ... a film so mind-blowingly horrible that it teeters on the edge of cinematic immortality\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sfgate.com/movies/article/FILM-CLIPS-Also-opening-today-2702523.php#alone |title=Film Clips / Also opening today |newspaper=San Francisco Chronicle |date=2005-01-28 |accessdate=2013-11-18 |first=Ruthe |last=Stein}}</ref> In 2009, he named it the worst film of the decade.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2010/01/01/MV9A1BAHMM.DTL&type=movies | work=The San Francisco Chronicle | title=Decade in review: Hartlaub's movie choices | date=2010-07-30}}</ref> Jeffrey Lyles of ''The Gazette'' considered it so bad that \"other legendary bad films ... await a film of this magnitude because it gets awfully lonely on the island of misfit movies\",<ref>{{cite news|url=http://ww2.gazette.net/gazette_archive/2005/200505/entertainment/moviefeat/258216-1.html |title='Dark' is dreary |newspaper=[[The Gazette (Maryland)]] |date=2005-02-02 |accessdate=2013-11-18}}</ref> while Scott Nash of ''Three Movie Buffs'' dubbed it \"one of the worst movies ever made\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://rottentomatoes.com/m/alone_in_the_dark/reviews/ |title=Alone in the Dark |website=Rotten Tomatoes |accessdate=2014-06-13}}</ref> Screenwriter Blair Erickson wrote about his experience dealing with Boll and his original script, which was closer to the actual game itself, and Boll's script change demands on the comedy website ''[[Something Awful]]''.<ref>{{cite news | title = Behind the Scenes: Uwe Boll and Uwe Boll's Alone In the Dark | url = https://somethingawful.com/feature-articles/behind-scenes-uwe/1/ | first = Blair | last = Erickson | date = 2005-02-02 | publisher = Something Awful}}</ref> It received two [[2005 Golden Raspberry Awards]] nominations for Worst Director (Uwe Boll) and Worst Actress ([[Tara Reid]]), and won three 2005 [[Stinkers Bad Movie Awards|Stinkers Awards]], for Worst Picture, Worst Director, and Worst Special Effects.<ref name=\"2005stinkers\">{{cite web|last=Weinberg |first=Scott |url=https://rottentomatoes.com/news/1646425/2005_stinker_awards_announced |title=2005 Stinker Awards Announced! |website=Rotten Tomatoes |date=2006-03-03 |accessdate=2011-01-17}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Aag'' (2007) ===\n\n''[[Aag (2007 film)|Aag]]'' is a remake of one of the most successful [[Bollywood]] films, ''[[Sholay]]'', directed by [[Ram Gopal Varma]]. [[Rajeev Masand]] gave it a zero out of five.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ibnlive.in.com/news/review-rgv-ki-aag-is-rgv-ka-daag/47834-8.html|title=Review: RGV Ki Aag is RGV ka daag}}</ref> ''[[Times of India]]'' stated that ''Aag'' \"destroyed Bollywood's greatest film\" and acknowledged that some \"consider it the world's worst film\".<ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2010-12-31/news-interviews/28236351_1_rakhi-sawant-salman-khan-vivek-oberoi |title=A Decade of decadence |newspaper=[[Times of India]] |date=2010-12-31 |accessdate=2013-08-25}}</ref> ''[[Hindustan Times]]'' awarded it the \"Lifetime's Worst Ever Movie Award\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/Entertainment/Reviews/Review-Ram-Gopal-Varma-Ki-Aag/Article1-245543.aspx |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111117015847/http://www.hindustantimes.com/Entertainment/Reviews/Review-Ram-Gopal-Varma-Ki-Aag/Article1-245543.aspx |url-status=dead |archive-date=2011-11-17 |title=Review: Ram Gopal Varma Ki Aag |newspaper=[[Hindustan Times]] |date=2007-08-31 |accessdate=2013-08-25 }}</ref> It came in first in a ''[[FHM (India)|FHM India]]'' list of the 57 worst movies ever made.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fhmindia.com/57-worst-films-ever-ii/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120912012157/http://www.fhmindia.com/57-worst-films-ever-ii/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=2012-09-12 |title=57 Worst Films Ever \u2013 II |publisher=[[FHM (India)]] |accessdate=2013-08-25 }}</ref> ''[[Total Film]]'' included it in their list of the 66 worst films of all time.<ref name=TotalFilm/> [[Amitabh Bachchan]], who appeared in the original film and returned for the remake, later admitted that the film was \"a mistake\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.digitalspy.com/bollywood/news/a329312/amitabh-bachchan-ram-gopal-varma-ki-aag-a-mistake.html |title= Amitabh Bachchan: 'Ram Gopal Varma Ki Aag a mistake' |website=[[Digital Spy]]|accessdate=2013-08-25}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Epic Movie'' (2007) ===\n\n''[[Epic Movie]]'' is a [[parody film]] by [[Jason Friedberg and Aaron Seltzer]] that mainly parodies [[Epic film|epic]] and [[Fantasy film|fantasy movies]], most notably ''[[The Chronicles of Narnia: The Lion, the Witch and the Wardrobe]]'' and the ''[[Harry Potter (film series)|Harry Potter]]'' films, but also contains references to all kinds of other then-popular films. Like most works of Frieberg and Seltzer, it received extremely negative reviews, holding an approval rating of 2% on [[Rotten Tomatoes]],<ref>{{Citation|title=Epic Movie (2007)|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/epic_movie|language=en|access-date=2019-02-25}}</ref> and a [[Metacritic]] score of 17/100, indicating \"overwhelming dislike\".<ref>{{Citation|title=Epic Movie|url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/epic-movie|access-date=2019-02-25}}</ref> Harry Fletcher of the ''[[Evening Standard|Standard]]'' said: \"Filmmakers and trash-peddlers Jason Friedberg and Aaron Seltzer have been responsible for some of the most pointless, lazy and unforgivable movies of the past decade and frankly, they need to be stopped. ''[[Disaster Movie]]'', ''[[300 (film)|300]]'' spoof ''[[Meet the Spartans]]'' and awful ''[[The Hunger Games (film)|Hunger Games]]'' mickey-take ''[[The Starving Games]]'' could easily have made this list of the worst movies ever made, but ''Epic Movie'' might be the worst of the lot. It offers the most uninspired, unfunny film pastiches imaginable, sometimes repeating entire sections of dialogue verbatim from the movies they\u2019re supposedly satirising.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/go/london/film/the-12-worst-films-ever-made-a3838756.html|title=The 12 worst films ever made|date=2018-05-15|website=Evening Standard|language=en|access-date=2019-02-25}}</ref> [[Nathan Rabin]] gave it an F score and said, \"''Epic Movie'' [...] strays so far from the solid fundamentals of filmmaking that it calls the very foundation of humor into question.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://film.avclub.com/epic-movie-1798202359|title=Epic Movie|last=Rabin|first=Nathan|website=Film|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-25}}</ref> Josh Rosenblatt of ''[[The Austin Chronicle]]'' said: \"I\u2019ve rarely seen a movie as hostile as this one, both to its audience and to its protagonists, and I don\u2019t think I realized before just how mean-spirited comedy can get (and I was raised on the Three Stooges).\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.austinchronicle.com/events/film/2007-01-26/438452/|title=Movie Review: Epic Movie|website=www.austinchronicle.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-25}}</ref> Jamie Russell of the [[BBC]] called it \"the most excruciating, unfunny film you'll see this year\u2026 if not your entire lifetime.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/films/2007/02/05/epic_movie_2007_review.shtml|title=BBC - Movies - review - Epic Movie|website=www.bbc.co.uk|access-date=2019-02-25}}</ref> At the [[28th Golden Raspberry Awards]], it received three nominations, for ''Worst Remake or Rip-off'', ''Worst Screenplay'' and ''Worst Supporting Actress'' ([[Carmen Electra]]). It is included in ''[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]''<nowiki/>'s and ''[[Flavorwire]]''<nowiki/>'s lists of the 50 worst movies ever made,<ref name=\"The 50 Worst Movies Ever\" /><ref name=\"Flavorwire\" /> ''[[Evening Standard|Standard]]''<nowiki/>'s list of the 12 worst films ever made, [[Movie Review Query Engine|MRQE]]'s 50 worst movies list<ref name=\"MRQE50\" /> and ''[[Newsweek]]''<nowiki/>'s list of the 50 worst comedy movies of all time.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/worst-comedy-movies-all-time-ranked-1071735|title=The worst comedy films of all time, from 'Scary Movie 5' to 'The Hottie & the Nottie'|last=Sim|first=David|last2=AM|first2=Eve Watling On 8/14/18 at 8:08|date=2018-08-14|website=Newsweek|language=en|access-date=2019-02-25}}</ref>\n\n=== ''I Know Who Killed Me'' (2007) ===\n''[[I Know Who Killed Me]]'' is a [[psychological thriller]] film directed by [[Chris Sivertson]] and starring [[Lindsay Lohan]] as identical twins, one of whom insists her identity is that of another woman after being abducted by a [[serial killer]]. At the [[28th Golden Raspberry Awards]], it set a record for most awards won in a single year by winning eight awards and it received two further nominations at the [[30th Golden Raspberry Awards]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2008/SHOWBIZ/Movies/02/23/razzie.awards/|title=Lohan's 'Killed Me' sets worst-film record - CNN.com|publisher=[[CNN]]|author=Leopold, Todd|date=February 23, 2008|accessdate=February 12, 2019}}</ref> The ''[[How Did This Get Made?]]'' podcast questioned, \"Is this the worst movie Lindsay Lohan has ever been in or flat out the worst movie ever?\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.earwolf.com/episode/i-know-who-killed-me/ |title= I Know Who Killed Me |publisher=[[Earwolf]]|work=[[How Did This Get Made?]]|date=October 18, 2011|accessdate=February 12, 2019}}</ref> [[Richard Roeper]] selected the film as the worst of the 2000s.<ref>{{cite book |first=Croft |last=Ally |url=https://books.google.com/?id=XOMzAgAAQBAJ&pg=PT87&dq=I+know+who+killed+me+richard+roeper#v=onepage&q=I%20know%20who%20killed%20me%20richard%20roeper&f=false|title= The Lindsay Lohan Story |publisher=[[Orion Publishing Group]] |year=2012 |isbn=978-1409136378}}</ref> Gabe Delahaye of ''[[Stereogum]]'' reviewed ''I Know Who Killed Me'' as part of his search for the worst movie ever made, writing that: \"Out of all the possible Worst Movies of All Time so far, none has been as painful to actually watch as I Know Who Killed Me\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.stereogum.com/1779984/the_hunt_for_the_worst_movie_o_10/vg-loc/videogum/|title=The Hunt For The Worst Movie Of All Time: I Know Who Killed Me|work=[[Stereogum]]|last=Delahaye|first=Gabe|date=June 23, 2008|accessdate=February 12, 2019}}</ref> It was named the 34th worst movie ever made in ''[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]''{{'}}s ''50 Worst Movies Ever'' poll<ref name=\"The 50 Worst Movies Ever\"/> and [[AfterEllen.com and TheBacklot.com|After Ellen]] named it the second worst ever made, after ''[[Gigli]]''.<ref name=\"afterellen\"/> MRQE includes it on its 50 Worst Movies list,<ref name=\"MRQE50\"/> and it has a rare [[CinemaScore#List of F films|F rating]] on [[CinemaScore]].<ref name=\"CinemaScore\"/>\n\n=== ''Meet the Spartans'' (2008) ===\nAnother 2008 parody movie by [[Jason Friedberg and Aaron Seltzer]], ''[[Meet the Spartans]]'' mainly parodied the movie ''[[300 (film)|300]]'', but contained numerous other pop cultural references as well. Like most Friedberg and Seltzer projects, it received extremely negative reviews, holding an approval rating of 2% on Rotten Tomatoes, with the consensus reading: \"A tired, unfunny, offensive waste of time, ''Meet the Spartans'' scrapes the bottom of the cinematic barrel.\",<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/meet_the_spartans|title=Meet the Spartans (2008)|last=|first=|date=|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango]]|access-date=April 17, 2019}}</ref> and a Metacritic score of 9/100, indicating \"overwhelming dislike\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/meet-the-spartans|title=Meet the Spartans|last=|first=|date=|website=[[Metacritic]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|access-date=April 17, 2019}}</ref> [[Josh Levin]] of ''[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]'' called it the worst movie he had ever seen.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://slate.com/culture/2008/01/meet-the-spartans-another-terrible-spoof-movie-from-the-nongeniuses-who-brought-you-date-movie-and-epic-movie.html|title=Meet the Spartans: another terrible spoof movie from the nongeniuses who brought you Date Movie and Epic Movie.|last=Levin|first=Josh|date=2008-01-30|website=Slate Magazine|language=en|access-date=2019-03-04}}</ref> It is included in ''[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]''<nowiki/>'s<ref name=\"The 50 Worst Movies Ever\" /> and ''[[Flavorwire|Flavorwire'<nowiki/>]]''s<ref name=\"Flavorwire\" /> lists of the 50 worst movies ever made, ''[[News.com.au]]''<nowiki/>'s list of the 15 worst films of all time,<ref name=\":1\" /> Metacritic's list of the all-time lowest-scoring films<ref name=\"Metacritic\" /> and [[Movie Review Query Engine|MRQE]]'s 50 Worst Movies list.<ref name=\"MRQE50\" /> At the [[29th Golden Raspberry Awards]], it received five nominations, including Worst Picture.\n\n<nowiki/>''[[Flavorwire|<nowiki/>]]''<nowiki/>''[[Flavorwire|<nowiki/>]]''<nowiki/><nowiki/>''[[Flavorwire|<nowiki/>]]''<nowiki/>''[[Flavorwire|<nowiki/>]]''<nowiki/>''[[Flavorwire|<nowiki/>]]''<nowiki/>''[[Flavorwire|<nowiki/>]]''\n\n=== ''Disaster Movie'' (2008) ===\n\n''[[Disaster Movie]]'' is a [[parody film]] written and directed by [[Jason Friedberg and Aaron Seltzer]], spoofing films in the [[Disaster films|disaster film]] genre. The film, like most films by Friedberg and Seltzer, received extremely negative reviews, and has a 1% rating on [[Rotten Tomatoes]] based on 73 reviews. The site's consensus states: \"Returning to their seemingly bottomless well of flatulence humor, racial stereotypes, and stale pop culture gags, Friedberg and Seltzer have produced what is arguably their worst ''Movie'' yet\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://rottentomatoes.com/m/disaster_movie/|title=Disaster Movie \u2013 Rotten Tomatoes|website=Rotten Tomatoes|accessdate=June 3, 2013}}</ref> It was ranked by Rotten Tomatoes as one of the worst reviewed films of the 2000s.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.cnn.com/2009/SHOWBIZ/Movies/09/25/decades.worst.movies.tomatoes/ | title = Site picks worst movies of the decade | work=[[CNN]] | date= 2009-09-25 | accessdate = 2013-04-17}}</ref> [[Jason Solomons]] of ''[[The Guardian]]'' stated that \"Nothing can convey the grimness of ''Disaster Movie'', which would be the Worst Movie Ever Made were it actually a movie at all.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Solomons|first=Jason|title=Disaster Movie|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2008/sep/07/comedy|work=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=June 3, 2013 | date=September 6, 2008|location=London}}</ref> Adam Tobias of ''[[Watertown Daily Times]]'' claimed that \"I just don't see how anyone could not find ''Disaster Movie'' one of the worst films of all time.\" Tobias went on to write that the title was appropriate because the film is \"a disaster\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Tobias|first=Adam|title=Disaster Movie one of the worst films of all time|url=http://www.wdtimes.com/features/screen_scenes/article_a665de71-6454-5ce5-9454-d13b9ad9ee18.html|work=[[Watertown Daily Times]]|accessdate=June 3, 2013|date=September 5, 2008}}</ref> It was featured in [[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]'s ''50 Worst Movies Ever'' poll,<ref name=\"The 50 Worst Movies Ever\"/> [[Total Film]]'s ''66 Worst Movies Ever'' list<ref name=TotalFilm /> Metacritic's list of the all-time lowest-scoring films,<ref name=\"Metacritic\"/> and the MRQE's 50 Worst Movies list (where it holds a score of 17, the lowest score on the site).<ref name=\"MRQE50\"/> ''Disaster Movie'' became the lowest ranked film on [[Internet Movie Database|IMDb]]'s Bottom 100 list days after its premiere<ref name=\"vh1.com\">{{cite web | url = http://www.vh1.com/celebrity/2008-09-05/update-disaster-movie-is-the-worst-collection-of-things-posing-as-a-movie-of-all-time | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20130927040609/http://www.vh1.com/celebrity/2008-09-05/update-disaster-movie-is-the-worst-collection-of-things-posing-as-a-movie-of-all-time | url-status = dead | archive-date = 2013-09-27 | title = Disaster Movie is the worst [Collection of things posing as a] movie of all time | work=[[VH1]] | date= 2008-09-05 | accessdate = 2013-04-17}}</ref><ref name=\"Byrnes\">{{cite news|last=Byrnes|first=Paul|title=Disaster Movie|url=https://www.smh.com.au/news/entertainment/film/film-reviews/disaster-movie/2008/10/02/1222651235778.html|work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|accessdate=June 3, 2013|date=October 2, 2008}}</ref> and it received a rare [[CinemaScore#List of F films|F rating]] on [[CinemaScore]].<ref name=\"CinemaScore\"/> The film is also notable for being the motion picture debut of [[Kim Kardashian]], whose performance garnered a nomination for [[Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Supporting Actress|Worst Supporting Actress]] at the [[29th Golden Raspberry Awards]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Fleeman|first=Mike|title=Kim Kardashian: Thanks for the Razzie Nomination! |url=http://www.peoplestylewatch.com/people/stylewatch/redcarpet/2009/article/0,,20249205_20254091,00.html|work=[[People (magazine)|People]]|accessdate=June 3, 2013|date=January 21, 2009}}</ref> It received five additional Razzie nominations.\n\n=== ''The Hottie and the Nottie'' (2008) ===\n\nThe romantic comedy ''[[The Hottie and the Nottie]]'' starring [[Paris Hilton]], [[Joel Moore]], [[Christine Lakin]], and [[The Greg Wilson]] opened to poor box-office takings and strongly negative reviews with a 5% rating on [[Rotten Tomatoes]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/hottie_and_the_nottie|title=The Hottie and the Nottie (2008)|last=|first=|date=|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango]]|access-date=12 July 2018}}</ref> The British newspaper ''[[The Sunday People|The People]]'', reviewing ''The Hottie and the Nottie'', claimed \"Paris Hilton is the world's worst actress and she's starring in the worst movie ever made.\"<ref name=\"tp\">{{cite news|title=The Hottie and the Nottie Review|date=March 23, 2008|newspaper=The People|location=London, England|quote=Disaster Of Paris; Bimbo is worst actress ever}}</ref> Nathan Lee of ''[[The Village Voice]]'' called it \"crass, shrill, disingenuous, tawdry, mean-spirited, vulgar, idiotic, boring, slapdash, half-assed, and very, very unfunny\".<ref>{{cite web|author=Nathan Lee |url=http://www.villagevoice.com/2008-01-29/film/the-hottie-and-the-nottie |title=Village Voice Review |publisher=Villagevoice.com |date=2008-01-29 |accessdate=2012-12-06}}</ref> Online film critic [[James Berardinelli]] described the film's comedy as \"about as funny as the anal [[rape]] scene in ''[[The War Zone]]''\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.reelviews.net/movies/h/hottie_nottie.html |title=James Berardinelli review |publisher=Reelviews.net |date=2007-05-13 |accessdate=2012-12-06}}</ref> [[Richard Roeper]] called it \"excruciatingly, painfully, horribly, terribly awful\", and argued that \"nobody in this movie really should have a career in movies\".<ref name=\"thatn\">{{cite web |url=https://rottentomatoes.com/m/hottie_and_the_nottie/ |website=Rotten Tomatoes |title=The Hottie and The Nottie |accessdate=25 October 2014 }}</ref> Connie Ogle in the ''[[Miami Herald]]'' described ''The Hottie and the Nottie'' thus: \"Imagine the worst movie you've ever seen. Got it? Now try to think of something worse. That something is this movie \u2013 wretched, embarrassing and a waste of the time and energy of everyone involved.\"<ref name=\"thatn\"/> The film appears on Metacritic's list of the all-time lowest-scoring films,<ref name=\"Metacritic\"/> and the MRQE's 50 Worst Movies list.<ref name=\"MRQE50\"/>\n\n== 2010s ==\n\n=== ''Birdemic: Shock and Terror'' (2010) ===\n[[File:Rifftrax_live_show_birdemic.jpg|thumb|right|[[Bill Corbett]], [[Michael J. Nelson|Mike Nelson]], and [[Kevin Murphy (actor)|Kevin Murphy]] during the live [[Rifftrax]] of [[Birdemic: Shock and Terror|''Birdemic'']]]]\nAn independently produced film that is an apparent homage to [[Alfred Hitchcock]]'s ''[[The Birds (film)|The Birds]]'', ''[[Birdemic: Shock and Terror]]'' tells the story of a romance between the two leading characters, played by Alan Bagh and Whitney Moore, as their small town is attacked by birds (which do not appear until 47 minutes into the film). Written, directed, and produced by James Nguyen, it was intended as a \"romantic thriller\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.viceland.com/blogs/en/2010/02/12/james-nguyens-birdemic-is-the-new-best-worst-movie-ever/ |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120914135451/http://www.viceland.com/blogs/en/2010/02/12/james-nguyens-birdemic-is-the-new-best-worst-movie-ever/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=2012-09-14 |title=Birdemic Has Romance and Suspense and All That |publisher=Viceland Today |date=2010-02-12 |accessdate=2011-04-16}}</ref> but is notable due to its poor quality, with reviewers calling out its wooden acting, bad dialogue, amateurish sound and editing, nonsensical plot and, in particular, its special effects, consisting primarily of poorly rendered computer generated eagles and vultures that perform physically awkward aerial maneuvers and explode upon impact with the ground. The film, which cost $10,000 to make,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/8604858.stm |title=Is Birdemic worst film ever made? |work=BBC News |date=2010-04-06 |accessdate=2011-04-16}}</ref> was called by the ''[[Huffington Post]]'' \"truly, one of the worst films ever made\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/review-embirdemic-shock-a_b_491140|first=Fabio|last=Periera |title=Review: Birdemic: Shock and Terror |work=HuffPost |date=2010-03-09 |accessdate=2019-12-03}}</ref> and by ''[[The Village Voice]]'' as \"one more in the pantheon of beloved trash-terpieces\".<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.villagevoice.com/2010-03-30/film/birdemic-shock-and-terror-one-more-for-the-trash-terpiece-heap/ |title=Birdemic: Shock and Terror, One More for the Trash-terpiece Heap |newspaper=The Village Voice |date=2010-03-30 |accessdate=2011-04-16 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110320100812/http://www.villagevoice.com/2010-03-30/film/birdemic-shock-and-terror-one-more-for-the-trash-terpiece-heap/ |archivedate=2011-03-20 }}</ref> ''[[Flavorwire]]'' ranked it #1 in its list of the 50 worst films ever made.<ref name=\"Flavorwire\"/> ''[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]'' deemed it among the worst movies ever made,<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.slate.com/id/2249870/pagenum/all/#p2 |title=The Worst Movies Ever Made |magazine=Slate |last1=Weiner|first1=Jonah|date=2010-04-06 |accessdate=2011-04-16}}</ref> while ''[[Salon (magazine)|Salon]]'' referred to it as \"a cult hit among bad-movie fans\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.salon.com/entertainment/movies/film_salon/2011/02/25/birdemic_review |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110228043216/http://www.salon.com/entertainment/movies/film_salon/2011/02/25/birdemic_review |url-status=dead |archive-date=2011-02-28 |title=\"Birdemic\": The magic of atrocious CGI, confirmed |work=Salon |date=2011-02-25 |accessdate=2011-05-06 }}</ref> and ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' stated that the film displayed \"all the revered hallmarks of hilariously bad filmmaking\".<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://variety.com/review/VE1117942491?refcatid=31 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110629203625/https://variety.com/review/VE1117942491?refcatid=31 |url-status=dead |archive-date=2011-06-29 |title=Variety Reviews \u2013 Birdemic: Shock and Terror |magazine=Variety |date=2010-03-29 |accessdate=2011-05-06 |first=Ronnie |last=Scheib}}</ref> Following the home media release of ''Birdemic'', [[Michael J. Nelson]], [[Kevin Murphy (actor)|Kevin Murphy]], and [[Bill Corbett]] of ''[[Mystery Science Theater 3000]]'' fame produced an audio commentary track to accompany the movie through [[Rifftrax]]. They later riffed upon the film again theatrically.<ref>{{cite web|author=eas106 |url=http://www.fandango.com/rifftraxlive:birdemic_157390/movieoverview |title=RiffTrax Live: Birdemic (2012) Movie Tickets, Reviews, and Photos |work=Fandango.com |date=2012-10-25 |accessdate=2013-11-18}}</ref> In response to the cult status of the first film, a sequel\u2014''[[Birdemic 2: The Resurrection]]''\u2014was released in 2013, and included many returning members of the cast and crew.\n\n=== ''The Last Airbender'' (2010) ===\n\n''[[The Last Airbender]]'' is a fantasy/adventure film written, produced, and directed by [[M. Night Shyamalan]] and is based on the [[Nicktoon]] ''[[Avatar: The Last Airbender]]''. Upon release, the film received extremely negative reviews, with critics panning the bad acting, numerous [[plot hole]]s, screenplay, poor special effects (despite its reported $150 million budget), and especially Shyamalan's directing. It was also ridiculed for the poor quality of its [[2D to 3D conversion|post-converted 3-D]], and the casting of white and Indian actors to portray characters who were East Asian or [[Inuit]] in the source material triggered accusations of racism and [[whitewashing in film|whitewashing]].<ref>{{cite news|author=Graeme McMillan|title=Avatar Casting Makes Fans See... White|accessdate=2008-12-19|date=2008-12-17|url=http://io9.com/5111680/avatar-casting-makes-fans-see-white| work=[[io9]]| publisher=[[Gawker Media]]}}</ref> Further criticism came from fans of the original cartoon series, who said the film differed tremendously from its critically acclaimed source material. David Onda of [[Comcast]] wrote that it \"has been called one of the worst ever made. The movie was universally panned by critics and failed to make back its production budget domestically.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Onda|first=David|title=The Last Airbender|url=http://xfinity.comcast.net/slideshow/entertainment-franchiseflops/10/|work=Comcast|accessdate=22 December 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131224104351/http://xfinity.comcast.net/slideshow/entertainment-franchiseflops/10/|archivedate=24 December 2013}}</ref> It garnered nine nominations at the [[31st Golden Raspberry Awards]], and won five, including Worst Picture and Worst Director.<ref>{{cite journal | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-12589752 | journal=BBC News | date= 27 February 2011 | title=M Night Shyamalan's Last Airbender wins Razzie Awards | accessdate=2011-02-27 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=The 31st Annual Razzie Awards|url=http://razzies.com/history/11winners.asp|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130103033553/http://razzies.com/history/11winners.asp|archivedate=2013-01-03}}</ref> [[Roger Ebert]] wrote, \"''The Last Airbender'' is an agonizing experience in every category I can think of and others still waiting to be invented. The laws of chance suggest that something should have gone right. Not here. It puts a nail in the coffin of low-rent 3D, but it will need a lot more coffins than that.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Ebert|first=Roger|title=The Last Airbender|url=https://rogerebert.com/reviews/the-last-airbender-2010|work=Chicago Sun-Times|accessdate=22 December 2013}}</ref> When asked if ''Last Airbender'' had been the worst film he has ever seen, Mike Ryan of ''[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]'' answered, \"Yes\".<ref>{{cite web|last=Ryan|first=Mike|title=25 Questions You May Have About The Last Airbender|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/online/oscars/2010/07/25-questions-you-may-have-about-the-last-airbender|work=Vanity Fair|date=July 1, 2010|accessdate=22 December 2013}}</ref> ''[[Hi (magazine)|Hi]]'' highlighted the film in their \"Worst Films Ever\" series,<ref>{{cite web|last1=Wilson|first1=Natasha|title=The Worst Films Ever: The Last Airbender|url=http://www.hihimag.com/hi/ents/film/2013/08/the-worst-films-ever-the-last-airbender/|website=Hi! Magazine|accessdate=29 June 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140808051629/http://www.hihimag.com/hi/ents/film/2013/08/the-worst-films-ever-the-last-airbender/|archive-date=2014-08-08|url-status=dead}}</ref> and [[Screen Rant]] and ''[[Digital Trends]]'' included it in their worst film lists.<ref name=\"Screen Rant\"/><ref name=\"digitaltrends\"/>\n\n=== ''Bucky Larson: Born to Be a Star'' (2011) ===\n''[[Bucky Larson: Born to Be a Star]]'' was produced by [[Adam Sandler]]'s [[Happy Madison Productions]] and featured [[Nick Swardson]] in the titular role as a small-town manchild who pursues a career in the [[pornographic film]] industry after learning that his parents were [[Pornographic film actor|porn star]]s in the 1970s. On [[Rotten Tomatoes]], ''Bucky Larson'' has a [[List of films with a 0% rating on Rotten Tomatoes|0% rating]] based on 35 reviews.<ref name=\"BuckyRotten\">{{cite news| title=Bucky Larson: Born to Be a Star (2011)|website=Rotten Tomatoes|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/bucky_larson_born_to_be_a_star/reviews/| accessdate= August 11, 2017 }}</ref> Linda Cook of the ''[[Quad-City Times]]'' described the film as \"the worst of the worst\",<ref>{{cite news|url=http://qctimes.com/entertainment/columnists/linda-cook/bucky-is-the-worst-of-the-worst/article_77c4eeea-dd6b-11e0-93fe-001cc4c03286.html|title='Bucky' is the worst of the worst|newspaper=[[Quad-City Times]]|last=Cook|first=Linda|date=September 12, 2011|accessdate=August 11, 2017}}</ref> while ''hollywoodchicago.com'' called it \"one of the worst comedies of all time\".<ref name=\"BuckyRotten\"/> In listing it as one of the ten worst comedies ever, [[Michael Musto]] stated that ''Bucky Larson'' was \"a badness the world had forgotten was capable of existing\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theblot.com/10-worst-film-comedies-ever-made-7720429|title=The 10 worst comedies ever made|last=Musto|first=Michael|work=The Blot Magazine|date=June 12, 2014|accessdate=August 11, 2017}}</ref> [[Screen Rant]] included it in its list of the 25 worst movies in film history and [[Mental Floss]] named it the fifth worst movie ever.<ref name=\"Screen Rant\">{{cite news|url=https://screenrant.com/worst-movies-list-all-time/|title=25 Worst Movies in Film History|last=Kendrick|first=Ben|work=[[Screen Rant]]|date=November 13, 2015|accessdate=August 11, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Mental Floss\">{{cite news|url=http://mentalfloss.com/article/503248/15-worst-movies-ever-made|title=The 15 Worst Movies Ever Made|last=Wood|first=Jennifer M|work=[[Mental Floss]]|date=August 10, 2017|accessdate=August 11, 2017}}</ref> ''Bucky Larson'' also appears on MRQE's 50 Worst Movies list,<ref name=\"MRQE50\"/> and Metacritic's list of the all-time lowest-scoring films.<ref name=\"Metacritic\"/> The film earned six nominations at the [[32nd Golden Raspberry Awards]], but lost in every category to ''[[Jack and Jill (2011 film)|Jack and Jill]]'', which was also produced by Happy Madison Productions.<ref name=RazzieWin/>\n\n=== ''Jack and Jill'' (2011) ===\n[[File:Adam Sandler 2011 (Cropped).jpg|thumb|[[Adam Sandler]] starred in ''[[Jack and Jill (2011 film)|Jack and Jill]]'' and ''[[That's My Boy (2012 film)|That's My Boy]]''. He also produced these films, as well as ''[[The Master of Disguise]]'' and ''[[Bucky Larson: Born to Be a Star]]''.]]\n''[[Jack and Jill (2011 film)|Jack and Jill]]'' is a comedy film starring [[Adam Sandler]] as Jack, a commercial director, who is visited by his \"identical\" twin sister, Jill (played by Sandler, in [[drag (clothing)|drag]]), during the holidays. ''[[Salon (magazine)|Salon]]'' stated that ''Jack and Jill'' \"received some of the worst reviews of any movie ever\" upon its release.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.salon.com/2011/11/14/the_tragedy_of_adam_sandler/|title=The tragedy of Adam Sandler|work= [[Salon (magazine)|Salon]] |last1=Eggers|first1=Toph|date=2011-11-14|accessdate=2013-08-23}}</ref> In the film, Jill is wooed by [[Al Pacino]], whom Jack wants to be in his [[Dunkin' Donuts]] commercial. [[Richard Roeper]] of the ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'' noted the irony of Pacino's presence, as the actor is best known for playing [[Michael Corleone]] in ''[[The Godfather]]'', which is widely considered [[list of films considered the best|one of the best films ever made]], in this film, which he called \"one of the worst movies in the history of cinema!\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.richardroeper.com/reviews/footlooselikecrazyandjackandjill.aspx|title=Footloose, Like Crazy, and Jack and Jill|publisher=Richard Roeper & The Movies|last1=Roeper|first1=Richard|accessdate=2013-04-25}}</ref> Ramin Setoodeh of ''[[The Daily Beast]]'' and [[Peter Travers]] of ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' reviewed it together in an article entitled \"Adam Sandler's 'Jack and Jill' Is the Worst Movie Ever Made\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2011/11/11/movie-review-adam-sandler-s-jack-and-jill-is-the-worst-movie-ever-made.html|title=Movie Review: Adam Sandler's 'Jack and Jill' Is the Worst Movie Ever Made|website=The Daily Beast|last1=Setoodeh|first1=Ramin|date=2011-11-11|accessdate=2013-04-25}}</ref> After an hour-long critique, [[RedLetterMedia]] claimed that it was \"so egregious that it ceased to be a film\", and the site also later called it \"the worst thing in the world\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://redlettermedia.com/half-in-the-bag-jack-and-jill/|title=Half in the Bag: Jack and Jill|publisher=RedLetterMedia|author=Mike Stoklasa, Jay Bauman|date=2011-11-20|accessdate=2013-04-25}}</ref> Mike McGranaghan wrote, on his website ''The Aisle Seat'': \"''[[Howard the Duck (film)|Howard the Duck]]'', ''[[Gigli]]'', ''[[Showgirls]]'', ''[[From Justin to Kelly]]''. What do they all have in common? They're all widely considered among the worst big studio movies ever made. You know what else they have in common? They're all better than ''Jack and Jill''.\"<ref name=\"JackandJill\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://aisleseat.com/jackandjill.htm |title=Jack and Jill |publisher=The Aisle Seat |last1=McGranaghan|first1=Mike|date=2011-11-01 |accessdate=2013-11-18}}</ref> ''Jack and Jill'' won a record 10 awards at the [[32nd Golden Raspberry Awards]], sweeping every category. It broke the record previously held by ''[[Battlefield Earth (film)|Battlefield Earth]]'' for having the most Razzies earned by a single film and is the only film to win every possible award.<ref name=RazzieWin>{{cite news |title=Adam Sandler movie Jack and Jill sweeps Razzie awards |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-17582458 |work=[[BBC News]] |date=April 2, 2012 |accessdate=May 17, 2012}}</ref> The film holds a 3% rating on [[Rotten Tomatoes]] based on 110 reviews.<ref name=\"JackandJill\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/jack_and_jill_2011|title=Jack and Jill (2011)|last=|first=|date=|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango]]|accessdate=June 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== ''That's My Boy'' (2012) ===\n\nAnother comedy film starring Adam Sandler, ''[[That's My Boy (2012 film)|That's My Boy]]'' concerns a middle school student named Donny Berger who has sex with his teacher, gets her pregnant, and in turn, earns a lifestyle of a minor celebrity, something he never intended to happen. Years later, Donny (played by Sandler) crashes his now-adult son's ([[Andy Samberg]]) wedding and bachelor party to get his money so he can pay his taxes, therefore avoiding prison. The film has been widely panned due to its comedic portrayal of [[incest]], [[hebephilia]], [[statutory rape]], and [[gerontophilia]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.foxnews.com/entertainment/2012/04/30/comedy-about-middle-school-statutory-rape-does-adam-sandlers-thats-my-boy-go/|title=Comedy about middle school statutory rape? Does Adam Sandler's ''That's My Boy'' go too far?|last=McKay|first=Hollie|date=April 30, 2012|work=|accessdate=April 17, 2019|publisher=[[Fox News]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://live.drjays.com/index.php/2012/05/21/is-adam-sandler-serious-with-thats-my-boy/ |title=Is Adam Sandler Serious With That's My Boy? &#124; DrJays.com Live &#124; Fashion. Music. Lifestyle |work=Live.drjays.com |date=2012-05-21 |accessdate=2013-12-19 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131212060031/http://live.drjays.com/index.php/2012/05/21/is-adam-sandler-serious-with-thats-my-boy/ |archive-date=2013-12-12 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://ncfm.org/2012/05/news/discrimination-against-men-news/adam-sandlers-new-movie-thats-my-boy-exploits-child-victims-of-sexual-assault-please-boycott-the-movie/ |title=Adam Sandler's new movie ''That's My Boy'' exploits child victims of sexual assault. Please boycott the movie. &#124; National Coalition For Men |publisher=NCFM |accessdate=2013-12-19}}</ref> with film critic Andrew O'Hehir of ''Salon'' stating, \"[Sandler's] new movie about a rape survivor and his estranged son is supposed to be funny, but radiates pain and rage.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.salon.com/2012/06/16/sympathy_for_adam_sandler/ |title=Adam Sandler hates you |work=Salon.com |date=2012-06-16 |accessdate=2013-12-19}}</ref> [[Richard Roeper]] of the ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'' proclaimed, \"To say ''That's My Boy'' is one of the worst movies of the year is to insult 2012. This is one of the worst movies I've ever seen\",<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.suntimes.com/entertainment/movies/13146305-421/pervs-will-be-pervs-in-thats-my-boy.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120617062159/http://www.suntimes.com/entertainment/movies/13146305-421/pervs-will-be-pervs-in-thats-my-boy.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=2012-06-17 |title=Pervs will be pervs in ''That's My Boy'' \u2013 Chicago Sun-Times |work=Suntimes.com |accessdate=2013-12-19 }}</ref> while Richard Haridly of ''[[Quickflix]]'' called it \"one of the saddest and most exhausting\" films he has ever seen.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.quickflix.com.au/news/reviews/thatsmyboy |title=That's My Boy review by Richard Haridy |publisher=Quickflix |accessdate=2013-12-19}}</ref> MaryAnn Johanson of ''Flick Filosopher'' outright panned the film for its inability to generate laughs as well as its depraved content, calling it \"a disgusting excuse for a comedy\" and possibly \"the most repulsive movie I've ever seen\",<ref name=\"myboy\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/thats_my_boy/reviews/|title=That's My Boy - Movie Reviews|last=|first=|date=|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango]]|accessdate=April 17, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.flickfilosopher.com/2013/01/thats-my-boy-review.html |title=That's My Boy (review) |work=FlickFilosopher.com |accessdate=2013-12-19}}</ref> and Jonathan Lack of ''We Got This Covered'' declared, \"''That's My Boy'' isn't just the worst film of 2012, it's one of the most morally reprehensible comedies of all time, a disgusting movie you should stay far, far away from.\"<ref name=\"myboy\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://wegotthiscovered.com/movies/boy-review/|title=That's My Boy Review|last=Lack|first=Jonathan R.|date=June 15, 2012|work=Wegotthiscovered.com|accessdate=April 17, 2019}}</ref> Furthermore, Ed Whitfield of ''The Ooh Tray'' stated, \"It may be the worst film, in any genre, ever made\".<ref name=\"myboy\"/><ref>{{cite web|author=The Ooh Tray |url=http://www.theoohtray.com/2012/09/09/film-review-thats-my-boy/ |title=Film Review: That's My Boy |publisher=The Ooh Tray |date=2012-10-02 |accessdate=2013-12-19}}</ref> In addition to the movie's overwhelmingly negative reviews, ''That's My Boy'' earned eight nominations at the [[33rd Golden Raspberry Awards]], such as Worst Picture and Worst Director, and won the awards for Worst Actor (Sandler) and Worst Screenplay.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.razzies.com/history/13winners.asp |title=Razzie Winners |work=Razzies.com |accessdate=2013-12-19 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130227010807/http://www.razzies.com/history/13winners.asp |archivedate=2013-02-27 }}</ref> It holds a 20% rating on [[Rotten Tomatoes]] {{as of|2019|April|17|lc=y|df=US}} based on 115 reviews.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/thats_my_boy/|title=That's My Boy|last=|first=|date=|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango]]|accessdate=April 17, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Run for Your Wife'' (2012) ===\n\nA British comedy film based on the [[Run for Your Wife (play)|stage farce]] of the same name, ''[[Run for Your Wife (2012 film)|Run for Your Wife]]'' starred [[Danny Dyer]] as John Smith, a bigamist, and [[Denise van Outen]] and [[Sarah Harding]] as his wives. ''Run for Your Wife'' was directed by the author of the play, [[Ray Cooney]] (who also makes an uncredited cameo appearance). Upon release, ''Run for Your Wife'' was savaged by film critics, with the South African newspaper ''Daily News'' saying \"''Run for Your Wife'' could be the worst film in history\",<ref>\"Movie may be the biggest Turkey ever\", ''Daily News'', South Africa, February 21, 2013.</ref> the [[Studio Briefing]] website reporting that \"Some writers are making the case that the British comedy may be 'the worst film ever{{'\"}},<ref name=\"studiobriefing\">[http://www.studiobriefing.net/2013/02/the-worst-film-in-history/#sthash.xFKOr9e6.dpuf The Worst Film in History?] ''Studio Briefing'', February 21, 2013. Retrieved February 13, 2015.</ref> and ''[[The Daily Mirror]]'' claiming ''Run For Your Wife'' \"was branded the worst British film ever\".<ref>[https://www.mirror.co.uk/tv/tv-news/danny-dyers-film-company-old-2343670 Danny Dyer's film company went bust with debt to taxpayer of \u00a325,000] ''Daily Mirror'', 6 October 2013. Retrieved 30 January 2015.</ref> ''Run for Your Wife'' met with such overwhelmingly negative reviews upon release that the reviews themselves were widely reported in the UK media.<ref name=\"studiobriefing\" /><ref>[http://uk.movies.yahoo.com/-run-for-your-wife----is-this-the-worst-movie-ever-filmed--114048296.html 'Run for Your Wife' \u2013 Is this the worst movie ever filmed?] ''Yahoo Movies \u2013 UK & Ireland'', 16 February 2013.</ref> The film was variously described as \"a catastrophe\", \"as funny as leprosy\" and \"30 years past its sell-by-date\", with ''[[The Guardian]]'' reviewer [[Peter Bradshaw]] saying that it \"makes ''[[The Dick Emery Show]]'' look edgy and contemporary\".<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/film/2013/feb/14/run-for-your-wife-review Run for Your Wife \u2013 review] ''The Guardian'', 14 February 2013. Retrieved 30 January 2015.</ref> ''[[The Independent (London)|The Independent]]'s'' Anthony Quinn wrote, \"The stage play ran for nine years \u2013 it [the film] will be lucky to run for nine days. Perhaps never in the field of light entertainment have so many actors sacrificed so much dignity in the cause of so few jokes ... From the look of it, Cooney hasn't been in a cinema for about 30 years\".<ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/reviews/film-review-run-for-your-wife-12a-8495806.html Film review: Run for Your Wife] ''The Independent (London)'', 30 January 2015.</ref> The cast featured numerous British celebrities in cameo roles, which was commented upon by several reviewers. The ''[[Metro (British newspaper)|Metro]]'' commented that \"no one emerges unscathed among the cameo-packed cast that reads largely like a roll-call for Brit TV legends you'd previously suspected deceased\".<ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/features/run-for-your-wife--as-funny-as-leprosy-8496873.html Run for Your Wife \u2013 'As funny as leprosy'] ''The Independent (London)'', 30th January 2015.</ref> The ''[[Daily Record (Scotland)|Daily Record]]'' described the film as \"an exasperating farce containing not one single, solitary laugh. {{sic|Comprised|hide=y| of}} people losing their trousers and falling over, the film looks like a pilot for a (mercifully) never-commissioned 70s sitcom\".<ref>\"[http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/entertainment/movies/movie-dvd-reviews/movie-review-run-your-wife-1711076 Movie Review: Run for your wife]\". ''Daily Record'', 30 January 2015.</ref> An article in the ''Independent'' described ''Run for Your Wife'' (along with the similarly panned ''[[Movie 43]]'') as contenders for the title of the \"worst film in history\".<ref>\"[https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/news/run-for-your-wife-is-this-movie-the-biggest-turkey-ever-filmed-8497478.html?origin=internalSearch Run For Your Wife: Is this movie the biggest turkey ever filmed?]\" ''The Independent''. 15 February 2013. Retrieved 30 January 2015.</ref> ''[[Hemel Hempstead Gazette|The Berkhamsted & Tring Gazette]]'' reported \"critics have being queuing up to batter recent release ''Run for Your Wife'', with general agreement that it ranks among the worst British comedies of all time\".<ref>\"Run for Your Wife\", ''Berkhamsted & Tring Gazette'', 11 March 2013.</ref> ''Run for Your Wife'' was also a [[box office bomb]], earning only \u00a3602 in its opening weekend at the British box office to its \u00a3900,000 budget.<ref>\"[http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2013-02-20/danny-dyers-run-for-your-wife-takes-just-602-at-the-box-office Danny Dyer's Run For Your Wife takes just \u00a3602 at the box office]\". ''[[Radio Times]]'', 20 February 2013. Retrieved 30 January 2015.</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/movies/news/a460182/danny-dyers-run-for-your-wife-flops-with-gbp602-at-the-box-office.html | title=Danny Dyer's 'Run For Your Wife' flops with \u00a3747 at the box office | website=Digital Spy|accessdate=30 January 2015}}</ref> ''Run for Your Wife'' has a [[List of films with a 0% rating on Rotten Tomatoes|0% rating]] on [[Rotten Tomatoes]] {{as of|2015|July|29|lc=y|df=US}} based on 15 reviews.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/run_for_your_wife_2013/|title=Run For Your Wife (2013)|last=|first=|date=|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango]]|access-date=April 17, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Movie 43'' (2013) ===\n\nProduced and co-directed by [[Peter Farrelly]] among others, ''[[Movie 43]]'' is a comedy film consisting of several vignettes each by a different director and a sizable cast of recognizable actors and actresses including [[Dennis Quaid]], [[Greg Kinnear]], [[Hugh Jackman]], [[Kate Winslet]], [[Liev Schreiber]], [[Naomi Watts]], [[Anna Faris]], [[Emma Stone]], [[Richard Gere]], [[Uma Thurman]], [[Chlo\u00eb Grace Moretz]], [[Gerard Butler]], [[Halle Berry]], [[Stephen Merchant]], [[Kristen Bell]], [[Terrence Howard]], [[Elizabeth Banks]], [[Kate Bosworth]], [[Johnny Knoxville]], [[Justin Long]], [[Chris Pratt]], [[Josh Duhamel]], and [[Jason Sudeikis]]. Several critics have called it one of the worst films ever made, including Peter Howell of the ''[[Toronto Star]]'', who said \"There's just one use for ''Movie 43'', apart from it being ground into the landfill that it deserves to become sooner rather than later. It provides me with a handy new answer to a question I'm often asked: 'What's the worst film you've ever seen?{{'\"}}<ref name=\"TS3\">{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com/entertainment/movies/2013/01/25/movie_43_review_the_worst_film_ever_gets_zero_stars.html|title=Movie 43 review: The worst film ever gets zero stars|last=Howell|first=Peter|date=January 25, 2013|work=[[Toronto Star]]|access-date=April 17, 2019}}</ref> Elizabeth Weitzman of the [[Daily News (New York)|New York ''Daily News'']] also considered it the worst movie she ever saw.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/tv-movies/movie-review-movie-43-article-1.1248520|title=Movie Review: Movie 43|last=Weitzman|first=Elizabeth|date=January 26, 2013|work=[[Daily News (New York)|Daily News]]|accessdate=April 17, 2019|location=New York}}</ref> Brady Murphy of Murphy Reviews wrote, \"A world where a film like this can exist only reminds me of the other contemptible acts performed by human kind since the dawn of time, and is rather eye-opening in that respect. That probably wasn't intentional, though\"; he went on to say that \"The idea that anyone could think that this would be in any way humorous is simply unbelievable.\" He concluded his review by saying the movie \"had no heart\", and gave it the site's first zero out of ten rating.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.murphyreviews.com/movie-43.html |title=Movie 43 |publisher=Murphy Reviews |date=2013-01-30 |accessdate=2013-11-18 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131020021708/http://www.murphyreviews.com/movie-43.html |archivedate=2013-10-20 }}</ref> [[Richard Roeper]] of the ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'' voiced similar hatred, calling it \"aggressively tasteless\" and \"the ''[[Citizen Kane]]'' of awful\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.suntimes.com/entertainment/17804431-421/theres-awful-and-then-theres-movie-43.html|title=There's awful and THEN there's ''Movie 43''|date=2013-01-25|work=Chicago Sun-Times|accessdate=2013-11-18|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130129011636/http://www.suntimes.com/entertainment/17804431-421/theres-awful-and-then-theres-movie-43.html|archive-date=2013-01-29|url-status=dead}}</ref> [[Lou Lumenick]] of the ''[[New York Post]]'' stated, \"If you mashed-up the worst parts of the infamous ''Howard the Duck'', ''Gigli'', ''Ishtar'' and every other awful movie I've seen since I started reviewing professionally in 1981, it wouldn't begin to approach the sheer soul-sucking badness of the cringe-inducing ''Movie 43''.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://nypost.com/2013/01/25/wtf-beyond-sketchy/ |title=WTF! Beyond sketchy |work=[[New York Post]] |date=2013-01-25 |accessdate=2013-11-28 |first=Lou |last=Lumenick}}</ref> ''Movie 43'' is on the MRQE's 50 Worst Movies list.<ref name=\"MRQE50\"/> It holds a 5% approval rating on [[Rotten Tomatoes]] based on 88 reviews, averaging out at a 2.23/10 rating.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/movie_43/|title=Movie 43|last=|first=|date=|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango]]|accessdate=May 22, 2019}}</ref> It won three awards at the [[34th Golden Raspberry Awards]]: Worst Picture, Worst Director, and Worst Screenplay. In the Worst Director category, all 13 directors won the award.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/envelope/moviesnow/la-et-mn-movie-43-named-worst-film-of-2013-razzie-awards-20140228,0,5893779.story |title='Movie 43' is named worst film of 2013 at the 34th Razzie Awards |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=2014-03-01 |accessdate=2014-03-01 |first=Susan |last=King}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Fateful Findings'' (2013) ===\n\n''[[Fateful Findings]]'' is a 2013 independent [[techno-thriller]] written, directed and produced by [[Neil Breen]]. Breen also starred in the film and took on most of the crew roles, including film editor, sound editor, accountant, caterer, set designer, wardrobe, makeup and casting.<ref name=\"NYDN\"/> The film follows an author-turned-hacker with supernatural powers who uses his abilities to reveal government and corporate secrets while struggling with his wife's drug addiction and his attraction to his teenage neighbor, ending with an extended sequence at a press conference where politicians and business people confess to corruption and kill themselves before an applauding crowd. Writing for ''[[Film Threat]]'', reviewer Mike Hodges described it as \"the worst movie ever made\", comparing it unfavorably to ''[[#Troll 2 (1990)|Troll 2]]'' and ''[[#The Room (2003)|The Room]]''.<ref>{{cite web|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222032832/https://filmthreat.com/reviews/66453/|url=https://filmthreat.com/reviews/66453/|first=Mike|last=Hodges|website=Film Threat|date=27 May 2013|archive-date=22 February 2014|accessdate=1 February 2018|url-status=dead|title=Fateful Findings}}</ref> [[Nathan Rabin]], writing for [[Rotten Tomatoes]], said ''Fateful Findings'' threatens ''The Room''{{'}}s position as \"best worst movie\",<ref>{{cite web|url=https://editorial.rottentomatoes.com/article/why-fateful-findings-deserves-cult-status/|title=Why Fateful Findings Deserves Cult Status|first=Nathan|last=Rabin|date=8 December 2015|website=Rotten Tomatoes|accessdate=1 February 2018}}</ref> while reviewers of the podcast ''[[The Flop House]]'' said \"Move over ''The Room'', move over ''[[#Birdemic: Shock and Terror (2008)|Birdemic]]''\" and ''Mystery Science Theater 3000'' head writer [[Elliott Kalan]] described it as the \"good-est bad movie, maybe, I've ever seen\".<ref>{{Cite AV media|url=https://soundcloud.com/the-flop-house/ep-187-fateful-findings|title=Ep. #187 - Fateful Findings|first1=Elliot|last1=Kalan|first2=Dan|last2=McCoy|first3=Stuart|last3=Wellington|date=19 September 2015|publisher=[[The Flop House]]|accessdate=1 February 2018|time=50:22 to 50:55}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Humshakals'' (2014) ===\nA [[Bollywood]] comedy film directed by [[Sajid Khan (director)|Sajid Khan]], ''[[Humshakals]]'' featured Indian actors [[Saif Ali Khan]], [[Ram Kapoor]] and [[Riteish Deshmukh]]. On [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film has an [[List of films with a 0% rating on Rotten Tomatoes|approval rating of 0%]], based on six reviews, with an average rating of 2/10.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/humshakals/ |title=Humshakals (2014) |website=Rotten Tomatoes |accessdate=July 10, 2017}}</ref> Mihir Fadnavis wrote in his ''[[Firstpost]]'' review, \"sexual tomfoolery, shrieking and hamming aside, there's much more to hate about this 'family movie'. It's disturbing to see such an atrocious, regressive, misogynistic, sexist, homophobic cinematic product force-fed to paying audiences. I can understand that a comedy need not be 'safe', but what goes on in ''Humshakals'' is simply too horrifying to bear.\"<ref name=\"Fadnavis\">{{cite news|url=http://www.firstpost.com/blogs/humshakals-review-saif-ali-khan-riteish-deshmukh-team-up-to-give-you-brain-damage-1580181.html |title=Humshakals review: How Saif, Riteish teamed up to give your brain damage |work=Firstpost |last1=Fadnavis|first1=Mihir|date=2014-06-22 |accessdate=2014-07-22}}</ref> Saurabh Dwivedi of ''[[India Today]]'' stated \"I can only say that ''Humshakals'' will be listed in one of the worst films of the century.\"<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/humshakals-movie-review-sajid-khan-riteish-deshmukh-saif-ali-khan/1/367688.html |title=Movie review: Humshakals is three times trash |last1=Dwivedi|first1=Saurabh|date=June 20, 2014|magazine=[[India Today]]}}</ref> Writing in ''[[Emirates 24/7]]'', Sneha May Francis said that it succeeded Khan's previous endeavor, ''[[Himmatwala (2013 film)|Himmatwala]]'', in becoming the worst Bollywood film ever.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.emirates247.com/entertainment/films-music/saif-ali-khan-s-humshakals-act-could-make-kareena-insecure-2014-06-19-1.553579 |title=Saif Ali Khan's 'Humshakals' act could make Kareena insecure |last1=Francis|first1=Sneha May|publisher=Emirates 24/7 |date=2014-06-29 |accessdate=2014-10-22}}</ref> Fadnavis went further, writing that it displaced ''Himmatwala'' as the \"worst possible product any film industry in the world can offer\".<ref name=\"Fadnavis\"/> Itrath Syed of ''[[The Georgia Straight]]'' stated that ''Humshakals'' was \"the absolute bottom of the cinematic barrel\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.straight.com/movies/673511/humshakals-redefines-dreadfulness|title=Humshakals redefines dreadfulness|work=The Georgia Straight|last1=Syed|first1=Itrath|date=June 25, 2014 |accessdate=July 10, 2017}}</ref> The film received five [[Golden Kela Awards|Golden Kela Award]] nominations,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/entertainment/humshakals-lead-nominations-list-at-golden-kela-awards/article6905214.ece |title=Humshakals' leads nominations list at Golden Kela Awards |newspaper=The Hindu |author=PTI|date=February 17, 2015 |accessdate=2014-10-22 |location=Chennai, India}}</ref> and won the \u201caward\u201d for Worst Film.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenational.ae/arts-lifestyle/from-holly-to-bolly/sonakshi-and-arjun-grab-top-golden-kela-awards |title=Sonakshi and Arjun grab top Golden Kela awards |newspaper=The National |author=IANS|date=March 15, 2015 |accessdate=August 17, 2015}}</ref> It also won two [[Ghanta Awards]]; the film won Worst Picture and Ram Kapoor, Saif Ali Khan and Riteish Deshmukh shared the Worst Actor award.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ibtimes.co.in/ghanta-awards-2015-complete-winners-list-sonakshi-sinha-ajay-devgn-win-worst-actor-awards-farah-625675 |title=Ghanta Awards 2015 Complete Winners List: Sonakshi Sinha, Ajay Devgn Win Worst Actor Awards; Farah Khan Worst Director |work=International Business Times|last1=Mehta|first1=Ankhita|date=March 9, 2015 |accessdate=August 17, 2015}}</ref>\n\nSeveral of the cast members also lamented their involvement in the film. Despite being the film's leading actress, [[Bipasha Basu]] did not participate in the film's promotions because she was \"extremely disturbed by the end result\" and stated that \"''Humshakals'' was the worst experience of my life\".<ref>{{cite news |date=August 8, 2014 |title=Sajid Khan's Humshakals left me disturbed: Bipasha Basu |newspaper=Hindustan Times |url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/entertainment/tabloid/sajid-khan-s-humshakals-left-me-disturbed-bipasha-basu/article1-1249663.aspx |author=IANS|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140809060246/http://www.hindustantimes.com/entertainment/tabloid/sajid-khan-s-humshakals-left-me-disturbed-bipasha-basu/article1-1249663.aspx |url-status=dead |archive-date=August 9, 2014 |location=Mumbai}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/slide-show/slide-show-1-bipasha-humshakals-was-the-worst-experience-of-my-life/20140826.htm |title=Bipasha: Humshakals was the worst experience of my life |publisher=Rediff.com |date=August 26, 2014}}</ref> Another cast member, actress [[Esha Gupta]], warned her family to not watch the film.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/Humshakals-I-asked-my-father-not-to-watch-the-film-says-Esha-Gupta/articleshow/37616095.cms |title=Humshakals: I asked my father not to watch the film, says Esha Gupta |newspaper=Times of India |date= Jul 2, 2014 }}</ref> After the release of the film, leading actor Saif Ali Khan lamented that \"I've been introspecting a lot and will never repeat a mistake that was ''Humshakals''.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/Saif-Ali-Khan-Humshakals-was-a-mistake/articleshow/38590378.cms |title=Saif Ali Khan: Humshakals was a mistake |newspaper=Times of India |date= Jul 18, 2014 }}</ref>\n\n=== ''Kidnapping, Caucasian Style!'' (2014) ===\n''[[Kidnapping, Caucasian Style!]]'' is a 2014 Russian comedy film.<ref>[https://letterboxd.com/film/kidnapping-caucasian-style-2014/ Kidnapping, Caucasian Style (2014)-Letterboxd]</ref> It is a remake of [[Leonid Gaidai]]'s 1967 Soviet film, ''[[Kidnapping, Caucasian Style]]'', and was harshly criticized for how closely it copied the original, essentially being a frame by frame reproduction with few modern references. ''[[Gazeta.ru]]'' described it as \"probably the worst film in the history of Russian cinema\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.gazeta.ru/culture/2014/08/21/a_6185217.shtml |script-title=ru:\u0428\u0443\u0440\u0438\u043a \u0432 \u0417\u0430\u043f\u0440\u0435\u0434\u0435\u043b\u044c\u0435|language=Russian|work=[[Gazeta.ru]]|date= August 22, 2014|accessdate=February 19, 2019}}</ref> ''[[Mail.Ru]]'' said it was the worst remake, while critic Maxim Shilimanov wrote that \"The film is so bad that it seems that it was shot badly on purpose so that film critics had something to write about.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.kritikanstvo.ru/movies/kavkazskajaplennica/|script-title=ru:\u041a\u0430\u0432\u043a\u0430\u0437\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u043f\u043b\u0435\u043d\u043d\u0438\u0446\u0430!|language=Russian|publisher=Kritikanstvo|date= November 28, 2017|accessdate=February 19, 2019}}</ref> In listing it as one of the worst remakes of Soviet cinema, ''[[Cosmopolitan Russia]]'' opted to quote from a user review from [[KinoPoisk]] that called it \"the worst film I've ever seen\" rather than describe the plot.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cosmo.ru/stars/krupnim-planom/veselye-rebyata-kavkazskaya-plennica-i-drugie-hudshie-remeyki-sovetskogo-kino/|script-title=ru:\"\u0412\u0435\u0441\u0435\u043b\u044b\u0435 \u0440\u0435\u0431\u044f\u0442\u0430\", \"\u041a\u0430\u0432\u043a\u0430\u0437\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u043f\u043b\u0435\u043d\u043d\u0438\u0446\u0430!\" \u0438 \u0434\u0440\u0443\u0433\u0438\u0435 \u0445\u0443\u0434\u0448\u0438\u0435 \u0440\u0435\u043c\u0435\u0439\u043a\u0438 \u0441\u043e\u0432\u0435\u0442\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u043a\u0438\u043d\u043e|language=Russian|work=[[Cosmopolitan Russia]]|date= November 18, 2018|accessdate=February 19, 2019}}</ref> It is the lowest rated film on KinoPoisk,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.aif.ru/culture/movie/proval_na_million_hudshie_rossiyskie_filmy_soglasno_reytingu_zriteley|script-title=ru:\u041f\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043b \u043d\u0430 \u043c\u0438\u043b\u043b\u0438\u043e\u043d. \u0425\u0443\u0434\u0448\u0438\u0435 \u0440\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0435 \u0444\u0438\u043b\u044c\u043c\u044b \u0441\u043e\u0433\u043b\u0430\u0441\u043d\u043e \u0440\u0435\u0439\u0442\u0438\u043d\u0433\u0443 \u0437\u0440\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u0435\u0439|language=Russian|work=[[Argumenty i Fakty]]|date= December 1, 2017|accessdate=February 19, 2019}}</ref> appears on [[review aggregator]] Kritikanstvo's all-time lowest-scoring films,<ref name=\"Kritikanstvo\"/> and [[RIA Novosti]] listed it as the second worst film after ''[[Guardians (2017 film)|Guardians]]''.<ref name=\"RIA\">{{cite news|url=https://ria.ru/20171128/1509765632.html?referrer_block=index_daynews3_1|script-title=ru:\u0421\u0430\u043c\u044b\u0439 \u0445\u0443\u0434\u0448\u0438\u0439 \u0444\u0438\u043b\u044c\u043c: \u043a\u0430\u043a\u0438\u0435 \u043a\u0430\u0440\u0442\u0438\u043d\u044b \u043f\u043e\u0441\u043b\u0435\u0434\u043d\u0438\u0445 \u043b\u0435\u0442 \u0440\u0430\u0437\u043e\u0447\u0430\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043b\u0438 \u0437\u0440\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u0435\u0439\n|language=Russian|publisher=[[RIA Novosti]]|date= November 28, 2017|accessdate=February 19, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Saving Christmas'' (2014) ===\n[[File:Kirk Cameron by Gage Skidmore.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Kirk Cameron]]'s plea for fans to support ''[[Saving Christmas]]'' backfired, resulting in it being the lowest rated film on [[IMDB]]]]\n''[[Saving Christmas]]'' is a [[Christian film industry|faith-based]] [[List of Christmas films|Christmas]] [[comedy film]] starring [[Kirk Cameron]], who plays a fictionalized version of himself attempting to convince his brother-in-law (played by the film's director, [[Darren Doane]]) that Christmas is still a Christian holiday.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=g1om1mtv5ZM The Troubling Philosophy of Kirk Cameron's Saving Christmas-Renegade Cut on YouTube]</ref> On [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film received a [[List of films with a 0% rating on Rotten Tomatoes|0% rating]], based on 13 reviews, with an average rating of 1.7/10.<ref name=\"savingrotten\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/kirk_camerons_saving_christmas/reviews/|title=Kirk Cameron's Saving Christmas|website=Rotten Tomatoes|accessdate=July 28, 2017}}</ref> Critic David Keyes described ''Saving Christmas'' as \"The worst holiday movie ever made\",<ref name=\"savingrotten\"/> ''[[Billings Gazette]]'' selected the film as the worst Christmas movie of all time,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://billingsgazette.com/entertainment/movies/the-worst-christmas-movies-of-all-time/collection_b50903c8-f2cf-54ce-8fea-90fac279d391.html|title=The 25 Worst Christmas Movies of All Time|work=Billings Gazette|date=December 12, 2016|accessdate=July 28, 2017}}</ref> and Will Nicol of ''Digital Trends'' included it on his list of the ten worst movies ever made.<ref name=\"digitaltrends\">{{cite web|url=https://www.digitaltrends.com/movies/worst-movies-ever-made/|title=10 Worst Movies You Can Watch|work=Digital Trends|last=Nicol|first=Will|date=May 10, 2017|accessdate=July 28, 2017}}</ref> [[Christy Lemire]] picked ''Saving Christmas'' as the worst film she has ever reviewed and called it  \"[[The Room (2003 film)|''The Room'']] of Christmas movies\" (while adding that she found ''The Room'' to be more enjoyable) and gave it a score of zero stars out of four.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://indiewire.com/2017/06/critics-worst-movies-ever-reviewed-1201843846/|title=Critics Pick the Worst Movies They've Ever Reviewed|work=Indiewire|last=Kohn|first=Eric|date=June 19, 2017|accessdate=July 28, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://christylemire.com/kirk-camerons-saving-christmas/|title=Kirk Cameron's Saving Christmas - Christy Lemire|date=2014-11-21|work=Christy Lemire|access-date=2018-09-09|language=en-US}}</ref> Bill Zwecker of the ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'' said: \"This may be one of the least artful holiday films ever made.\"<ref name=\"savingrotten\" /> In response to the criticism, Cameron asked fans to give the film positive reviews on Rotten Tomatoes.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.christianpost.com/news/kirk-cameron-urges-fans-to-improve-saving-christmas-rating-help-me-storm-the-gates-of-rotten-tomatoes-130072/ |title=Kirk Cameron Urges Fans to Improve ''Saving Christmas'' Rating, 'Help Me Storm the Gates of Rotten Tomatoes' |author=Koonse, Emma |newspaper=The Christian Post |date=November 21, 2014 |accessdate=July 28, 2017}}</ref> This resulted in a backlash in which Internet users traveled to the Rotten Tomatoes page and condemned the film.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://cinemablend.com/new/Kirk-Cameron-Tried-Cheat-Rotten-Tomatoes-It-Did-Go-68399.html | title=Kirk Cameron Tried To Cheat Rotten Tomatoes, It Did Not Go Well | work=CinemaBlend | date=November 25, 2014 | accessdate=July 28, 2017}}</ref> Three weeks after its release, ''Saving Christmas'' became the lowest-rated film on IMDb's bottom 100 list. Cameron blamed the low rating on a [[Reddit]] campaign by \"haters and [[Atheism|atheists]]\" to purposely lower the film's ratings.<ref>{{cite news|last1=O'Neal|first1=Sean|date=December 5, 2014|title=Kirk Cameron Is Crucified at the Hands of IMDb Users, Rises with Jesus Coffee|url=https://avclub.com/article/kirk-cameron-crucified-hands-imdb-users-rises-jesu-212677|newspaper=The A.V. Club|accessdate=9 December 2014}}</ref> The film won four awards, including Worst Picture, at the [[35th Golden Raspberry Awards]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=King|first1=Susan|date=February 21, 2015|title=Kirk Cameron's Saving Christmas'' Dominates the 35th Razzie Awards|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/moviesnow/la-et-mn-kirk-cameron-35th-razzie-awards-20150220-story.html |newspaper=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=July 28, 2017}}</ref> ''[[MSN Entertainment]]'' ranked it #2 in its list of the 100 worst films of all time and ''Digital Trends'' included it in its worst film list.<ref name=\"digitaltrends\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/movies/gallery/100-worst-movies-of-all-time/ss-BBS3EmT#image=100|title=100 Worst Movies of All Time|website=www.msn.com|access-date=2019-09-25}}</ref>\n\n=== ''United Passions'' (2014) ===\n\nA 2014 English-language French [[Drama (film and television)|drama film]] about the origins of the soccer world governing body [[FIFA|F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association]] (FIFA), ''[[United Passions]]'' starred [[Tim Roth]] (as FIFA President [[Sepp Blatter]]), [[G\u00e9rard Depardieu]] and [[Sam Neill]], and was directed by [[Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Auburtin]]. ''United Passions''{{'}} release in the U.S. occurred simultaneously with the [[2015 FIFA corruption case]], in which several current and former members of FIFA's executive committee were arrested for charges of corruption,<ref name=\"Scheck\">{{cite news |last=Scheck |first=Frank |title='United Passions': Film Review |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/united-passions-film-review-799879 |newspaper=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |accessdate=4 June 2015}}</ref> and Blatter himself resigned following repeated accusations of corruption at FIFA under his leadership.<ref>{{cite news |last=Parker |first=Graham |date=2 June 2015 |title=Sepp Blatter: A history of scandal |url=http://america.aljazeera.com/articles/2015/6/2/sepp-blatter-a-history-of-scandal.html |publisher=[[Al Jazeera]] |access-date=4 June 2015}}</ref> ''United Passions'' was accused of ignoring these long-running claims.<ref name=\"Scheck\"/><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.goal.com/en/news/1717/editorial/2015/06/09/12556292/is-united-passions-the-worst-movie-of-all-time-fifa%E2%80%93|title=Is United Passions the worst movie of all time? Fifa propaganda film paints Blatter as a bastion of morality|last=Koylu|first=Enis|date=|website=Goal.com|access-date=April 17, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"field\">{{cite news |last=Field |first=Paul |date=3 June 2015 |title=United Passions review: FIFA's hideous \u00a316 million movie is unintentional comedy gold |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/football/news/united-passions-review-fifas-hideous-5817599 |newspaper=[[Daily Mirror]] |access-date=25 June 2015}}</ref> ''[[London Evening Standard]]''{{'}}s [[Des Kelly]] wrote that ''United Passions'' was \"the worst movie ever made\" and \"the most extraordinary vanity exercise; a vile, self-aggrandizing, sugar-coated pile of manure where Blatter and Co. manage to make North Korea's [[Kim Jong-un]] look self-effacing\".<ref>[https://www.standard.co.uk/sport/football/des-kelly-sugarcoated-fifa-film-is-spreading-around-europe-like-a-virus-9820165.html Sugar-coated FIFA film is spreading around Europe like a virus] Des Kelly, ''London Evening Standard'', 27 October 2014. Retrieved 25 June 2015.</ref> Daniel Gold of ''The New York Times'' claimed ''United Passions'' is \"one of the most unwatchable films in recent memory, a dishonest bit of corporate-suite sanitizing that's no good even for laughs\",<ref>Daniel M. Gold. \"[https://www.nytimes.com/2015/06/05/movies/review-in-united-passions-a-fictionalized-fifa-underwritten-by-the-soccer-group.html Review: In 'United Passions', a Fictionalized FIFA, Underwritten by the Soccer Group]\". ''New York Times'', June 4, 2015. Retrieved 25 June 2015.</ref> later stating it would make the top three of his list of all time bad films.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/videos/world/2015/06/14/exp-new-film-about-fifa-opens-in-the-u-s-.cnn|title='United Passions' not getting good reviews|publisher=CNN|date=June 14, 2015|accessdate=September 4, 2015}}</ref> Several critics noted the irony of the film's depiction of Blatter as an anti-corruption campaigner. Paul Field of the ''[[Daily Mirror]]'' said that this created \"unintentional comedy gold\",<ref name=\"field\"/> while Sara Stewart of the ''[[New York Post]]'' described it as \"hilariously ill-timed\".<ref>{{cite news |last=Stewart |first=Sara |date=3 June 2015 |title=Lame 'United Passions' an ironic ode to glory of FIFA |url=https://nypost.com/2015/06/03/lame-united-passions-an-ironic-ode-to-glory-of-fifa/ |newspaper=[[New York Post]] |access-date=25 June 2015}}</ref> On [[Rotten Tomatoes]], ''United Passions'' has [[List of films with a 0% rating on Rotten Tomatoes|an approval rating of 0%]] based on 16 reviews,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/united_passions|title=United Passions (2015)|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango Media]]|access-date=September 28, 2019}}</ref> while on [[Metacritic]], the film holds a score of 1 out of 100, based on 9 critics, and is tied for the lowest scoring film on the site.<ref name=\"Metacritic\"/>\n\n''United Passions'' was also a [[box office bomb]],<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2X1AU1ArE0k Top 10 Worst Movies of 2015-WatchMojo on YouTube]</ref> becoming the lowest-grossing film ever in American history with a total take of $918,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://avclub.com/article/fifa-vanity-project-united-passions-breaks-box-off-221084|title=FIFA vanity project ''United Passions'' breaks box-office record (not the good kind)|last=Rife|first=Katie|date=June 19, 2015|work=[[The A.V. Club]]|publisher=[[The Onion]]|accessdate=April 17, 2019}}</ref><ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=vDGp2_6iEe4 Another Top 10 Movies So Bad They Were Pulled From Theatres-WatchMojo on YouTube]</ref> which surpassed the previous record held by ''[[I Kissed a Vampire]]'' ($1,380) in 2012. The film additionally went [[Direct-to-video|directly to DVD]] in France and was not distributed in a number of other European countries.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/sports/sportsnow/la-sp-sn-fifa-movie-united-passions-bombs-20150608-story.html|title='United Passions,' which cost FIFA $29 million, has $607 box-office take|author=Austin Knoblauch|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|publisher=([[Tribune Publishing]])|date=25 June 2015|accessdate=8 June 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Ikav\">{{cite web|url=http://www.espnfc.com/fifa-world-cup/story/2496658/fifa-film-united-passions-among-worst-in-us-history|title=FIFA film 'United Passions' one of worst in U.S. box office history|author=ESPN Staff|work=[[ESPN FC]]|publisher=([[ESPN]])|date=25 June 2015|accessdate=21 June 2015}}</ref> Several of the people involved in ''United Passions'' later expressed regret over the film. Director Auburtin called ''United Passions'' \"a disaster\" and added: \"Now I'm seen as bad as the guy who brought AIDS to Africa or the guy who caused the financial crisis ... apparently I am a propaganda guy making films for corrupt people.\"<ref name=\"Ikav\"/><ref name=\"r&r\">{{cite news|url=https://hollywoodreporter.com/news/fifa-movie-director-breaks-silence-802760|title=FIFA Movie Director Breaks Silence on Bomb: \"It's a Disaster; My Name Is All Over [This Mess]\"|author1=Scott Roxborough |author2=Rhonda Richford |lastauthoramp=yes|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|publisher=([[Prometheus Global Media]])|date=17 June 2015|accessdate=25 June 2015}}</ref> Tim Roth apologized for taking part in the film and admitted that he took the job in ''United Passions'' for the money.<ref name=\"r&r\"/>\n\n===''Dirty Grandpa'' (2016)===\n''[[Dirty Grandpa]]'', a 2016 comedy movie starring [[Robert De Niro]] and [[Zac Efron]] as a grandfather and grandson going to [[Florida]] during [[Spring break]], received negative reviews for its [[Off-color humor|gross-out]] and [[Shock humour|shock humor]] that was also considered as [[Sexism|sexist]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://sassymamainla.com/2016/01/how-dirty-grandpa-made-my-feminism-hurt/.html|title=How DIRTY GRANDPA Made My Feminism Hurt: An Expos\u00e9|last=Howard|first=Courtney|date=January 22, 2016|website=Sassy Mama in LA|language=en-US|access-date=September 28, 2019}}</ref> [[Homophobia|homophobic]] and [[Racism|racist]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://slate.com/human-interest/2016/02/comedies-like-dirty-grandpa-get-hard-are-horribly-homophobic.html|title=Some of Hollywood's Most Successful Comedies Have a \"Hipster Homophobia\" Problem|last=Lang|first=Nico|date=February 10, 2016|website=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate Magazine]]|language=en|access-date=September 28, 2019}}</ref> Mike Ryan of [[Uproxx]] said: \"''Dirty Grandpa'' is the worst movie I\u2019ve ever seen in a movie theater. Burn it.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiewire.com/2016/01/reviews-is-dirty-grandpa-robert-deniros-worst-movie-ever-124909/|title=Reviews: Is 'Dirty Grandpa' Robert DeNiro's Worst Movie Ever?|last=Murthi|first=Vikram|last2=Murthi|first2=Vikram|date=2016-01-22|website=IndieWire|language=en|access-date=2018-12-26}}</ref> He later also picked it as the worst film he had ever both reviewed<ref>{{cite news|last1=Kohn|first1=Eric|title=Critics Pick the Worst Movies They've Ever Reviewed|url=https://indiewire.com/2017/06/critics-worst-movies-ever-reviewed-1201843846/|accessdate=January 16, 2018|work=[[IndieWire]]|date=June 19, 2017}}</ref> and seen.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ryan|first1=Mike|title='Dirty Grandpa': The Most Important Movie Ever Made|url=http://uproxx.com/movies/dirty-grandpa-review/|accessdate=January 16, 2018|publisher=[[Uproxx]]|date=January 21, 2016}}</ref> Pete Hammond of [[Deadline Hollywood]] said: \"... ''Dirty Grandpa,'' is not just the worst movie [De Niro] has ever been in, but it may be the worst movie ''anyone'' has ever been in.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2016/01/dirty-grandpa-review-zac-efron-robert-de-niro-worst-ever-1201688276/|title='Dirty Grandpa' Review: The Worst Film Of Robert De Niro's Career (Or Maybe Anybody's)|last=Hammond|first=Pete|last2=Hammond|first2=Pete|date=2016-01-22|website=Deadline|language=en|access-date=2018-12-26}}</ref> Glenn Mcdonald of [[Indy Week]] said: \"The awful, ugly ''Dirty Grandpa'' is the comedy equivalent of torture porn ... In fact, in the dizzying moments after being bludgeoned by this miserable specimen, I was convinced it's among the worst movies ever made.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://indyweek.com/api/content/5adaaa95-3951-5e39-8f24-20d058c698b4/|title=Movie review: The awful, ugly Dirty Grandpa is the comedy equivalent of torture porn|last=McDonald|first=Glenn|date=2016-01-22|website=INDY Week|language=en-us|access-date=2018-12-26}}</ref> [[Richard Roeper]] gave the film zero stars, writing, \"If ''Dirty Grandpa'' isn't the worst movie of 2016, I have some serious cinematic torture in my near future.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://chicago.suntimes.com/entertainment/dirty-grandpa-robert-de-niro-deserves-better-than-this-dreck/|title='Dirty Grandpa': Robert De Niro deserves better than this dreck|website=Chicago Sun-Times|language=en|access-date=2018-12-26}}</ref> On his YouTube channel, Roeper also said: \"I'm not ready to say ''Dirty Grandpa'' is the worst movie I've ever seen, but I'm also not ready to say it's ''not'' the worst movie I've ever seen.\"<ref>{{Citation|title=Richard Roeper Reviews \"Dirty Grandpa\"|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=XOu2gzJiaCg|language=en|access-date=2019-09-29}}</ref> [[Mark Kermode]], on his [[BBC Radio 5 Live]] show (''[[Kermode and Mayo's Film Review]]''), said that he found the film \"truly, genuinely horrible\" and went on to say, \"after ''Dirty Grandpa'' I did feel genuinely unclean, I wanted to go and have a shower, because it's just so revolting. Somewhere in hell there is a multiplex playing this on a double bill, with ''[[Movie 43]]'' and ''[[Entourage (film)|Entourage]]''.\"<ref>{{Citation|last=kermodeandmayo|title=Dirty Grandpa reviewed by Mark Kermode|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=05GwDHYXlmI|access-date=2018-12-27}}</ref> He would later go on to brand it his least favorite film of 2016.<ref>{{Citation|last=kermodeandmayo|title=The Ten Worst Films of 2016: Part Two|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4NwzBUjeMl0|access-date=2018-12-27}}</ref> Glenn Kelly of ''[[RogerEbert.com]]'' said: \"The actor [[Bela Lugosi]] appeared in some landmark, perhaps even great, films at the beginning of his Hollywood career in the 1930s. ... Lugosi's final film was 1959's ''[[Plan 9 from Outer Space]]'', frequently cited as the worst film ever made. The cinematic landmarks of De Niro's career include films such as [[Francis Ford Coppola|Coppola]]'s ''[[The Godfather Part II]]'' and [[Martin Scorsese|Scorsese]]'s ''[[Raging Bull]]''. He has been featured in a good number of very bad films in the years since. But this? This might just be his own ''Plan 9''\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/dirty-grandpa-2016|title=Dirty Grandpa Movie Review & Film Summary (2016) {{!}} Roger Ebert|last=Kenny|first=Glenn|website=www.rogerebert.com|language=en|access-date=2019-02-17}}</ref> The film has an approval rating of 11% at [[Rotten Tomatoes]] based on 133 reviews, with an average rating of 2.76/10,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/dirty_grandpa/|title=Dirty Grandpa (2016)|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango Media]]|access-date=September 28, 2019}}</ref> while on [[Metacritic]] it has a score of 21 out of 100 based on 27 critics, indicating \"generally unfavorable reviews\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/dirty-grandpa|title=Dirty Grandpa Reviews|website=[[Metacritic]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|access-date=September 28, 2019}}</ref> At the [[37th Golden Raspberry Awards]] it received five nominations, for Worst Picture, Worst Actor (De Niro), Worst Supporting Actress ([[Julianne Hough]] and [[Aubrey Plaza]], respectively) and Worst Screenplay, but did not win in any category.\n\n=== ''Guardians'' (2017) ===\n''[[Guardians (2017 film)|Guardians]]'' is a Russian [[superhero film]]<ref>[https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/guardians-movie-trailer-2017-russian-923229 'Guardians' Movie Trailer 2017: Russian Superheroes Unite|Hollywood Reporter]</ref><ref>[https://mubi.com/films/guardians-2017 Guardians (2017)-MUBI]</ref> about a team of Soviet superheroes created during the [[Cold War]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://letterboxd.com/film/guardians-2017/|title=Guardians (2017)|last=|first=|date=|website=Letterboxd|access-date=April 17, 2019}}</ref> It was criticized for having a derivative plot, bad acting and direction, cheap CGI, [[plot hole]]s and overall low quality. ''Kg-portal.ru'' wrote that \"''Guardians'' is a film from which Russian cinema should be protected. It's like a sequel to ''Plan 9 from Outer Space'', filmed by [[Uwe Boll]], with the screenplay by [[Tommy Wiseau]] and with him in the lead role\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://kg-portal.ru/movies/zaschitniki/reviews/5269/|script-title=ru:\u0414\u0435\u0440\u044c\u043c\u043e \u043d\u0430 \u044d\u043a\u0441\u043f\u043e\u0440\u0442\n|language=Russian|work=kg-portal.ru|date=October 23, 2017|accessdate=February 19, 2019}}</ref> ''[[Rossiyskaya Gazeta]]'' commented that the film was \"Worse than you can imagine.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://rg.ru/2017/02/24/zashchitniki-sarika-andreasiana-naskolko-eto-ploho.html|script-title=ru:\u041e\u0441\u043b\u0438\u043a, \u0441\u0443\u0441\u043b\u0438\u043a, \u0410\u043d\u0434\u0440\u0435\u0430\u0441\u044f\u043d\n|language=Russian|work=[[Rossiyskaya Gazeta]]|date=February 24, 2017|accessdate=February 23, 2019}}</ref> ''[[Meduza]]'' compared the film's director, [[Sarik Andreasyan]], to ''Plan 9 from Outer Space''{{'}}s director, [[Ed Wood]], and said that ''Guardians'' \"is a convincing answer to the eternal question of why we can never catch up with Hollywood even in our own box office\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://meduza.io/feature/2017/02/23/filmy-na-nedelyu-patrioticheskie-i-uzhasayuschie-zaschitniki-a-takzhe-dzheki-toni-erdmann-i-slishkom-svobodnyy-chelovek|script-title=ru:\u0424\u0438\u043b\u044c\u043c\u044b \u043d\u0430 \u043d\u0435\u0434\u0435\u043b\u044e: \u043f\u0430\u0442\u0440\u0438\u043e\u0442\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0435 (\u0438 \u0443\u0436\u0430\u0441\u0430\u044e\u0449\u0438\u0435) \"\u0417\u0430\u0449\u0438\u0442\u043d\u0438\u043a\u0438\", \u0430 \u0442\u0430\u043a\u0436\u0435 \"\u0414\u0436\u0435\u043a\u0438\", \"\u0422\u043e\u043d\u0438 \u042d\u0440\u0434\u043c\u0430\u043d\u043d\" \u0438 \"\u0421\u043b\u0438\u0448\u043a\u043e\u043c \u0441\u0432\u043e\u0431\u043e\u0434\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0447\u0435\u043b\u043e\u0432\u0435\u043a\"|language=Russian|work=[[Meduza]]|date=October 23, 2017|accessdate=February 19, 2019}}</ref> ''[[Afisha]]'' said that it was the Russian answer to ''[[Howard the Duck (film)|Howard the Duck]]'',<ref>{{cite news|url=https://daily.afisha.ru/cinema/4639-zaschitniki-nash-otvet-govardu-utke/|script-title=ru:\"\u0417\u0430\u0449\u0438\u0442\u043d\u0438\u043a\u0438\" \u0421\u0430\u0440\u0438\u043a\u0430 \u0410\u043d\u0434\u0440\u0435\u0430\u0441\u044f\u043d\u0430: \u043d\u0430\u0448 \u043e\u0442\u0432\u0435\u0442 \u0413\u043e\u0432\u0430\u0440\u0434\u0443-\u0443\u0442\u043a\u0435|language=Russian|work=[[Afisha]]|date=October 23, 2017|accessdate=February 19, 2019}}</ref> and [[Ivi, Inc.]] commented that \"a more talentless film is hard to imagine\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ivi.tv/watch/143155/reviews/44706|script-title=ru:\u0417\u0430\u0449\u0438\u0442\u0438\u0442\u0435 \u043d\u0430\u0441 \u043e\u0442 \"\u0417\u0430\u0449\u0438\u0442\u043d\u0438\u043a\u043e\u0432\"|language=Russian|work=[[Ivi, Inc.]]|date=October 23, 2017|accessdate=February 19, 2019}}</ref> [[RIA Novosti]] placed it at the top of their worst film list,<ref name=\"RIA\"/> and it appears on Kritikanstvo's all-time lowest-scoring films.<ref name=\"Kritikanstvo\">{{cite news|url=http://www.kritikanstvo.ru/top/movies/worst/alltime/|script-title=ru:\u0425\u0443\u0434\u0448\u0438\u0435 \u0444\u0438\u043b\u044c\u043c\u044b|language=Russian|publisher=Kritikanstvo|accessdate=February 19, 2019}}</ref> Critics outside of Russia generally panned the film but were not as harsh, as it has a 30% rating on Rotten Tomatoes based on 10 reviews.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/guardians_2017|title=Guardians (Zashchitniki)|last=|first=|date=|work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango]]|accessdate=February 23, 2019}}</ref> A sequel was planned,<ref>{{cite web |url= https://hollywoodreporter.com/news/russian-superhero-film-china-release-868671|title= Russian Cold War Superhero Film to Get China Release Under Import Quota|first= Vladimir|last= Kozlov|date= February 23, 2016|accessdate= February 23, 2019|work= [[The Hollywood Reporter]]}}</ref> but the film was a box office bomb, which resulted in the film's production company, [[Enjoy Movies]], subsequently filing for bankruptcy, and the [[Cinema Foundation of Russia]], which provided part of the budget, suing the company and demanding a return of the investment.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://lenta.ru/news/2017/07/05/zashitniki/ |script-title=ru:\u0424\u043e\u043d\u0434 \u043a\u0438\u043d\u043e \u043f\u043e\u0442\u0440\u0435\u0431\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043b 51 \u043c\u0438\u043b\u043b\u0438\u043e\u043d \u0440\u0443\u0431\u043b\u0435\u0439 \u0443 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0434\u044e\u0441\u0435\u0440\u043e\u0432 \"\u0417\u0430\u0449\u0438\u0442\u043d\u0438\u043a\u043e\u0432\"|language=Russian|work=[[Lenta.ru]]|date=July 5, 2017|accessdate=February 19, 2019}}</ref><!-- Please do not add The Emoji Movie or Holmes & Watson. They have already been submitted many times but do not meet the inclusion criteria for this list and will be deleted. Generally, before submitting a film, please check the talk page and the list of removed films to see if the movie has already been rejected in the past.  -->\n\n== See also ==\n{{portal|Film|Lists}}\n* [[List of films considered the best]]\n* [[Box office bomb]]\n* [[List of box office bombs]]\n* [[List of films with a 0% rating on Rotten Tomatoes]]\n* [[CinemaScore#List of F films]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|20em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://rottentomatoes.com/ Rotten Tomatoes]\n* [http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20050811/COMMENTARY/50808002 Ebert's Most Hated]\n* [http://www.razzies.com/ Golden Raspberry Awards]\n* [https://metacritic.com/film/lowscores.shtml Metacritic: Worst-Reviewed Movies]\n* [http://www.mrqe.com/movies/special/50_worst_movies Movie Review Query Engine's 50 Worst]\n* [https://www.imdb.com/chart/bottom IMDb Bottom 100] (user scores)\n\n{{Worst works}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:List Of Films Considered The Worst}}\n[[Category:Lists of films by type|Worst]]\n[[Category:Lists of worsts|Films]]\n[[Category:Film and video fandom]]\n", "name_user": "SAaphIrEblUE", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eDeath Of A Nation (2018)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_films_considered_the_worst"}
